<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COSTLY VICTORY FOR DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK -- It's a win the Dodgers will remember for many of the
right reasons, and one they surely won't forget soon because two of
the most integral pieces of the team were injured.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers scored four runs in the ninth inning, the final
three coming on Devon White's two-out homer, and Eric Karros'
second homer of the day in the 10th inning lifted the Dodgers to an
unthinkable 6-5 win against the Mets at Shea Stadium on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But in the midst of ending a three-game losing streak, the
Dodgers lost much more. Right-handed ace Kevin Brown fractured his
right pinkie and is expected to miss three to four weeks. Left
fielder Gary Sheffield suffered a high ankle sprain. X-rays were
negative and he's listed as day-to-day, but a more definitive
timetable should be available after he's evaluated today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice win, but at the expense of the win we would have
rather taken the `L' and been healthy,'' Karros said. ``Hopefully,
we weather the storm until those guys return. Everyone talked about
how much deeper we are this year and we'll find out. This is as big
a test as we can have.''
</P>
<P>
   White and Karros took front and center late against the Mets.
All but finished, Karros led off the ninth with a homer against
John Franco, who walked Chad Kreuter and allowed a single to Kevin
Elster. Jose Vizcaino flied out, but White hit Franco's first pitch
over the right-center field fence to tie it 5-5.
</P>
<P>
   Karros then homered off Armando Benitez with two outs in the
10th to give the Dodgers the lead. Mike Fetters (1-0) recorded the
win in relief and Jeff Shaw had his first save, but there was
concern afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was cheating,'' White said. ``I was looking on the outside
part of the plate and it was up.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only are the Dodgers faced with not having Brown for the
next month, but they must hope Sheffield's injury isn't serious and
he can return shortly.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, right-handed reliever Gregg Olson could miss
significant time with a strained right forearm. The Dodgers trailed
5-1 entering the ninth after Olson, grimacing after almost every
pitch, allowed a pair of runs in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great game to win at a terrific cost,'' Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said. ``We have the young arms who had a great
opportunity last year, and they're going to have to stand up.
There's a good feeling on this ball club. He's a terrific loss, but
other guys are just going to have to step it up. We can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers spent the spring talking about depth in starting
pitching in Eric Gagne, Jeff Williams and Mike Judd. Now, it
appears two of the three will get opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   While obviously not enthused with the injuries, Dodgers general
manager Kevin Malone instead chose to look ahead to how much more
prepared each of the aforementioned young pitchers are to help this
year after gaining valuable experience last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Williams, Judd and Gagne, that is one area where we have
some depth,'' Malone said. ``I'm going took at this as an
opportunity to show what we can do. It's an opportunity for young
guys to pick us up early in the year. We're fortunate in a sense
that we have some good, young arms.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield injured his ankle when he twisted it on the warning
track chasing a fly ball in the first inning. Brown broke his
pinkie when he tried to bunt a Pat Mahomes pitch in the top of the
fifth. The ball struck Brown's hand squarely, though he remained in
the game and pitched the bottom of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely not what you want to see,'' Dodgers right
fielder Shawn Green said. ``Those are two huge pieces of the
puzzle. You hope you get them back quick. Both are competitors and
know how to play with pain.As soon as they can go, they'll be ready
to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said decisions will be made today on whom to place on
the disabled list. Brown, barring a miracle, is expected to make
his fifth career trip to the disabled. Olson is also a favorite to
go on the disabled list while questions about Sheffield's health
should be cleared today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
