<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGH SURVIVES TOUGH CONDITIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. - Saturday at the Masters, two things occurred that
have been forecast all week: a squall struck Augusta National Golf
Club and Tiger Woods stormed up the leaderboard.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, one of the first dozen players to tee off in the third
round after surviving by one shot the second-day cut, enjoyed the
best of the bad weather and he took full advantage. The 1997
Masters champion posted a 4-under-par 68 that swept him out of a
tie for 39th, where he had started the day, into a tie for second
in the clubhouse at 1-under-par with Davis Love III, who also fired
a 68, and Canadian Mike Weir (70).
</P>
<P>
   The gathering gale forced the suspension of play for two hours
shortly after noon, before the final 10 pairings had teed off.
Those golfers, which included the 36-hole leader David Duval, would
bear the brunt of the winds, which gusted to 25 miles per hour in
the afternoon after play resumed.
</P>
<P>
   Given the conditions, Vijay Singh's 2-under-par showing through
14 holes was suitable for framing. He'll apply the finishing
touches to his third round today along with seven other golfers who
were chased off the course by darkness, and then return to the
course for his final round.
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who has been doggedly pursuing his first Grand Slam
victory, was 2-over-par for his round and is three shots behind
Singh, his playing partner.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, 24, was in the midst of a four-birdie stretch that
started on the par-4 seventh hole when play was suspended. ``To all
of the sudden have that come to a stop was a little
disconcerting,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was downright discomfiting for the sexagenarian set. Jack
Nicklaus, 60, and Tommy Aaron, 63, clearly had a tough time getting
their creaky limbs loose after inertia was allowed to settle like a
draft into their old bones.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus, who began the day at even par, struggled to a
9-over-par 81, his worst score in 155 rounds here.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron, who became the oldest golfer in Masters history to
survive the 36-hole cut, parred the first six holes before the rain
delay and played the first two holes after it in 4-over-par. He
would finish with an 86.
</P>
<P>
   Woods grabbed a bite to eat during the delay and continued to
chew up the course once play resumed. He parred 11 and birdied two
of the next four holes before giving back a stroke with a missed
six-foot par putt at 17.
</P>
<P>
   He scrambled nicely on the par-4 finishing hole to escape with a
par and with his red-number running score intact. In his mind, the
die was cast on his resplendent round hours before he stood over
his putt on 18.
</P>
<P>
   Woods knew it was going to be his day when his tee shot on the
par-3 fourth hole sailed left of the green but he got up and down
to save par. ``More than anything,'' Woods said, ``it's a
confidence-builder knowing you can hit a bad shot like that and go
on to par (the hole].''
</P>
<P>
   That's just what the other 56 golfers vying for the Masters
green jacket wanted to hear. Woods gaining more confidence is like
Shaquille O'Neal getting more height.
</P>
<P>
   It's scary.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't hear that from Davis Love III, though. Love, 35, was
criticized by his peers after admitting last month at a tournament
in Orlando that Woods has become an intimidating presence on the
Tour.
</P>
<P>
   After matching Woods stroke for stroke, Love amended his earlier
comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say that Tiger Woods is very hard to beat right
now,'' Love said. ``And if he plays 100 percent (today), he's going
to be hard to beat. But I came here this week to win. So did a lot
of other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on how Singh fares in the frost and much later in the
furnace that is the finishing back nine, a lot of other guys could
yet don the green jacket. Steve Jones is putting superbly and has
20 holes remaining to move up from plus-1.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman, the 1996 British Open champion, also has 20 holes to
rocket from plus-1 to No. 1. In all, 10 of the 17 golfers
positioned just below Singh at Saturday's end have won at least one
of golf's four majors.
</P>
<P>
   One of those players, Nick Price, perhaps put it best after
living to tell about his third-round 73. ``Whatever is going to
happen out there,''he said, ``is going to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
