<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALMER LOOKS GOOD FOR USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Spring scrimmages don't usually prove a lot,
especially by the time fall rolls around.
</P>
<P>
   But USC's spring scrimmage did prove two things Saturday:
Quarterback Carson Palmer's arm is as strong as ever, and the
Trojans' kicking game is shaky as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer had no problem throwing the deep ball in USC's 102-play
scrimmage before 4,000 at the Coliseum, although his receivers
didn't always help him out. As for the kicking game, there's plenty
to work on before the Aug. 27 season opener against Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   Palmer, who redshirted last year after breaking his collarbone,
completed 14 of 21 passes for 155 yards and one touchdown, and his
stats would have been even better if some perfectly thrown long
balls were not dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good,'' Palmer said. ``It's going to take awhile to be
in the position I was. I have a ways to go. I still need to get my
timing back.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the kicking game, it has more than a ways to go. USC
converted just one of five field goals. Junior David Newbury was 1
for 4 with one kick blocked, and senior David Bell was 0 for 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know my dissatisfaction with the kicking game and we're
going to spend a lot of time on it,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said.
``Our two kickers have to get a lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Between the two, Bell clearly had a better spring, but he got
all the attempts in last week's scrimmage, so Hackett let Newbury
take most of the kicks Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In a change, Hackett decided to work the first-string offense
against the first-string defense, and the Trojans defense pretty
much shut down the running game except for Malaefou MacKenzie's
71-yard touchdown run up the middle. MacKenzie finished with 87
yards in 10 carries. His counterpart, Sultan McCullough, gained 26
yards in eight carries, and it appears the two will enter training
camp sharing time at tailback.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could co-exist, and if they did, I'd like to have both in
the backfield at the same time,'' Hackett said. ``We're going to
have both on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   It will get even more complicated when incoming freshman Chris
Howard of Banning High arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Former Alemany High tailback Miguel Fletcher had 33 yards in 11
carries.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Marcell Allmond had four receptions for 93 yards,
including an 18-yard touchdown pass from Palmer. Steve Stevenson,
playing on the second-team offense, had five catches for 55 yards,
including a 5-yard touchdown pass from Mike Van Raaphorst (11 for
22 yards, one touchdown,one interception).
</P>
<P>
   The defense was led by strong safety Ife Ohalete, playing on the
second unit, with 13 tackles. The No.1 defense featured Troy
Polamalu at strong safety and DeShaun Hill at free safety.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Lonnie Ford had six tackles, including three
sacks. Linebacker Zeke Moreno also had six tackles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the defense looked fast and played good coverage,''
Hackett said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
