r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN     04-09 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS STRUGGLE WITHOUT SHAQ
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even with a bum ankle, even with his afghan-sized
No. 34 jersey hanging in the locker room, even while sitting
courtside in a periwinkle suit, Shaquille O'Neal showed again
Saturday why he's the MVP of this league.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps it was his teammates who made the case for him.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it meant a loss for the Lakers, who without O'Neal
looked overwhelmingly uninspired and were routed 98-80 by the San
Antonio Spurs at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   They lost O'Neal to an ankle sprain before the game had begun.
Then they lost a golden opportunity to send a message to the Spurs,
their frequent tormentor and potential second-round playoff
opponent. They lost their 11-game winning streak and 14-game home
streak.
</P>
<P>
   And they lost the chance to reach the hallowed 70-win mark this
season.
</P>
<P>
   How's that for a losing streak?
</P>
<P>
   Meaningless as it all was -- the Lakers (64-13) already have the
NBA's best record wrapped up -- it still stung.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm embarrassed,'' Rick Fox said. ``It's the first time we've
played without (O'Neal) in a long time. And we didn't step to a
level that we should have.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they sunk to a level the Lakers hadn't visited in
months.
</P>
<P>
   Their scoring total was a season low, a point less than they
scored in a Feb. 1 loss at San Antonio. The 18-point margin of
defeat was second only to the 24-point loss the Spurs handed them
in that same game. Their shooting percentage (31.6) was a season
low, rivaled only by the 33.7 they posted in a Nov. 12 loss to
Houston -- not coincidentally, the last time O'Neal missed a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really played a poor game today,'' coach Phil Jackson said.
``We shot the ball poorly, and outside of one little run early in
the ballgame, we really didn't contest this team very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers fell to 0-2 in games without their leader in scoring,
rebounding, shooting percentage and blocked shots, not to mention
visceral emotion. It was a harsh reminder of how much the Lakers
(64-12) have come to rely on O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we've been on his back all year,'' Fox said, ``and
there's a reason why he's MVP. We faced the (defending) world
champions tonight, and they played like the world champions. And we
played like a team without Shaq.''
</P>
<P>
   They also played like a team with nothing left to gain in the
regular season, which they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always play the game with a fire,'' Fox said. ``Obviously,
it burned kind of low tonight for some reason. Shaq is more than
just our offensive and defensive anchor, he's also a lot of emotion
for us, a lot of adrenaline. We even missed him out in our huddle
when we first started the game.''
</P>
<P>
   That 7-foot-1, 330-pound void was tough to fill, in body or
spirit, especially against the Spurs' two 7-footers. Tim Duncan
went for 26 points and four blocked shots, David Robinson got 15
points.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant looked determined to make up for O'Neal's absence by
himself, taking a career-high 30 shots and making only 12 of them,
for 26 points, eight rebounds and five assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had some difficult shots he put up, some shots that weren't
high-percentage shots,'' Jackson said. ``He probably missed four or
five shots that looked good, were good, and probably took five
shots he shouldn't have taken.''
</P>
<P>
   John Salley, Travis Knight and 6-10 Robert Horry took turns at
center,combining for six points and 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be situations in the playoffs when Shaq's
going to be in foul trouble or whatever and we're going to have to
execute without him,'' Knight said. ``That's something we're going
to have to work on.''
</P>
<P>
   As for a 70-win season, ``It means we can do it next year,''
said Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't provide the energy necessary today to support that
and give ourselves the opportunity to get there,'' Jackson said of
70 wins. ``That's OK. That wasn't a goal. The goal was that we're
on track with what we want to do and go forward from there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
