<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO TIME TO GAMBLE FOR LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the Lakers clinched the NBA's best record
last week, they earned the right not to take unnecessary gambles,
so Shaquille O'Neal sat in street clothes Saturday while his team
played the San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal's sprained left ankle isn't serious enough to keep him
out of a must-win game, but it is enough of a concern that no one
wanted to push it, with the playoffs just two weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that if it was in the playoffs, definitely we'd play
him, and it wouldn't be a question,'' coach Phil Jackson said,
``but at this time, no, it's definitely precautionary.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal did not speak to reporters before ducking into the
training room for treatment before the game and left quickly
afterward. The sprain has been classified as mild, but it might
also keep him out of Monday's home game against Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said basically, if it was the playoffs, it wouldn't be a
question, that he'd have to go, if it was an important, meaningful
game like that,'' Jackson said. ``This is meaningful, but as far as
whether or not it ultimately means anything when it comes all the
way down to the end of the season, no, this is one you have to sit
out and take your lumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go game-to-game probably. We have to see how he
recovers, because it's obvious that if he doesn't play Monday,
he'll have two or three extra days rest until (the Lakers play)
Sacramento next Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Jackson, O'Neal sprained the ankle in the first
half of the Lakers' victory at Golden State on Wednesday, on a play
when O'Neal blocked a shot by the Warriors' Jason Caffey. Jackson
said he was unaware of the injury, and O'Neal played the rest of
the game, finishing with 49 points.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal missed just his second game of the season, and first
because of injury. His only other absence, Nov. 12, was the result
of a suspension for fighting.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!Hot Rice:!off! Without O'Neal, the offense struggled, but
Glen Rice reemerged, at least for a quarter. With a 12-point burst
in the third quarter, Rice scored 17 points, his highest output in
five games.
</P>
<P>
   And after going four games without making a 3-pointer, Rice hit
all three of his attempts Saturday. He did struggle a bit overall,
hitting 5 of 14 field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't challenge Glen. I wanted him to provide that energy
for himself,'' Jackson said. ``He knew what needed to be done out
there, and he tried to get going. Obviously, things didn't come
back to him as often as he would have liked, and he didn't have as
many opportunities as he would like, but he hit our only 3-point
shots tonight. That was the best thing about his game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
