<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCKER HAS FOND MEMORIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM - Angels reliever Kent Mercker had just entered the
clubhouse after batting practice Saturday afternoon when a reporter
asked him if there was anything special about the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's my dad's birthday,'' Mercker said.
</P>
<P>
   And?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah. This is the anniversary of my no-hitter,'' he said.
``My wife called me this morning to remind me of my dad's birthday,
and that's when I remembered the no-hitter because it happened on
the same day.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 8, 1994, Mercker, pitching for the Atlanta Braves,
threw a no-hitter against the Dodgers at Dodger Stadium. He
remembered a couple of nice defensive plays, one by third baseman
Terry Pendleton and one by center fielder Deion Sanders. He got the
last out on a comebacker.
</P>
<P>
   ``That seems like a long time ago.... I've played with six
different teams since then,'' he said. ``I think what stands out
was in the top of the ninth, I came to the plate and everyone was
standing and cheering for me. That was weird coming on the road.
Then with two outs in the bottom of the ninth, the crowd was going
wild. Other than it happening in Atlanta, I don't think there would
be a better place than Dodger Stadium. Sandy Koufax was my idol.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker was the fifth starter for the Braves that year, behind
Greg Maddux, John Smoltz, Tom Glavine and Steve Avery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony of it all was I think I'm the only guy in baseball
history to throw a no-hitter and then have my next start skipped
because we had an off-day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it was Mercker's first start of the season, when
pitch counts are usually strictly enforced, Braves manager Bobby
Cox let Mercker go the distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no-hitters after six innings twice once in '91 and once
in '93 and Bobby pulled me,'' Mercker said. ``I was primarily a
reliever back then; I wasn't conditioned to throw that many
pitches. But this time, I think he just thought he'd better let me
go.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mercker was pulled from the game after six no-hit innings
in 1991, Mark Wohlers (two innings) and Alejandro Pena (one inning)
completed the combined no-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Healed starter: Jarrod Washburn made 63 pitches in three innings
of a rehab start at Single-A Lake Elsinore and proved the strained
oblique muscle in his right side has healed.
</P>
<P>
   He was optioned to Triple-A Edmonton, where he will join the
starting rotation and make his first start Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Needs to be held: First, Mo Vaughn showed the Yankees, then the
Red Sox. Both teams didn't hold Vaughn at first and he stole
second. He got such a good jump against the Red Sox, he stole
second standing up.
</P>
<P>
   The two steals equal the most since he had 11 in 1995, when he
was the MVP of the American League. Last season, because of a badly
sprained ankle, he had none.
</P>
<P>
   ''Last year, I couldn't do nothing,'' he said. ''So they played
back. But I know how to read the pitcher, so I gotta go. That's
another run. No more station-to-station. They're giving me that,
I'm going to take it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
