<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAYSTATION-ANIMALS-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATE HALTS EXOTIC ANIMAL RESCUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DONNA HUFFAKER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Wildlife Waystation, the nation's largest
rescue sanctuary for exotic animals, has run afoul of regulations
intended to protect the health of people.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Fish and Game has ordered the facility
closed to tour groups, as well as to any more animals. The
sanctuary already is home to nearly 1,200 lions, tigers, wolves and
other creatures. The order came Friday, one week after Department
of Fish and Game inspectors said they found animal excrement
washing into a creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our major concern is the health and safety of the people who
might come into contact with these animals and the people who live
downstream,'' said Stanley Young, communications director of the
state Resources Agency, which oversees the Department of Fish and
Game.
</P>
<P>
   The situation leaves the future of the internationally renowned
sanctuary uncertain and has infuriated Martine Colette, the founder
and director.
</P>
<P>
   ``They closed us down. That's what they did,'' Colette said.
``We can't raise funds. We can't raise money to feed the animals. I
don't know where the animals are going to go. I'm where they go
when they have nowhere to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Colette denies there is any danger to the public from the way
she operates the 160-acre sanctuary in a remote area of the Angeles
National Forest hills, above the San Fernando Valley. She also
denies washing animal excrement into streams that run from the
Waystation into the Tujunga Wash.
</P>
<P>
   The cease-and-desist order came after the most thorough
inspection ever conducted at the Wildlife Waystation, which has
operated without a required state permit since February 1998.
Officials would not renew the permit because they said the
sanctuary is crowded and some cages are unsecured.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about cages prompted the inspection, and then
inspectors saw the apparent contamination of clean stream water
with animal waste, Young said, and concern arose about public
health and safety.
</P>
<P>
   Young said officials also are concerned about disposal of waste
from a chimpanzee that carries hepatitis B, a serious disease that
can be passed through bodily waste. The chimp is quarantined, but
state officials do not know how its waste is disposed, Young said.
</P>
<P>
   The question: What should be done with the Waystation's lions,
tigers, bears, monkeys and other exotic animals rescued from
medical researchers, exhibitors and individual owners.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from the Department of Fish and Game said they
will continue working with the Waystation to gain compliance with
state regulations. The object is to get the facility running safely
and legally, said Steve Martarano, department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   That could take hundreds of thousands of dollars that the
Waystation doesn't have, Colette said.
</P>
<P>
   To regain a permit, which allows exhibiting exotic animals, the
center must prove it has a proper disease-prevention program, and
it must improve cages that are crowded and roofless.
</P>
<P>
   Spending hundreds of thousands of dollars on improvements would
make it impossible for the Waystation workers to rescue and feed
more animals, they have said.
</P>
<P>
   But the state order puts rescuing any more exotic animals on
hold for the Waystation, and it calls for reducing the number of
animals already there, Martarano said.
</P>
<P>
   Colette insists there is no public safety issue. Waystation
workers do not wash anything directly into the streams, she said.
Pond water, however, flows into the streams as water runs downhill,
she conceded. Fish and Game officials have known that for 25 years,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions are safe, she said, adding that 100 people, including
herself, live on the compound.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole life has been about saving and caring for these
animals. They are safe, and they are comfortable. We have done all
that we can do,'' Colette said.
</P>
<P>
   The Waystation, with an annual budget of $2.5 million, relies
heavily on sponsor donations and membership dues to keep the animal
sanctuary running, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Waystation is seeking exemptions from some very expensive
requirements, said Byron Countryman, an attorney and member of the
facility's board of directors.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so incredible what is required; it's so expensive.
When we had to make a choice between the animal's welfare and its
cage, the answer was simple,'' Countryman said.
</P>
<P>
   Of more than 200 cages, inspectors last week found roughly 1/3
adequate, 1/3 cramped and 1/3 in need of drastic changes.
</P>
<P>
   Colette said some cages have been fixed, but the biggest problem
is in the temporary housing for chimpanzees until a new primate
center is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 30 chimps -- most of the 50 she rescued from biomedical
research two years ago -- are living in cages surrounded by plywood
and roofing. The cages are high enough for the chimps to stretch
and swing, Colette said, but they should be exposed to more
daylight. Also, some of the cages do not meet state requirements
for the amount of space per animal.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
</TEXT>
