<HEADLINE>
HILL, ERSTAD DELIVER FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM - Going into the season, two of the Angels' biggest
question marks were Ken Hill and Darin Erstad. But so far, Hill and
Erstad have been more like exclamation points.
</P>
<P>
   The two continued their early-season successes Saturday night,
helping the Angels to a 7-5 victory over the Boston Red Sox before
27,369 at Edison Field. It was the Angels' third win in a row and
put them in a tie for first in the AL West with the Seattle
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   That is significant because the Angels haven't had a share of
the top spot in the division since last April 17. At 3-2, it's the
first time the Angels have been over .500 since last April 16
(6-5).
</P>
<P>
   The Angels survived a late-inning rally by the Red Sox against
the Angels bullpen, but Troy Percival pitched the ninth for his
first save.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Hill a question mark for the Angels is his arthritic
right elbow. But his performances in his first two starts have
shown his elbow is fine for now. Saturday, he gave up one run and
two hits in six innings while making 98 pitches. He struggled a
little with his control, walking five. In addition to his
opening-night start against the Yankees, Hill has given up three
runs and six hits in 11 innings (2.38 ERA).
</P>
<P>
   Erstad was a question mark because he had struggled miserably
since making the All-Star team in 1998. Last season he hit only
.253, after hitting .299 and .296 in his first two full seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Erstad went 3 for 5 to raise his batting average to a
league-leading .583 (14 for 24). He singled twice, doubled, drove
in a run and scored another.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad led off the bottom of the first with a single, the fourth
time in five games he's led off the game for the Angels with a hit.
After a walk by Adam Kennedy, Mo Vaughn singled to left field to
score Erstad for a 1-0 Angels lead.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Salmon's flyout to deep center field moved Kennedy from
second to third, and he scored when Garret Anderson grounded into a
fielder's choice to make it 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hill was making quick work of the Red Sox hitters,
with a little help from his defense.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman led off the first inning with a walk but was
thrown out by catcher Bengie Molina trying to steal. In the second,
Nomar Garciaparra singled but was erased on a double play. Carl
Everett followed with a walk, but he, too, was caught stealing.
</P>
<P>
   After walking Darren Lewis with two out in the third inning,
Hill retired the next nine hitters. But with two out in the sixth,
Offerman walked and took second on a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Trot Nixon followed with a grounder to the hole at second, where
Kennedy made a diving stab of the ball. But when he tried to
transfer the ball from his glove to his hand, the ball popped free,
allowing Nixon to reach with a hit and Offerman to score from
second. Nixon went to second on a wild pitch and Brian Daubach
walked, bringing up Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, that would mean trouble, but Garciaparra has struggled
so far this season. Going into the game, he was hitting .125 (2 for
16) with only one RBI. He flied out to left field to end the threat
and Hill held onto his 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Ken, we want to get him to stay within his mechanics and
stay within his delivery, and to be pitch-efficient,'' Angels
manager Mike Scioscia said. ``We'll gradually increase pitch count
so he can pitch deep into ballgames. This is as strong as he's felt
in the last couple years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels increased their lead with four runs in the bottom of
the sixth, including an RBI double by Troy Glaus, and a two-run
homer by Scott Spiezio, his first as an Angel. Erstad doubled in
the fourth run of the inning for a 6-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox scored two runs in the seventh off the Angels
bullpen, but it could have been worse. Kent Mercker and Shigetoshi
Hasegawa combined to walk three and give up two hits, but Hasegawa
got out of it by getting Nixon to hit into an inning-ending double
play with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox added two more runs off Mark Petkovsek in the eighth
on a couple of two-out hits - Everett's RBI double and Jason
Varitek's RBI single.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
