<HEADER>
A1447 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-WAYSTATION-ANIMALS-2n     04-09 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAYSTATION-ANIMALS-2ndtake-LADN </SLUG>
 
LOS ANGELES: space per animal. 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles County veterinary officials said the Waystation
workers could not provide medical records for the animals during
last week's inspection, the first in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Field inspectors examined Waystation programs for handling and
preventing animal diseases. Dr. Patrick Ryan, county veterinary
health spokesman, said it was not clear whether the animals had
been vaccinated against tuberculosis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're concerned about disease prevention programs. Primates
are very susceptible to TB,'' Ryan said.
</P>
<P>
   Colette said the animals are treated well.
</P>
<P>
   One day, the chimps will move into a primate center designed
especially for them, she said. But that project, said Colette,
shaking her head, is another nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a surveyor's error, the mammoth primate center was
built partly on U.S. Forest Service Land, she said. Ironing out the
problem has taken years, but it appears resolved. So the chimps,
who on Thursday nibbled on chunks of ice, strawberries and jelly
beans Colette fed to them, will be relocated when construction is
done.
</P>
<P>
   The chimps' temporary housing is still far better than the tiny
cages they occupied in laboratories, Colette said.
</P>
<P>
   But expensive improvements to the temporary housing would be
impractical, Countryman said.
</P>
<P>
   Fish and Game officials sympathize with the herculean task
facing the Waystation, said Mervin Hee, regional patrol chief for
the Fish and Game.
</P>
<P>
   Impressed that Colette has saved thousands of animals on a
limited budget since the sanctuary opened in 1976, Hee reiterated
his department's goal of helping the center.
</P>
<P>
   If that's true, Colette said, state officials should grant her
an exemption from some of the state codes.
</P>
<P>
   Take old Jake the grizzly bear, for example. Under state
regulations, a cage or enclosure for a grizzly bear must measure at
least 400 square feet and have a ceiling or roof at least 8 feet
from the floor or ground.
</P>
<P>
   Colette stopped at Jake's chain-link home and pointed out the
violation: no roof. Jake, a slow-moving, hulking bear, waddled
across the otherwise code-compliant cage and nuzzled his head
against Colette's hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are fat, lazy bears. They're not nimble cubs that are
going to scurry on out of there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Colette stopped at Idaho Row, a neighborhood of Waystation pens
named for the 27 lions she rescued five years ago from what she
said was a squalid facility in Idaho. Those cages also do not meet
state code because of missing tension bars and poles that cross the
cage roof.
</P>
<P>
   State officials will continue investigating the Waystation,
Martarano said, including reports of Waystation chimps that were
exposed to HIV. ``We hope to get them into compliance. We don't
want to have to shut them down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
