<SLUG> BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS READY AND WAITING FOR JOB OFFERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF   
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As many as 10 NBA coaching jobs could open in the
next month, and you can bet Isiah Thomas will try to land one of
them. But not much else is known, except for the fact that college
coaches probably will not get a single one.
</P>
<P>
   Check out recent history, and see how well John Calipari, P.J.
Carlesimo and Rick Pitino have worked out. So let's handicap the
current or soon-to-be-available jobs and what might happen.
</P>
<P>
   Hawks: Lenny Wilkens is out? Well, let's put it this way. He's
building a house in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks: Don Nelson has reluctantly announced he will not
return, hence the Mavs' sudden surge in the standings. But one, or
all, of his 10 assistants would like the job. The front-runner is
former Lakers coach Del Harris, but new owner Mark Cuban wouldn't
mind a big name and is considering Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Clippers: Jim Todd will be cleaning out his office as soon as
the season ends, and there's plenty of speculation that Dennis
Johnson and/or Kareem Abdul-Jabbar could join him. Mike Fratello's
name keeps surfacing, although let's hope it's for nothing more
than the TV analyst position.
</P>
<P>
   Grizzlies: Lionel Hollins threatened to quit Thursday night,
before Vancouver gave him a cash settlement to bring his assistant
coach's salary to an acceptable level. New consultant Dick Versace
is expected to bring in his own guy, and that means a retread
should be running the team next season.
</P>
<P>
   There was some semblance of competency this week, when Chuck
Daly was offered a job as team president, but Daly turned it down.
</P>
<P>
   Pacers: Larry Bird already announced he's quitting, and while
assistant coach Rick Carlisle would probably be a super fit, or
even former Laker and former Pacer Byron Scott could get the job,
watch out for Thomas. Pacers GM Donnie Walsh has been doing some
background checks on the CBA commish/NBA studio man. That should
make everyone in Indy sufficiently nervous.
</P>
<P>
   Pistons: The Pistons were supposed to conduct a search that
would include taking a close look at former player Bill Laimbeer.
But interim coach George Irvine has done such a good job, they may
be forced to keep him, especially if Grant Hill delivers his
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Wizards: Washington is expected to take another try at hiring
Michael Jordan buddy/Golden State assistant Rod Higgins after the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Nets: Don Casey's stock keeps sliding, and Stephon Marbury's
injury has not helped the situation. Brace yourself for the latest
name to surface at the Meadowlands. Would you believe... Rick
Pitino?
</P>
<P>
   Warriors: Garry St. Jean has Golden State on the brink of an
18-win season. He isn't expected back, but the Warriors are so
hapless, no names have even surfaced. One person who would love the
job is former Warriors great Rick Barry, who has basically been
blacklisted throughout the league for his strong opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Nike speaks: A few weeks back, we reported that Sonics forward
Ruben Patterson blamed his foot injury on his Nikes. Patterson also
said Gary Payton and Vin Baker had problems with their shoes.
</P>
<P>
   A Nike spokesperson wrote this week, and we'd like to give him
equal time. The spokesperson said that Nike ``learned that Ruben,
despite receiving many pairs of shoes per month from Nike, was
wearing the same pair for several weeks at a time, for games and
practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most NBA players change to new shoes much more frequently, and
some even wear a new pair for every game (like Michael Jordan did).
We also have been told that Patterson does not untie his shoes, but
kicks them off, which wears down the back of the shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Nike also offered to correct Patterson's shoes, if a problem
existed. Stay tuned for further developments.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket scandal: The MSG Network has put longtime Knicks TV and
radio analyst John Andariese on ``administrative leave'' for the
rest of the season. No reason was originally given for the action,
but MSG later issued a joint statement with Andariese that the
broadcaster violated the Garden's internal policy prohibiting the
resale of tickets.
</P>
<P>
   There is some question as to whether Andariese will ever get his
job back, which means his penalty could be more severe than fellow
MSG announcer Marv Albert, who was brought back after 10 months
following his hotel-room escapades.
</P>
<P>
   Bugs are repellent: Charlotte players held a players-only
meeting to discuss how to get their younger players to raise their
concentration for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie point guard Baron Davis was the main target of the
veterans' ire, for not playing hard enough. His lackluster play in
an ugly win over the Bulls was a prime source of contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know now's the time we've got to start working harder in
practice and keeping our concentration in games,'' Davis told the
Winston-Salem Journal. ``This is the time of year when we have to
step it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Portsmouth update: This weekend, college players are competing
in the Portsmouth Invitational in Virginia, where draft sleepers
are usually found. So far, this year's sleeper is center Dan
McClintock of Northern Arizona, who had 17 points, nine rebounds
and six blocked shots in one game. He's already being talked about
as a potential second-round pick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
