<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-NORTHDAKOTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC FROZEN OUT AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE _ Boston College came up just short. Again.
</P>
<P>
   The title rich got richer and the Eagles are left still looking
for their second NCAA hockey championship overall and first since
1949.
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota scored two goals in the third period to come from
behind and beat BC, 4-2, Saturday &UR;  &LR; night at the Providence Civic
Center. It was the Sioux's seventh championship overall and second
in four years.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles have put together a great run: They lost to Michigan
in the finals in overtime two years ago, to Maine in the semifinals
in overtime last year, and now in the finals again.
</P>
<P>
   So close.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so tough to get here, you want to win it so bad,'' said
BC goalie Scott Clemmensen, who had 32 saves against the
hard-charging Sioux. ``It's a long, long road and we had a really
good bunch of guys and we thought this was our year.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Sioux's.
</P>
<P>
   They made it a Boston sweep. In 1997, North Dakota beat Boston
University for their sixth title. Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, it was Boston
College's turn to take the hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Sioux, upset before the Frozen Four each of the last two
years and the Western Collegiate Hockey Association regular-season
champ the last several, took a different route to the title this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six weeks ago, we would never have dreamed of this after
losing sight of the WCHA regular-season title,'' said coach Dean
Blais. ``Instead of getting bummed out, the guys kicked it into
gear and got it done.''
</P>
<P>
   To add to the insult, the Sioux beat Boston College with a
Boston-bound guy.
</P>
<P>
   Senior forward Lee Goren, a Bruins draft pick, led the North
Dakota charge in the third. Goren, a 6-3, 205-pound scorer, scored
to tie it 2:43 into the third. He helped set up the winning goal by
Jason Ulmer with 5:38 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Then Goren scored another, into an open net, for good measure.
That goal ended any chance of a comeback and sent Hobey Baker
winner Mike Mottau sliding into the Boston College net on one knee,
where he stayed for several moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year there have been a lot of ups and downs,'' Mottau
said. ``That goal really hurt. I thought we had a chance to tie it
right before that goal. We had a real flurry at the other end. To
have my college career come to an end like that was not the way I
wanted to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the rink, North Dakota goaltender Karl
Goehring skated aorund his net in celebration. North Dakota
finishes at 31-8-5. BC, which knocked North Dakota out of the
tournament last year, is 29-12-1.
</P>
<P>
   BC's three-year quest for a title _ led by seniors Mottau, Jeff
Farkas, Blake Bellefeuille, and Kevin Caulfield _ came to a
stunning end.
</P>
<P>
   Goren and Ulmer teamed up to make it 3-2 with 5:38 left in the
game. Ulmer dropped a pass for Goren. Clemmensen stopped Goren's
shot, but the rebound bounced to the other side and Ulmer beat a
defenseman to it and banged it in.
</P>
<P>
   Just like two years ago at the FleetCenter against Michigan, the
Eagles led, 2-1, with a period to go. And just like two years ago,
the enemy tied it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pretty much took it to us,'' Mottau said. ``We were back
on our heels most of the period. It's real difficult to swallow.''
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota defenseman Mike Commodore opened the scoring 3:48
into the game and Farkas tied it with a power-play goal with 3:13
left in the first.
</P>
<P>
   Marty Hughes scored from Brian Gionta at 6:59 of the second and
the Eagles had their lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sioux were getting the better of the play. Shots were
even in the first period, but North Dakota outshot BC, 22-10, the
rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the third, they took the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Goren made the most of a second chance to even things at 2-2 at
the 2:43 mark of the third. Goren had just broken through the
middle and was in alone on Clemmensen, but the goalie stopped his
backhander. The next time down, Goren took a drop pass from Ryan
Bayda and shot from just inside the top of the right circle. The
puck went between the legs of defenseman Rob Scuderi and a screened
Clemmensen.
</P>
<P>
   It was Goren's 33d goal of the year. Soon, he would have his
34th.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles had trouble generating offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very good defensively,'' said BC coach Jerry York.
``They boxed out well. They protected their goaltender very, very
strongly. It wasn't for a lack of our trying to get at him. They
shut us down but it was still 2-2 with seven minutes left and we
were trying to get a break. We didn't get it, but if you get it,
the momentum changes in a hurry.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles could have used a break at the midpoint of the third.
The score was 2-2 and Mottau had a chance in close. And hit the
post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept it in at the blue line and fed it down to Gionta,''
Mottau said. ``He found Marty Hughes in the slot and I decided to
crash down. The puck was bouncing a little bit and he was at the
side of the net and I had some net to shoot at and it happened to
hit the post.''
</P>
<P>
   No bounce. No break. And no title.
</P>
</TEXT>
