<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-AVENGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVENGERS TRY TO GET FANS' ATTENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The provocative billboards began coming down
Friday, leaving just one remaining matter of business for what has
been hyped as Los Angeles' only professional football team: an
actual game.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment begins today, when the Avengers make their local
Arena Football League debut with an exhibition game against the
Oklahoma Wranglers at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Team officials say the game will be sold out, but it's unlikely
most of the fans in attendance today - and that includes Mayor
Richard Riordan - are quite sure what they are showing up to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way to explain it until you experience it, with
guys flying into walls,'' Avengers quarterback Scott Semptimphelter
said. ``I haven't been to a game yet that isn't fan friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   But is it football?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little different. But it's football,'' Avengers owner
Casey Wasserman said.
</P>
<P>
   Players will crash into walls, balls will bounce off nets, and
running plays will be virtually eliminated. Above all, Arena
Football is supposed to be entertaining, and the Avengers have
promised to live up to that image.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what will make me happy is to hear people after the
game say they had a great time and they fell in love with the
sport,'' Wasserman said.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-year-old owner has done everything possible to spark the
interest of notoriously skeptical Los Angeles sports fans. That
included renting more than 1,300 billboards throughout Southern
California that drew the ire of some for their controversial
content.
</P>
<P>
   But more importantly, the billboards brought more media
attention than anyone imagined.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we wanted to do is to create an attitude with
the team. We're doing things a little differently,'' Wasserman
said. ``We had to establish a voice for ourselves. A lot of teams
don't have a voice. The Dodgers have lost their voice a little bit.
The Angels too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lakers have a voice. Everyone knows they are Showtime.
They've built a new version with Kobe and Shaq. Everyone knows the
Lakers win.''
</P>
<P>
   Wasserman's already won over some big-time Los Angeles sports
figures. Among the season-ticket holders are former Dodgers owner
Peter O'Malley and New York Jets wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   The double-edged task of the Avengers is that in addition to
providing entertainment value, they also want to win, or else they
could quickly fall off the crowded sports landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to win a championship and not just two games,''
Semptimphelter said. ``To set goals of less than a championship is
ludicrous, in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Avengers coach Stan Brock, a former NFL lineman with New Orleans
and San Diego, isn't quite as brash when making predictions, but he
doesn't want his team to be a typical expansion squad either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect us to compete in every game,'' Brock said. ``My goal
is to be in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Brock is quite serious about winning. One example is starting
Semptimphelter at quarterback. It would be more popular to start
former USC and Raiders quarterback Todd Marinovich, but he's still
learning how to play arena football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience outweighs ability and Scott will be my starter,''
Brock said. ``I'm very pleased with Scott.''
</P>
<P>
   It's clear that the players are just as competitive as in the
NFL, and not just playing some weird trash-sport, when
Semptimphelter talks about his role on the team, and how it relates
to the widely known Marinovich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the day I've gotten here, he's gotten a lot of
attention,'' Semptimphelter said. ``No one knows who I am. I'm sure
I will surprise people by starting. But I was not brought here to
be the backup.''
</P>
<P>
   About 75 percent of the team is composed of Arena Football
League veterans, so few names will be familiar to fans.
</P>
<P>
   Some aspects of the game should also catch people off guard. On
field goals and kickoffs, a ball is live if it hits the nets behind
the end zones, and it takes awhile to figure out who can actually
rush the quarterback. One linebacker cannot move out of an
imaginary box.
</P>
<P>
   But the thought is that fans will be more impressed by scores
such as 54-47, the final of the Avengers' exhibition victory over
Arizona last week, than the nuances of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's an electric crowd and people are fired up about
football being back in L.A.,'' Semptimphelter said.
</P>
<P>
   Wasserman says he will be happy if the team averages 10,000 per
game this season, adding there is even a possibility the team could
make money by its second year.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his friends were skeptical about why he would sink
nearly $8 million into this venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of people who would say `Arena Football?'''
Wasserman said. ``There was bewilderment, maybe. Until they see it
on Sunday, they clearly see reservations.''
</P>
<P>
   But he believes after tonight's game, Los Angeles will embrace
the Avengers. Just as long as they can win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-factor is how well we do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There might be a chance the fans are not as tough to please as
expected. On the Avengers' Web site, fans were asked what they look
forward to seeing most today, other than football.
</P>
<P>
   A clear majority of 51 percent listed the team's cheerleaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
