<SLUG> BC-HKC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILENCE OF TITLE LOSS DEAFENING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE _ It was close to midnight when the last of the
Boston College hockey players left the arena. Their postgame locker
room had been so silent that even the most ordinary sounds seemed
strange. You could hear a shower running, but it sounded like rain
sizzling on summer asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing you can say to an athlete who has just lost a
championship game. There is nothing you can give, either. So as the
red-eyed players left the Providence Civic Center after their 4-2
loss to North Dakota Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, they were oblivious to many
things. One thing, especially.
</P>
<P>
   The second-place trophy rested on a table outside the BC locker
room. The players walked by and ignored it as if it were the
mystery dish at a holiday party. Coach Jerry York's wife, Bobbie,
stood next to the trophy. When it was awarded to captain Mike
Mottau after the loss, he accepted it and promptly skated to the BC
bench. He gently placed it there. Clearly, it was the last he
wanted to see of it. ``I know,'' York said, looking at the trophy,
``Motts doesn't want it.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone takes a title-game loss hard, but you could see the
pain most in two players. After North Dakota's Lee Goren scored an
empty-netter with less than a minute remaining, Mottau crouched
inside the empty net. York gathered his team to the bench and said
a few words. Very few. He has lost a championship as a BC player,
too. That was in 1965. Some things haven't changed in 35 years. You
lose a championship that you feel you should have won _ that you
feel you deserved _ and the pain is unspeakable.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as this loss was official, the North Dakota team piled
on their half of the ice and celebrated with the handful of fans
who had come to see them. On the other end, BC forward Mike Lephart
took his stick and whacked it against the post. It snapped in half.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the ``correct'' thing to do would have been to stand
with hands on hips and give props to the champions. But if you have
ever lost a championship, or the equivalent of a championship, you
know the follow-the-dots path to losing gracefully rarely happens.
</P>
<P>
   ``You lose a game like that, you don't know what to do,''
Lephart said. ``That's sports and that's life, but it's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The toughest part was sitting there. The game was over. BC had
lost its third Frozen Four in the past four years. Seniors Mottau,
Jeff Farkas, Blake Bellefeuille, Kevin Caulfield, and Tony Hutchins
had been on the ice for all the losses. So they watched as the kids
from Fargo country celebrated. They watched until Mottau was called
to accept the trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's hard,'' Lephart said. ``You're sitting there watching
them celebrate. You're trying to contain your emotions . . . I just
wish we could have won it for the seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   After placing the trophy near the bench, Mottau whispered to his
teammates. He picked up his stick and tapped the ice. The Eagles
followed. They saluted the fans. Then they left.
</P>
<P>
   This was tough for many reasons. Some players wanted to win the
title to reward the seven fans who drove to Madison, Wis., to watch
them play in the early rounds. Mottau wanted to win it for his
sister, Charlene Alger, who is pregnant and could not come here.
Bellefeuille wanted to win it for his family. His brother, Brian,
played at Maine and didn't win a championship. The senior even
jokingly told his father that he couldn't attend because a title
hasn't come while he's been watching.
</P>
<P>
   At least BC knows there was nothing superstitious about
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's loss. The Fighting Sioux are the quickest team
the Eagles have faced all year. They scramble to the puck. They
scored first, and then fell behind, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   In the third period, ironically, a Bruins draft pick changed the
game. Goren was quiet in the first two periods. During the second
intermission, a local hockey coach approached the pressbox and
said, ``The Goren kid is soft.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after that, the 6-foot-3-inch Canadian scored. He then
assisted on the goal that put the Sioux ahead for good. Then he
scored the empty-netter. The coach was right. He had played soft _
for two periods.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Mottau sat at a table and said he didn't want
his career to end like it did. He said it was a pleasure to play
for York and to play at BC. Before the third, he told his teammates
that if they could hold on to the lead, they would ``walk together
for the rest of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That will still happen,'' York said. ``Even though we lost,
these guys will still remember each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles had left here by midnight. It was still noisy. North
Dakota's flight out of town had been delayed three hours, so there
was a raucous party. They cheered. They clapped. They sang the
North Dakota fight song.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Eagles, they didn't have to listen or watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
