<SLUG> BC-HKN-NORTHDAKOTA-GOEHRING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOEHRING HAS HEAD FOR GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MONAHAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE _ North Dakota junior Karl Goehring made a comeback
he's proud of.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-7-inch, 150-pound goaltender from Apple Valley,
Minn., had to give up his starting role when he suffered a head
injury in practice three weeks ago. Doctors made him sit out three
games, but he finally got the green light to resume play at the
Frozen Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got banged up in a practice back home,'' said Goehring. ``We
had a spirited practice and there was plenty of activity in front
of my net and I just got whacked real hard. You never know what to
expect after a head injury and people were cautious about me
playing. But it turned out OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Goehring made 21 saves Saturday &UR;  &LR; night while beating Boston
College, 4-2. ``I have to credit my defense in general and the
forechecking of all the forwards,'' said Goehring. ``Let's face it,
Boston College is a terrific team with lots of scoring power. They
showed it real early. Then my guys played tougher as the game went
on and I saw fewer and fewer shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a matter of fact, I didn't have to work too hard in the
second and third periods (five and four saves, respectively).
Sometimes I think it's better to be making more saves. But I can't
fault this. We won it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Goehring was beaten by BC's Jeff Farkas in the first period when
BC had a power play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had it under my pads,'' said Goehring. ``It just
slipped under me and Farkas got a stick on it. Good play by him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles went up, 2-1, at 6:59 of the second when Marty Hughes
beat him with a wraparound goal.
</P>
<P>
   Said Goehring, ``That was all my fault. He just tucked it in. I
gave a little space and he jammed it in.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, I just said to myself to relax and play smarter.''
</P>
<P>
   He did.
</P>
<P>
   North Dakota coach Dean Blais praised Goehring saying, ``Before
we came here, I was worried because he hadn't played in three
weeks. He's capable of putting up a zero. Karl is the winningest
goalie in UND history and it says a lot about him as a person. He's
learned how to anticipate shots and he learned to deflect passes
that come through the crease.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Kollar spelled Goehring in the last game of the regular
season and in the West Regionals. He posted a 3-0 record, upping
his season mark to 11-2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Said Blais, ``I'm very proud of what Andy did. I held off naming
my starter here, but when both were healthy I just looked at the
numbers. Karl had a 1.95 goals-against average and a .924 save
percentage. Those figures are great and I just had to go with him
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly did his job.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second period, Goehring took a BC stick on the head and
fell to the ice. ``It wasn't serious. Just a blow,'' he said. ``The
trainer looked at me and I was not uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Goehring had high praise for his backup Kollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was glad and proud the way Andy played in those three games
I was out. We're good friends and we help each other. He's the
closest thing I have to a goalie coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watch each other and we talk a lot about how to improve.
We're good for each other. Besides, we think team more than
ourselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
