<SLUG> BC-HKC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-YORK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YORK GRACIOUS IN DEFEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE _ His eyes gave his inner feelings away.
</P>
<P>
   They were red and swollen.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College hockey coach Jerry York was hurting after his
Eagles fell to North Dakota, 4-2, in Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's NCAA title
game.
</P>
<P>
   He was hurting for himself and for seniors Mike Mottau and Kevin
Caulfield, with whom he shared the post-game press conference
podium. And he was hurting for seniors Blake Bellefeuille and Jeff
Farkas, who stayed behind in the somber BC dresing room.
</P>
<P>
   But as much as it hurt, he was gracious in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no complaining, we took a hit and the team feels North
Dakota played better than we did in the third period. I love that
feeling,'' said York.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not complaining about this or complaining about that.
We wanted to win the hockey game, but we lost it, we'll take the
hit and we'll move on. Give full measure to North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like (Mottau) said, they played extremely well in the third
period, limited our offensive chances and they do that from being
well coached and from having good players. There are no complaints
from our end.''
</P>
<P>
   BC lead, 2-1, after two periods, but North Dakota tied it 2
minutes, 43 seconds into the third period on a goal by Lee Goren.
York thought that was the key.
</P>
<P>
   ``That seemed to energize (North Dakota),'' he said. ``We're
going into the third period up 2-1 and we expected that. You don't
expect to be in the championship game and think it's going to be
8-7 or they're going to lead, 7-0. We knew it would be a tight,
hard game to play with not a lot of ice out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought when they got that second goal they just seemed to
have a lift to them. Then when it was 2-2, I think (Mottau) hit the
post. That may be the break you need in a game like this.''
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the podium, York moved to the BC dressing room,
where his graciousness continued. As hard as it was, he never
ducked a question and there were many thrown his way.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked if the fact the team hadn't won a national
championship since 1949 weighed heavily on the program
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great motivating force for us to win another
championship,'' he said. ``I think you can tell that from our
resurgence of the past three years. We're focused and we want to
win a national championship. But you don't always get what you wish
for. I don't think (not winning since 1949) is a negative factor.
It's more like let's go win another one.''
</P>
<P>
   When someone asked how the team was doing, York's eyes filled
with tears and his voice quivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not doing real well because this was something we had
our heart and soul set on doing. To get to the championship game
like this and be ahead, 2-1, we're 20 minutes away from achieving
that goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to tell you, though, they gave full credit to North
Dakota. They played very well. I told our guys to stand up and
shake a senior hand. our four seniors played their hearts out. I
think there's a special feeling in the lockerroom right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, York was asked if this, or losing the title game in
overtime to Michigan two years ago, hurt more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current is most hard,' he said. ``It's hard to reflect
back. We were 20 minutes from winning the game and with that game
comes the national championship. You don't get that opportunity
very often.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he retreated into the lockerroom, where the tears and the
consoling began anew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
