<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BURN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION FALL SHORT IN DALLAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The Revolution's long road trip wound down in
frustration as the team lost the offensive cohesiveness which had
carried it through the first three games of the season and fell,
2-1, to the Dallas Burn Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   But the Revolution, 0-2-2 going into Saturday's home-opener
against D.C. United, displayed some encouraging signs, ending the
game on the attack and taking the potential tying shot from the
goal area just before the final whistle.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Torres had a productive game at striker, converting his
first goal of the season in the 41st minute. And in his season
debut at central defense, Dan Calichman filled in strongly for Ivan
McKinley (suspended).
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, though, played like a team which has maintained a
consistent style of play and had few personnel changes in recent
years. The Burn was more resourceful, and its experience, plus the
attacking skills of Ariel Graziani paid off.
</P>
<P>
   The Burn exploited Revolution mistakes, and caught the team off
guard to score. Dallas also gained control of the midfield for long
periods of time in the first half, causing the Revolution to chase
the game and placing heavy pressure on the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not frustrated but I am disappointed in the performance of
certain players,'' Revolution coach Fernando Clavijo said.
</P>
<P>
   Clavijo singled out Eduardo Hurtado for ``lack of effort.'' But
the Revolution did not have a strong offensive game in the first
half, while Hurtado was on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Hurtado entered in the second half in place of Wolde Harris, and
did not have an impressive game. But he did pressure defender Eric
Dade, and he won the corner kick which resulted in the last-second
near-miss by Torres.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a difficult situation for everybody,'' Clavijo said.
``It was not Wolde Harris' day, but you can't blame him. It could
be that it wasn't (Hurtado's) day, but the effort wasn't there. I
was tremendously disappointed in his performance.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution, though, also had some tactical shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   Shaker Asad replaced Mauricio Ramos (suspended) left side of
midfield, but was supposed to have responsibilities as a central
midfield choreographer as well as defending on the wing. Asad had
some excellent touches, and his through ball to Torres in the 66th
minute beat goalkeeper Matt Jordan before being cleared by Ricardo
Iribarren.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Pierce had another strong game at right back, but was
caught out of position on the deciding goal.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce stifled Graziani early, and Graziani retaliated by
knocking him down and cleating his thigh. But Dallas began taking
control midway through the first half. Revolution midfielder Leonel
Alvarez, who had been the Burn's leading figure for three of their
first four years, tangled with Colombian countryman Oscar Pareja
and both received cautions in the 30th minute.
</P>
<P>
   And the Burn began dictating the tempo. Graziani shot wide from
20 yards in the 35th minute, and three minutes later he finished a
move which began with a Ted Chronopoulos giveaway. Sergi Daniv
dribbled toward the penalty area, passed to Jason Kreis, who
flicked a backheel to Chad Deering, who centered for Graziani. The
goal might have been disallowed for offside, but the Burn buildup
was quick enough to surprise the linesman. And the interplay was
dazzling enough to earn the benefit of the doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani also poked a rebound off the left post in the 45th
minute, and played an important part in the deciding goal. Ted Eck
set up the goal, taking a throw-in behind the halfway line,
dribbling toward the penalty arc and finding Mark Santel on the
left wing. Santel's cross was dummied by Graziani, and Kreis
finished in front of Chronopoulos in the 74th minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution added William Sunsing in place of Asad, and
pushed forward in desperation in the final minutes. But Dallas had
enough resolve to hold them off, and Kreis helped goalkeeper Matt
Jordan stop the final shot, then spent several minutes on the
ground after the game recuperating from the collision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
