u s BC-HKC-NORTHDAKOTA-GOREN     04-09 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-NORTHDAKOTA-GOREN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS GET A GOOD LOOK AT GOREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARVIN PAVE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE _ Lee Goren gave his father, Chuck, the most special
of 50th birthday presents Saturday &UR;  &LR; night _ a national championship
to celebrate with his son and a third period full of memories for a
lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Goren, North Dakota's senior assistant captain and a third-round
draft pick of the Bruins in 1997, scored the tying goal, assisted
on the winner, and salted the national championship away with an
empty-netter, all in the final period at the Civic Center where the
Fighting Sioux beat Boston College, 4-2, for the NCAA title.
</P>
<P>
   Goren wound up as the country's leading goal scorer with 34 and
was named the NCAA tournament's Most Outstanding Player.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Playing in the NHL) will be great, whether it's Providence or
Boston,'' said the younger Goren, who met with Bruins assistant
general manager Mike O'Connell this week. ``Maybe I'll be back in
this building soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Goren, who played four seasons at Lake Superior State and
now owns a string of doughnut shops in Winnipeg, said the Bruins
have hinted they'd like to see his son in a Providence Bruins
uniform if that team can get to the second round of the upcoming
American Hockey League playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's in April or late summer training camp, said North
Dakota coach Dean Blais, the Bruins will find themselves with ``a
self-driven player. He worked hard all last summer lifting weights
and he wants to be a member of the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great leader in the dressing room and he's what you saw
tonight. He plays big in big games and he's done that all year
long. He's got a real knack for scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Goren's tying goal, said BC coach Jerry York and captain
Mike Mottau, that gave the Fighting Sioux the fight to live up to
their nickname.
</P>
<P>
   ``That goal really energized them,'' said Mottau of Goren's
strike early in the third period. ``That was the turning point.''
</P>
<P>
   Goren, whose younger brothers were playing Saturday &UR;  &LR; night in
the Manitoba junior championships _ Chuck Goren was trying to find
a telephone just before midnight to check on that game _ joked that
after North Dakota's national championship win over BU in 1997 (he
was redshirted that year) and Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's victory, he wasn't
sure what kind of welcome he'd get in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But any player who can score in the clutch and carry a team on
his shoulders in the biggest game of his career will be more than
welcome in the Hub.
</P>
<P>
   Goren, who hit a post and was also stopped by BC goalie Scott
Clemmensen on a breakway, said of his early frustration
Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, ``I was wondering if I could shoot the puck in the
ocean.''
</P>
<P>
   And he wasn't thinking about passing BC's Brian Gionta (33
goals) with his empty-netter for the national goal scoring lead.
``The important thing was that we got four and they got two,'' said
Goren, ``and that I couldn't have given my dad a better 50th
birthday present. One of the reasons I came to North Dakota was
that it was close to Winnipeg and my parents could come to see me
play.''
</P>
<P>
   Goren said he worked on his entire game to get ready for what
turned out to be a championship season. ``Like the team, we got
better and better as the year went on. Last year, BC beat us in the
regionals. We owed them and we wanted them. They put a sour feeling
in our gut last year and we wanted to do the same thing to them
this year.''
</P>
<P>
   But what was sour for the Eagles was oh-so-birthday-cake sweet
for Lee and Chuck Goren. ``Dad had me playing hockey when I was 3
years old,'' said Lee, ``and I'm so glad he was here tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Goren said he was happy for his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a way to go out. What a terrific feeling for Lee. Now, he
wants to play for Boston,'' said the proud father. ``I think
everything will work out in the next week or so and we're excited.
He (Mike O'Connell) would like to see Lee play in Providence this
year and if they get into the second round, I'm sure Lee will be
here to help them. Hopefully he'll be moving to Boston later in
May. We all want him to be a Boston Bruin.''
</P>
<P>
   If he helps the Baby B's and the parent club like he lifted his
Sioux mates Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, then Goren will be the people's choice
in Boston as well as in Grand Forks, N.D.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
