<SLUG> BC-HKO-WOMEN'SWORLDCHAMPIONSHIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM USA ROLLS INTO FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MISSISSAUGA, Ontario _ Thanks to Team USA's 7-1 win over Sweden
and Canada's 3-2 edge over Finland in Saturday's semifinals, the
United States and Canada will face off Sunday night for the sixth
time in the final game of the World Championship of women's ice
hockey. Since 1990, when the tournament began, no other team has
ever been on the ice with the world title at stake. Finland is
getting better; Sweden, too. But when everything's on the line,
it's still ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' vs. ``O Canada''
</P>
<P>
   The United States is getting a little tired of the latter.
Although the team brought home the Olympic gold medal, Team USA
players have yet to earn the right to call themselves world
champions. Five title games against Canada, five losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still hungry,'' said captain Cammi Granato, the only US
player who has been around since the beginning. ``We haven't
achieved a gold (at worlds) yet. That's something we really want
under our belts.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the United States has beaten Canada only once in eight
tries since returning from Nagano, a 4-1 win in an exhibition this
February. But that was before the return of the gold-medal twins.
Yes, the Sara/hs are back. For the first time since the Olympic
triumph, goaltenders and friends Sarah Tueting and Sara DeCosta
have been reunited, and hopes are high that their experience,
poise, skill and chemistry will provide the yeast this team needs
to rise to the challenge. Their timing couldn't be better,
especially coupled with the absence of defenseman Tara Mounsey,
recovering from ACL surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just having those two back in net is a real security for us,''
said Granato. ``They're both so talented. Sara DeCosta is one of
most sound goalies technically I've ever seen play the game, and
Sarah Tueting is the biggest-game player.''
</P>
<P>
   Although each has played in a few international games since
Nagano, circumstances have kept the Sara/hs apart. Tueting, one
class away from her degree at Dartmouth, took a year's break from
hockey , while DeCosta returned to Providence College and devoted
herself to playing for the Friars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the decision to play for Providence and I felt I had a
loyalty to them,'' said DeCosta, whose 62 saves in a
double-overtime loss against Dartmouth in the quarterfinals of last
month's ECAC tournament may have been her last for the Friars
despite another year of eligibility. The 22-year-old from Warwick,
R.I., hopes to instead be gearing up for 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``If given the opportunity to play at this level and go on tour,
that's definitely what I'm going to do,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for Tueting, now more than ever. After deciding
she wasn't yet ready to give up hockey, the 23-year-old premed
student rejoined the US squad only to sprain her left ankle so
badly in a December exhibition game against Harvard that she missed
11 weeks of training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long winter,'' she said. ``I did a lot of time in the
pool. I felt like I was training for the Summer Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Sara/hs, roommates on this trip, are tickled to be back
together. As it was on the road to Nagano, they share net duty.
Asked after Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's win which netminder would start
against Canada _ they are each 2-0 in this tournament_ Smith
replied: ``You know the answer: Sara/h.''
</P>
<P>
   They were in there together in the gold-medal game in Nagano.
When starter Tueting took to the ice, she wore a good-luck angel
pin that had long been DeCosta's. Although Tueting tried to give it
back to her teammate afterward, it's still safely in her jewelry
box back home. ``It was a gift to her,'' said DeCosta. ``I'm sure
she'll use it the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Tueting: ``We'll see come 2002 where it needs to go.''
</P>
<P>
   In Saturday &UR;  &LR; night's victory over Sweden, the United States got
off to a fast start when Alana Blahoski scored her sixth goal of
the tournament just 1:47 into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``To come out of the first period 1-0 is kind of a concern,''
said Smith, ``because we gave them a foothold.''
</P>
<P>
   Team USA regained control with a three-goal second, however, and
was up 4-0 before Sweden ruined the shutout with a goal 4:43 into
the third before Krissy Wendell, Blahoski and Karyn Bye wrapped
things up for the United States. Stephanie O'Sullivan of Dorchester
notched two assists, giving her 12 points in four games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
