<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANGELS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX NIGHTMARE CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ No, Sox fans, it doesn't look any better in
the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Even after wiping the sleep from your eyes and chugging your
first cup of joe, there's no disguising the distressing events
taking place on the Left Coast while most of New England slumbers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite exhaustive efforts by an Anaheim bullpen seemingly
determined to give away a five-run lead, the Red Sox lost their
fourth straight game, 7-5, before a gathering of 27,369 in Edison
International Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who trailed, 6-1, after six innings but had the tying
run on base in the eighth, are off to their worst start since 1996,
another season that began with exalted expectations. The Sons of
Kevin Kennedy, coming off a division title the year before, lost
their first five games and 12 of their first 14 to fall out of
contention by Patriots Day that year. The fallout from that season
included Kennedy's firing and Roger Clemens's exodus from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The Sons of Jimy Williams, coming off back-to-back wild-card
appearances, have lost four in a row since an Opening Night win by
Pedro Martinez, who pitches again Sunday afternoon and will attempt
to keep the Sox from matching their longest losing streak of last
season, when they dropped five in a row in June.
</P>
<P>
   It will be up to Martinez to do what their other franchise
player, Nomar Garciaparra, has been unable to accomplish.
Garciaparra had a single in three trips and was robbed of another
by Angels shortstop Gary DiSarcina but is off to the worst start of
his four-year term with the Sox, one in which he is 0 for 6 with
runners in scoring position and batting .158 (3 for 19) overall.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox already have lost more games this season (2) to the
Angels than they did in all of '99, when they took 9 of 10 from the
fallen Halos. They haven't held a lead in the last 21 innings,
keeping the pressure on a shaky pitching staff that nevertheless
shouldn't take the blame for all that has gone south on this West
Coast swing.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox scored twice in both the seventh and eighth innings,
taking advantage of four walks. Jeff Frye, playing third base in
the absence of the injured John Valentin, singled home one run and
beat an attempted force play to set up another in the seventh,
which ended with Trot Nixon hitting a one-hop smash that Angels
rookie second baseman Adam Kennedy turned into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, after Troy O'Leary had doused a two-on, no-out
rally by hitting into a double play, two-out hits by Carl Everett
(double) and Jason Varitek (single) drew the Sox to within 6-5. But
Lou Pote, the Angels' fifth pitcher, struck out Frye on three
pitches to end the inning, and the Angels added a run in the bottom
of the inning on Scott Spiezio's double and Benji Molina's single
off Sox reliever Rheal Cormier. ``We got a good guy going tomorrow,
but so do they,'' said Sox manager Jimy Williams, referring to
Angels righthander Kent Bottenfield, who won 18 games for St. Louis
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we battled back in the latter part of the game and we'll
take that into tomorrow's game. We haven't been scoring runs (10 in
the first four games) and we scored five tonight. Good things can
happen, but we've got to make them happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox were down, 2-0, after one inning Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, with
Mo Vaughn contributing an opposite-field, 0-2 RBI single to put
Brian Rose in an early hole. The Sox came into the game with just
four hits in 30 at-bats with runners in scoring position. That
number didn't change through the first five innings against Lynn's
Ken Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, coming off a season in which he won just four games and
had persistent elbow trouble, took a one-hitter into the sixth,
when the Sox finally broke through when Jose Offerman drew a
two-out walk, took second on a wild pitch, and hustled home when
Angels second baseman Adam Kennedy made a diving stop of Nixon's
grounder but saw the ball pop out of his glove as Offerman never
broke stride.
</P>
<P>
   But Rose was bounced in the sixth, when Garret Anderson singled,
Troy Glaus doubled him home, and Spiezio followed with a two-home
run home run that made it 5-1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
