r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-     04-09 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILL, ERSTAD DELIVER FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Going into the season, two of the Angels' biggest
question marks were Ken Hill and Darin Erstad. So far, Hill and
Erstad have been more like exclamation points.
</P>
<P>
   Hill and Erstad continued their early-season successes Saturday
night, helping the Angels to a 7-5 victory over the Boston Red Sox
before 27,369 at Edison Field. It was the Angels' third win in a
row, and put them in a tie for first in the A.L. West with the
Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   Significant because the Angels haven't had a share of the top
spot in the division since last April 17. At 3-2, it's the first
time the Angels have been over .500 since last April 16 (6-5).
</P>
<P>
   The Angels survived a late-inning rally by the Red Sox against
the Angels bullpen, but Troy Percival pitched the ninth for his
first save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've made a statement to the league,'' Percival said.
``We've shown we're not going to be pushovers. We're going to play
hard for nine innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they felt the same way last season before the
injuries hit. Shortstop Gary DiSarcina, who missed half of last
season with a broken bone in his forearm, had to leave Saturday's
game after the seventh inning with a bruised left thumb. He
sustained the injury knocking down a smash by Nomar Garciaparra in
the second inning. Angels manager Mike Scioscia said DiSarcina will
not start today.
</P>
<P>
   What has made Hill a question mark for the Angels is his
arthritic right elbow. But Hill's performances in his first two
starts have shown his elbow is fine for now.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, he gave up one run and two hits in six innings while
making 98 pitches. He struggled a little with his control, walking
five. But otherwise controlled the game, using his splitter
effectively.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his opening-night start against the Yankees, Hill
(1-1) has given up three runs and six hits in 11 1/3 innings (2.38
ERA).
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple of years, my biggest problem has been locating
pitches,'' Hill said. ``But when my arm's healthy I'm able to do
it. Now I'm healthy -- knock on wood.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Erstad was a question mark because he had struggled
miserably since making the All-Star team in 1998. Last season he
hit only .253, after hitting .299 and .296 in his first two full
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Erstad went 3 for 5 to raise his batting average to a
league-leading .583 (14 for 24). He singled twice, doubled, drove
in a run and scored another.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad led off the bottom of the first with a single, the fourth
time in five games he's led off the game for the Angels with a hit.
After a walk by Adam Kennedy, Mo Vaughn singled to left field to
score Erstad for a 1-0 Angels lead. Garret Anderson drove in the
second run of the inning with a fielder's choice.
</P>
<P>
   Hill took a shutout into the sixth, and got two quick outs. But
two walks, two wild pitches and a single resulted in a run.
However, he got out of the inning by getting Garciaparra on a
flyout to left with two runners on.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get a guy of Garciaparra's stature after being out there
that long in that inning showed me a lot,'' Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels increased their lead with four runs in the bottom of
the sixth, including an RBI double by Troy Glaus, and a two-run
homer by Scott Spiezio, his first as an Angel. Erstad doubled in
the fourth run of the inning for a 6-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox scored two runs in the seventh off the Angels
bullpen, but it could have been worse. Kent Mercker and Shigetoshi
Hasegawa combined to walk three and give up two hits, but Hasegawa
got out of it by getting Nixon to hit into an inning-ending double
play with the bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox added two more runs off Mark Petkovsek in the eighth
on a couple of two-out hits -- Everett's RBI double and Jason
Varitek's RBI single. But Lou Pote came in and struck out Jeff Frye
on three pitches to end the inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
