<HEADER>
A1469 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LAKERS-MELEE-2Takes-L     04-09 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAKERS-MELEE-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TICKET SALE POSTPONED AFTER MELEE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Detailed information about the new playoff ticket sale
procedure is at the bottom of the second take of this story. Note
that the new procedure will start next weekend when the sales
suspension is lifted.) 
(This story is moving in the ``a'' national news file, the ``s''
sports news file and in the ``n'' California news file.) 
By JENNIFER HAMM  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Playoff fever broke into a cold sweat when a melee
erupted among 1,500 excited Lakers fans at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of police in riot gear were called to the center Saturday
to calm a crowd that became hysterical after the ticket sales
process turned chaotic. Police and Staples Center officials decided
selling tickets could make the unruly crowd dangerous, and sales
were suspended throughout the Los Angeles area.
</P>
<P>
   One man was arrested and dozens of people suffered cuts and
scrapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the ground getting trampled,'' said Glendale resident
Joe Briones, 18, who arrived at Staples Center before dawn.
``People were getting crushed. I was moving and my feet weren't
even on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials announced sales will resume next Sunday at 10 a.m.
with a new procedure to guarantee order.
</P>
<P>
   Staples Center president Timothy J. Leiweke took no
responsibility for the problems Saturday, saying only that the
arena was supporting the Lakers' efforts to eliminate brokers from
hoarding playoff tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret that these efforts caused an inconvenience for the
fans,'' Leiweke said in a statement. ``However, we will continue to
have zero tolerance for ticket brokers and their ability to profit
from faithful fans.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers declined to comment Saturday, noting it is Staples
Center that is selling the playoff tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday wasn't the first time Staples Center has had difficulty
accommodating customers since its opening. Another ticket-line
snafu delayed opening night in the fall; slow ticket distribution
at the will-call office kept the Bruce Springsteen and the E Street
Band concert off the stage for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The one-week Lakers ticket delay enraged fans eager to watch the
team, which has the NBA's top record, pursue its best shot at a
national title in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers fans, many of whom waited overnight for tickets that
included every round, blamed Staples Center officials, saying not
enough was done to keep the crowd organized and calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made it total chaos,'' said Danny Johnson, 38, of
Palmdale.
</P>
<P>
   Staples Center officials spent most of the day assessing what
went wrong and how to make next weekend go smoother.
</P>
<P>
   Problems began to develop early Saturday as Lakers fans lined up
along the perimeter of the parking lot, waiting to get a hand
stamp. The stamp would entitle them to receive a ticket with a
random number that would determine their place in line.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said that hours before tickets were set to go on sale,
two Staples Center officials announced from the center of the
parking lot that everyone in line should come to them to receive a
stamp.
</P>
<P>
   That triggered a mob rush as eager fans pushed and clawed their
way to receive the stamp, the witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   The witnesses said an attempt to distribute the random-number
tickets angered the crowd even more when an official threw the
tickets up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   There was another frenzy as fans dove for the small pieces of
paper, leaving many with cuts and scrapes on their arms and legs.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Police Department officers were called in to calm
the crowd. Some 40 officers in riot gear marched in and formed
lines in front of the Staples Center entrance, said Sgt. Dave
Nunez.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Staples Center didn't have the ticket sales in an orderly
manner,'' said Nunez. ``We came to restore the peace ... because
the crowd was so disorderly.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most fans formed an orderly line that stretched around
the side of the arena, a large group of unruly fans at the front of
the line demanded to know how tickets would be sold.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd began chanting ``We want tickets'' and ``Staples
Center sucks'' when it was announced ticket sales would be delayed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very upset. It's an injustice,'' said Denise Hall, 41, of
Los Angeles. ``You get down here and you can't purchase tickets.
It's outrageous.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &LR; Hall had promised her two sons that she would get them playoff
tickets. She woke up at 5 a.m. to go to Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Just after 10 a.m., police instructed the crowd to leave but
many remained until baton-wielding officers marched toward them.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles radio reporter Eoin Montemayor of KLAC was hit by a
baton, struck back at officers and was cited at the scene on
suspicion of battery on an officer, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the problem at Staples Center, thousands of Lakers
fans throughout Southern California were turned away from ticket
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   The ticket sale system was aimed at giving everyone an equal
chance of getting seats for the playoffs, Staples Center officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers fans at Staples Center said they have bought playoff
tickets in an orderly manner for years at the Great Western Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the Forum, there has never been a problem,'' said Allan
Ansdell of Anaheim, who buys playoff tickets every year. ``(The
Staples Center) should have expected it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, who won 30 of their past 31 games prior to Saturday
night's game against the defending champion San Antonio Spurs, will
open the postseason on either April 22 or 23 at home.
</P>
<P>
   New playoff sale procedure
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday
</P>
<P>
   6 a.m.: Fans permitted to line to receive wristband.
</P>
<P>
   7 a.m. to 10 a.m.: Distribution of 500 numbered wristbands.
Those receiving wristbands are not guaranteed a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Notable: Names taken to verify information at time of ticket
purchase. Wristbands can be removed only by Staples Center employee
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday
</P>
<P>
   8 a.m.: Parking lot (Num)2 at Staples Center opens for fans
wearing wristbands.
</P>
<P>
   9 a.m.: A random number between 1-500 will be selected to
determine the wristband number of the person designated as first in
line. Everyone else will then take their position in line behind
the first person chosen.
</P>
<P>
   10 a.m.: Playoff tickets go on sale at Staples Center box
office, TicketMaster locations and TicketMaster charge-by-phone.
</P>
<P>
   Notable: No guests allowed to stand in line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
