<SLUG> BC-SENIOR-WORK-0410-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Limits no more
 &HT;    By Stephanie Allmon
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Before they step up to the counter to order their
chicken sandwiches and french fries, customers at Chick-fil-A are
greeted by Ethel Beard's warm smile and kind words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, welcome to Chick-Fil-A. How are you today?'' she says
as restaurant patrons walk in the double glass doors.
</P>
<P>
   The 63-year-old woman, whom employees and regular customers
affectionately call, ``Miss Ethel,'' has worked as the restaurant's
hostess for almost three years. She says that unlike most folks her
age, who look forward to retiring and kicking up their feet, she'd
rather be busy on hers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not a house person,'' she said. In fact, she plans to
work five to 10 more years.
</P>
<P>
   The money she earns working full time helps her live more
comfortably than relying solely on Social Security or disability,
which she started receiving after suffering three strokes, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Seniors like Beard who want to work past age 65 will no longer
face a reduction in Social Security benefits, thanks to a new law
that President Clinton signed Friday. The law, approved unanimously
in both houses of Congress, eliminates the earnings test for
working seniors between the ages of 65 and 69, retroactively to
Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Social Security earnings test was designed to discourage
older Americans from continuing to work by reducing their benefits
as they earned more. Under the policy, the roughly 800,000 people
ages 65-69 who worked and received Social Security benefits saw
their benefits cut $1 for every $3 they earned above $17,000;
benefits were reduced to zero if they earned more than about
$52,595.
</P>
<P>
   Those seniors whose benefits were withheld under the earnings
test will receive them in next month's Social Security checks.
</P>
<P>
   Eliminating the earnings test will not only benefit seniors who
want to work, but also the employers who hire them.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Swift, project director for the AARP Foundation/Senior
Community Service Employment Program, said lifting the penalty
should increase the pool of qualified job applicants for employers
because it will encourage more seniors to apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it should certainly provide more experienced workers
to the marketplace and perhaps help businesses in filling some
vacancies they have in the labor market that they have currently,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The AARP employment program helps seniors find jobs and leads
employers to seniors looking for jobs. Swift said she expects to
see more people in her office, enticed by the fact that they no
longer have to watch what they earn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most (seniors who want to work) have been reluctant to take
full-time positions or approach it if it's going to put them over
(the earnings limit),'' she said. ``For a lot of people it's really
going to make it easier because for many of them, Social Security
isn't an amount they can live on comfortably.''
</P>
<P>
   And a lot of folks just aren't ready to r
</P>
</TEXT>
