<HEADER>
A1500 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-MANDOLIN-MAKER0410-CO     04-09 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MANDOLIN-MAKER0410-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mandolin maker has spare time on a happy note
 &HT;    By Bill Osinski
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JEFFERSON, Ga. _ First thing in the morning, Tony Ianuario has a
chat with his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Shall we do some crafty woodworking today? Shall we make music?
Shall we be scientific? Or artistic?
</P>
<P>
   Frequently, he and his hands can't pick a single discipline for
the day. So, they decide to do them all by building mandolins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a fascinating thing to get a note from a piece of
wood,'' said Ianuario.
</P>
<P>
   On weekdays, Ianuario is an engineer, working as a county
utilities inspector. All other times, he and his hands are doing
something around the Victorian house he restored in Jefferson,
where he lives with his wife, Ann.
</P>
<P>
   Ianuario has been making mandolins for only about seven years.
But his instruments are good enough to have been picked by none
other than the late bluegrass music legend Bill Monroe. Also,
Ianuario has caught the eye of Colorado-based photographer Jack
Jacobson, who spent more than two years traveling the country
photographing musical instrument makers for his recently published
book, ``Heart &AMP; Hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Ianuario is one of 18 Georgia artisans among the approximately
250 Jacobson photographed during the project. The Smithsonian
Institution is sponsoring a traveling exhibit of Jacobson's works,
and the first stop is the Georgia Mountains History Museum in
Gainesville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   For most of his life, Ianuario has been aware he has the gift of
being able to visualize something and then just make it with his
hands.
</P>
<P>
   He still isn't totally sure how he came to focus his skills on
the mandolin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just had the passion of wanting to build a fine instrument
for myself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, it could have been in his genes all along. He recently
learned that his paternal grandfather brought a mandolin with him
when he left his native Italy to come to America.
</P>
<P>
   What Ianuario does know is he's always enjoyed old-style country
music. After dabbling with playing and restoring guitars and
fiddles, he was captivated by the beauty of the shape and sound of
the mandolin.
</P>
<P>
   It is perhaps the most complicated and ornate of the stringed
instruments. There are simply no flat surfaces to a mandolin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a piece of sculpture almost,'' Ann Ianuario said. ``And
Tony is an artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Ianuario starts with a single block of wood for the instrument's
top. He saws it into the basic shape, with two or three pointed
curls and a graceful scroll near the neck. Then he carves to get
the varying thicknesses he wants in different parts of the surface
and uses a series of small planes _ tools as small as an inch or 2
long _ to smooth them.
</P>
<P>
   Ianuario took the second mandolin he made to a bluegrass music
festival, where he invited Monroe to play it. After the master had
tested it, he told Ianuario that it was indeed a fine instrument,
worthy of keeping. Some of the onlookers immediately offered to buy
the mandolin Monroe had played, but Ianuario still has it.
</P>
<P>
   It takes Ianuario about four months to make a mandolin, and he
prices those he sells at $3,000 to $4,000. But making his craft
into a full-time business has never appealed much to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want people to play my instruments,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of disregard for the commercial is something that
Jacobson found over and over as he visited the artisans and
photographed them for his book.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are people who are passionate about what they do,''
Jacobson said. ``They put their hearts and their hands into what
they do. They have devoted their lives to their crafts.''
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration for the ``Heart &AMP; Hands'' project came from
Jacobson's youth, when his clarinet teacher, Glen Johnston, allowed
him to join jam sessions of the musicians who came to Johnston's
instrument repair shop. Jacobson made a documentary film about
Johnston, ``The Mouthpiece Man.''
</P>
<P>
   About four years ago, Jacobson decided to seek out more
instrument makers. He spent about two years and put about 90,000
miles on his car as he journeyed to make the photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all the instrument makers he photographed are people who
receive little recognition and minimal financial rewards, for all
their highly refined skills, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are unsung heroes of our country,'' he said.
``It's extremely important that we honor them as the national
treasures that they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
