<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Monday, April 10:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-WARRIORS (Suan Phum, Thailand) _ Between them, the
12-year-old twins command 400,000 invisible soldiers. If anybody
shoots at them, the bullets just bounce off. And they can kill
their enemies simply by pointing a rifle at the ground and
concentrating really hard. It sounds like the fantasy of a million
schoolboys. But it is a belief that has led grown men into battle
behind the two child warriors who lead a ragged ethnic insurgency
called God's Army, just across the border in Myanmar, the former
Burma. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   SKOREA-LIVESTOCK-VIRUS (Kumpari, South Korea) _ An infectious
outbreak in South Korea has taken on all the seriousness of a
national emergency. The threat that has gripped South Korea is
foot-and-mouth disease, one of the most destructive cattle diseases
known. And with critical national elections set for this week, the
government has pulled out all the stops to limit the damage _ not
only to agriculture, but to its political support as well. By
Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   PERU-ELECTION (Lima, Peru) _ Peru votes in a presidential
election after a campaign marred by dirty tricks. By Clifford
Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   GREECE-ELECTION (Athens, Greece) _ Greece votes in national
elections. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PEACE-TALKS (Washington) _ Prime Minister Ehud Barak will
visit Washington to meet with President Clinton this week in an
effort to push forward peace talks with the Palestinians. By
Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAV-TRIBUNAL (The Hague, Netherlands) _ The international
tribunal for the Yugoslav war completes an extraordinary month:
opening the first trial to focus on sexual violence and another for
a general held responsible for one of Europe's worst massacres
since World War II. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-RAPE (Mexicali, Mexico) _ The case of a 14-year-old girl
who was raped and, though abortion is legal in her state in such
cases, finally abandoned the idea after weeks of confrontations
with senior state authorities. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Washington) _ Developments in the Elian Gonzalez
case.
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY-EXILES (Miami) _ ``Libertad.'' The word lords over
Elian Gonzalez's house in Little Havana. It is the first word that
rolls off people's tongues as they try to answer the questions so
many outside the Cuban community have been asking. Why so much
outrage? Why so much consternation over the fate of a little boy
whom most of them have never met? Why keep a boy from his father?
By Lizette Alvarez.
</P>
<P>
   RAMPAGE-KILLERS-II (Undated) _ Shots explode at a school in
Oregon or a brokerage office in Atlanta, and the nation is witness
to a sudden violent rampage. The killers' neighbors and families
submit to interviews, and inevitably, they say: ``He just
snapped.'' But the killers do not ``just snap.'' An examination by
The New York Times of 100 rampage murders found that most of the
killers spiraled down a long slow slide, mentally and emotionally.
Most of them left a road map of red flags. But in case after case,
the warning signs were missed. Second of four parts. By Laurie
Goodstein and William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   TOBACCO-LAWSUIT (Undated) _ The Miami smoking lawsuit shows how
hooked the states have become in keeping the tobacco industry
alive. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-MARIJUANA (Las Vegas) _ On the first-ever science
conference to gather together all that is known about the medical
uses of marijuana. By Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
