<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000409.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1516 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-IRS10-COX     04-09 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRS10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UNLOVED TAX AGENCY PUTS ON A SMILE, BUT STILL MAKES GOOFS
 &HT;    With IRS-DATA.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Tax attorney Daren Larsen recently represented a
prosperous professional who owed the Internal Revenue Service more
than $100,000 dating back to his younger, wilder years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's single, makes $10-12 grand a month and has few
expenses,'' said Larsen, who works in Camarillo, Calif. ``The IRS
guys should be salivating over a guy like this.''
</P>
<P>
   But they weren't. To her client's delight, the IRS concluded
that he could not pay the total within the prescribed three-year
period, so they dropped the case. His tax debt was reclassified as
uncollectible.
</P>
<P>
   Larsen, who worked at the IRS for 13 years, was amazed. ``They
could have garnisheed his pay, but they didn't,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the kinder, gentler IRS, two years after passage of
the most sweeping reform in half a century.
</P>
<P>
   The reform act provided new taxpayer rights, an independent
overseer board and the establishment of a separate IRS taxpayer
advocate office.
</P>
<P>
   The agency now seizes property only rarely, audits a declining
percentage of returns, and teaches more of its employees to have
cheerful telephone voices and to refer to taxpayers as ``our
customers.''
</P>
<P>
   It also collected $2 billion less in delinquent taxes last year
than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these results will be examined at a House Government
Reform subcommittee hearing Monday and at a three-day House
Republican tax reform ``summit'' starting Tuesday, during the week
that taxpayers are filling in the last lines of their 1040 forms
for the April 17 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   So far, reviews of the IRS overhaul have been mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give them about a B,'' said Rep. Rob Portman, R-Ohio, chief
House sponsor of the reform act, whose chief goal was more
protection for taxpayers. ``We're still on track to get a new IRS,
but we're not there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, the agency has a huge backlog of requests under the
new ``innocent spouse'' rules. As of last fall, the agency had
41,000 claims for relief from taxes incurred by former spouses.
</P>
<P>
   As for the decline in collection of back taxes, Portman said
that is not the fault of reform. ``There is no inconsistency in
better service and compliance,'' he said. ``They work together.
That's the challenge over the next couple of years.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Taxpayers Union, a private watchdog group, gives
the IRS some credit for progress. Spokesman Pete Sepp said the
group's grade for the IRS has moved from F to C-minus. Complaints
to his group about abusive tax agents have dropped by at least
half, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, bureaucratic mistakes continue to plague the IRS and
its ``customers.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Huffine, an Atlanta cellular phone consultant, was trying
to buy a house early last year when a credit check discovered that,
unknown to him, the IRS had filed a lien against him for unpaid
taxes dating back to 1987.
</P>
<P>
   A flurry of telephone calls and letters over the next 15 months
produced contradictory information. During one call to an IRS
toll-free number, he was told the lien had been removed. Next, he
was told that the $3,868 debt was still on his record and that he
also owed $6,673 in interest and penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Huffine said the IRS had not notified him of the mounting debt.
In fact, the IRS had sent him three tax refunds. ``Impossible,''
one IRS representative told him. Yet the next day, Huffine found
another refund check in his mail.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantan has now paid the original bill, but he is fighting
the rest of the charges in the newly strengthened IRS office of the
national taxpayer advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Such mix-ups are plentiful in the IRS's bureaucratic maze of
100,000 far-flung employees and a 1960s computer system that dates
to the Jurassic era of data processing.
</P>
<P>
   A recent audit by the U.S. General Accounting Office, the
investigating arm of Congress, found that it sometimes took as long
as 10 years to record a taxpayer's payments. On the other hand, the
IRS sent a $15,000 refund to a person who owed $350,000 in back
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   IRS Commissioner Charles O. Rossotti has been quick to
acknowledge such problems.
</P>
<P>
   In candid testimony last month to a Senate committee, he
conceded that ``we are not yet meeting the legitimate service
expectations for the vast majority of compliant taxpayers who
voluntarily pay their taxes, while compliance activity, such as
examination coverage and collection enforcement activity, is
dropping rapidly, thus potentially undermining the fairness of the
whole tax system.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti blames the problems on cuts in IRS personnel dating
back to 1993, the shift of enforcement staff to taxpayer assistance
work, and the outmoded computer system, which will take an
estimated eight more years to replace. He is asking Congress for as
many as 10,000 new workers for the agency.
</P>
<P>
   His frankness has won praise.
</P>
<P>
   However, Portman and others worry that Rossotti's reforms may
not become permanent, especially since an independent board of
overseers, a key element of the 1998 act, is still not activated.
President Clinton was more than a year late in finalizing the
board's nominees, and confirmation has hit a snag in the Senate
over an unrelated dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics of the IRS question how much progress Rossotti can
make under the current tax law.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a courageous, thoughtful man'' who has a ``sensible''
reorganization plan, said Michael J. Graetz, a Yale University law
professor and author of the book ``The Decline (and Fall?) of the
Income Tax.''
</P>
<P>
   But Graetz added that the problem lies with the 2,840-page tax
code and its 46,000 pages of rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that you are going to completely restructure the IRS
without changing the basic tax law that they've got to administer
is like thinking you can turn a Winnebago around without taking it
out of the garage. It just can't be done.''
</P>
<P>
   For more information: www.irs.gov, jec.senate.gov
</P>
<P>
   Julia Malone's e-mail address is juliam(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
