<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Friday, 04/07/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) ALBANY, New York -- April 8, 2000 --
NY-ABORTION-ANNIVERSARY -- Thirty years ago this week, New York
state legalized abortion, adopting what was the most liberal law in
the country, three years before the Supreme Court made abortion
legal nationwide. New York Senator Roy M. Goodman, who spoke
against the ``butchery'' women endured in illicit abortions in
1970. (Chang W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LOS ANGELES -- April 8, 2000 -- DEMS-CONVENTION -- The
Democratic National Convention, to be held in Los Angeles in
August, seems to be shaping up as another disaster in the making.
Fund-raising was behind schedule, the billionaire moguls who helped
lure the convention were portrayed as bickering among themselves,
and the worst police corruption scandal in decades erupted which
sent the city's public officials into a kind of collective
meltdown. Noeila Rodriguez, who is now in charge of the host
committee for the Democratic convention, at the main office in
downtown Los Angeles. (Monica Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WILLIAMSVILLE, N.Y. -- April 8, 2000 -- BUFFALO -- Once a
bustling home to 1.1 million people, Erie County, which includes
Buffalo and its suburbs, now has is now 926,000 and is shrinking
fast. Last year alone, more than 10,000 people moved away, leading
to one of the steepest population drops of any county in the
nation, according to new federal census estimates. On the
waterfront, glory had largely given way to contamination and
idleness. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) HACIENDA HEIGHTS, Calif. -- April 8, 2000 -- MEDICAL-INFO
-- A growing number of companies are adding specialized services to
help their employees navigate through the mass of medical
information available today. Beverly Fernandez was told in early
1999 that her son Dominic, now 4, needed immediate open heart
surgery and possibly a transplant. Having learned more through a
service provided by her employer, she chose to wait, and her son
did fine without a transplant. (Ed Carreon/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SEATTLE -- April 8, 2000 -- EARTH-DAY -- Summoning the
will to confront global warming is the chief goal of the
Seattle-based Earth Day Network, which says the biggest rally in
this country on April 22 will be on the Mall in Washington. Dennis
Hayes, chairman of Earth Day, who has been with the organization
from it's beginnings in 1970, sits in the Seattle headquarters with
a map showing upcoming Earth Day events. (Larry Davis/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LOS ANGELES -- April 8, 2000 -- CALIF-JANITORS-STRIKE --
Thousands of janitors in Los Angeles are on strike for higher pay
after rejecting a wage plan offered by building maintenance
companies. The strike came after janitors voted to reject a pay
plan put forward by a group of building maintenance companies that
would have offered a 50-cent raise the first year and 40-cent
raises the next two years. The workers seek a $3 increase in their
hourly pay over the next three years. (Monica Almeida/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- April 8, 2000 -- BUSH-REPUBS -- House
Republicans say they realize George W. Bush, shown with republican
senators last June, is a weaker candidate than they had hoped for.
Just as House Republicans are charting their own course, the Bush
campaign has made a tactical decision that it does not want to
march in lock step with the Republican-run Congress, trying to push
through a common legislative agenda. (Paul Hosefros/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ROZAJE, Montenegro -- April 8, 2000 --
MONTENEGRO-AFTERSHOCKS-2 -- Surrounded on all sides of it's borders
with political tension, the people of Rozaje, Montenegro find not
only that they have received little thanks for their open-armed
welcome of Kosovo Albanians as NATO bombed Yugoslavia, but they
feel battered, financially poorer and still trapped by the
pressures of war. Vasvija Muric wonders what happened to her
husband, Dervis, a Montenegrin Muslim taxi driver who went on an
errand into Kosovo in July, 1999, with a friend. Both men vanished
without a trace and are feared dead. (Andrew Testa/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ROZAJE, Montenegro -- April 8, 2000 --
MONTENEGRO-AFTERSHOCKS-1 -- Surrounded on all sides of it's borders
with political tension, the people of Rozaje, Montenegro find not
only that they have received little thanks for their open-armed
welcome of Kosovo Albanians as NATO bombed Yugoslavia, but they
feel battered, financially poorer and still trapped by the
pressures of war. Elsana Nurkovic, a Rozaje resident, stands next
to a photograph of her father, who disappeared in Kosovo and is
feared dead. (Andrew Testa/The New York Times)
</P>
