<DOCNO> NYT20000409.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 16:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1551 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-DA-BRAT-INTERVIEW0410     04-09 1533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DA-BRAT-INTERVIEW0410-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rapper Shawntae Harris refuses to be neatly defined. She's
everything you've heard. And more.
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Well aware that this is a story for the newspaper,
rapper Da Brat doesn't present herself as the character who's
brazen enough to mix drinks and offer marijuana to hip-hop magazine
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   We're backstage at the American Airlines Arena, an hour before
she takes the stage as opening act for good friend and pop star
Mariah Carey. The performer born Shawntae Harris is calm, cool and
_ with the help of probably too many Advils _ relaxed on a brown
leather sofa.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes before, her wild side got a warm-up in a conversation
with the music video request channel, The Box.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching y'all the other day when you were doing your
`Bad Girls' (segment),'' she told one of the executives, a smile
spreading across her face. ``Watched the whole thing. Even
requested something, I think. Then it got to the end _ no Brat! I
was like, `Where's my (stuff) man?' I'm going to have to (mess)
y'all up!''
</P>
<P>
   But now she's sitting down for her first interview since being
charged with battery March 7 for a fight in an Atlanta club. And
while the endearing performer is still smiling, she's speaking in a
measured whisper quite unlike her fast-paced, slightly nasal, rap
style.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey guuuuys,'' she asks the two people she introduces as her
sister and brother, assistant Tina Spence and protege Twenty II.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you keep it down a little bit so I can do this?''
</P>
<P>
   Not the demeanor you'd expected from someone accused of beating
another woman in the face.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't take long to realize there are many sides to Da
Brat.
</P>
<P>
   Harris grew up in two Chicago homes. One was what she calls the
``sanctified, sanctified, oh so sanctified'' Pentecostal household
of her mother and grandmother. There, she had to wear skirts that
hung past her knees. ``Granny'' sent ``Shawnie'' to church Sunday,
Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday, where she played the drums and sang
in the choir. And if Harris wanted to have music by then-favorite
rappers LL Cool J or Monie Love, she had to write a gospel artists'
name on the spine of the cassette cover.
</P>
<P>
   But at her father and his mom's house (her parents never
married), the only child known as ``Boo-Boo'' recalls, ``I could
cuss when I want to, listen to whatever I wanted to and beat up
whoever my cousins told me to.''
</P>
<P>
   So being both ``Shawnie'' of the once-sanctified household and
the ``Boo Boo'' who shares matching tattoos with her dad is how
Harris has lived all of her 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   She turns 26 Friday, ending what what will certainly be a
whirlwind week. Her third album, ``Unrestricted,'' comes out
Tuesday. And two days later she's due in Atlanta Municipal Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm maintaining my innocence,'' is all Harris offers,
specifically, about the incident that landed her in front of the
law.
</P>
<P>
   According to the police report, that late Tuesday night she
ordered an aspiring rapper named Reszue Robateue to get off the
railing near the Chilli Pepper's VIP lounge, where Harris was
sitting. Robateue refused and the two began to fight. Witnesses
said Harris hit Robateue with either a gun or a shot glass. In the
end, Robateue was charged with a misdemeanor while Harris was
charged with felony aggravated battery because of the seriousness
of the injuries to Robateue's forehead and eye.
</P>
<P>
   Police initially thought a shooting five nights later in front
of Harris's Atlanta townhome was payback for the fight. Since then
officials have said it was drug-related and meant for someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Which was neither good nor bad news to Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really thought about it,'' she says. When gunfire
erupted outside her place, she was in Mexico shooting a video for
the sexually suggestive single ``What `Chu Like.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't bother me because I was in Cancun,'' she says.
``Working, not bothering anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   But less then a week later, Harris' family moved her out of the
gated community, where monthly rent ranges from $800-$2,000. She
wasn't asked to leave, she says, and doesn't feel comfortable
revealing where her new place is.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family just wanted to get me out of there,'' Harris says.
Then she narrows her big almond eyes into a splinter, and shakes
her neatly braided head: ``They don't play when it comes to me.''
</P>
<P>
   RAPS TO HER OWN BEAT
</P>
<P>
   When she made her entrance at the Ocean Boulevard offices of
cable channel The Box earlier that afternoon, she took a limo _
even though the $700-a-night hotel she's staying in is yards away.
</P>
<P>
   But hey, she's a star.
</P>
<P>
   And yet she treats everyone waiting for her like a longtime
member of her constellation.
</P>
<P>
   A Box employee approaches Harris: ``Hello Brat, I met you. . .
''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the Jagged Edge party a couple weeks ago,'' she says, not
missing a beat. He holds his hand out; She greets him with a big
hug. As he returns it, one arm slightly lifts up Harris' white
T-shirt to reveal an unlikely undergarment: White, puffy,
cartoon-stamped boxer shorts. At 5-foot 4, the rapper's 140-pound
frame is still conditioned years after playing basketball and
running track at Chicago's Kenwood Academy.
</P>
<P>
   She wears her favorite designer jeans, Girbaud, backwards; a nod
to Atlanta rap duo Kris Kross's early '90s style. The two
introduced Harris to their producer, Jermaine Dupri, who signed her
to Atlanta-based So So Def Records. He was, he remembers, impressed
with her immediately.
</P>
<P>
   ``She rapped with so much confidence,'' says Dupri, ``and she
wasn't scared to say whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   When Harris' first album, ``Funkdafied,'' came out in 1994,
female rappers like Queen Latifah, Salt-N-Pepa and Yo Yo played up
their femininity. Their lyrical focus was often on the pluses and
minuses of being women (sometimes to the detriment of the
accompanying track). And while they were respected, they still had
a hard time generating sales in what has traditionally been a
male-dominated genre.
</P>
<P>
   Harris came on the scene with the same braided hairstyle that
Kris Kross and Dupri wore. She just had colored barrettes on hers.
Clothes? Same thing. Baggy shirts and jeans, worn backwards. And
her debut embraced the more musical, band-oriented R&AMP;B of the '70s
era when the Isley Brothers and Parliament-Funkadelic flourished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brat was the kind of girl guys could feel comfortable
around,'' says Chris Smith of Kris Kross. And obviously more than a
few felt comfortable buying her music. ``Funkdafied'' was the first
album by a solo female rapper to sell a million copies.
</P>
<P>
   Its 1996 follow-up, ``Anuthatantrum,'' sold half as many, but
her hip-hop profile has only risen. Guest appearances on hit
records by pop singer Mariah Carey (``Always Be My Baby,''
``Heartbreaker'' remixes), R&AMP;B quartet Dru Hill (``In My Bed''
remix) and fellow rappers Lil' Kim, Missy ``Misdemeanor'' Elliott,
Lisa ``Left-Eye'' Lopes and Angie Martinez (the Grammy-nominated
``Not Tonight'') have kept her in the public ear, and eye, during
the four years between her own releases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which is the master plan right now,'' she spouts at the three
cameramen in the Box. ``To keep Da Brat-tat-tat-tat in y'alls face
all the (expletive) time! Shocking people! ''
</P>
<P>
   That may mean getting out of her still-preferred tomboy gear and
putting on a tight-fitting jumpsuit every once in a while, which
she did on last year's Soul Train Awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's cool, I don't mind showing a little skin,'' she
adds, citing her generous backside and other assets (``32-Bs or
32-Cs,'' she says, ``depending on the cut of the bra). ``I'm not
all cellulited or keloided up underneath here.''
</P>
<P>
   Wanting to ``stay in people's faces'' may also mean she'll have
to take her 6-foot-4 inch, 225-pound bodyguard with her when the
urge for Gladys Knight's Chicken and Waffles hits. (The same
bodyguard, mind you, who had three auditions for the imposing
Michael Clarke Duncan's role in the movie ``The Green Mile.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``But that makes a lot of sense to me because when stars like
her are out, people are always at them for something,'' says radio
personality Ryan Cameron, one of Harris's friends. ``I see it all
the time. She needs security. I mean she's young, enjoying life, so
she's going to be out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Literally and figuratively.
</P>
<P>
   All you have to do is pick up the May issue of hip-hop magazine
XXL to see that. In it, she goes so far as to detail exactly how to
drive a man wild at, shall we say, that critical moment.
</P>
<P>
   But talking that way to a mainstream audience is another matter
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the people who are going to read this will probably
only pick it up because they heard about that mess last month,''
she says on the sofa, still waiting for the Advil to kick in. ``And
I want them to know I'm not a violent person... I'm not stupid. I
know there's a time and place for everything. A time for playing,
cursing and acting silly, because that's me too. And a time to act
like I have the sense my family gave me.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly Granny.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
