<DOCNO> NYT20000409.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 16:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1553 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INTERNET-DYSON-ART-11     04-09 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-DYSON-ART-1175(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNING IN CYBERSPACE, DYSON IS NO POLITICIAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Esther Dyson was presiding over the most recent meeting of
Icann, the controversial international group that is trying to
create the Internet's first democracy. While she sat on a stage
facing an audience of several hundred, her frustration and
impatience grew increasingly apparent, as people filed to a
microphone in the aisle to voice their complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Many opposed the interim board's proposal to elect permanent
members through an indirect process. But Dyson, the interim
chairwoman, defended the policy of using an electoral council
instead of letting the world's Internet users vote directly for
their board representatives. That was the best way, she told the
group, to prevent the nomination of ``people who are stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, after seeing her remark on The New York Times Web
page, Dyson took exception. ``Out of context,'' she said. ``I might
have said it, but it was out of context.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever her intention, the remark put Dyson directly at odds
with some of the same civil liberties groups that have long been
among her staunchest supporters. And the incident last month in
Cairo, Egypt, made clear that despite her unofficial titles of
doyenne of cyberspace and queen of the digerati, a politician is
one thing that Dyson is not.
</P>
<P>
   It has been nearly two years since Dyson was chosen to be
interim head of Icann _ Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and
Numbers _ with the mandate of leading the Clinton administration's
effort to move oversight of the network from federal contractors to
the international Internet community.
</P>
<P>
   But she has ruled Icann's fractious public meetings with a mix
of impatience, frustration and condescension. And the paucity of
diplomacy, some Internet executives say, has played a role in
Icann's rocky start. Among the missteps, two of the group's
earliest decisions _ to hold closed meetings and to levy a $1 tax
on Internet addresses _ were later rescinded under pressure from
the administration and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that what you see sometimes is that she doesn't quite
have the common touch,'' said Mike Godwin, a lawyer who worked with
Dyson in the early 1990s at the Electronic Frontier Foundation, a
public interest group devoted to the defense of free speech and
civil rights on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that there is a dimension of being a political being
that involves going out and getting hands on and dealing with
individuals,'' said Godwin, who is now senior legal editor of
E-Commerce Law Weekly, a print publication. ``I don't think she is
terribly comfortable with that. I think she is democratic in
principle but not entirely democratic in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week at her cluttered office in New York,
on a rare day when she was not traveling, Dyson defended her
leadership style. ``I don't have a tolerance for having my time
wasted; I'm straightforward,'' she said. ``It's not a question of
intelligence; it's a question of appropriateness.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, most who know Esther Dyson say she does not suffer fools
gladly. But she was picked to head Icann not for her tact but
because of her international reputation for independence, integrity
and straightforward manner.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 foot 3 and 47 years of age, Dyson is a wiry, almost elfin
figure, with seeming disregard for the trappings of makeup and
fashion. She keeps her hair short and simply cut. She scurries
around her office and official meetings wearing socks without
shoes. And she often wears faded blue jeans, typically accompanied
by an oversized T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of the renowned physicist Freeman Dyson, she is
described by another Electronic Frontier Foundation colleague, John
Gilmore, as having ``formidable intelligence.'' But Dyson's fast
mind can manifest itself in ways that may come across as dismissive
and condescending.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is not a people person,'' said Jerry Michalski. For five
years, Michalski wrote Release 1.0, the influential technology
newsletter that Dyson's company, EDventure holdings, publishes
monthly. Michalski left about two years ago to become a freelance
consultant and speaker, a decision made in part, he explained, by
the emotional wall that he said she kept between them.
</P>
<P>
   ``She likes humans,'' he said. ``She just doesn't do small talk.
If you hang out with her, it feels awkward. If you start talking
about feelings, she will turn around and leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever her interpersonal skills, over the last 20 years Dyson
has cultivated long-standing relationships with a wide circle of
some of the most influential people in the computer and Internet
industries.
</P>
<P>
   A graduate of Harvard with a bachelor's degree in economics,
Dyson began her career in the computer world in the 1970s, covering
the budding industry as a reporter for Forbes magazine. From there
she moved to Wall Street as an analyst.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982 she formed her venture capital firm after buying a
computer industry newsletter that she renamed Release 1.0. With
that newsletter came a related annual conference, which she has
parlayed into an invitation-only event, called PC Forum, that the
industry's top executives and digerati are afraid to miss _ even at
a registration fee of $4,500.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson is also on the board of numerous companies and nonprofit
groups around the world and has become a mainstay at Internet
conferences and policy panels. And she has positioned herself as a
well-paid, highly sought speaker.
</P>
<P>
   As former chairman, and now vice chairman, of the Electronic
Frontier Foundation, she espoused some of the earliest predictions
about the complex challenges the Internet would pose for
intellectual property and privacy. And she has served on special
federal commissions on intellectual property, privacy and
encryption.
</P>
<P>
   In her role as a civil libertarian, however, Dyson is more of an
observer, a thinker, than an activist, according to people who know
her well, who say she seems more comfortable with identifying tough
issues than taking on the hard fight to resolve them.
</P>
<P>
   And certainly that limitation drew criticism to her 1997 book,
``Release 2.0: A Design for Living in the Digital Age,'' which some
critics derided as a naive collection of only sometimes interesting
observations.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Lambert, reviewing the book for Business Week, said
Dyson ``glosses over the obstacles that lie in the way'' of
achieving the ``electronic Utopia she foresees.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when Dyson talks, people in the digital world listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Esther starts talking about something, and you don't know
why, you better start paying attention,'' said Miljenko Horvak, a
former Citibank executive who is involved in several Eastern
European start-up companies with Dyson. For instance, Horvak said,
Dyson started talking about online privacy five years ago, well
before it became a cause celebre.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this thing that I call Esther's orbit,'' Horvak said.
``She, by the gravitational pull of her personality and her person
get all of these different kinds of people to be in orbit around
her.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And that ``pull,'' Horvak says, does not involve charisma or
charm. But finding someone to say anything more critical for public
attribution is nearly impossible. ``Can we go off the record?'' is
the first thing many people said when asked to comment for this
article.
</P>
<P>
   As one acquaintance put it: ``People are afraid to say bad
things about Esther. Not because she is not a nice person, or out
of fear of retribution from her, but because they think it will
cast negatively on them.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent Icann controversy is the issue of electing half
of the 18-member board. Originally the voting was to be complete by
the end of this September, but it is now not expected to be
finished until sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as some blame Dyson for not being a better leader and
problem solver, many give her credit for dedicating the time
necessary to keep the very fragile Icann experiment from blowing up
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Cochetti, who as a policy executive with IBM helped select
Dyson as Icann's interim chairwoman, said the decision was not
based on the assumption that she had a unique insight into the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are probably about 1,000 people in the world who are as
insightful about the Internet as Esther,'' Cochetti said. ``People
may disagree with Esther, and they may disagree with either her
substance or her tactics, but it's rare _ if ever _ that anyone has
ever questioned her integrity,'' he said. ``She is a person who
from my experience operates from her principle. You can rely on
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before taking on the Icann duties, Dyson was spending 70
percent to 80 percent of her life on the road, attending her
different board meetings and conferences and overseeing the
personal investments she has in some 30 technology companies around
the world _ many of them obscure ventures in Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Her Icann work comes atop this heavy load. And the strain of the
group's highly contentious process shows during Icann's public
forums, which are purposely held in a different country each time _
and at which Dyson has become increasingly curt to the people who
line up at the microphones to challenge proposed policies or
question the group's procedures.
</P>
<P>
   It is because Dyson has built a career as a seeming voice for
the little guy, the individual user of digital technology, that
some people in the electronic libertarian community say they feel a
bit abandoned by Dyson in the Icann process.
</P>
<P>
   They cite an episode last fall, when a coalition of nonprofit
groups traveled to Chile for an Icann board meeting. The group
asked the board to slow its policy-making until Icann had
representation from noncommercial interests and individuals. As
critics lined up to question how Icann, for example, had arrived at
its business-backed policy for cracking down on so-called
cybersquatters, Dyson's growing irritation became evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respect,'' she told the audience, ``we are less
interested in complaints about the process'' and more interested in
``doing real work and moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   And in the case of last month's meeting in Cairo, Dyson and the
rest of the board at first resisted demands from powerful groups
like Common Cause and the Center for Democracy and Technology that
they reconsider the election plan.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, despite Dyson's ``people who are stupid'' remark,
the interim board listened and agreed to allow direct election of
the new members. But it remains unclear whether the hostilities
will dissipate and the board will again attempt to work closely
with the civil libertarians.
</P>
<P>
   Dyson admits that Icann has made mistakes. But she said she was
not sure how she might have made things work better. ``Could I have
been more forceful in raising some of things that I think were
mistakes?'' she said. ``I don't know. It might have worked and it
might have backfired.''
</P>
<P>
   And many of her critics and her supporters agree that, whatever
the shortcomings, she has credibly performed a thankless job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone could have done it any better than Esther
has,'' Godwin said. ``It's to Esther's credit that Icann hasn't
been laughed out of existence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
