<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1561 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TV-SOPRANOS-MEDIA-ART     04-09 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SOPRANOS-MEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SOPRANOS' REMAINS BOSS AT SEASON'S END
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 BY BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mob family hit ``The Sopranos,'' burdened this season with
expectations heavier than cement shoes, finished its second burst
of 13 episodes Sunday night more than ever the biggest programming
phenomenon in HBO history.
</P>
<P>
   Ratings soared for ``The Sopranos'' in its second season,
climbing more than 60 percent _ even though the show did not
attract the season-long surge of media coverage that accompanied
its first season.
</P>
<P>
   Though the ratings are important, there is something broader at
stake for HBO, a unit of Time Warner. The cable channel does not
measure the success of its series in direct income. Because it is a
subscription channel dependent on monthly revenues from subscriber
fees, the prime consideration, HBO's top executive said, is selling
people on HBO in an increasingly crowded marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about ensuring that the pool of people who get HBO
like what we do,'' said Jeffrey L. Bewkes, the HBO chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Bewkes said he expected the channel to add 1 million to 2
million homes to its subscriber list this year. ``Is that all
because of `The Sopranos'?'' he said. ``We can't say that. But it
certainly helps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the business of trying to be the most-noticed network
on television,'' Bewkes said. ``And this show is right on target
for that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   But viewers who are going to miss their weekly Sunday night
appointment with Tony and Carmela Soprano and their extended family
(now minus a few members) are in for an extra-long wait. Though HBO
has now committed to another two seasons of episodes, Season 3 will
not be on the air until next March. The first two seasons started
in January.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, said Brad Grey, one of the show's executive
producers, was to give the show's creator and lead writer, David
Chase, more time to map out where he wants his characters to go.
``We made a deal to do 26 more episodes,'' Grey said. ``This gives
David the opportunity to think two seasons out at once. We're
probably not going back into production as soon this year.''
</P>
<P>
   In the previous two years, the show started production in July.
With the extra time, production may not start until late August.
That will delay the show's introduction on the air until March.
</P>
<P>
   Avid fans may have to content themselves with repeats of the
current season, which will play on HBO again in June, Bewkes said.
Season 1 may also come back, he said, though the channel has not
decided on that yet. And HBO could always bring back this year's
episodes one more time in a weeklong marathon before the start of
Season 3 as it did with Season 1 before this year's new episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Bewkes said HBO wanted to be careful with what it considers its
prize program. For that reason, the channel has resisted releasing
the episodes from the first seasons on videocassette and most
likely will still resist. But HBO has sold ``The Sopranos'' to
networks internationally with great success, Bewkes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without giving a full list,'' he said, ``it's safe to say the
show is available in most of the countries of the world that you'd
expect: almost everywhere in Europe and much of Asia and Latin
America.''
</P>
<P>
   HBO viewers have never liked anything as much as they like ``The
Sopranos.'' Last year, it became by far the highest-rated series in
the channel's history when it averaged an 8.3 rating, or about 4.4
million viewers, in HBO homes. (Last season, about 25 million homes
received HBO.)
</P>
<P>
   This season that rating climbed to a 13.6, or about 6.5 million
viewers. (The total number of homes is now about 27 million.) Both
figures were for only the initial weekly showings on Sunday nights.
The show was repeated on Tuesdays, Wednesdays and Fridays.
</P>
<P>
   Bewkes said that when the four showings were counted together,
about 13 million viewers a week were watching ``The Sopranos,'' or
close to half the homes that subscribe to HBO.
</P>
<P>
   ``The acceptance of the second season has been as intense or
even more intense than the first season,'' Grey said. ``The numbers
are proof of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Another indication is how much in demand the stars of the show
are. After turning down numerous offers to appear in movies during
last year's hiatus in shooting, James Gandolfini, who has emerged
as one of television's biggest stars with his performance as Tony,
is currently in the cast of a film called ``The Mexican.'' His
co-stars _ Julia Roberts and Brad Pitt _ are one indication of the
stature Gandolfini has attained.
</P>
<P>
   Edie Falco, who plays Carmela, has been starring in the play
``Sideman'' in London. Michael Imperioli, who plays Tony's nephew
Christopher, and Lorraine Bracco, who plays his psychiatrist, are
also shooting movies. Dominic Chianese, Uncle Junior, has signed to
do a play with Al Pacino.
</P>
<P>
   Grey noted that all the principal cast members (the ones whose
characters are still alive after Sunday night's episode) are signed
on for the new 26-episode deal.
</P>
<P>
   As for Chase, he has signed a deal to write and direct a film,
which he may or may not start this year. At the moment, he is
treating himself to a monthlong vacation in France.
</P>
<P>
   Most series that reach this level of success after two seasons
settle in for long runs. But Bewkes said HBO was not looking past
the next two seasons at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly can see this going several more seasons,'' he
said. ``But we don't sell commercials. We're not going to continue
making the show just because we could still take in a certain
amount of advertising revenue. We won't keep it going just to keep
it going. What we're interested in is being able to make the show
at the same level of quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Grey indicated that Chase might decide that two more years is
enough. ``David is committed to stay for those 26 more. We'll see
how much more we'll do, if any, after that. It may indeed go no
further.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
