<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1562 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PATENTS-ART-NYT &LR;      04-09 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIANS TAKE A LONGER VIEW OF NET BATTLES
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV:  Graphic  is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Patent and Trademark Office has been enmeshed in
controversy of late, with critics charging that it is awarding too
many patents that cover too much ground and questioning whether its
staff truly understands the technology it is evaluating.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com's recently awarded patent for one-click online
shopping has received much attention because of its breadth. But
Amazon is by no means the leader in Internet patents.
</P>
<P>
   America Online is sitting on at least 14. In fact, in recent
months AOL has received one patent that covers customizing online
shopping for individual shoppers and another for a system that will
``search all resources on the Internet with one search command.''
Scores of other Internet-related patents quietly tumble out of the
patent office each week.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, much of the current controversy about patents,
according to historians of technology and communications, lacks a
sense of historical context. They say the patent battles looming on
the Internet horizon have historical precedent in those that arose
with other innovations in communication, including the telegraph,
telephone, radio and television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see the development of the Internet as being
significantly different from the development of other
communications technologies since the 1840s,'' said Brian Winston,
the head of the School of Communication, Design and Media at the
University of Westminster in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``The creation of the Internet falls into a pattern. It's part
of that pattern that there will always be a terrible row over
patents.''
</P>
<P>
   Patent prospecting by Internet companies has been criticized in
a wide range of forums, from anonymous one-sentence postings on
slashdot.org, a Web site for computer programmers, to a scholarly
symposium conducted by the National Academy of Sciences in
February.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of these new Internet patents, which by definition have
a software component, contend that software creation is far more
incremental than other kinds of invention.
</P>
<P>
   But Winston and many historians of technology argue that most
invention builds on existing innovation, rather than being the
result of a singular insight. Furthermore, many people are often
developing the same ideas at the same time. This phenomenon, they
say, is by no means exclusive to software _ or to the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most extreme example of simultaneous development is when
you have Alexander Graham Bell and Elisha Gray arriving at the
patent office on the same day with the idea of the telephone,''
said Winston, who is the author of ``Media Technology and Society:
A History From the Telegraph to the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray and Bell settled their differences, with Gray getting a
$100,000 settlement and lucrative contract work. But the early days
of the telephone were marked by many other patent disputes. At one
point the Bell System had 600 pending patent infringement cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general conception of invention is probably epitomized by
the image of a light bulb going off over your head,'' said Robert
Rosenberg, director of the Thomas A. Edison Papers Project, a
documentary editing project based at Rutgers University. ``But
inventions come out of other people's work, they come out of your
own work. They are almost always incremental.''
</P>
<P>
   And when social conditions and technology are both ripe,
Rosenberg said, patents become vigorously contested precisely
because they are so valuable and so many similar ideas bubble up at
the same time.
</P>
<P>
   It may also be instructive to consider the example of Samuel
F.B. Morse and his first patent.
</P>
<P>
   Morse's contribution, to use anachronistic terms, was not so
much hardware as software. Others were inventing their own versions
of the telegraph, but Morse contributed the code _ putting dots and
dashes together so that information could be transmitted
efficiently, using electricity, over the new device.
</P>
<P>
   The historical precedent that most closely parallels the
development of the Internet is the evolution of radio, according to
the historian Amy Friedlander. She has written a series of
monographs on the development of large-scale infrastructures for a
nonprofit organization created by Robert Kahn, co-inventor of the
TCP/IP protocol that is at the heart of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``A radio patent pool was finally formed in 1919,'' said
Friedlander, who is the editor of iMP, an online journal of
technology and public policy. ``One of the reasons it was formed
was there were so many patents and so much cross-licensing that
development of radio had become almost sclerotic.''
</P>
<P>
   Although patents have often served as an important spur to
invention, she said, ``the capacity of patents to stifle innovation
is not new to our times.''
</P>
<P>
   The pendulum of history, just as everywhere, has its swings at
the patent office and in the courts that interpret patent law.
</P>
<P>
   Today, in addition to coming under fire for broad patents, the
patent office is roundly criticized for issuing patents that cover
dubious inventions like the physics-defying ``hyper-light-speed
antenna'' that serves as a portal to a ``new dimension.'' In
February, a patent was issued to a Colorado inventor for just such
a device.
</P>
<P>
   But in the mid-19th century, for example, Scientific American
published diatribes arguing exactly the opposite _ that the patent
office was far too stingy about handing out patents.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also contend that the patent office is issuing a number
of bad patents because it has become so technologically backward
that it cannot distinguish true innovation from fantastic theory or
hoary precedent.
</P>
<P>
   But for as long as it has existed, the patent office has been
confronted with new technology that may initially have sounded like
science fiction. ``The lag between the skills of the patent office
and innovation has been there a long time,'' said Philip Scranton,
a Rutgers professor who specializes in the history of industry and
technology. The watershed, according to Scranton, was not the
advent of software in the 20th century, but the electrical
inventions of the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``By inspecting mechanical drawings you can at least identify
what is similar between inventions, what is different and what
might be an infringement,'' he said. ``But with electrical
inventions arrived a whole new level of engineering and
mathematical considerations.''
</P>
<P>
   The most fundamental question that critics of Internet patents
pose is whether business models like the Amazon one-click process
should be patented at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been here before,'' said Winston, who sees no problem
with business-model patents. ``There's a whole tendency to look at
new technologies as being outside of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   But others say it may be a little too early to tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are people going to look back a hundred years from now and
think that one-click ordering was a revolutionary model?'' said
Paul Ceruzzi, a historian at the Smithsonian Institution's National
Air and Space Museum and the author of ``A History of Modern
Computing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know,'' he said. ``We have to wait for the dust to
settle.''
</P>
<P>
   (Patents may be viewed at www.uspto.gov on the Web or may be
ordered through the mail, by patent number, for $3 from the U.S.
Patent and Trademark Office, Washington 20231.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-00 1705EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000409.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 17:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1563 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-R-NEWS-DELIVERY-MEDIA     04-09 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NEWS-DELIVERY-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES(945)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG NEWS ON LITTLE SCREENS
</HEADLINE>
 
(REPEATING to add photo and graphics notes)  
(ATTN: R.I., Tenn. Ga., Calif.)  (ART ADV:  Photo  is being sent to NYT photo clients.  Graphic  is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 BY FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bob Egan, a technology research executive, sounds jaded when
asked to predict the future of news delivery on cellular phones and
hand-held computers. ``You are entering this story at the moment of
maximum hype,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But then there are moments like this: on Sunday, after missing
his daughter's high school softball game because of a business
trip, Egan turned on his Palm Pilot hand-held organizer on a
beachfront boardwalk in San Diego and pulled in the news of the
team's victory and the favorable reviews of his daughter's pitching
from The Woonsocket Call in Rhode Island.
</P>
<P>
   From America Online and Microsoft to Reuters and The Associated
Press to The New York Times, E.W. Scripps' Knoxville News-Sentinel
and Knight Ridder's MercuryCenter.com, news and information
organizations are bringing their wares to the diminutive screens of
portable electronic devices. The new medium is something between a
curiosity and a business, and the media groups involved, still
trying to find their financial sea legs on the Internet, are
hesitant to predict how these services will pay for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a widespread consensus that consumers will develop
a taste for getting up-to-the-minute data on traffic and movies and
sports and even news while they are on the go. ``The value here is
that people are going to be able to get at personal and relevant
information services when they are traveling,'' Egan, a vice
president of the Gartner Group, said. Traveling, he added, does not
have to be business travel _ it could be ``travel between the PTA
and work or driving the kids around.''
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of news on tiny screens _ some so small they can
accommodate only 30 words at a time, others able to handle as many
as 150 words _ has been drawing gradually nearer for a decade,
starting with paging devices that transmitted headlines and
financial data from organizations like CNN, Bloomberg News and
ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   But the popularity of cellular phones and personal organizers
like Palm Pilots is soaring just as new technologies arrive to
transform them into mini-printing presses. So large numbers of
investors, analysts, telecommunications companies and news
providers are becoming convinced that, eventually, people who
hunger for news will be happy to get it fresh in bit-sized digital
chunks whenever they need it.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Sacks, senior vice president and general manager of AOL
Interactive Services, said, ``You could go out of your mind
listening to Elian Gonzalez stories, when all you want to know is
why did you see 16 ambulances down the road from your house.''
</P>
<P>
   Providing the answer to such a question is the eventual goal of
services like those offered by America Online and Access Atlanta,
the flagship Web site of the Cox Enterprises unit Cox Interactive
Media. Providing a constantly updated digest of general news is the
current practice of USAToday.com, Yahoo, Fox Sports, ABCNews.com,
Reuters and The Associated Press. Providing up-to-the-minute news
of stock prices, mergers and new technologies is the aim of a
myriad of business and technology news services.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to hardware and software, the corporate guests at
the wireless information party could fill a fair-sized hotel
ballroom. But, as with the Internet, the entire wireless
information industry is casting about for an economic model that
works.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Zollman, an analyst for the Advanced Interactive Media
Group, sees a bright spot, however, in the fact that these services
are so new that relatively few people are accustomed to getting
them for free. ``There has come to be on the Web an expectation
that content is free,'' he said. ``On the wireless devices, that
expectation has not been set yet.''
</P>
<P>
   One possible revenue stream, he said, could develop by offering
wireless information services ``free or at a reduced rate to people
who subscribe to the print edition'' of a newspaper. Another, Egan
said, would be charging a cell phone user not by the number of
minutes connected but by services received.
</P>
<P>
   Making a business out of all of this is the goal not only of
these news providers, but the software companies _ AvantGo, i3
Mobile, Aether Systems, InfoSpace.com, Phone.com, Microsoft's MSN
Mobile, AnyDevice.com and numerous others _ that serve as digital
clipping or delivery services. Their customers are likely to be the
manufacturers of the mobile devices.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the creators of the protocols and digital
languages _ like the Wireless Application Protocol, or WAP, and
Bluetooth, a radiowave-based protocol that allows hand-held devices
to talk to others nearby _ that are the ink of this on-the-go,
print-with-electrons process. And finally, there are the
infrastructure builders, like IBM, Nortel and Ericsson, and the
device makers _ Palm, Psion, Sharp, Motorola, Nokia _ and finally
telecommunications firms worldwide, from Sprint, AT&AMP;T and Bell
Atlantic's Verizon to Vodafone AirTouch and Japan's NTT DoCoMo.
</P>
<P>
   The small screens will simply be a technical and editing
challenge, not an impediment, to the growth of wireless news,
argues Mitchell Stephens, author of ``A History of News'' (Harcourt
Brace, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   ``News has adapted itself to all sorts of formats throughout its
history,'' Stephens, a professor of journalism and mass
communications at New York University, said. ``The very first
newspapers in Europe had very short, what we would almost call
telegraphic news items. When the telegraph came in, news compacted
itself to travel over those expensive lines. Then you had news on
zippers in Times Square. News has fit in all sorts of places and it
will fit here.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even in the infancy of the mobile news business, there are
distinctive cultural accents to the business. In the United States,
analysts say, hand-held ``personal companions'' _ the Palm Pilot
has 68 percent of the worldwide market _ have become the early
favorite among wireless news delivery devices, picking up where the
abbreviated paging devices, with their sports-and-stock-bulletin
capacity, left off. In Europe and Japan, users prefer cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   Extending out from its U.S. base, the Palm is gaining a toehold
in the rest of the world. Currently, according to Michael Mace,
chief competitive officer for Palm Inc., there are about 6.5
million devices with the Palm operating system worldwide _ the vast
majority of them Palm Pilots. His company shipped 3 million in
1999, he said, double the rate of the previous year. An increase of
40 percent over 1999 sales sales is forecast for 2000 but, Mace
said, the sales in the first quarter of 2000 were more than double
the number in the comparable period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But these figures are dwarfed by the sales of cellular phones _
about 275 million worldwide last year. About 1 billion cellular
phones will be in use by 2003, according to several research
estimates _ though a much smaller number will be able to tap into
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how many users are getting access to the Internet
through these devices is still hard to measure, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   The number of intermediate firms, which provide data to wireless
devices, grows weekly. Of those serving the Palm, AvantGo is among
the best known, offering services for free to users of the
hand-held devices and hoping to earn its keep with a portion of the
revenues the media companies earn from the new mobile readers.
</P>
<P>
   Felix Lin, founder and chairman of AvantGo, said the company was
founded at about the same time as the first batch of Palm Pilots
was shipped in 1996. By developing alliances with media companies
like the News Corp.'s Fox unit, stock tracking services like Stock
Smart, and other sources of information _ providers of maps, ski
resort information, restaurant and movie listings, games,
horoscopes and the like _ AvantGo has developed an inventory of
hundreds of ``channels'' that mobile device owners can receive when
they log in, either through synchronization devices that reach the
Internet through desktop computers, or through wireless antennas.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe and Japan, cellular telephones became popular far
earlier than in the United States. The development of the Wireless
Application Protocol, simplifying the delivery of news to these
devices, coupled with the pervasiveness of cellular phones, have
made these devices the instrument of choice to receive news on the
go, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   But most existing phones can only receive short messages. Scott
Woefel, general manager and editor in chief of CNN.com, said 41
million cellular phone users could get news, sports and financial
data from CNN, but he did not know what fraction of this group
actually subscribed to CNN's service.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the network has a full-time staff dedicated to
reformatting its news reports for pagers and cellular phones, 24
hours a day. Separately, the company, like many other news
organizations, has a deal with AvantGo, through which a portion of
its Web site's content can be transferred to hand-held devices
running on the Palm Pilot operating system, or its rivals,
Microsoft's Windows CE and Symbian's EPOC.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is part of our bigger strategy,'' Woefel said.
Delivery of CNN news, he said, should come in ``three primary ways
_ TV in the home, a computer in the office, and one of these
hand-held devices everywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to align ourselves too closely with one
technology or one company,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters, too, is pushing for predominance in mobile information,
both through the news and financial data it supplies to Web sites
and through investments in companies like Phone.com, Yahoo and
Aether, according to Jonathan Baile, managing director of Reuters
Wireless Services.
</P>
<P>
   David Wachtel, publisher of Bloomberg Media, said the type of
news delivered would be determined in part by the device involved.
``The idea that people are going to read their entire newspaper
over the phone is wrong,'' he said. ``But quick bits of information
in a hurry, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   The editing of news for hand-held devices is becoming a
necessary skill at news Web sites. Several providers, like
Space.com. CNet's News.com, The New York Times and many Knight
Ridder newspapers offer a bouquet of eight to 20 headlines and
summaries, sometimes grouped under categories like sports and
entertainment. When a user clicks on a headline, a full story or
commentary becomes available.
</P>
<P>
   Other news providers, like The Financial Times' site, ft.com,
and USAToday.com offer streamlined, 250- or 300-word articles but
cover a broader range of subjects. News.com, like CNNfn and ESPN,
provide updates frequently; the articles can be brief or as long as
800 words.
</P>
<P>
   In general, financial and sports offerings, from sites like The
Wall Street Journal's wsj.com and espn.com, are much more likely to
be kept current. Gannett's USAToday.com is one of several general
news providers that offer updates on most topics throughout the
day. The New York Times offering of front page articles on Avantgo,
which are not updated, is the service's most requested channel,
Avantgo executives say.
</P>
<P>
   But it is often the most prosaic information that is the most
popular. Through AvantGo, the Web site of The Knoxville News
Sentinel offers detailed traffic reports, and Access Atlanta offers
weather bulletins that can be urgent during tornado season.
</P>
<P>
   But Jonathan Bell, Knoxville's senior Web designer, said, ``The
thing people are asking us for are movie times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
