<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1566 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NEW-ECON-COLUMN-NYT     04-09 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ECON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ECONOMY: INTERNET SCENE MAY HAVE A LOT IN COMMON WITH THE
'60S  
 BY LESLIE KAUFMAN  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Joshua White, the vibe at Pseudo.com, the dot-com enterprise
where he is employed these days, is amusingly reminiscent of a
different era: the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   White is a senior vice president in charge of production at
Pseudo, a company that creates original off-beat shows on
everything from the space program to hip-hop music to broadcast
over the Web. The struggle of the young staff to use the developing
medium in ways uniquely suited to the Internet strikes him as a
perfect parallel to his own life in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   That year, White was a 25-year-old lighting artist who went to
work for the rock promoter Bill Graham at the Fillmore East theater
in Manhattan's East Village. White's job and his passion were to
create light shows to match the kinetic new rock music emerging
from artists like the Grateful Dead and Jimi Hendrix. He was at the
center of cultural change, and it felt good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't chasing after anything traditional,'' he recalls. His
job, after all, was something no one had done before.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this feeling among those that were in it,'' he
added, ``that we were involved in something that older people would
not get. And then, like now, everyone over 30 is an outsider. They
come by and want to be part of it, but they just don't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   What is it about the zeitgeist of the Internet of today that
keeps calling to mind the radical 1960s? Let's have no illusions:
The two decades are decidedly at odds in terms of ideology.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier era was defined by a rejection of prevailing social
norms, from segregation to sexual modesty to name a few. Today's
dot-com babies think about transforming commerce not values and
mores. And they are working happily within establishment parameters
to do it, fighting not in the streets but on the Street.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, dropping out meant dodging the draft and moving to
Canada to join a farming collective. Today, it means skipping out
of college before graduation to join a technology start-up and cash
in on millions of options.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sense of empowerment is the same,'' Vern Keenan, who runs
a San Francisco Internet consulting firm, observes dryly, ``but the
politics is very different. Then the group party was socialism; now
it is libertarianism.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for their obvious differences, the two eras are linked in
the psyches of many. Part of the connection is that many of the
Net's founding fathers came from the crucible of rebellion culture
in California _ Steve Wozniak of Apple Computer and Bill Joy of Sun
Microsystems to drop two prominent names. But the similarities run
deeper than that.
</P>
<P>
   Most obviously, the Internet is a radically youth-centric
culture, convinced that dewy college graduates can better see the
future than those already tainted by their role in the old economy.
Surely, the hippie slogan, ``Don't trust anyone over 30,'' is as
apt for this emerging generation as it was for the 20-something
protesters who coined it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the university there is an inverse correlation between age
and experience,'' said Clay Shirky, a professor of new media at
Hunter College. ``The younger they are, the better they are at
speaking the new language. So undergraduates know more than
graduates, and freshmen know more than seniors _ all of which
really upsets the traditional order.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also an aura of vitality and era-defining importance
around the activities of those who are plugged into the new economy
_ only some of which was lost in the recent stock market slide. It
is a common refrain for reporters to hear people talk about not
wanting to be bystanders to the digital revolution, as if working
for a dot-com is on par with going to Haight-Ashbury to drop acid
during the Summer of Love.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Skeen is one of those mid-30-somethings drawn to the new
economy, in part, for the scene. Last month, Skeen left a
comfortable job at the publishing side of GQ, the men's magazine
published by Conde Nast to join Powerful Media Inc., whose
soon-to-be-introduced Web site Inside.com, aims to be a must-read
news service for media professionals. He is thrilled to have left
the polished Times Square offices of the big publishing company for
an enormous warehouse building on 11th Avenue, where numerous new
media enterprises make their home and the elevators are packed with
gadget-porting post-pubescents. ``It is an incredible
counterculture going on here,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Skeen also sees the 1960s in his adventures. He equates, for
example, the lure of money in the 1990s to the lure of drugs in the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Locke, co-author of ``The Cluetrain Manifesto,'' (Perseus
Books, 2000), a polemic that is rising quickly on the best-seller
lists, argues that the Internet revolution is the logical heir to
the 1960s on another front: communications.
</P>
<P>
   The 1960s saw giant strides toward the democratization of
information, Locke argues, pointing to alternative publications
like Rolling Stone and journalists like the great Gonzo himself.
``Hunter Thompson was writing about what he was engaged in,'' Locke
said. ``He was not pretending to be objective or out of context.''
</P>
<P>
   The Web, in Locke's view, brings the revolution against the
sonorous all-knowing corporate voice to its inevitable climax and
resolution in favor of the plebeians. ``The Internet enables people
to talk directly to each other and to corporations,'' he said. ``It
is something businesses ignore at their own peril.''
</P>
<P>
   Heavy, man, heavy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-00 1723EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
