<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEEPING WORLD SAFE FOR COMFY UNDERWEAR  
 MEDIA MUSEUM STARTS AN INTERNET COLLECTION  
 SOCIALIST REALISM: TAKING TO THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The Dav spelling in the fifth graf is correct.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Holy Fruit of the Loom! There is an anti-Harry Potter, and he is
faster than a snapping waistband, more powerful than boxer shorts.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Underpants may not have a big-time movie deal, adult
respect or a Nimbus 2000 broom, but the tales of his search for
``truth, justice and all that is preshrunk and cottony'' are
stealthily gaining popularity against the more mainstream Potter.
</P>
<P>
   The two characters share the same children's publisher,
Scholastic Inc., which has issued more than six million copies of
books in the series of epic novels featuring Captain Underpants.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth volume in this irreverent series _ ``Captain
Underpants and the Perilous Plot of Professor Poopypants'' _ has
climbed to No. 2 behind Harry Potter on the Book Sense children's
best-seller list, based on early April sales compiled from more
than 300 independent booksellers across the country. Still to come:
``Captain Underpants and the Wrath of the Wicked Wedgie Woman.''
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, Captain Underpants is actually a cranky
school principal by day who is transformed into a superhero with a
3-D hypno ring wielded by George Beard and Harold Hutchins, chronic
troublemakers at Jerome Horwitz Elementary. The guidance counselor
suspects the pranksters suffer from attention deficit disorder,
much like the author, Dav Pilkey, 34, who said severe hyperactivity
was diagnosed during what he calls the ``dark ages'' of his early
schooling.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, expectations were rather modest for the literary
future of Captain Underpants when he first emerged in the adult
world in 1997. (A primitive version of Captain U. actually leaped
from Pilkey's pencil when he was a second grader in 1973.)
Scholastic printed just 35,000 copies of the first volume and then
watched the word spread through school fairs, where Captain
Underpants was a subversive favorite among students who could
select the books themselves. The books were particularly popular
with boys 7 to 10 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Now executives at Scholastic are moving ahead with a novel
marketing effort. Toilet plungers were passed out to the company's
sales representatives when Scholastic introduced ``Captain
Underpants and the Attack of the Talking Toilets.'' Custom toilet
paper, emblazoned with the distinctive C.U. logo, was lavished on
booksellers to promote their hero. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA MUSEUM STARTS AN INTERNET COLLECTION  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone can go to the Museum of Television and Radio in New York
City and watch Richard Nixon's ``Checkers'' speech, listen to radio
episodes of ``The Green Hornet'' or watch Coca-Cola's ``I'd Like to
Teach the World to Sing'' commercials.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the museum will add another medium to its 100,000
hours of radio and television archives. It will announce Monday
that it has formed a partnership with RealNetworks, an Internet
company whose products deliver audio and video content over the
World Wide Web, to create an archive of Internet content and data.
</P>
<P>
   But just exactly how will the museum's curators decide what to
preserve from the great electronic sea? Will they preserve, for
example, the stomach-stapling operation of Carnie Wilson, the pop
singer, broadcast last year on AdoctorinyourHouse.com? America
Online's home page? Anything from The Drudge Report?
</P>
<P>
   Robert M. Batscha, the museum's president, said the same
criteria that apply to collecting television and radio material
would apply to the collection of archives from the Internet. The
three criteria, he said, were artistic excellence, historical
significance and social impact. (Which taken together do not
necessarily explain why the museum has an archived copy of the
``Star Trek'' episode ``The Trouble with Tribbles,'' but no
matter.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We will collect what we consider great work,'' Batscha said.
``And as we have television material about the Kennedy
assassination and presidential inaugurations and things like that,
we will look at how historical events on the Internet are
transmitted. And we will look at social impact, societal changes,
attitudes toward minorities and women.''
</P>
<P>
   Batscha said that the curatorial staff of the museum, which now
employs three full-time curators of television and radio, would
hire additional staff members to surf the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``To use television as an analogy, we are in the kinescope age
of the Internet, and we are lucky to begin collecting now,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Has any material been chosen yet? Batscha said some work that
Tom Fontana (the writer for the television programs ``Homicide''
and ''The Beat'') has written for the Internet has already been
selected, as well as some animation.
</P>
<P>
   What about the Starr report on President Clinton's relationship
with Monica Lewinsky?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't be any more specific,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOCIALIST REALISM: TAKING TO THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There is one class of magazines for which reaching a 76th
birthday is a sign that a publication is still a youngster. They
are the stalwart political journals. On both the right and the
left, periodicals like The Nation, National Review, The Progressive
and The New Leader, despite operating on the margins of
profitability, have continued to publish decade in and decade out,
regardless of which way the political winds are wafting.
</P>
<P>
   This year, The New Leader _ founded in 1924 as a successor to
New York City's Socialist daily newspaper, The Call _ marks its
anniversary by doing what most of the other political journals have
already done. Bowing to the call of the Internet, the magazine,
which combines political essays with book reviews and broad
cultural reporting, is starting a Web site, while at the same time
cutting back its print publication schedule to every two months
from every two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But the executive editor, Myron Kolatch, rather than sounding
ecstatic about forging into new territory, said he was distinctly
unhappy about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we thought that we ought to in some way adjust to what
is sometimes called the `communications revolution,' '' Kolatch
said, his voice separating out the words ``communications
revolution'' with disdain. ``So despite my intense skepticism about
it, we are now going to have a Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kolatch acknowledged that the Web site would probably help
keep him in touch with readers. That is something the magazine will
now have to do with special care because with the March/April issue
The New Leader, which Kolatch says has a a circulation of about
15,000, will be published less frequently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the magazine would have perhaps greater depth and a
little more heft as well,'' Kolatch said. ``And it would appear
less often so people who are now involved in reading everything off
the Internet would not find this uncomfortable. Basically, our
feeling was that magazines of this kind, general magazines, are
somewhat in a state of limbo, so we thought we'd do something to
shake it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, coming late to the Internet game has its price. The
Web name ``newleader.com'' was already taken by ``some company in
California that trains middle management,'' Kolatch said.
</P>
<P>
   The New Leader's Web site, which will be introduced in the fall,
will be called Newleadermag.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care,'' Kolatch said. ``I am not convinced people will
read it online anyway.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
