<HEADER>
A1572 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      04-09 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Monday, April 10. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
Night Supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
lyhoog(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAV-TRIBUNAL (The Hague, Netherlands) _ Confounding the
many critics who long called the international tribunal here a mere
fig leaf for Western shame, the court dealing with Yugoslav war
crimes has just completed an extraordinary month. It has opened the
first U.N. trial ever to focus exclusively on sexual violence
against women, such as gang rape and the use of women as sexual
slaves as part of war strategy. It has also begun the trial of one
of the top generals alleged to be responsible for the carnage in
1995 at the Bosnian town of Srebrenica, probably Europe's worst
massacre of civilians since World War II. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   RAMPAGE-KILLERS-II (Undated) _ Shots explode at a school in
Oregon or a brokerage office in Atlanta, and the nation is witness
to a sudden violent rampage. The killers' neighbors and families
submit to interviews, and inevitably, they say: ``He just
snapped.'' But the killers do not ``just snap.'' An examination by
The New York Times of 100 rampage murders found that most of the
killers spiraled down a long slow slide, mentally and emotionally.
Most of them left a road map of red flags. But in case after case,
the warning signs were missed. Second of four parts. By Laurie
Goodstein and William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SPRINGSNOW (Undated) _ On Saturday, golf courses were filled
with duffers in shirt sleeves. On Sunday, they were filled with
sledders in snowsuits. In a post-winter storm, eastern and northern
New York were hit with most of the snow. Albany had 12 inches by 2
p.m., when the storm started to subside. The snow at one point in
and around Albany during the early morning fell at 2 inches an
hour, according to the National Weather Service. (Summary from
wires.)
</P>
<P>
   SECONDHAND-STORES (Undated) _ There have always been shoppers
who reveled in picking up what others discarded. But a new wave of
customers is elevating secondhand stores to pillars of retailing.
Americans spent some $17 billion on secondhand merchandise in 1999,
up 23 percent from the year before. Online auctioneers such as eBay
are making such shopping fashionable, and vendors are helping as
well: Goodwill has even added coffee bars and couches to the used
book sections of some stores. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   STATE-BUDGETS-SURPLUS (Lansing, Mich.) _ Lawmakers here and in
many other states, now writing their budgets for the 2001 fiscal
year, are witnessing the biggest of six consecutive years of rising
revenues, inspiring inventive new ways to spend money and wave upon
wave of tax reductions. ``The states are overflowing with money and
spending a lot of money,'' said Stephen Moore, an economist at the
conservative Cato Institute. ``You are starting to see _ among
Republican governors, by the way _ budget increases of 6, 7, 8
percent a year.'' By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   SILICON-GEEKS (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ This is one of the few
places in the Western Hemisphere where men outnumber women. Santa
Clara County has 68,000 more single men than women. And San Jose,
which competes with Palo Alto for the right to call itself the
epicenter of Silicon Valley, has a larger surplus of single men
than anywhere in the country. Given that the Valley is also the
land of the highest-educated, highest paid workers in the world _
single women should be having a ball. But Silicon Valley is a weird
world, unto itself. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-WARRIORS (Suan Phum, Thailand) _ Between them, the
12-year-old twins command 400,000 invisible soldiers. If anybody
shoots at them, the bullets just bounce off. And they can kill
their enemies simply by pointing a rifle at the ground and
concentrating really hard. It sounds like the fantasy of a million
schoolboys. But it is a belief that has led grown men into battle
behind the two child warriors who lead a ragged ethnic insurgency
called God's Army, just across the border in Myanmar, the former
Burma. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   (With map.)
</P>
<P>
   GLF-MASTERS (Augusta, Ga.) _ Final round of the Masters. By
Clifton Brown.
</P>
