<DOCNO> NYT20000409.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1578 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-UGA-FRAT0410-COX     04-09 1537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGA-FRAT0410-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UGA officials hope fatal accident will bring about change
 &HT;    By James Salzer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Brian Harbin had heard ``horror stories'' from
relatives about their experiences getting into fraternities, so
when he started school at the University of Georgia, he chose one
that wouldn't put him through extensive hazing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would you want to be a brother with someone who paddled
you or made you clean the toilets at 3 a.m.?'' asked Harbin, a
member of Sigma Phi Epsilon, a fraternity suspended during the
mid-1990s over a booze-guzzling hazing that sent a student to the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Talk with fraternity members at UGA and they're likely to
divulge little if anything about what they go through to earn their
stripes. Police and college officials say they only know about
hazing when something bad happens, like a student winds up in an
emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   Greek members say the university has been cracking down, and
there are strict rules and plenty of talk of a zero tolerance on
hazing.
</P>
<P>
   But the prank that wound up in the death of Alpha Tau Omega
member Benjamin Folsom Grantham III a week ago is a reminder that
while there is a line drawn by college officials and fraternity
leaders, it's impossible to know how often it's crossed on or off a
campus where thousands of students are part of the Greek system.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really don't see things unless something bad happens,''
said Chuck Horton, longtime chief of the UGA police. ``I hear
through the grapevine that people don't do things any more. It's
like speeding violations. We have speed limits all over, but it
doesn't stop people from speeding.''
</P>
<P>
   Cases brought before UGA officials or police during the past
decade include a myriad of accusations, including paddlings,
students forced to streak on campus and used as chauffeurs,
underage drinking, injuries caused by excess partying and brawls.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, 10 UGA fraternities and sororities have
been disciplined for hazing, alcohol or curfew abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Wynn Smiley, executive director of the national Alpha Tau Omega
organization, has tried to make it clear that the ``road trip''
Grantham was involved in _ an old fraternity prank _ was not a
``chapter event.''
</P>
<P>
   School and ATO rules prohibit ``road tripping,'' where a student
is driven out to a location and left, either to find their way back
or be found by others.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about 18, 19, 20 year-old guys,'' he said.
``They're going to do stupid stuff ... it goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiley said Grantham was a willing participant in the game, a
fact that does not prohibit school officials from sanctioning the
group for hazing.
</P>
<P>
   During a memorial service last week, Grantham was described as a
Star-Trek loving, Camel-smoking frat boy who, like most college
students, knew how to have a good time. Some members of other frats
said ATO's reputation for partying was no greater than that of
other Greek chapters. Others used the immortal phrase of American
frat lexicon: Animal House. Still others called such
characterizations an exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   During the ceremony, there was an air of deep reflection,
although members also said they planned to go out and party
afterward in memory of Grantham.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me and a lot of the brothers, it's been a real life-check
moment, realizing it can all end that quick,'' said Bo Pihl, the
chapter's vice president. ``For most of us, this is the first time
we've had to deal with losing someone.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of soul-searching UGA Greek Life officials hope
has come from the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``All our groups need to reflect on how they treat each other,''
said Eric Atkinson, fraternity adviser in UGA's Greek Life office.
``This should be a message to all of our chapters.''
</P>
<P>
   Members agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a gut-check for the whole fraternity system,'' said Mike
McAuliffe, a member of UGA's Beta Theta Pi fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   Beta Theta Pi has a ``dry,'' or no-alcohol rush and has been
successful in raising money for groups like the American Cancer
Society. McAuliffe's mother, Ceci, was proud that her son knew
where to draw his personal line of behavior and what he wanted out
of a fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of pledge pranks, she said, he took part in chapter
projects. ``I would rather have Mike refinish the floor (of his
frat house) than be taken up to South Carolina and forced to find
his way back,'' she said. ``It's a great bunch of kids who I'm
thrilled my son is involved with.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike McAuliffe said a few of his friends pledged with
fraternities because they had great parties, but now they wished
they hadn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a connection to my fraternity that doesn't have
anything to do with alcohol or girls,'' he said. ``With us, it's
not an attitude that we're out to get the pledges.''
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe said he checked out other fraternities, and that
hazing goes on.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that there was a line he simply wouldn't cross in
pledging.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a self-respect line,'' he said. ``There were times I
was thinking, `I don't need this.' I was going to do things I'm
comfortable with that would build brotherhood but not be
entertainment for the brothers. ``
</P>
<P>
   Clint Powell, vice president of the chapter, said, ``I hope all
this stuff that has been going down will serve as a wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   Hazing has been around on campuses across the country for
decades, and not just at fraternities and sororities. Horton
remembers athletes being hazed in the early 1970s, when he played
football at UGA. Rituals that would be considered hazing in college
have been part of pro sports as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not of concern to the national organizations and
university people 20 years ago. People weren't dying,'' said Bill
Bracewell, former longtime director of student judicial programs at
UGA.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-hazing and party rules for fraternities and sororities are
stricter than in the past, and Greek leaders are reenforcing them
with new, self-policing guidelines set to take effect this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that schools keep a closer eye on fraternities may mean
there are fewer problems and less hazing. Or it may mean activity
that still occurs has been driven behind closed doors or off
campus.
</P>
<P>
   The school's hazing policy outlaws forcing students to drink or
eat anything or to do calisthenics, tying them up and throwing food
or something else at them, paddling, ``road trips,'' inhibiting
sleep or making them run personal errands.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials say few of the problems they've seen over the
years have involved sororities. And most of the time problems arise
at frats, Atkinson said, alcohol is involved. That, in turns, adds
to the stereotype people have of Greek life as one big party.
</P>
<P>
   Greek organizations, many of which do extensive charity work,
say that's a mischaracterization brought on by the fact that the
media tends to focus only when things go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do like to have a good time, but what college student
doesn't like to have a good time?'' said Derick Corbett, who is a
member of Lambda Chi Alpha fraternity.
</P>
<P>
   UGA's social events registration form points to strict
standards. At parties, everyone is responsible for bringing their
own alcoholic beverages, the amount is limited, and beer kegs
aren't allowed. The total number of people at parties is limited
and all unlocked entrances and exits to party areas must be
monitored by a security guard or chapter member. Advertising is
prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   Some fraternity members also say the UGA Greek Life office sends
people to events to make sure there is no underage drinking.
``You'd be amazed how long the arm of Greek Life is,'' Harbin said.
``The days of Animal House are definitely over.''
</P>
<P>
   Atkinson said, ``It's not spying, it's just trying to make sure
we have chapters enforcing their own rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Such rules have probably led to less action at Greek houses, and
more at the dozens of bars in and around the campus area, according
to some UGA officials. The school also has year-around education
programs for Greek members on subjects like hazing, alcohol and
gambling, and has a hazing hotline.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jay Kimbro, a Sigma Chi member and president of UGA's
Interfraternity Council, said members have to police their
chapters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must hold ourselves to a higher standard,'' he said. ``As
fraternity men, we need to act like mature adults and hold each
other accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   If not, some are worried more fraternities will be shut down, or
UGA President Michael Adams will create a ``Greek park'' to
concentrate house chapters in one area of campus. Such a park was
created at Centre College in Kentucky, where Adams was previously
president.
</P>
<P>
   While that issue was discussed during a forum last year on
campus, Adams indicated at the time that such a proposal is a long
way from becoming reality.
</P>
<P>
   Some schools have outlawed Greeks on campus, and members realize
how they react to the latest incident is important to the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future, people will start wising up and realizing there
is only one way to stay a Greek system,'' McAuliffe said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
