<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1579 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-LISTON-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     04-09 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LISTON-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE DEVIL AND SONNY LISTON': HAZY START, DARK END, CHAMPION IN
BETWEEN
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Near the start of his unusual biography, ``The Devil and Sonny
Liston,'' Nick Tosches writes: ``A guy who knew Sonny once said, `I
think he died the day he was born.' Nobody, not even Sonny, knew
exactly when that day was, or where he was born. Only he and the
men who killed him knew the date of his death. His life began and
ended in a blur.''
</P>
<P>
   That's right: ``the men who killed him,'' Tosches writes. Which
means he's going to clear up the old mystery behind the death in
January 1971 of the 39-year-old former heavyweight boxing champion,
whose body was found in the bedroom of his Las Vegas house with
drug paraphernalia lying nearby. So Liston didn't die of a
self-administered overdose, as was rumored at the time? The
prospect of answering this question is reason enough to read
Tosches' biography.
</P>
<P>
   But there are several other reasons. For one thing, Tosches
offers persuasive answers to another big mystery about Liston's
life: whether he threw not one but both of his championship bouts
against Muhammad Ali (who was known as Cassius Marcellus Clay until
their first fight on Feb. 25, 1964), and if so, why.
</P>
<P>
   Tosches has little but disdain for Clay, both as a fighter
compared to Liston and as ``the darling of a more elite mediocrity,
a white intelligentsia who sought meaning and metaphor in boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere he writes: ``Mediocrity and media, it should be
remembered, are cognates of the same Latin root. ... Clay should be
regarded as the first made-for-TV boxing idol. As he danced and
cavorted in acceptable and inoffensive outrageousness before the
masses and the cameras and the microphones of mediocrity, so
mediocrity embraced him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tosches makes a cogent case that the young Clay could not have
stood up to the real Liston. He cites among other evidence the
words of Chuck Wepner, who fought them both: ``Ali didn't hit like
Liston. Liston was the only man that ever hurt me.''
</P>
<P>
   So why, in the first fight, were Liston's blows ``delivered with
none of the awesome power that in the past had felled man after
man''? Why, in the rematch at Lewiston, Maine, in May 1965, was
Liston knocked out in the first round by a punch too short to do
serious damage, prompting the sports columnist Red Smith to write
that Liston took a dive that raised the level of the Androscoggin
River by a foot?
</P>
<P>
   Tosches rejects the theory that Liston and his people owned a
piece of Ali's future, or that Liston was intimidated by the Black
Muslims, who had recently won over Ali. He argues instead that
mobsters _ specifically Paul John (Frank) Carbo and Frank (Blinky)
Palermo _ owned Liston glove, shoe and trunks and had done so
practically from the instant he had turned professional.
</P>
<P>
   But they were tired of him, Tosches suggests. ``Sonny as a
champion was bad, bad news,'' he writes. He was unpopular. He
drank. He persistently got in trouble with the law. He was on the
verge of being revealed as a rapist. So they told him to pack it
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did what they told me to do,'' Liston told his eldest
brother, according to Tosches' account. And the people who ran
Liston ``went for the money,'' Tosches says. He writes that a
former chairman of the Nevada State Boxing Commission said of the
first Ali fight: ``They got $300,000 for the fight, and they bet it
seven-to-one. They got $2.1 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Tosches is an exhaustive reporter. He seems to have dug up
everyone ever connected to Liston and got them to talk,
particularly about the network of mob connections.
</P>
<P>
   He also can write vividly when moved, as when he recalls his
boyhood fascination with Liston: ``He was the ultimate outlaw. Man,
those narrow-lapeled sharkskin suits, that felling left and that
slaughterhouse right, and that scowl: his badness transcended
race.'' Any reader who wants more of Tosches' writing can get it in
a newly available volume, ``The Nick Tosches Reader'' (Da Capo
Press), an anthology of his occasional prose and excerpts from his
previous books, including ``Dino,'' his much-praised biography of
Dean Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ultimately ``The Devil and Sonny Liston'' fails to bring its
subject to life. The book may contain a sampling of Liston's famous
so-called mother-wit, like, ``The only thing my old man gave me was
a beating'' (omitting one of my favorites, uttered before his bout
with the German heavyweight Albert Westphal: ``Westphal, Eastphal,
that boy's gonna fall''). But there remains an odd dissonance
between this Liston and the one Tosches tries to animate with his
complex, heavy-breathing metaphors:
</P>
<P>
   `` `I ain't complaining,' he would say, later in 1960. He spoke
as one who knew in his blood what few others admitted: that no man
. . . was ever his own man. ... That, and that alone, was nature;
and to be aware of this, in thought and in blood, or in blood
alone, was to possess something of wisdom, and therein lay the only
manumission, the only, elusive windblown cornsilk strand of freedom
that was real amid the illusive and delusive freedom that all
professed and praised.
</P>
<P>
   ```They treat me good,' he would say.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end ``The Devil and Sonny Liston'' turns out to be a bit
of a tease as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he took too much dope and died,'' Tosches concludes
his analysis of all the murder theories surrounding Liston's death.
``I look back to a sentence that I wrote over a year ago, a
sentence that appears in the earliest of these pages:  &UR; Only he and
the men who killed him knew the date of his death. &LR;  Looking at it,
I realize that it can be easily and cleanly deleted, plucked from
the page, with no effect on the words or meaning that surround it.
But I choose to leave it there, because it expressed my feeling at
that time, and because, unlike a statement proven untrue, it very
well might express not only my past feelings, but also the truth,
which, in this matter, will never be known.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be less here than meets the eye.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE DEVIL AND SONNY LISTON'
</P>
<P>
   By Nick Tosches
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 266 pages. Little, Brown &AMP; Co. $24.95. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
