<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1581 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-DRAFT0410-COX     04-09 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT0410-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hard knocks drive Ellis
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After Saturday's NFL draft, Shaun Ellis' mother
finally will get to walk away from the dough.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, a defensive end from Tennessee, is projected to be among
the first 25 players drafted, which would make him an instant
millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   After he's drafted, Ellis says one of the first things he'll do
is ask his mother, Annie Ellis, to quit her job.
</P>
<P>
   Five days a week, Annie Ellis clocks in at 5 a.m. at a bakery in
Anderson, S.C. She stands for hours, despite suffering from
arthritis that he worries may eventually leave her crippled.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a hard-working lady and it's taken a toll on her body,''
Shaun Ellis said. ``It's time for her to give it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellis, 6 feet 4 and 280 pounds, nearly watched his dream of
playing in the NFL vanish two years ago. On March 16, 1998, Ellis
was driving back to Knoxville from his mother's home.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 minutes outside of Knoxville, Ellis fell asleep at the
wheel of his Ford Taurus. The car hit a cement drain and then some
trees. The car flipped several times before it landed in an
embankment.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Ellis was wearing a seat belt. A nurse on her way to
work witnessed the accident, stopped to help and called an
ambulance. A fractured hip kept Ellis out of spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   Miraculously, he returned to two-a-day practices that fall and
played in the first game of his junior season. He says his hip is
fine, and the only scars from the accident are on his lower lip,
which was nearly torn off.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what drives me today,'' Ellis said. ``Every time I
think things get hard, I just think about that time.''
</P>
<P>
   And he thinks about his mother and how he'll change her life.
That's why he decided to leave Tennessee one year early.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Ellis was academically ineligible as a freshman because
he was accepted to school as a partial qualifier. But because Ellis
had finished at least 75 percent of his degree in four years, he
was awarded an additional year of eligibility by the NCAA.
</P>
<P>
   He won't need it.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Volunteers played Nebraska in the Fiesta Bowl on Jan.
2, Ellis decided to enter the NFL draft. He knew the decision would
help stop his mother's pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get tired of your mom having to struggle so hard to make a
living,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ellis is hoping to make it hard on NFL offensive tackles.
He's widely regarded as the second-best defensive end in the draft,
behind Penn State's Courtney Brown, who could become the No. 1
pick.
</P>
<P>
   Despite playing with a pinched nerve in his neck last season,
Ellis was still chosen All-SEC. He had 42 tackles, 11 stops for
loss and 8 1/2 sacks in his final college season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I bring a powerful type of rushing to the game,'' he
said. ``I've got real quickness and not just in stopping the run. I
can rush from either side. I can put either hand down on the
ground, too. I can play every down. I can play against the run or
the pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
