<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ELIAN _ WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department ``would be
prepared'' to order Juan Miguel Gonzalez to remain in the United
States with his son Elian while courts determine custody rights,
Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder said Sunday. Also Sunday, the
father met with a government-appointed team of psychologists and
with Florida fishermen representing Elian's Miami relatives. The
relatives reportedly were preparing new court action Monday as an
expected midweek deadline to turn over the boy approached. (Lipman,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   PERU-FUJIMORI _ LIMA _ Peru's Alberto Fujimori hopes to claim a
third, but constitutionally questionable, term as president in
Sunday's closely watched election. But Fujimori's plans could be at
least temporarily delayed if he fails to win a majority and is
forced into a runoff. (Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH _ One day last week, sandwiched between trolling for votes
in Pennsylvania and California, Gov. George W. Bush spent a few
hours planning for something he hopes he's not involved in _ the
2001 legislative session. A look at the weirdness of preparing for
a job Bush hopes to lose. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   IRS _ WASHINGTON _ Tax attorney Daren Larsen recently
represented a prosperous professional who owed the Internal Revenue
Service more than $100,000 dating back to his younger, wilder
years. To her client's delight, the IRS concluded that he could not
pay the total within the prescribed three-year period, so they
dropped the case. Welcome to the kinder, gentler IRS, two years
after passage of the most sweeping reform in half a century.
(Malone, Cox News Service). With IRS-DATA _ Chart material on IRS
collections. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MLK-GA-FLAG _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ While South Carolina is
still fighting an increasingly uncivil war over the Confederate
battle flag, this city has apparently made peace before controversy
could flare. Workmen were completing the Martin Luther King Jr.
Landmark Memorial Thursday afternoon when electrician John Padgett
happened to glance up at the 21 flags that had just been raised.
``I couldn't believe that for Martin Luther King they would have
that flag up there, with all that's going on now,'' Padgett said
Saturday. (Hayes, Palm Beach Post). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   UGA-FRAT _ His relatives told him horror stories about what they
went through in college to get into fraternities, so UGA student
Brian Harbin of Atlanta chose one that wouldn't haze him. ``Why
would you want to be a brother with someone who paddled you or made
you clean the toilets at 3 a.m.?'' he asked. Talk with fraternity
members and they're likely to divulge little about what they go
through to earn their stripes as pledges, and police and college
officials only know about hazing when something bad happens, like a
student winds up in the hospital with alcohol poisoning. Despite
claims that they are cracking down, and assurances that they have
taken a zero tolerance on hazing, incidents like the prank that
wound up killing popular UGA frat boy Ben Grantham last month seem
to pop up a couple of times a year. (Salzer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-MORENO _ Linda Moreno went to see her doctor to lose
weight four years ago. Today her lawyers expect her to die soon
from the side effects of the once popular drug combination
fen-phen. Her lawsuit against the makers and sellers of the ``fen''
in fen-phen alleges they engaged in illegal and unethical marketing
practices and raises a troubling question: how far is a drug
company willing to go for a profit? (Bhatt, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   DA-BRAT-INTERVIEW _ The part-time Atlanta resident born Shawntae
Harris is better known as the young rapper Da Brat. This is a big
week for her: Her third album, ``Unrestricted,'' comes out Tuesday;
she's due in Atlanta Municipal Court on Thursday to face battery
charges stemming from a Buckhead bar incident. And she turns 26 on
Friday. In her first interview since she became a police story in
her adopted hometown, she talks to us about her life here and the
struggles of her kind of fame. (Murray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).WITH PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   MANDOLIN-MAKER _ First thing in the morning, Tony Ianuario has a
chat with his hands. Shall we do some crafty woodworking today?
Shall we make music? Shall we be scientific? Or artistic?
Frequently, he and his hands can't pick a single discipline for the
day. So, they decide to do them all by building mandolins.
(Osinski, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SENIOR-WORK _ WACO, Texas _ Before they step up to the counter
to order their chicken sandwiches and french fries, customers at
Chick-fil-A are greeted by Ethel Beard's warm smile and kind words.
``Hello, welcome to Chick-Fil-A. How are you today?'' she says as
restaurant patrons walk in the double glass doors. The 63-year-old
woman, whom employees and regular customers affectionately call,
``Miss Ethel,'' has worked as the restaurant's hostess for almost
three years. She says that unlike most folks her age, who look
forward to retiring and kicking up their feet, she'd rather be busy
on hers. (Allmon, Waco Tribune-Herald). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   HUMAN-WIRED _ Barely 50 years after its invention, the computer
is already listed with the wheel, the printing press and the steam
engine as a technology that has changed the world. Like the
printing press, the computer has greatly accelerated the flow of
information. Like the steam engine, the computer can be applied to
a variety of industrial uses, making the entire economy more
efficient. But in its impact on how human beings live, the computer
is best compared to a humble technology called the clock. (Bookman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
