A1588 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     04-09 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 Copyright 2000 Chronicle Publishing Company 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A PRACTICAL TEXAS SOLUTION TO ROAD RAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; George Olson  &LR; forwards a passel of letters to the editor of the
Dallas Morning News about motorists' manners. Among the indignant
drivers was  &UR; A.C. &LR; , who said that speed limits ``are just stinkin'
fund-raisers,'' and  &UR; C.R. &LR;  of Dallas, whose letter was headlined
``I have had it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am now taking up arms for myself,'' he wrote, after
describing offenses by rude and dangerous drivers. ``I have always
been a gun opponent and do not condone the taking of a life. I now
find that I am losing that dislike for weapons and have found a
purposeful use for them. I will buy one, license myself, and the
next time you decide to run me off the road when turning the
corner, you will be driving on four flat tires. I will shoot them
out for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are allowed to use a motor vehicle as a weapon, then,
in like manner, I too must use any means possible to defend myself.
So shall it be written, so shall it be.''
</P>
<P>
   Going somewhere in Dallas? Maybe it's best to saddle up.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Madonna &LR; , who's vowed to keep her daughter out of the
limelight, has posed with her for an Ebel wristwatch ad that
appears in the latest Town &AMP; Country. The image is the hand of
 &UR; Madonna &LR; , her wrist adorned with a diamond-studded sports watch,
being clenched by the hand of her 3-year-old daughter,  &UR; Lourdes &LR; ,
whose nails are artfully manicured in scarlet.
</P>
<P>
   - Rock star  &UR; Ted Nugent &LR; 's telling audiences at concerts in
Texas last week that ``if you can't speak English, get out of
America'' has drawn criticism from the League of United Latin
American Citizens. ``We feel it was directed in hatred at
Hispanics,'' said LULAC's  &UR; Charles Flores &LR; . ``I'm sure he could
have worded it better.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Marla Maples &LR;  and her daughter  &UR; Tiffany Trump &LR; , 6, have been
studying kabala, and Maples is in the process of converting to
Judaism, says the New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Gregory Peck &LR; 's daughter  &UR; Cecilia &LR;  named her new baby
 &UR; Harper &LR; , after  &UR; Harper Lee &LR; , who wrote ``To Kill a Mockingbird,''
the novel turned into the movie that won her dad an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Tony Reveaux  &LR; is wondering if the Bay Bridge toll plaza sign
that says ``Toll violation $100 minimum fine enforced by video''
means that if you're caught you get strapped into a chair and
forced to watch taped reruns of a TV show you always despised.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHISTLE WHILE YOU WORK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - A Richmond-bound BART train was stopped for a few minutes the
other night when the motorman announced he couldn't get permission
to proceed _ a new phone communication system wasn't working, he
said, nor was the old one _ and asked, ``Can somebody loan me a
cell phone?'' After accepting a phone loan &LR;  from a passenger
sitting just behind him, he called headquarters and the merry
journey continued.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Andrea Thompson &LR; , the short-haired blond detective on
``NYPD,'' is leaving the show at the end of the season to become a
reporter and anchor on the CBS affiliate station in Albuquerque,
N.M. Thompson, 40, told People magazine that she never went to
college and is preparing for the job by studying for her SATs.
</P>
<P>
   - At  &UR; David Grenley &LR; 's office, a neat sign next to a box of
cookies at the coffee station said, ``Please support the Math
Engineering and Sciense Association at HFK High School.'' Affixed
was a Post-it with ``Give a couple of bucks to the spelling
department, too.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Tom Geller &LR; , whose office ill wind was explained here
recently, says it's now blowing at 6:06 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Sally Sachs &LR; ' name for those big-bucks computer whizzes:
dot-commissars. - Calming influences: Workers at one South of
Market company have been offered Camo Soda Break software to nag
them into taking breaks, meditation seminars ``with sandwich
buffet'' and stress management workshops that teach  &LR; such
 &LR; techniques as ``Alphabet Animals,'' ``Mental Compression'' and
``End-of-the-Movie,'' presumably not Hitchcock.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I had a remote control, I don't believe I understood a
thing about the culture. ... The culture is about flipping. People
don't watch a show on television. They watch the television. They
flip around and watch two seconds of this and five seconds of that.
And if you grow up with the remote control, you have no sense of
narrative, and that is probably the biggest leap in the notion of
literary narrative. There's no structure to it. In that way, this
is the dream of the Surrealists.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Fran Lebowitz  &LR; in Traditional Home magazine.
</P>
