<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIR-GETTHERE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH AIRWAYS IN CORPORATE TRAVEL VENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British Airways and the online business-travel service
GetThere.com plan to announce Monday that they will create
customized Web sites to provide corporate travel agency services
for small and mid-sized business in Britain and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The new sites will be based on GetThere's Global Manager, an
electronic travel service used by large corporations like Nike and
Cisco Systems to book business trips for employees. British Airways
will enable small and mid-size business users to book air, car and
hotel reservations with the same management and reporting tools
that large corporations use. While companies will be able to book
flights on other airlines, British Airways will be the default
choice. A small business, for example, could identify certain
employees who would be allowed to book business-class fares and
designate other employees as eligible only for coach-class fares.
The employer might also create guidelines governing the kind of
accommodations various types of employees are allowed to book. The
system would allow employees to identify preferred airlines or
hotels with which the company has negotiated discounts.
</P>
<P>
   Companies will be able to create their own customized sites
within the portal.
</P>
<P>
   The new site is part of British Airways' push into electronic
commerce, particularly into the vaunted business-to-business
portion of that market. The new site also fits with the airline's
shift, after recent losses, toward attracting more customers
willing to pay business-class fares, which have a significantly
higher profit margin than coach seats.
</P>
<P>
   Simon Parks Smith, manager of British Airways'
business-to-business ventures, said the new is site was ``an
opportunity for us to use e-commerce'' to reach small and mid-size
European businesses.
</P>
<P>
   For GetThere, based in Menlo Park, Calif., the link-up with
British Airways gives the young company considerable marketing
muscle without having to spend the vast sums of cash that some
dot.com companies are forced to invest to build their brands.
</P>
<P>
   GetThere has been eyeing the European market for some time. It
opened a London office here recently and is adding new features to
its site to offer European customers services like booking
reservations on trains and ferries.
</P>
<P>
   Whether GetThere will ever put American Express' corporate
travel service out of business remains questionable _ or perhaps
the wrong question. The company's clients include American Express,
which uses the GetThere service for some of its own clients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
