<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1598 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CHASE-FLEMING-NYT &LR;      04-09 0350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHASE-FLEMING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHASE SET TO ACQUIRE BRITISH BANK FOR $8 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Robert Fleming Holdings, one of Britain's last
independent banks, is expected to announce as soon as Tuesday that
it will be acquired by the Chase Manhattan Corp. for close to 5
billion pounds, or nearly $8 billion, executives close to the talks
said.
</P>
<P>
   The price is higher than most analysts expected when reports of
the negotiations emerged last month.
</P>
<P>
   While the details of the deal have not been completed, the
executives said, they were confident the acquisition would go
through. Executives from both banks have been working out the
particulars since the banks acknowledged on March 22 that they were
in negotiations. The new company would be called Chase Fleming in
Europe, the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Several executives close to the talks acknowledged that one of
the main reasons for confirming the discussions last month was to
``prime the market'' so that when the deal was finally announced,
the deal and price would not surprise analysts and market makers.
</P>
<P>
   That strategy may have backfired because initial speculation
about the price for Fleming focused on a considerably lower figure
of 3 billion pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that it was too early to say whether Chase was
paying a fair price, but one analyst who spoke on the condition of
anonymity said, ``Five billion pounds sounds a bit outrageous to
me. Are we talking about the same Fleming?''
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to the talks also said that the deal would not
include Fleming's 50 percent stake in the $35-billion Rowe
Price-Fleming International Inc., a fund management joint venture.
The executives said Price Fleming plans to sell the stake to T.
Rowe Price Associates Inc., its partner in the venture.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is part of Chase's strategy to bolster its
business in Europe and Asia. The deal follows Chase's $1.35-billion
acquisition of the Hambrecht &AMP; Quist Group last year, which helped
strengthen Chase's high-technology investment banking business. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-00 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000409.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1599 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DRUGS-MORENO0410-COX     04-09 1641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-MORENO0410-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawsuit alleges illegal and unethical practices by drug company
 &HT;    By Sanjay Bhatt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ Linda Moreno went to see her doctor to
lose weight four years ago. Today, her lawyers expect her to die
soon from what they claim are the side effects of the once popular
drug combination fen-phen.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawsuit against the makers and sellers of the ``fen'' in
fen-phen alleges they engaged in illegal and unethical marketing
practices. If those claims are proved in court, it could raise a
troubling question: How far is a drug company willing to go for a
profit?
</P>
<P>
   The maker of the weight-loss drugs Pondimin (fenfluramine) and
Redux (dexfenfluramine) withdrew them from the U.S. market in
September 1997 after the federal Food and Drug Administration
received more than two dozen reports of patients with heart-valve
damage.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno's suit, filed in 1997, alleges that the maker of Pondimin
and its chemical cousin, Redux, fraudulently withheld information
about the drugs' adverse side effects from the FDA, doctors, the
public and even the drug companies' own sales representatives, all
in the name of profits.
</P>
<P>
   Defendant American Home Products and its subsidiaries, including
Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories, deny the allegations with 52 legal
theories _ among them, that it provided adequate warnings to
Moreno's physicians, followed all laws and is not liable for
conduct protected by the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Internal company documents subpoenaed in the lawsuit show top
executives at Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories, which had the rights to
sell the drugs in the U.S., discussed plans to stir up buzz on
Redux with articles on treating obesity in prominent medical
journals and with a weekend trip to Scottsdale, Ariz., for about
100 doctors. The lawsuit calls the articles ``unethical sleaze on
the part of a pharmaceutical company.''
</P>
<P>
   The documents also show the sales force at A.H. Robins,
Wyeth-Ayerst's sister company, was given information on clinical
studies done by Michael Weintraub, a University of Rochester
physician who concluded combining Pondimin with phentermine was
safe and effective in helping patients lose weight. Such
``off-label'' use of Pondimin _ the FDA had not approved combining
the drug this way _ became wildly popular after Weintraub's
findings were published in 1992. Sales reps were instructed not to
encourage doctors to use the drug combination. But they were also
told to give doctors the studies' citations if they were
interested.
</P>
<P>
   SUIT CLAIMS MISREPRESENTATION
</P>
<P>
   The suit claims the company failed to correct inaccurate
statements by news media about Pondimin and Redux and
misrepresented the true risk of its drugs in news releases and its
product labels.
</P>
<P>
   As Pondimin sales zoomed to $49 million in 1995 from $8.5
million the previous year, fueled by fen-phen doctors, Wyeth-Ayerst
executives feared that generic drugmakers would move in on their
market dominance, company documents in the court file state.
</P>
<P>
   Redux, which was in the final stages of FDA clearance, would
give the company a patented, more profitable weight-loss drug to
replace Pondimin, which no longer had patent protection and could
be copied by generic drug makers who could sell it for a lot less,
thereby cutting into Pondimin's sales.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Redux sales would be hurt if the drug's label had
a black box warning for primary pulmonary hypertension (PPH), a
fatal heart-lung disorder, or if the company had to state an
incident rate of 1 in 45,000 instead of 5 per million, a company
marketing executive wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``As you know, this is probably the biggest single factor
remaining to determine future sales performance of the product,''
her memo said. The FDA later allowed the drug to be sold without
the warning box.
</P>
<P>
   By March 1996, the company's sales force was making final
preparations to blitz doctors and the public with an aggressive
marketing campaign upon Redux's approval, which occurred a month
later.
</P>
<P>
   CONVENTION INCREASED SALES
</P>
<P>
   Conventions would be a key: James Donovan, executive director of
marketing, noted a study that found physicians who visited product
exhibits increased their prescription-writing for those products by
18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A large consultant's conference on obesity involving almost
100 obesity experts will be held in Scottsdale, Arizona April
19-21,'' according to a marketing memo. ``This educational meeting
will also help develop product advocates who will be provided with
patient starter supplies to generate early post-approval clinical
experience. These experts will also provide for local and regional
media needs.''
</P>
<P>
   The company had a list of 51 speakers on obesity treatments, of
whom 41 received money from the company or its subsidiaries for
clinical studies, according to the documents.
</P>
<P>
   A 1995 memo in the court files from one Wyeth-Ayerst executive
to another points out that Europe was expected to restrict the use
of mixtures like fen-phen for fear of causing the fatal heart-lung
disorder PPH _ the same disorder Moreno's lawyers say she suffers
from.
</P>
<P>
   Wyeth-Ayerst's Arizona conference was held in 1996, a year
later. But in the company's workbook for conference participants,
its clinical investigator said the rate of PPH in obese patients
was only ``about 23 to 46 per million.''
</P>
<P>
   But later the same year, according to the court file, the
chairman of an international study group that examined Pondimin,
Redux and other appetite suppressants wrote the company to complain
that its press releases about Redux were inaccurate. The real
chances of contracting PPH were much higher, he claimed. His group
had estimated the chance of PPH in obese patients who used the drug
over a long period of time to be about 100 per million.
</P>
<P>
   ARTICLES INTENDED TO TARGET WIDER AUDIENCE
</P>
<P>
   In December 1996, months after Redux was cleared for sale by the
FDA, Excerpta Medica, a subsidiary of a major medical journal
publisher, billed Wyeth-Ayerst $200,000 for 10 papers, according to
court documents. The fee ``reflects the developmental costs of
researching, writing, editing and revising the paper, the author's
honorarium ($1,500), and the management fee,'' according to the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The articles, reviewed by Wyeth-Ayerst, were to appear in
journals targeting primary care physicians, osteopathic physicians,
gynecologists, cardiologists, nurse practitioners, physician
assistants, pharmacists and managed care administrators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wyeth-Ayerst should consider broader targeting as opposed to
the highly targeted, high prescriber focus at introduction that has
become the industry standard,'' explained a February 1996 memo to
marketing executives.
</P>
<P>
   High prescribers, it turns out, were happy with fen-phen and
skeptical of giving patients a single pill of the new,
patent-protected Redux because its chemical cousin Pondimin didn't
work on its own, the memo said.
</P>
<P>
   For primary care physicians, Excerpta Medica suggested a paper
whose objective was ``to provide the reader with an update on the
dexfenfluramine experience.'' The author had not been determined,
but the article would appear in the American Journal of Medicine, a
journal published by Excerpta's parent company, Reed Elsevier.
</P>
<P>
   The American Journal article on treating obesity said that
fenfluramine (Pondimin was the leading brand name) was the ``only
available appetite suppressant in the United States,'' and didn't
disclose anywhere that Wyeth-Ayerst had reviewed the article or
paid for it, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   ACCURACY AND ETHICS QUESTIONED
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Moreno complained that the article ``was
commissioned, paid for, drafted by a company paid by AHP (American
Home Products), and published in a journal owned by the same
company!''
</P>
<P>
   The truth has been taken out of context and twisted, said Jean
Dolan, Excerpta Medica's executive vice president. The author
controlled the paper's content, not the drug company, and the
peer-reviewed journal's publisher didn't even know Excerpta Medica
had helped the author with searching the medical literature, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no collusion involved, and nothing unethical was
done,'' Dolan said. ``We try to get well-respected authorities in
the field. These people aren't going to compromise their reputation
for $1,500. I find that idea offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   Wyeth-Ayerst's market research also showed most high prescribers
were primary care physicians in solo practice without any
dieticians or physician assistants on staff.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Daisey Merey, a board-certified bariatrician, or weight-loss
specialist, said too many consumers and doctors relied on the pills
without paying attention to diet, exercise and mental health. She
misses having Pondimin and Redux in her arsenal for treating obese
patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of physicians who were not bariatricians were using the
drug (combination) hoping it would do everything,'' Merey said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreno's trial could hinge on whether, and if so, why the
defendants delayed for more than a year changing Pondimin's label
to reflect the higher number of users developing primary pulmonary
hypertension or dying. The court file includes an internal memo in
1994 warning that the number of incidents was higher than mentioned
on the label.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know, other doctors didn't know, nobody knew,'' Merey
said.
</P>
<P>
   She recalls going to a dinner meeting on Redux put on by
Interneuron Pharmaceuticals Inc., which held the drug's U.S.
license and partnered with American Home Products to market the
drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``A dinner is not a big incentive,'' Merey said. ``Continuing
education is very important for physicians. ... That's where we
gain our expertise.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-00 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000409.0087 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1600 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-OED-ONLINE-ART-1800(2     04-09 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OED-ONLINE-ART-1800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAID KNOW-IT-ALL GOES HIP AND ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos of James Murray and of one of his descendants,
Thomas Murray, are being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By SARAH LYALL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OXFORD, England _ In its familiar version, the Oxford English
Dictionary stretches over 20 volumes, weighs 138 pounds and so
thoroughly plumbs the history of 640,000 words and phrases that
there would seem to be nothing left to plumb. Shakespeare, its most
quoted author, is cited 33,000 times. There are 20 pages devoted to
the verb ``to set.''
</P>
<P>
   That's nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier last month the mild-mannered dictionary ducked into a
phone booth, put on some high-tech tights and a cape, and emerged
as the Superman of reference works. Its new electronic version does
not fit on any shelf, but it is the first phase of a $55 million,
10-year overhaul that will add more than 600,000 new words _ and
revise the 19th-century entries for many old ones.
</P>
<P>
   The new dictionary isn't cheap. Annual subscriptions cost $795
and higher for institutions and $550 for individuals. But its
editors hope that the format will enable the OED, as the work is
generally known, to reach far more people than it does already,
with most of the users logging on through libraries and
universities (Web site: www.oed.com).
</P>
<P>
   It is hard not to conclude that the electronic format is the
only one expansive enough to allow for the explosion of new English
words and expressions in a language hard-pressed to keep up with
its evolution. Already the format has revolutionized the way
readers can search for words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, if you've got a print dictionary you're limited in
the way you can look through it: You can either look up something
by the head word, or you can browse serendipitously, opening the
book at random for guidance,'' said John Simpson, the dictionary's
chief editor.
</P>
<P>
   But online, he said, you can summon and compare all the
citations that quote Milton, or Mark Twain, or the musician Brian
Eno (Eno is cited for his representative use of the word ambient).
You can ask for a snapshot of the English language in 1492, when
Columbus was still sailing the ocean blue and American English,
frisky and rambunctious as a precocious child, was as yet unborn.
</P>
<P>
   And if _ for reasons known to yourself _ you would like a list
of all the English words that take in every vowel (plus y) in order
(``abstemiously,'' for one), there is nothing to stop you from
getting one.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed recently in the dictionary's vast, cubicled offices,
Simpson, 46, did not seem like someone riding the crest of a
technological and lexicographical revolution, although his desk had
two computers on it and not much paper. He has worked for the OED
since 1976, but the years have not dimmed his enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   He does not play favorites among words. ``There's usually
something interesting you can say about any word,'' he said.
``You're dealing with the whole history of a word, not just its
definition, but the word in the social context in which it
appears.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot has happened to society and the context for language since
1879, when professor James Murray took control of an awesomely
ambitious (and awesomely unrealized, at that point) project to
create an all-inclusive historical tour of the English language. In
Murray's vision, words were followed by their myriad definitions,
etymological roots and quotations illustrating shades of meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Murray had a long gray beard that gave him the appearance of a
Slavic mystic. He also had a single-minded devotion to the cause,
which was helpful because it took 44 more years to complete.
</P>
<P>
   He died at the letter T, though, in 1915. When the last volume
was published 13 years later, it was already on its way to
obsolescence. Among other things, the complicated nature of the
undertaking meant that once a volume was printed, it was impossible
to correct early omissions and errors.
</P>
<P>
   The word African was left out, for instance, a decision Murray
regretted by the time he got to American. (He included American,
even though it was too late for African.) And there was another
problem: the dictionary experimented with editorial styles as it
went along, failing to come up with a uniform system until the
letter M.
</P>
<P>
   Several supplements with younger, spryer words were published
over the years, the most recent appearing in 1986. In 1989 all the
entries were consolidated into what became known as the second
edition. But the dictionary as a whole has never received a
thorough going-over, until now. The vast majority of the words,
definitions and citations date to Murray's day.
</P>
<P>
   Under his stewardship words in the OED came almost exclusively
from the English literary canon, from the earliest Old English
poets to the latest Victorian novelists. Some rude words were left
out, and there were few citations from works published later than
1900. But the current editors, aided by a worldwide network of
volunteers, are consulting documents from the United States,
Australia and other English-speaking countries, and using
nonliterary works from the past and the present.
</P>
<P>
   A written inventory of Henry VIII's holdings after his death,
for instance, has yielded a surprisingly early use of the term
``breakfast table.'' It has also proved the source of the earliest
known use of the adjective ``rat-eaten,'' in descriptions of the
late king's worse-for-wear household linen, said Bernadette Paton,
one of four principal editors at the OED. ``Personal letters,
wills, travel diaries _ they're all a great source that weren't
available to us before,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rechecking all the entries and adding new ones is no easy
matter, even though it is being done by a team of hundreds,
including 60 editors and research assistants at the Oxford
headquarters, 200 consultants in universities and at businesses and
an army of free-lance contributors. So far only a sliver of the
dictionary _ the 1,045 words between the letter M and the word
mahurat (a word of Hindi origin meaning ``an auspicious moment for
beginning an enterprise'') _ has been completely revised.
</P>
<P>
   Some entries, like the Australian phrase ``mad as a meat ax,''
have grown to incorporate new scholarship. Others have been added
wholesale after a rigorous vetting process in which, among other
things, a word has to be cited in print in at least five different
places by five different authors. New words that have made the cut
include Ma-and-Pa store; mack, American slang meaning a
smooth-talking ladies' man; magnum force; and mad cow disease. From
other parts of the alphabet there is himbo (the male equivalent of
a bimbo), mellowing out, post-traumatic stress disorder,
eco-terrorist, get a leg over (British slang for make love) and
e-mail.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Graeme Diamond, 27, a senior assistant editor with longish hair
and eclectic passions, is the resident voice of youth in the OED
office. Under his direction the dictionary is drawing on
contemporary sources from rap music, sports, fashion, politics and
the like.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I really enjoy is finding new things to put in,'' Diamond
said. In a recent instance he was thrilled to unearth documentary
evidence for the expression ``pile of pants,'' British slang for
rubbish or nonsense. (Pants is one of those words that take
different meanings on different sides of the Atlantic: it means
underpants in Britain and trousers in the United States.)
</P>
<P>
   As an expression of displeasure, pile of pants is generally used
in connection with pop culture, as in the example now immortalized
in the OED ``Yup, this is a pile of pants,'' a reviewer said of a
rock concert last year in The Glasgow Herald, ``and no amount of
hip paranoia is going to convince me otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, slangy English is seeping into written language much
faster now than it did 100 years ago, said Edmund Weiner, the OED's
principal philologist, whose business is the origin and history of
words.
</P>
<P>
   ``One hundred years ago it wasn't respectable to put a lot of
colloquial language and slang words into print,'' Weiner said.
``It's only been in the last century that the gap between written
and spoken language has narrowed.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, should something as low-rent as ``pile of pants'' be
allowed in the eminently respectable OED, alongside Chaucerian,
Shakespearean and Faulknerian English?
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely, the dictionary's editors say. As staid as it may
appear to the untrained eye, the OED no longer discriminates
against words that are racy, rude or offensive. It is an
equal-opportunity dictionary, and it embraces whole categories of
words and expressions that, for instance, would never be printed in
The New York Times _ at least not under the paper's current rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The OED is authoritative, but it's not prescriptive,'' said
Jesse Sheidlower, the principal editor of the dictionary's North
American editorial unit. He is an expert on slang who is charged
with bringing in all manner of new American (and Canadian) words
and citations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dictionary tells what the history of the language has been
and how words have been used,'' Sheidlower continued. ``If that
includes words that some people think are ungrammatical or vulgar,
the OED has a responsibility to include them anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   As exotic as the electronic OED might seem, it is still the same
old dictionary at heart. Many of its new words and citations still
come from volunteers, known as readers, who mail in candidates just
as readers did a century ago.
</P>
<P>
   In Murray's day one of the most learned and prolific of the
contributors was an inmate at the Broadmoor Criminal Lunatic Asylum
named Dr. W.C. Minor. Today one of his spiritual descendants is
Stuart Y. Silverstein, who does not live in a mental hospital. (He
lives in Los Angeles.)
</P>
<P>
   Silverstein is a lawyer, the author of ``Not Much Fun: The Lost
Poems of Dorothy Parker'' (1996) and an expert in American usage
from the early 20th century. He became an OED contributor several
years ago when he was trawling through a Life magazine from the
1940s and saw a reference to the noun ``hit,'' in the sense of
murder-for-hire.
</P>
<P>
   He looked the word up in the OED, which gave 1970 as the
earliest known use. And that was the beginning of a beautiful
friendship in which Silverstein has contributed crucial information
about hundreds of words, including pastrami, gimmick and movie
star. The dictionary's editors consider him one of their richest
sources of Americana.
</P>
<P>
   Silverstein said he was motivated by a desire for historical
precision, a feeling of competitiveness and a sense that the
dictionary is an important constant in a fickle world. ``Tomorrow
morning you could wake up and go outside and be hit by a truck,''
he said. ``But have you contributed anything to the world?''
</P>
<P>
   He continued: ``No one's going to remember what I did in law.
But I know that no matter what else happens, I will have done
something to make a contribution to knowledge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
