<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1604 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-ELIAN10-COX     04-09 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OFFICIALS SEE LONG U.S. STAY FOR ELIAN, FATHER AS TRANSFER NEARS
 &HT;    850&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the government prepared to ``do what is
necessary'' this week to transfer Elian Gonzalez to his father,
Justice Department officials said Sunday they expected Juan Miguel
Gonzalez to remain in the United States until a federal appeals
court rules on custody of the boy.
</P>
<P>
   A scheduled meeting Monday between Elian's Miami relatives and a
panel of child psychology experts appeared in doubt after the boy's
21-year-old cousin and primary caretaker, Marisleysis Gonzalez, was
reportedly again hospitalized for exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whether that meeting takes place, attorneys for
Lazaro Gonzalez, the great-uncle who has been caring for the
6-year-old Cuban rafter since late November, prepared to file
another round of court petitions designed to block Attorney General
Janet Reno's order that he be transferred to his father this week.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder repeated that they
expect the Miami relatives to agree to a peaceful transfer of
custody. ``We will do what is necessary to reunite father and son,
however,'' Holder insisted.
</P>
<P>
   With a climax to the months-long drama apparently only days
away, events Sunday occurred on three fronts:
</P>
<P>
   _ In Washington, Elian's father met with the
government-appointed psychologists and with the Florida fishermen
who rescued his son.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Miami, demonstrations by those opposed to the boy's return
to Cuba continued. About 40 cars draped with banners formed a noisy
procession through city streets, and about 200 demonstrators
continued their vigil near the Little Havana house where Elian is
staying.
</P>
<P>
   _ Justice officials and others involved in the case presented
their arguments in a round of television talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting described as emotional, Juan Miguel Gonzalez met
with Sam Ciancio and Donato Dalrymple, the two cousins who found
Elian floating in an inner tube three miles off Fort Lauderdale on
Nov. 25. Elian's mother and 10 others died when their boat sank
while fleeing Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The fishermen, who have said they want Elian to remain in the
United States, said they were warmly greeted by Juan Miguel, who
offered to have them visit his son in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was eternally grateful to me. He embraced me. And you can
tell that it was not fabricated,'' Dalrymple said. He said Juan
Miguel ``feels so bad ... he feels that his boy has been held back
from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez also met with the psychologists at the office of his
attorney, Gregory Craig, according to Craig, who gave no details of
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Holder, appearing on several news programs, said they
expected Juan Miguel Gonzalez to remain in the United States until
the appeals process was completed. However, they differed slightly
over whether the government would force Gonzalez to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, in a CNN interview, said she thought the father would
voluntarily agree to remain during the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Holder, appearing on NBC, acknowledged that the Justice
Department had the legal authority to order the father to stay in
the United States. ``If we had to, we would be prepared to do
that,'' Holder said. ``But, as I said, I don't think we're going to
have to.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig, also appearing on NBC, said his client was prepared to
remain in the United States during the appeal, which he predicted
could last up to 10 months. He repeated Gonzalez's request that a
group of Elian's classmates and teachers be allowed to come to the
United States as a ``support group.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she did not believe the appeals process would last
that long and made no comment on whether the expanded group would
be allowed to join Juan Miguel here.
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez has appealed to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Atlanta to overturn a federal court ruling upholding a
previous federal order giving Juan Miguel sole authority to speak
on Elian's behalf on immigration matters. A hearing on that appeal
is set for May 11.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, his attorneys planned to file a petition Monday in
state court in Miami challenging the father's fitness as a parent
and seeking to award custody to Lazaro.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Garcia-Pedrosa, an attorney representing the Miami
relatives, claimed on CBS that Juan Miguel Gonzalez had a ``violent
temperament. That's why he divorced Elisabeth,'' Elian's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia-Pedrosa claimed that Elian ``has told psychiatrists that
he is deathly afraid of his father, because his father beat him
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder, appearing on the same program, said there was no
evidence that Juan Miguel Gonzalez was an unfit parent and noted
that such suggestions have surfaced only in the past few days as
Elian's transfer appeared imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, in her CNN interview, said Juan Miguel Gonzalez apparently
had been a good father.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very special little boy. His father did a darn good
job raising him until he was 6, along with his mother. It's time we
reunited them. And, it's time we do it in a peaceful way. Elian
deserves that,'' Reno said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Still unresolved late Sunday was how the family would respond to
the instructions that they meet with the panel of psychologists and
help transfer Elian to his father.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Reno dated Saturday but released Sunday, Lazaro
Gonzalez said, ``It is my family's wish that all of us be present
at the meeting together,'' and added he was certain the experts
would want to meet with Marisleysis.
</P>
<P>
   A family spokesman said it was doubtful Marisleysis would be
physically able to meet with the experts on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Osberg-Braun, another attorney for Lazaro Gonzalez, said
the family objected to the terms of the meeting with the experts.
She said the family would prefer that the panel interview Elian and
determine whether he would be psychologically harmed by being
uprooted from the Miami relatives, particularly Marisleysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This little boy is going to lose his mother figure for a
second time,'' Osberg-Braun said on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, acknowledging the bond Elian has formed with the Miami
relatives, nevertheless said the four months he has spent with them
were not enough to outweigh the nearly six years he spent with his
father.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and Holder again denied reports the government has
finalized plans to use force to remove Elian from his Miami
relatives if they refuse to voluntarily relinquish him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not received, nor reviewed, nor approved any plans that
would do that,'' Reno said on CNN. But she said Justice officials
were preparing responses to various possible scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   Holder called suggestions that the government would move in on
the house in the middle of the night to seize Elian
``inflammatory,'' and ``totally untrue. ... The government does not
plan to rip him out of the house in the middle of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Osberg-Braun said the Miami relatives would not forcibly resist
government agents if they came to the house in Miami to take Elian,
but she said she did not think Lazaro would ``morally'' agree to
take him somewhere else to meet his father.
</P>
<P>
   She said the family wants Juan Miguel to come to the Miami house
to get Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said Juan Miguel Gonzalez would be willing to travel to
another neutral place to pick up his son, but would not travel to
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``The circumstances in Miami are so fragile, so passionate, so
emotional that it would be bad for Elian, and we have ruled that
out,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   Osberg-Braun said the family would not try to inhibit the
hundreds of protestors who have been filing the street outside the
house in Little Havana from making a human chain to resist such an
action. And she warned that Elian would be emotionally disturbed by
the prospect of being forced out of the house through the crowd of
shouting protestors.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
