<HEADER>
A1605 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-FALCONE-FLOP-NYT &LR;      04-09 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-FALCONE-FLOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS WONDERS WHERE `FALCONE' WENT WRONG 
</HEADLINE>
   By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Was ``Falcone'' throttled by ``The Sopranos''? Did
the new CBS series about the Mafia prove too tame in contrast to
the darkly funny, profane and complex HBO show about New Jersey
mobsters? Was CBS's core audience, traditionally older and female
viewers, simply turned off by all the violence? Or is there simply
Mafia overkill in television and movies?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, ``Falcone,'' a heavily promoted series
based loosely on the 1997 movie ``Donnie Brasco,'' has performed
dismally in its first few nights. And CBS executives, who said
post-mortems have begun on the series, are wondering why
``Falcone'' has been such a disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   No decision has been made about the future of ``Falcone,'' which
had a tepidly received two-hour premiere last Tuesday. Not only did
the show come in at No. 3 in its first hour, but its audience
dropped sharply in its second hour, an obvious sign of flagging
viewer interest. The show, which spans eight nights, continued
through the week, skipped Sunday night, and picks up again Monday
night through its final episode on Wednesday. No other shows have
been filmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really badly,'' said Mark Johnson, one of the executive
producers of the series. ``CBS did everything possible that they
could. I was almost embarrassed at how much they promoted the show.
But it's clear that we didn't open, to use a movie term. Our
numbers weren't very good. And for some reason the show didn't
appeal to the CBS audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who also was a producer of ``Donnie Brasco,'' said the
shadow of ``The Sopranos'' weighed heavily on ``Falcone.'' He said:
``Every review mentioned `The Sopranos.' We have an entirely
different show. What can you do?''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Ender, senior vice president for communications at CBS
Entertainment, said: ``We developed a terrific show and supported
it with an aggressive programming and promotion strategy. It
doesn't appear to be working but we're proud that we tried it. In a
changing marketplace, we cannot shy away from trying things
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS is hardly alone in its disappointment for its newest show.
Another new series, ABC's ``Wonderland,'' which has stirred even
more publicity than ``Falcone'' and is about a hospital for the
criminally insane, has also failed to lure audiences, perhaps
because its subject is dark and intense. Like that of ``Falcone,''
the future of ``Wonderland'' is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Falcone'' is based on the story of Joseph Pistone, a former
undercover agent for the Federal Bureau of Investigation who led a
double life as a suburban father working for the government and an
ambitious mobster named Joe Falcone. Pistone was an adviser to the
show, which stars Jason Gedrick as Falcone and Titus Welliver as a
mobster.
</P>
<P>
   The reviews for the show were mixed, comparing it negatively to
``The Sopranos,'' but also raising questions about whether
``Falcone'' broke any new ground in the Mafia genre. As television
executives repeatedly point out, the viewing audience of HBO's
``Sopranos'' is small, at around 6.4 million for its Sunday night
episodes, compared to network audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The Mafia genre has been heavily mined in films like Francis
Ford Coppola's classic ``Godfather'' movies, as well as Martin
Scorsese' ``Goodfellas'' and ``Casino'' and comedies like ``Married
to the Mob,'' directed by Jonathan Demme, and ``Analyze This,''
directed by Harold Ramis.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset executives at CBS as well as other networks were
surprised, if not startled, by the weak response to ``Falcone.'' In
the first hour of its premiere, the series came in third after
ABC's ``Dharma and Greg'' and ``Sports Night,'' and NBC's ``Will
and Grace'' and ``Just Shoot Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more significant was the drop-off in the second hour. In
its first hour ``Falcone'' had 11.6 million viewers. In its second
hour the number dropped to 9.3 million. It didn't help ``Falcone''
that ABC's ``NYPD Blue'' was its rival in that second hour, with an
audience of 15.5 million. The No. 2 show, ``Dateline NBC,'' had
13.1 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   After the premiere ``Falcone'' lagged behind its rivals. On
Wednesday, for example, the show was No. 3 with only 7 million
viewers, in contrast with NBC's ``Law and Order,'' with 18 million
viewers, and ABC's ``20/20,'' with 12.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend the number of viewers of ``Falcone'' picked up
a bit. On Friday 8.6 million viewers watched ``Falcone,'' behind
ABC's ``20/20'' (11.9 million) and NBC's ``Law and Order: Special
Victim's Unit'' (10 million). On Saturday ``Falcone,'' with 9.5
million viewers, came in second after the ABC broadcast of the film
``First Knight,'' with Richard Gere and Sean Connery (9.6 million
over three hours).
</P>
<P>
   But CBS was hardly upbeat about ``Falcone.'' A top CBS executive
said: ``Was the show, demographically, too much of a reach for our
audience? Was the promotion on target? Was it too mobster, or not
mobster enough?''
</P>
<P>
   Another CBS executive, who also spoke on condition of anonymity,
said there was some feeling that offering the series over eight
nights may have backfired, and that audiences probably did not want
to invest virtually every night in the same show. CBS officials
pointed out that several years ago the network made the mini-series
``Mario Puzo's The Last Don,'' which also starred Gedrick, and was
imitative of the author's ``Godfather.'' It proved highly
successful.
</P>
<P>
   But some rival network executives said that CBS, in seeking a
younger, male audience with ``Falcone,'' may have stretched the
limit for its core viewers. The network is populated by such
successful series as ``Judging Amy,'' ``King of Queens,'' ``Nash
Bridges'' and ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' which are especially
popular among older men and women. Trying to broaden a network's
reach can be hard: NBC recently had a cartoon series, ``God, the
Devil and Bob,'' which failed perhaps because that network's
audience was unaccustomed to such a show.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the producer of ``Falcone,'' said no one could be
faulted for its performance. ``CBS went out on a limb to support
`Falcone,''' he said. ``It was an attempt to appeal to a different
audience.''
</P>
<P>
   Has he given up on the show? Johnson spoke candidly. ``It's not
my nature to give up,'' he said. ``I'm not conceding defeat, but
I'd be a liar if I said we were in good shape.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
