<HEADER>
A1610 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SOFT-LITIGATION-NYT &LR;      04-09 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFT-LITIGATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD MICROSOFT'S FATE BE IN PRIVATE HANDS?  

</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a federal judge ruling last week that Microsoft repeatedly
violated the law, the government has the easy part of the antitrust
case behind it. The real policy challenge comes now: what are the
right remedies?
</P>
<P>
   Last week's ruling came because of the breakdown of four months
of settlement talks _ mediated by Judge Richard A. Posner, a
federal jurist who is regarded as one of the leading thinkers on
antitrust _ in which the two sides could not agree on the
appropriate remedies.
</P>
<P>
   Robert E. Hall, an economist at Stanford University, has a novel
recommendation for the government. ``Just declare victory and walk
away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very effective means of dealing with the Microsoft
problem _ our system of private litigation,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   A senior fellow at the Hoover Institution and co-author of the
original flat-tax proposal in the early 1980s, Hall is a
conservative who believes antitrust laws are essential rules for
the health of free-market capitalism. He advised the Justice
Department's antitrust division on an earlier Microsoft case and is
also a respected economist who has been mentioned as a candidate
for the Nobel prize.
</P>
<P>
   Hall believes Microsoft's main offense was its restrictive
contracts and behavior, which artificially raised the barrier to
entry by potential challengers to Microsoft. He has devised a
method for measuring the damage the company's behavior caused to
consumers, and he explained his approach in a paper presented at
the American Economic Association's annual conference in January.
</P>
<P>
   Using rough assumptions, the Hall paper concluded the economic
damage from Microsoft's practices amounted to overcharging about
$10 for each copy of its Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Hall said the overcharge calculation could well
be higher, depending on what assumptions are used, so the total
damage caused by Microsoft's practices in recent years could be
more than $7 billion. And that is before the triple damages called
for in private antitrust suits.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you charge Microsoft three times the cost of the harm, it
is a huge disincentive to engaging in the same kind of
anticompetitive conduct ever again,'' said Hall, who added he has
no interest in serving as an expert witness in any of the private
suits against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Litan, a former justice department official who is
director of economic studies at the Brookings Institution, said
that if the government followed Hall's modest proposal, it would be
an ``utter abdication of governmental responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The government does not bring antitrust suits to prepare the
ground for private litigants, he said, but to ensure remedial steps
are taken to stop illegal behavior by a monopolist and prevent it
in the future.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Litan said he had doubts about how well the private
litigants will do against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Microsoft is ready to fight a major war in the private
cases,'' he said. ``Its experts will argue that there is no proof
that consumers suffered from Microsoft's conduct. And there is not
a lot of evidence in the government's case of the current damage
that consumers suffered.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-00 1850EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
