<DOCNO> NYT20000409.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 18:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NC-FILM-NOTEBOOK-1135     04-09 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-FILM-NOTEBOOK-1135(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: NO SWELLING UNSEEN CHORUSES, JUST HARD TRUTH ON
FILM 
</HEADLINE>
   By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. _ The air here on Thursday evening was soft and
warm, the gentle denouement to a perfect southern spring day of
80-degree temperatures and sultry breezes.
</P>
<P>
   But on one of the three screens in the Carolina Theater, a
handsomely restored Beaux-Arts cinema in the center of the city, a
band of explorers was risking death from exposure and starvation as
they weathered the brutal extremity of the polar climate with
dwindling supplies and failing equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the 35-mm cameras they had brought along by ice
boat, seaplane and dirigible on their expeditions across Antarctica
and the ice fields of the frozen North did not fail. The explorers
_ lonely, silent figures etched into the blankness of the landscape
like figures drawn on an empty page _ were accompanying Roald
Amundsen, the Norwegian adventurer whose life and legend are the
subject of ``Frozen Hearts,'' a new documentary by Stig Andersen
and Kenny Sanders that opened the third annual Double Take
Documentary Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frozen Hearts'' is a curious, unwitting collaboration between
filmmaker and subject. Amundsen, whose plane was lost over the
Arctic before the advent of sound film, shot his earlier treks with
the intention of recording his own intrepid heroism, but Andersen
and Sanders use the film he and his crews shot, along with
re-enactments and mordant voice-over narration, to rub some of the
luster from Amundsen's self-burnished legend and to bring to light
the narcissism and callousness lurking beneath his undeniable
bravery.
</P>
<P>
   A documentary is a film that uses real people to tell a true
story. This definition turns out to be as complex as it is
straightforward. Over the four days of the festival, which is
affiliated with the Center for Documentary Studies at Duke
University, 50 films, culled from more than 400 submissions, were
shown in competition for jury and audience awards. An additional
two dozen or so appeared as part of special out-of-competition
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The jury prize was awarded to ``The Way I Look at You: Five
Stories of Driving School,'' by Jean-Stephane Bron, which deals
with the offbeat interactions between driving instructors and their
students.
</P>
<P>
   The audience award was shared by Edward Rosenstein's ``The
Gospel According to Allen,'' an examination of life in a Harlem
drug-treatment center, and Linda Duvoisin's ``You Don't Know What I
Got,'' an intimate look at the lives of five American women. At the
prompting of an audience member the jury added an award for best
short film to Eugene Richards for ``But, the Day Came,'' about a
92-year-old Nebraska farmer.
</P>
<P>
   It was impossible to see everything at what is the largest
festival of its kind in North America, and it was also impossible
not to be struck by the elasticity and capaciousness of the
documentary form.
</P>
<P>
   Though the range of subjects was impressive _ from Amundsen to
the late Alabama Gov. George Wallace to the illustrator Barry
Moser, from the inmates at a juvenile detention center to devotees
of fast-pitch softball to the members of a Bombay ``laughing club''
_ the films also displayed a remarkable diversity of visual styles,
narrative methods and influences.
</P>
<P>
   D.A. Pennebaker and Chris Hegedus, who were at the festival to
receive its lifetime achievement award, represent the still-lively
tradition of cinema verite that was pioneered by filmmakers like
Albert Maysles, Richard Leacock and Pennebaker himself in the
1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Their best-known work from that era, like ``Don't Look Back,''
Pennebaker's film about Bob Dylan, was made according to the
principle that the filmmaker should be as unobtrusive as possible,
allowing the story to tell itself and forswearing devices like
narration, interviews and music. But Pennebaker and Hegedus, a
married couple whose films together include ``Town Bloody Hall,''
``The War Room'' and ``Moon Over Broadway,'' don't regard
themselves as purists.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no rules,'' Pennebaker remarked during a panel
discussion on Friday on the subject ``representing reality.'' The
power of documentary derives not from any set of formal procedures
but from the relationship between the filmmakers and their subject.
``The audience should never lose the sense of that relationship,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of the films shown in competition, including ``The
Sound and the Fury'' by Josh Aronson, about a deaf family, and Liz
Garbus' ``Juvies,'' which follows three teen-agers through the
Maryland juvenile justice system, share this ethic. ``I try to open
myself to the characters and let them lead the story,'' Garbus
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another filmmaker whose influence was clearly in evidence was
Ken Burns, who showed a portion of his 10-part, 18{-hour series
``Jazz'' (to be broadcast on PBS in January) on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Burns' style _ slow pans across still photographs accompanied by
evocative music, sonorous narrative alternating with talking-head
recollections and interpretations, individual stories flowing like
tributaries into a larger narrative stream _ is immediately
recognizable.
</P>
<P>
   It has become the standard for public-television historical
documentaries like his brother Ric's ``New York'' series (part of
which was shown here), Barak Goodman's somber ``Scottsboro: An
American Tragedy'' and Peter Stekler and Daniel McCabe's boisterous
``George Wallace: Settin' the Woods on Fire,'' also festival
entries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The documentary,'' Burns said in an interview, ``offers not
only unlimited subject matter but the widest possible spectrum of
stylistic approaches.''
</P>
<P>
   It is also an impulse that finds expression in a variety of
media. Burns shoots and edits on film, as did Pennebaker and
Hegedus until last year, but the field is increasingly dominated by
video, which is cheaper and more portable than film and which makes
up for its relative lack of visual depth and beauty with a sense of
immediacy and verisimilitude.
</P>
<P>
   The accessibility of the new technology means that filmmakers
can shoot first and look for production money and distribution
later. Sheila Nevins, vice president in charge of documentary
programming at HBO, who received the festival's industry award,
used to receive written proposals from filmmakers hoping to sell
their movies to her network. Now she receives videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   Nevins _ whose productions include this year's Oscar-winning
``King Gimp,'' and Alan and Susan Raymond's ``Children in War''
(shown in competition here), as well as late-night soft-porn
sociology series like ``Taxicab Confessions'' and ``Real Sex'' _
said in a telephone interview: ``It used to be that to tell your
story in a moving picture was a costly thing. Now someone can make
a film for nothing and sell it to us. They can shoot on their own,
edit at the kitchen table and sell it to HBO.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Though all of the festival entries were projected on wide
screens in spacious, ornate theaters, the largest of which even has
a balcony and mezzanine, they are most likely to be seen in the
future on television.
</P>
<P>
   PBS and HBO are established outlets for nonfiction movies, as
are basic cable channels like A&AMP;E, Discovery and the History
Channel. But the most visible presence at this year's festival was
MTV, which was a major sponsor and which presented a special
program on youth called ``Outside Looking In: Coming of Age
Stories,'' with the director Alan Berliner as curator.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the films in competition were included in this program,
along with relevant older works like Frederick Wiseman's ``High
School'' (1968), Martin Bell's ``Streetwise'' (1984) and David Van
Taylor's ``Dream Deceivers,'' a film made in 1993 for PBS about a
Nevada teen-ager whose parents blamed his suicide attempt on the
heavy-metal band Judas Priest.
</P>
<P>
   The issues Van Taylor explored _ the relationship among
violence, family and popular culture in the lives of American young
people _ have been a staple of MTV's news and documentary
programming in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionalists may object to MTV's fast cutting and jazzy
camera angles, as well as to its canny use of popular music to
underscore _ or undermine _ what is being said on camera. But
Lauren Lazin, the channel's vice president in charge of news and
documentaries, said these techniques reflect the sensibilities of a
sophisticated, media-savvy audience while upholding the basic
documentary tenet of telling stories truthfully and
sympathetically.
</P>
<P>
   And MTV, which showed some 30-second public-service
announcements as part of its presentation, has sufficient faith in
its audience's attention span to have begun co-producing
feature-length documentaries like Banks Tarver's ``I'm a Pro
Wrestler'' and Garbus' ``Travelers,'' about a group of homeless
young people.
</P>
<P>
   Films like these will jostle for attention on a broadcast
spectrum crowded with ``reality programming'' of every kind and
quality. But a festival like this one offers a sustained,
concentrated exposure to the sheer emotional power of documentary
filmmaking, its ability to communicate the drama embedded in human
experience. In Durham last week you could walk into the stately
dark of the Carolina Theater and lose yourself in real life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
