<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1613 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH0410-COX     04-09 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH0410-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush prepares priorities for 2001 legislative sessionBy Ken
Herman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In his Capitol office last week, sandwiched
between coast-to-coast presidential campaigning in Pennsylvania and
California, Gov. George W. Bush dropped in for some cramming toward
something he hopes to miss: the 2001 session of the Texas
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush priorities, in the embryonic stages at the staff level,
include transportation, math and efforts to preserve his legacy
after he is gone, sooner or later. The governor acknowledges all
these issues could be overshadowed by the anticipated battle to
redraw legislative districts, but he has decided to let lawmakers
take the lead on this issue, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush hopes the nation's voters will make it sooner by handing
him the White House keys in November. The 2001 legislative session
opens Jan. 9. The next president takes office Jan. 20, though Bush
might resign from his current job before then if he is elected
president.
</P>
<P>
   The peculiarities of working toward a legislative session the
boss hopes to avoid are not lost on Bush aides.
</P>
<P>
   ``We come to work every day and play like this really means
something,'' said Terral Smith, Bush's top legislative aide. ``And
it might. You never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, while Bush was in a meeting on transportation
issues, the man who could be governor next January was meeting with
key legislators in his Capitol office. Republican Lt. Gov. Rick
Perry expects Bush to become president, which means Perry expects
to become governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the constitution requires that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It all adds up to an unprecedented run-up to a Texas legislative
session as Bush tries to become the first incumbent Republican
governor to win the White House since Ohio's William McKinley did
it in 1896.
</P>
<P>
   If he fails, Bush would become the first Texas governor to serve
during four consecutive legislative sessions. Last year, halfway
through the third session, Bush aides already were bemoaning the
difficulty in coming up with ideas and enthusiasm for a fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Bush insists there is no lack of either. During a campaign-trail
interview last month, Bush was asked if he is preparing for the
legislative session he may not see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush took a pass when asked to name some legislative
priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``My staff has been working on something,'' he said. ``I will
sit down and visit them about it, but I intend to win. But this
summer I'm going to spend some time (working on legislation). Our
staff has been working on some ideas. I will discuss it after they
brief me.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith says it's not hard to get Bush's attention _ when he is in
town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier than one might suspect because when you get him in
the office he seems to like to work on these issues,'' said Smith.
``It's like a respite from the other campaign, and my view from
just watching him and listening to him is that this is so easy for
him compared to the national campaign and maybe some of the
national issues. He is so familiar with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't found that his mind is somewhere else when he is
with us _ when we've got him in the office,'' Smith said. ``And
that's about a day and a half a week right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Transportation, targeted as a key quality-of-life issue, is a
primary part of the Bush package being ginned up in case Al Gore
becomes president. At the heart of the issue is a desire to
streamline the road-building process.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a culture in the Texas Department of Transportation
that we need to begin to break, and it's a culture that makes
things go slow,'' said one Bush adviser. ``It's a culture of, 'This
is the way we've always done it and it's always worked.'''
</P>
<P>
   One thing getting attention from Bush's staff is the possibility
of spending up to $1 billion _ half in cash, half in bonds _ to
build more beds for a state prison system about to hit capacity
again, as well as provide pay increases for prison guards. Finding
money for health insurance for teachers also is on the drawing
board. Currently, the state does not help pay for insurance
premiums and local districts have the option to help.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, between surplus and anticipated new revenue, early
projections show Texas lawmakers could have an additional $5
billion to spend for the next two-year budget cycle. The current
two-year budget totals $98.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   On education, a Bush priority in previous sessions, the governor
wants to focus on math as he has on reading in previous years,
including special training for teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the works is a strategy to protect his legacy. The
governor's staff is looking for lawmakers _ preferably younger ones
who will be around for a while _ to fend off future efforts to undo
key portions of Bush's programs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's long-range impact on state government also is being
addressed through the appointments process. Many of his first
appointees, named in 1995, come to the end of their terms next
February. Bush can begin appointing a new round of appointees to
serve another six years.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has began making changes in leadership at major state
agencies, naming new chairs for the Texas Lottery Commission, Texas
Department of Transportation and Texas Real Estate Commission, with
others expected.
</P>
<P>
   Come January, if Bush is gone, his legislative package would be
passed on to Perry in an advisory capacity. Perry, who already has
staked out higher education as his priority issue, says he would be
glad to take a look at anything Bush leaves behind.
</P>
<P>
   Perry says his staff has been in close touch with Bush's, but a
source in the governor's office says it's been something of a
balancing effort to make sure that House Speaker Pete Laney, a
Democrat who has worked well with Bush, doesn't get his nose out of
joint.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, when Laney _ something of a natural legislative rival
of Perry _ had an inkling that Bush was working with Perry on
appointments, he made it clear it was not appreciated. In no
uncertain terms, Laney let Bush's staff know that Perry is not yet
the governor of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Perry has doubts that the 21st century's first
legislative session will be one for the ages.
</P>
<P>
   ``During a session that a substantial number of the members are
going to be focused on redistricting, I think the idea that this is
going to be an ambitious session on any issue would be a stretch,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
