<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, April 10, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Snow flurries will linger over northern New England and winds
will slowly diminish as an intense storm pushes north to Labrador.
Dry, chilly weather will persist over southern New England.
</P>
<P>
   A new storm will develop quickly over Kansas and spread
inclement conditions into the Middle West and southern Great Lakes.
There will be light to moderate snow, with accumulations of up to
several inches, from Fargo, N.D., to Milwaukee. A cold rain will
soak much of Iowa and thunderstorms will develop over Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   A flow of warm and more humid air from the Gulf of Mexico will
cause thundershowers in Texas. Stronger storms may develop Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered showers will accompany low pressure near the Four
Corners. High pressure building into the Pacific Northwest will
drive low clouds offshore in some sections. The Southwest will turn
cooler with ample sun.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Ground Zero
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the mercury rose to 76 degrees in Albany, N.Y.,
before a sharp cold front reached the Hudson Valley. By Sunday
afternoon, over a foot of snow had fallen on the capital district,
driven by 30-mph winds. This April snowstorm was the third-largest
on record since 1884. An exceptionally intense low-pressure system
formed over Long Island, N.Y., and moved slowly along the New
England coast, as frigid air swept into eastern New York. Another
period of snow is possible by Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
