<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAKED-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NAKED': MIRA SORVINO TWISTS IN UNFORGIVING WINDS OF LIVE THEATER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Opportunities for emotional connection between actors
and audience are scarce in the clueless new revival of Luigi
Pirandello's ``Naked,'' which opened Sunday night at the Classic
Stage Co. in one of those productions that make you want to look
anywhere but at the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Still, every so often, a blurring of the lines between
performers and theatergoers occurs that might, in a pinch, qualify
as Pirandellian. This occurs every time the evening's star, Mira
Sorvino, looking wan and exhausted, clutches her stomach in a
gesture that suggests something more piercing than mere gastric
distress.
</P>
<P>
   You get the fleeting impression that some transubstantiated part
of her has joined the spectators in the dark and been forced to
observe what's going on up there in the footlights. Ouch. It really
hurts.
</P>
<P>
   Watching a gifted film actress, which Sorvino undeniably is,
twist in the unforgiving winds of live theater isn't much fun, but
the experience appears to be on its way to becoming a tradition at
the Classic Stage Co. Last year the troupe gave us Uma Thurman
battling her way through the rhymed couplets of Moliere's
``Misanthrope'' like an unclothed baby in a briar patch.
</P>
<P>
   Now here is Sorvino, the Oscar-winning star of ``Mighty
Aphrodite,'' wrestling with a role defined by its very lack of
identity, something the actress principally suggests by keeping her
voice low, soft and flat. One is grateful to the Classic Stage Co.
for encouraging vital young screen talents to cut their teeth in
the New York theater. But surely this could be achieved with
projects a little easier on the molars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naked,'' a 1922 tale of a modern-day Melisande adrift in a
world of exploitative men, isn't easy to bite into under the best
of circumstances. Avoiding the diverting, form-bending mind games
of such better-known works by Pirandello as ``Six Characters in
Search of an Author,'' the play is instead a harrowing philosophy
lesson masquerading as a straightforward melodrama.
</P>
<P>
   It's a fascinating work, with its intimations that the greatest
human fear is not of death but of formlessness, of the lack of any
shaping personality. It received a London production from the
Almeida Theater in 1998, starring Juliette Binoche (another
Oscar-winning actress, by the way), that critics described as
riveting. But it's a wordy, often florid piece, and you can
understand why it is so seldom staged.
</P>
<P>
   The director, John Rando, who has shown a deft hand for comedy
on other occasions, has brought no discernible point of view to
``Naked,'' which is performed here in a new translation by the
dramatist Nicholas Wright. Indeed, the only confident interpretive
elements of the production are technical, manifested in Derek
McLane's set, Russell H. Champa's lighting and David Van Tieghem's
sound, which collectively suggest an uneasy interpenetration of
public and private worlds.
</P>
<P>
   At the play's center is Ersilia Drei (Sorvino), a beautiful and
cryptic young woman whose attempted suicide has been chronicled
breathlessly in the Italian newspapers. The tragedy that inspired
the attempt is rehashed by a novelist (Daniel Benzali) who has
taken her in as a resident muse, a journalist (Bray Poor), the
novelist's prurient landlady (Rebecca Schull) and two pompous,
upper-class men from Ersilia's past (Peter Rini and Michel R.
Gill). The flow of information, as rendered here, is not what you
would call fluid.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the overall effect is of people with headsets, as at a
United Nations conference, waiting for translations of what the
others have said before responding. There may be some thematic
point to this disjunctiveness, but here it registers as
amateurishly stilted.
</P>
<P>
   Her dark eyes feverishly aglitter in a deathly pale face,
Sorvino is a compelling presence when she takes her first tentative
steps onto the stage. Soon enough, however, the boundaries between
the discomfort of the character and of the actress portraying her
start to melt in ways that do nothing to enrich the play.
</P>
<P>
   Sorvino, whose sharp-edged portraits on film are notable for
their attention to vocal accent and timbre, is being asked to
create a woman who is effectively without a voice, who is
existentially naked. The resulting exposure is far more unfair and
unflattering than any physical nudity might be.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `NAKED'
</P>
<P>
   By Luigi Pirandello, in a new version by Nicholas Wright;
directed by John Rando; sets by Derek McLane; costumes by Ilona
Somogyi; lighting by Russell H. Champa; sound by David Van Tieghem;
production stage manager, Karyn Meek; general manager, Jason
Loewith. Presented by the Classic Stage Co., Barry Edelstein,
artistic director; Beth Emelson, producing director. At 136 E. 13th
St., East Village.
</P>
<P>
   With: Mira Sorvino (Ersilia Drei), Daniel Benzali (Ludovico
Nota), Rebecca Schull (Signora Onoria), Bray Poor (Alfredo
Cantavalle), Peter Rini (Franco Laspiga), Tina Bruno (Emma) and
Michel R. Gill (Consul Grotti).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
