<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENDERSON'S CRASH AND MEDIA BOYCOTT PART OF METS WACKY SEASON  
 RUSCH RETURNS  
 HAMILTON OPTIMISTIC  
 ANOTHER SNOW DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bobby Valentine has seen enough in his career to know
that in baseball, the unusual is common. So when the Mets' manager
showed up at Shea Stadium at 7:30 a.m. Sunday and was greeted by
harsh winds and a snow-covered field, he was bemused but not
surprised. The Mets' game against the Los Angeles Dodgers was
snowed out, another strange-but-true tale in an already eventful
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``If abnormal is regular, as I feel it is,'' Valentine said,
``then this will be another regular, wacky, abnormal season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets and Dodgers will make up the game at 7:10 p.m. on April
24, a day on which the Mets had been scheduled off during a
homestand and the Dodgers were scheduled to travel from Cincinnati
to Atlanta. Sunday's game was the first that had been snowed out at
Shea since an exhibition with the Yankees on March 31, 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The game was postponed as most of the Mets were arriving at the
ballpark; some then took the team bus to Philadelphia, where the
Mets start a three-game series with the Phillies on Monday night.
Other players received permission to travel on their own Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Driving to Shea Stadium in the difficult conditions Sunday
morning, outfielder Rickey Henderson was involved in a minor
accident. Henderson's car was hit from behind just before getting
on the Grand Central Parkway, after he had left the Triborough
Bridge. Henderson's car was knocked into a guardrail and hit again
as the other car spun around.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson hit his head in the accident, but neither he nor the
other driver was hospitalized. Henderson continued on to Shea,
where he was examined by Mets trainers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We evaluated his condition and he seems to be OK,'' said the
trainer Fred Hina, who added Henderson was given no specific
treatment. ``There's no concussion. He's fine. Fortunately, the car
got the worst end of the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson did not have much to add. ``I'm alive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The 41-year-old leadoff hitter, who has said his focus has
wavered because of unhappiness with his contract, said he is
boycotting the news media for a month. To illustrate why, he tore
off a newspaper article with the headline ``Rickey Must Go'' and
affixed it to the back of a television set hanging from the ceiling
in the middle of the Mets' clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a month,'' Henderson told reporters. ``I know you
went to school and they told you what a month is.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson's saga has been only one sideshow in a season already
filled with them. The Mets began the season in Japan, of course, so
they opened spring training earlier than most clubs. Valentine
conceded that it feels later in the year than it is.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's day off, then, was welcomed. The Mets would have been
without relievers Armando Benitez, who had worked three days in a
row, and Pat Mahomes, who started on Saturday. Another reliever,
Rich Rodriguez, sprained an ankle on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't like to play a game as many guys short as we were
today,'' Valentine said.  &QL; 
RUSCH RETURNS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Mets activated the left-hander Glendon Rusch Sunday, and
optioned the right-hander Eric Cammack to Class AAA Norfolk. Rusch
was scheduled to start Sunday, but his turn in the rotation will be
skipped and Bobby J. Jones will face the Phillies Monday night, as
planned.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said Rusch will be available for relief work and will
start in Pittsburgh on Saturday or Sunday. Al Leiter's turn comes
up on Friday in Pittsburgh, but he has a strained groin and will
test it Monday by throwing 20 to 25 pitches in a simulated game at
Veterans Stadium. Mahomes, who worked five and two-thirds strong
innings in Leiter's place Saturday, will start for Leiter again if
needed, Valentine said.  &QL; 
HAMILTON OPTIMISTIC &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Darryl Hamilton did not accompany the Mets to
Philadelphia; he is on the disabled list with a sprained left foot
and will meet with a doctor Monday to determine how to treat the
injury. The 35-year-old Hamilton has been discouraged by the
lingering pain that accompanies his arthritic left big toe, but he
believes Monday's meeting will answer a lot of his questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that somehow, some way it will work out,'' he said.
``I'm not really too worried about it.''  &QL; 
RODRIGUEZ SAYS HE'S READY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rich Rodriguez aggravated a problem with his left ankle in the
weight room Saturday, but told Valentine he was available to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years ago, I tweaked it in spring training,'' Rodriguez
said. ``It just flared up today. I told them I was ready, yesterday
and today.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez then joked that he got recognized for a minor ankle
injury, but not for the three scoreless innings he worked last
Wednesday. The left-hander, who was signed as a free agent from the
San Francisco Giants in January, enjoyed the lengthy relief stint;
he worked only 56 2/3 innings last year, his fewest in a full major
league season since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   He said he worked with Mets pitching coach Dave Wallace on
placing his foot in front of the middle of the rubber, instead of
toward the first base side. Rodriguez had been flying open with his
front shoulder when he tried to throw inside to right-handed
hitters.  &QL; 
ANOTHER SNOW DAY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mets outfielder Jon Nunnally was a pinch-hitter for the Kansas
City Royals at the Yankees' home opener in 1996, when it snowed in
the Bronx. Sunday's conditions at Shea were worse, Nunnally said,
but not by much.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a blizzard,'' he said. ``But it was snowing that day _
big flakes. Late in the game it started doing it, but it was
already freezing cold. We just kept playing on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
