<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HBO DOCUMENTARY MAKES BILL RUSSELL UNDERSTANDABLE, AND WARM 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bill Russell had just watched his life pass before
his eyes last week in the form of an HBO documentary when he stood
on a podium to say: ``I find the whole thing totally and completely
embarrassing. I rather enjoyed it, but to tell the truth, it was
boring because I'd seen everything in it before.''
</P>
<P>
   His infectious cackle filled the midtown Manhattan screening
room.
</P>
<P>
   Russell's enigmatic personality made him a long shot to be the
subject of an HBO documentary. If they are alive, they usually
cooperate with HBO. But Russell was not even on HBO's wish list
despite a compelling story that includes growing up in the Deep
South, 11 National Basketball Association championships in 13 years
with the Boston Celtics and a place in the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   His distance from the sport he once dominated reinforced old
perceptions that he is aloof and enigmatic. And he didn't care. He
was at peace with his life and achievements. But his daughter,
Karen, and friends like John Thompson, his former Celtics backup,
urged him to leave his seclusion.
</P>
<P>
   So, last year Russell emerged to promote the ceremony for the
re-retirement of his number at the Fleet Center (the first time his
No. 6 was raised, he mandated that Boston Garden be empty) and
consented to many interviews to help sell tickets.
</P>
<P>
   An interview with Frank Deford for a long article in Sports
Illustrated last May led to Deford's telling HBO that Russell was
ready to tell his story.
</P>
<P>
   Ross Greenburg, the executive producer of HBO Sports, said: ``It
became intriguing to me that, at age 65, he hadn't sat down to tell
his story. The intrigue became that he wanted to tell it. I knew he
had compelling stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell said, ``We wanted to have the story told from our
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Russell: My Life, My Way,'' makes its debut next Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Russell's decision to sit down with HBO contrasts with his
refusal to be interviewed by ESPN last year for its
``SportsCentury'' series. Russell was the only living member of the
top 50 athletes of the 20th century to decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was gracious, and made sure Karen talked to us, but if
you're willing to pay Bill Russell or contribute to his charity,
he'll talk to you,'' said Mark Shapiro, who oversaw production of
the series and who now runs ESPN Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Greenburg said Russell never asked for payment, charitable
contribution or editorial control. ``There were no constrictions,''
he said. ``Our only deal was he would promote the documentary and
appear at the screenings.''
</P>
<P>
   Russell, who had not appeared in a commercial for nearly 30
years, is now featured in spots for Coors and Invesco, a financial
services company. He also signs autographs for money, contradicting
his longstanding resistance to provide his signature to fans or
teammates for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   If Russell has projected coldness through his choice to be a
nonpublic person, the documentary makes him understandable, even
warms him up. The portrait of Russell here is not surprising: a man
who is smart, humane, intelligent, arrogant and unapologetic for
his life's choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Russell did not ask for permission to be a human being,''
Thompson said. ``Bill Russell wouldn't say, `Oh please, treat me
like a person.'''
</P>
<P>
   Racism is a leitmotif of his life, as it was for other
African-Americans of his generation. ``My mother told me the white
people in Monroe, La., were really quite mean,'' said Russell, who
was born in Monroe. ``And so she did everything she could to keep
me protected, so that they didn't get a chance to do anything to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   During the 1957 National Basketball Association finals, Russell
recalled a St. Louis fan telling the Hawks star Bob Pettit: ``
`Hey, Pettit, don't get no chocolate on you.' And that was the
nicest thing I heard that night.''
</P>
<P>
   Touched by the welcome shown to him at a dinner in his honor at
a country club in Reading, Mass., in the early 1960s, Russell and
his family moved into a house there. But soon after, vandals
destroyed most of his trophies and defecated in his bed.
</P>
<P>
   But he played on a racially mixed, color-blind team that
recognized his greatness, and for a coach, Red Auerbach, who
preached Russell's defensive genius to those who mistakenly
believed the Celtics were Bob Cousy's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Russell was this savior,'' said Tom Heinsohn, the
Celtics forward. ``Red became Bill Russell's John the Baptist. He
spread the word.''
</P>
<P>
   The words Russell spread about himself in the documentary may be
the last ones he offers willingly for 20 more years. When he
finishes promoting it, he will return to his current home on Mercer
Island, Wash. Quiet again. A pity. When he wants to be, Russell is
an electric personality incapable of being unrevealing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago, I told my dad, `I have to talk to you, so put
in your hearing aid,''' he said about his father, Charlie, now 88,
after the screening.
</P>
<P>
   He said he sat in front of him and told him, right to his face,
that when he was a boy, he wanted to beat him up.
</P>
<P>
   Russell said his father smiled and replied: ``If you tried that
20 years ago, we would have had a good tussle. But now, I'd just
have to shoot you.''' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-00 1924EDT &QL; 
