<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-CAPITALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLANDERS' CZERKAWSKI SCORES A HAT TRICK 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNY KELLNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y. _ For Mariusz Czerkawski, it was mostly about
the present. For Coach Butch Goring, it was a little bit about the
past. But when the season ended Sunday for the Islanders, it was
all about the future.
</P>
<P>
   With his first hat trick since 1997, Czerkawski led the
Islanders to a 3-2 victory over the Florida Panthers in front of
9,316 boisterous fans at the Nassau Coliseum. The Islanders ended
their season at 24-49-9, meeting Goring's goal of equaling last
year's victory total despite having a payroll of $16.4 million and
the youngest roster in the National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been some radical changes since last year, and for
this young and inexperienced hockey club to win 24 games is a good
accomplishment and a real nice stepping stone,'' Goring said.
``We're only going to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Islanders may have built a solid foundation this season
with its young players, it is the imminent sale of the team to
Charles Wang, founder of Computer Associates, that fans hope will
resurrect the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If new ownership comes in, there's nothing to stop this team
from progressing and progressing rapidly,'' said Mike Milbury, the
Islanders' general manager. ``For the sake of the franchise, for
the sake of the players, for the sake of the manager, it's time to
stop the bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders, who have missed the playoffs for six straight
seasons, have been plagued by declining attendance and diminishing
talent. Last year, citing annual losses of more than $10 million,
the current owners, Ed Milstein and Steven Gluckstern, moved such
high-profile, high-salaried players as Zigmund Palffy, Trevor
Linden, Bryan Berard and Bryan Smolinski. Milbury cobbled together
a team with minor-leaguers, juniors, college players and a handful
of veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Among those left was the 27-year-old Czerkawski, who Milbury
said had been, ``from time to time, a whipping boy.''
</P>
<P>
   Czerkawski, whom Goring challenged before the season by Goring
to become a more all-around player, responded with his best season,
leading the team in scoring with 35 goals and 70 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot on the table,'' said Czerkawski, who scored
goals at 12 minutes 28 seconds and 14:08 of the second period and
got the hat trick _ the only one this season by an Islander _ at
7:13 of the third period. Pavel Bure and Mike Sillinger scored for
the Panthers, but the rookie goalie Roberto Luongo made 29 saves
for the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was pressure on me to produce, to be the offensive
guy,'' Czerkawski said. ``Personally, I am pretty happy. I wanted
to hit 30 goals, and I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to finish strong. I got a lot of help today and
Roberto was brilliant.''
</P>
<P>
   Luongo made his first NHL appearance since being sent to the
minors on Feb. 29. ``It felt like it was my first game all over
again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Luongo, the Islanders' No. 1 draft choice last year, came back
from Lowell on Saturday after Kevin Weekes was injured in Friday
night's game. The Islanders face having two No. 1 goaltenders in
training camp this September, , a situation Goring said he would
address later.
</P>
<P>
   The play of Weekes, acquired with Dave Scatchard and Bill
Muckalt in the trade that sent Felix Potvin to Vancouver, was one
of the more pleasant surprises for the Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were definitely some players who played better than I
expected, including Eric Cairns and Brad Isbister and Tim
Connolly,'' Goring said. ``Tim exceeded what I thought he was going
to get done. As an 18-year-old, he did more than just make it.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he said he felt wonderful, adding that he appreciated
the irony of being the only hockey coach in the New York area not
fired despite having the worst record, Goring said he was very much
aware that the Islanders were still ``on the outside looking in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still only 24 wins,'' Goring said. ``But we feel this
group of people wants to get better'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
