<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-CANOE0410-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlantan earns Sydney trip
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUCKTOWN, Tenn. _ Atlanta's Rebecca Bennett Giddens turned in
the performance of a lifetime Sunday on the Ocoee River, toppling
one of the icons of women's paddling and earning the kayak spot on
the 2000 Olympic Slalom team.
</P>
<P>
   Giddens, 22, was down 3.36 points after a slow first run plus
four penalty points on Saturday and came into Sunday's competition
an underdog.
</P>
<P>
   The leader, two-time Olympian Cathy Hearn of Garrett Park, Md.,
already had dealt with this kind of pressure in 1992 and 1996 and
won.
</P>
<P>
   This time, though, Hearn, 42, got an early message. She paddled
a flawless 126.07 (seconds), yet was buried by Giddens who blazed
down the raging whitewater course so fast that even two penalty
points only raised her score to 123.07.
</P>
<P>
   Giddens did her second run in 122.63 with four penalty points
for a total 126.63.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Leith of Grosse Point, Mich., surprised the crowd with a
strong 124.12 (two penalties) to finish second and Hearn dropped to
third, and out of the Olympics for the first time in more than a
decade, with a 129.36 (two penalties).
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, despite miserable weather, Atlanta resident Scott
Shipley secured his third consecutive Olympics berth with a
dominating performance.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
