<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1638 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BIKE-PARIS-ROUBAIX-RA     04-09 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIKE-PARIS-ROUBAIX-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEEUW WINS 2 YEARS AFTER ALMOST LOSING A LEG 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL ABT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROUBAIX, France _ The king of the classics reclaimed his throne
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after he fractured his left knee in the Paris-Roubaix
race and nearly lost the leg to gangrene, Johan Museeuw, 34, of
Belgium returned to that race and won it after a long, solitary
ride. It was his 10th career victory in one-day classics and his
first since the accident.
</P>
<P>
   As he neared the finish line in the velodrome in Roubaix alone,
Museeuw blew a kiss to the heavens and then clapped his hands. Just
across the line, he suddenly lifted his left leg from the pedal,
thrust it outright and pointed to the knee.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard to miss his point.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the race where, two years ago, I thought my career was
over,'' Museeuw, the leader of the Mapei team, said afterward.
Referring to his 33rd-place finish in the Tour of Flanders in his
backyard last Sunday, Museeuw added, ``This second victory in
Paris-Roubaix means more to me than a fourth victory in the Tour of
Flanders would have.''
</P>
<P>
   He won Paris-Roubaix, a 273-kilometer (170-mile) jaunt over
nearly 50 kilometers of cobblestones, for the first time in 1996
with teammates second and third close behind him. This time Museeuw
did it all himself, joining an attack by Frankie Andreu of the
United States Postal Service team with just over 50 kilometers to
go. He left Andreu behind 10 kilometers farther on and then held
off what was left of the 176-man field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With 30 kilometers and five of the 25 cobblestone sections over
back-country roads to go, Museeuw built a lead that reached 2
minutes 40 seconds. Thereafter, as he bounced along or shifted from
side to side of the road to find a trail of tar, the lead began to
come down.
</P>
<P>
   He was still 1:55 up with 17 kilometers left when he began
losing some steam. Behind him, a handful of pursuers linked up and
began working together, taking turns at the front to set a pace
faster than Museeuw's solo effort.
</P>
<P>
   With 11 kilometers to go, the lead had dropped to 1:20, and with
5 kilometers to go, it was 1:05. As the kilometers clicked off on
the long straightaway to the Roubaix velodrome, his advantage
clicked off too: 56 seconds at the four-kilometer mark, 45 seconds
at the three-kilometer mark, 36 seconds at the two-kilometer mark.
</P>
<P>
   Periodically, Museeuw turned back to see where the pursuit was _
often the sign of a tiring or not confident rider. He was still
turning his head as he passed the red triangle that signifies the
final kilometer and even once he reached the track. Finally there
were no more doubts, and he stared only ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Museeuw finished 15 seconds ahead of Peter Van Petegem, a
Belgian with the Farm Frites team, with Erik Zabel, a German with
Telekom, third; Tristan Hoffman, a Dutchman with Memorycard,
fourth; and Stafano Zanini, an Italian with Mapei, fifth. They were
all in the same time as Van Petegem.
</P>
<P>
   Museeuw was clocked in 6 hours 47 minutes, an average speed of
40 kilometers an hour _ about 25 miles an hour _ for the race in
cool, dry weather with brisk winds.
</P>
<P>
   This was the fifth victory in six years for Mapei in
Paris-Roubaix but just its first victory in 3 of the 10 World Cup
classics so far this season. When a sponsor spends $10 million a
year on a 39-rider squad, as Mapei does _ both figures are double
those of most other teams _ it expects results, and Museeuw's
comeback Sunday qualifies.
</P>
<P>
   Another team, with a far smaller budget, also did well. That was
the United States Postal Service, which recorded a 6th place by a
surging George Hincapie, an American; 16th by Slava Ekimov, a
Russian; and 20th by Andreu, another American.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-nine of the 176 starters finished as punctures and
crashes on the cobblestones took their usual toll. As one of the
dropouts, Oleg Kozlitinne, a Kazakh with the St. Quentin-Oktos
team, said as he toweled himself dry partway through, ``You get a
flat and have to wait two or three minutes for a new wheel, it's
all over.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
