<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-FRANCO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS' FRANCO TRYING TO DEAL WITH HIS DIMINISHED ROLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ John Franco emerged from the athletic trainer's room
Sunday, spotted a few reporters who wanted to ask him about his
Saturday afternoon fiasco and feigned running from them. Franco
laughed at his own joke and casually walked into the middle of the
Mets' clubhouse, right toward reporters and the probing questions
that might hound him all season.
</P>
<P>
   One horrible game will cause this, and even Franco had to
concede that he was awful while permitting the Dodgers two homers
and four runs in the ninth inning. Franco turned a 5-1 lead and
what would have been a special victory for so many reasons into a
tie score and the Mets eventually succumbed, 6-5, in 10 innings
when Armando Benitez stumbled. A day later, Franco tried chuckling
over his failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting some work done on my neck,'' said Franco, whose
neck glistened with a pain-relieving ointment. Then Franco snapped
his neck back once and then twice, reminding everyone how helpless
he looked while watching two homers soar out of Shea Stadium.
Everyone laughed, but no one needed a reminder.
</P>
<P>
   The day after a reliever mishandles a potential victory can be
unpleasant. Franco knows this routine because he has saved 416
games and botched 91, but the routine is a bit different for him
this season. Franco is not the closer anymore. Benitez is and,
while Franco is shrewd enough not to grouse publicly, it bothers
him that he is not closing and it bothers him when the Mets fans
treat him like he is wearing a John Rocker mask.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the beginning of every season since 1986, Franco does not
know when he will get anywhere near the mound in the ninth again.
Franco wanted to pitch Sunday and erase the stale taste of defeat,
but the snow interfered and the Mets-Dodgers game was postponed. So
Franco waits, the wounds from Saturday still fresh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough night,'' Franco said, his comedy routine
finished.
</P>
<P>
   Once the one-liners fade, Franco's body language is the body
language of a proud pitcher who has always been doubted and who
feels like that has happened again. Franco was hesitant to even
call himself a setup man in spring training, perhaps believing that
he would eventually get the chance to pitch the ninth. Manager
Bobby Valentine gave Franco the chance in the seventh game and
should not do it again soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one part of a long season,'' Franco said.
</P>
<P>
   Or is it something more? Franco did not complain about his
diminished role and admonished himself for two poorly located
fastballs. Eric Karros drilled a high fastball for a homer and
Devon White's game-tying shot came off a fastball that caught too
much of the outside corner. For Franco, who cannot simply rely on
fastballs, the adjustment period is ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the eighth inning has got to be like my save situation,''
Franco said. ``Or whenever I'm called upon, seventh, eighth, ninth
inning. I got to make the best of it.''
</P>
<P>
   When someone talks about making the best of a situation, it
usually means they are dealing with something that does not
enthrall them. That is the perfect way to describe Franco's
situation. After flirting with asking the Mets to trade him in the
off-season, Franco decided to stay. It made sense because Franco
had reached the postseason for the first time in his 16-year career
with the Reds and Mets, and there was no guarantee he would close
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   But Franco has to accept his setup role. With his slider,
changeup and sinking fastball, Franco can be an effective counter
in the eighth to Benitez's fastball in the ninth. Franco admitted
it was possible his ``concentration level wasn't where it should
be,'' on Saturday, a surprising admission.
</P>
<P>
   The ninth is still the ninth, whether a team is leading by one
run or four runs. If Franco had a concentration problem, that is a
problem for the Mets and a problem he must overcome. Could Franco
be unnerved by the fans who booed him almost as soon as he jogged
in from the bullpen?
</P>
<P>
   ``The skin has got to stay thick,'' said Franco, who allowed
more homers on Saturday than the one he gave up in 402/3 innings
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Someone asked him if his skin gets thicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like alligator,'' Franco said. ``It's got to. You really don't
know how to describe it unless you're there on the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   Franco might be the symbol for the successful native New York
athlete who plays for a New York team and is loathed, not loved.
Mark Jackson was booed as a Knick, but no one has been vilified as
consistently as Franco. Some of it is deserved since his efforts
can decide games. Some of it is not.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Franco, who often dances around questions about
the abuse, did not tango when asked if he thinks some fans want him
to falter. That sounds incongruous. Fans want teams to succeed, no
matter who contributes. But Franco said it is plausible that some
fans want him to flop, which reveals a lot about his thoughts and
about how complicated this season could get for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like it,'' Franco said. ``It's kind of mind-boggling.
I tried figuring that out a long time ago, and then I just gave up.
I'm not going to worry about it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
