u s BC-CAR-SAN-MARINO-NYT &LR;      04-09 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-SAN-MARINO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMACHER EDGES HAKKINEN BY 1.1 SECONDS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BRAD SPURGEON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IMOLA, Italy _ Michael Schumacher finally got his chance to race
Mika Hakkinen to the finish line, and Schumacher came out on top.
He won a tense battle to the last second Sunday in the San Marino
Grand Prix. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Before 115,000 ecstatic Italian fans at his team's home race,
Schumacher drove his Ferrari over the 62 laps and nearly 190 miles
at an average speed of 124.247 miles an hour. Hakkinen followed
only 1.1 seconds behind, while David Coulthard, in the other
McLaren-Mercedes, finished third, 49.8 seconds back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was Schumacher's third straight victory this year, his second
straight at Imola and the 38th of his career. It was also his third
at Imola, where he won in 1994 driving a Benetton, and last year in
a Ferrari, in the first victory for Ferrari at Imola since 1983.
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher increased his total in the drivers' standing to a
perfect 30 points for three races, 21 ahead of his teammate, Rubens
Barrichello, who finished the race in fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But Schumacher's real victory was that Hakkinen, who won the
last two world championships and is still considered his biggest
threat, has only 6 points after three races.
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher has said repeatedly in recent weeks that he wanted a
showdown on the track against the McLaren cars after Hakkinen's car
fell out of the first two races with technical breakdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what we wanted to do,'' Schumacher said. ``I said after
the first two races that I wanted to race the McLarens, to see
where we are. And now we know where we are. We won the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher began from second place on the grid, but got off to a
bad start as his wheels spun. That allowed Hakkinen, who was on the
pole position, to take off comfortably in first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the worst ones,'' Schumacher said of his start.
``It was a bungled start. I was lucky that nobody went by, except
Mika, so that I could drive my race.''
</P>
<P>
   Pit-stop strategy was a deciding factor.
</P>
<P>
   Both drivers pulled in for their first stop on Lap 27, and the
duel was won by McLaren, as Hakkinen stopped in 7.6 seconds, while
Schumacher stopped in 9.9 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   So Ferrari tried a different strategy for the second stop and
did not pit when Hakkinen did. On Lap 44 Hakkinen stopped in 8.3
seconds, while Schumacher stepped on the accelerator to gain time
without Hakkinen on the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``The four laps before the second stop was the decisive moment
when I pushed very hard,'' Schumacher said.
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher stopped on Lap 48, the last of the top six cars to do
so. He returned to the track after just 6.2 seconds, just ahead of
Jarno Trulli's Jordan car, which was in seventh place and blocking
Hakkinen.
</P>
<P>
   All around the track the Italian fans leaped to their feet and
waved their flags as Schumacher came out in the lead. He had a
3.7-second gap on Hakkinen, but there were 14 laps left and
Hakkinen was catching up fast.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic, however, held Hakkinen up and he could not catch
Schumacher. Despite the frequent waving of blue flags by officials
to tell cars to let him pass, Hakkinen was blocked more than once.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are about 20 years old, those blue flags,'' he
said, ``And they are not so blue anymore. So I suppose it's a bit
difficult to see them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hakkinen also said he had run into a metal object on the track,
which he said damaged his car and caused him to go slower. He also
said he lost three or four seconds when his engine cut out at one
point. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
