u i BC-SKOREA-LIVESTOCK-VIRU     04-09 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKOREA-LIVESTOCK-VIRUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPIDEMIC OF CATTLE DISEASE INFLICTS TOLL ON SOUTH KOREA 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOWARD W. FRENCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUMPARI, South Korea _ In this region of machine gunners'
trenches and foxholes hard by the border with North Korea, the
roadblocks manned by grim-faced soldiers in camouflage-painted
trucks give every appearance of preparation for an imminent
invasion.
</P>
<P>
   For all of the military presence, the vigilance has nothing to
do with war. As the reeking blankets drenched with germ-killing
chlorine and stretched across feeder roads in this farmland make
clear, the enemy in this case is an infectious outbreak that has
taken on all the seriousness of a national emergency.
</P>
<P>
   The threat that has gripped South Korea in the last three weeks
is foot-and-mouth disease, one of the most destructive cattle
diseases known. And with critical national elections set for this
week, the government has pulled out all the stops to limit the
damage _ not only to agriculture, but to its political support as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Since the outbreak of this extremely contagious viral disease
was confirmed last week, upsetting livestock markets throughout the
Far East, South Korea has taken increasingly muscular measures to
prevent a spreading epidemic from becoming the story of this week's
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Foot-and-mouth disease causes blisters with an infectious
discharge in the mouths and on the extremities of cattle and pigs,
provoking loss of appetite, high fevers, and ultimately death _
often to entire herds. Humans seldom contract the disease, though
they may be carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The last time a confirmed outbreak of the disease occurred in
the region, in Taiwan in 1977, it forced authorities to slaughter
over 3 million pigs, nearly devastating a $1.5 billion industry.
Fearing an outbreak on that scale, and perhaps a wildfire-like
spread throughout the region, China, Taiwan, Australia and Japan
have all quickly imposed bans on beef and pork imports from South
Korea.
</P>
<P>
   The country's pork exports to Japan, its major customer, are
worth an estimated $400 million annually. Japan has also reported a
small number of confirmed cases of the disease in Miyazaki
prefecture since mid-March and so far has destroyed at least 19
cattle.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to calling the army to enforce quarantines, the
South Korean government's anti-epidemic measures so far have
included closing more than 130 livestock markets, banning sales of
meat and milk in affected areas, destroying about 500 cattle and
vaccinating 300,000 others.
</P>
<P>
   The mobilization is such that for vehicles entering and leaving
this Paju Valley region of wide swaths of rich, river-irrigated
farmland ringed by high mountains, 35 miles north of Seoul, there
is an obligatory wash with disinfectants.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point I think it has been reduced to a very sporadic
problem,'' said Bong Kyun-park, a swine virologist at Seoul
National University who has advised the government throughout the
crisis. ``We have found only ten confirmed cases in the entire
country. This involves only four sites, and we are very excited
about its confinement.''
</P>
<P>
   Park and other officials involved in the containment effort may
be excited, but the country's livestock farmers share none of this
enthusiasm. In fact, in the last few days their reaction to a ban
on the trade in animals, milk, cattle and pork products has turned
increasingly angry.
</P>
<P>
   Furious farmers rioted at roadblocks on the approaches to the
capital on Saturday, demanding that they either be allowed to sell
their products or be reimbursed at full value. Opposition parties
have sought to portray the government as unprepared for an
epidemic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we are worried,'' said Myoung Soon-im, a 61-year-old
rancher whose face is deeply etched by years of working in the
fields. ``We can't even sell our milk. We have no idea what to
expect next, and don't know what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Although his farm stands on high ground less than two miles from
the site of the initial outbreak, he said, his cows had been
vaccinated by visiting government teams, and had so far shown no
signs of illness.
</P>
<P>
   While the government has worked aggressively to contain the
outbreak, conversations with farmers suggested that little effort
had been spent on education about the disease or how to prevent its
spread.
</P>
<P>
   The government has told farmers to try to keep their cattle in
barns, or otherwise shielded from the yellow smog that hangs over
South Korea this time of year, and which has been especially heavy
this year.
</P>
<P>
   The yellowish tinge is widely believed to come from dust blown
in from the Gobi Desert, in China, and the strong suggestion in
those messages seems to be that the infection may have somehow
drifted in from afar, as well.
</P>
<P>
   As the old rancher spoke, at the edge of the corral where his 30
milk cows fed, his wife rushed out of their manure-filled barn to
shoo away visitors, telling them that the government had sternly
warned farmers not to talk about the outbreak to outsiders _ and
especially not to journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know anything about this disease,'' she said. ``What
we know is that when there are visitors there is more trouble.
Please go away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
