<HEADLINE>
SHEFFIELD WORRIED ABOUT INJURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - Gary Sheffield walked into the Dodgers clubhouse
Sunday with the aid of crutches, placed them into his locker and
then hobbled into the trainer's room.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers' left fielder said it's too early to tell how
long his sprained right ankle would keep him out of the lineup.
Sheffield also said he wasn't sure whether he's heading for the
disabled list or whether he'll be back in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't seem too optimistic,'' Sheffield said. ``If some
miracle is going to happen, I'll play. But I'm not optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield suffered the high ankle sprain in the first inning of
the Dodgers' 6-5 win in 10 innings Saturday against the Mets. His
availability was supposed to become more clear Sunday, but the
Dodgers will give it another day and evaluate him today in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers officials are hopeful Sheffield will be able to play
during the three-game series. Sheffield is concerned about the
injury because of what happened with the Angels' Mo Vaughn when he
suffered a similar injury last season. And the Dodgers,
understanding Sheffield's value, won't allow him to play before
he's ready.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be right when I get out there,'' Sheffield. ``I'm
going to talk to (Vaughn) and find out what he did to get back. Mo
Vaughn, he's more of a back leg hitter than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Snowed in: Sunday's game with the Mets was canceled at 10:30
a.m., but that didn't help the Dodgers get out of New York any
faster. The plane they chartered wasn't due into New York until
late afternoon, so the bus couldn't leave for the airport until
4:45 p.m., which made for lots of chess and card games in the
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Also, manager Davey Johnson wasn't too pleased about having to
play the makeup on Monday, April 24, at 7:10 p.m. The Dodgers were
supposed to have an off day between series in Cincinnati and
Atlanta, but that's apparently out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not real fond of it,'' Johnson said. ``I'd rather come
back later on when the weather is nicer, but it's not my call.''
</P>
<P>
   What's with the ball: The San Francisco Giants were going to
help christen their new ballpark by using the last ball pitched at
Candlestick Park in the first-pitch ceremonies at Pac Bell Park on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But alas, the ball remains in Eric Karros' possession, where
it's been since the Dodgers and Giants closed out the 'Stick last
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in my closet in a plastic bag with a little notecard that
says, `Last ball used at Candlestick-3Com, Marvin Bernard-ground
ball' '' Karros said. ``That's so I remember what it is. I got it
sitting in there. I'm just curious to see if they throw out the
first ball. That's what I heard, but I don't know if that's going
to happen. Nobody's ever asked me about it, and I heard the
previous trainer from that ballclub presented their owner with the
ball. I read about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Herges' reprieve: When the Dodgers optioned lefty Carlos Perez
to Triple-A Albuquerque on Friday, it meant right-hander Matt
Herges continued his amazing survival tactics and will be with the
club at least for another week. But it took some reassurances when
he got to the ballpark Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got back to my room and I had a fax waiting for me,'' Herges
said. ``I called down and they had somebody bring it to me. It was
an itinerary to go to New Orleans (Saturday) at 2:45 p.m. Whew! I
didn't sleep much. I got to the park, my uniform was still in the
locker, so I asked somebody and they said I'm still here.''
</P>
<P>
   The original plan was for Herges to join Albuquerque on its
season-opening road trip so outfielder Geronimo Berroa could come
to New York. But after Perez bombed in his start Thursday at
Montreal, plans changed. It also helps that Herges hasn't allowed a
hit in four innings this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
