A1654 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r BC-CAR-NASCAR0410-COX     04-09 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR0410-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Martin's `worst' enough
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARTINSVILLE, Va. _ The Roush gang stole the show Sunday at
Martinsville Speedway and then gleefully turned themselves in.
</P>
<P>
   Stuck back in the pack and admittedly ``the worst driver here
and I know it,'' Mark Martin took the lead with 64 laps remaining
and held on to win the Goody's Body Pain 500.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stole this thing,'' Martin said. ``That's how I feel. I
thought I had a 15th-place car, maybe 10th. I was leading, I ran
hard and nobody came (to challenge). I just ran like a mean dog.
Right now, this feels like the biggest win of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin beat Roush teammate Jeff Burton's Ford by 1.505 seconds.
It was an afternoon of comebacks for Burton, who had fallen to 37th
place after being penalized for leaving pit road before receiving
the signal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel me finishing second today is a borderline felony,''
Burton said. ``We might need to spend a few hours in jail before we
go home. We didn't deserve to finish second. Today's as bad as
we've ever run.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first win of the 2000 Winston Cup season for Martin,
the only driver among the top five points leaders without a victory
before Sunday. He remains second in points but climbed within 36 of
leader Bobby Labonte, who finished 12th.
</P>
<P>
   Martin also is the eighth different winning driver at the start
of the season, a NASCAR record. The all-time overall record is 13
consecutive different winners, set in 1961; the modern era record
is 11 straight different winners in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Martin and Burton were among the survivors of an event-record 17
cautions for 112 laps that slowed the average speed to 71.161 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Martin maintained his lead through the last three restarts.
Rusty Wallace had the dominant car, leading for 343 laps, but
changes to his No. 2 Ford over the last 64 laps took it out of
contention. The yellow flags began flying from the third lap, when
Kenny Wallace, who started on the outside pole, had a stuck
throttle and drove into the wall at Turn 3.
</P>
<P>
   And they were flying as late as lap 489, when Michael Waltrip's
car knocked out Michael Andretti in Turn 2.
</P>
<P>
   Martin won the race in one moment of brilliance. Crew chief
Jimmy Fennig told him to stay out on lap 437 when the leaders,
including Wallace, pitted.
</P>
<P>
   Martin had pitted, without much company, on lap 411. ``I called
it and Jimmy (agreed),'' he said. ``I thought it was time to do it
and then I questioned it when the leaders didn't come (in). He
said, `You come.' So we did, and that's how it went.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin took home $104,650 and the grandfather clock the Speedway
awards the winner. ``My wife,'' he said, ``has nagged me about one
of those grandfather clocks for 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
