<SLUG> BC-SECONDHAND-STORES-1070(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECONDHAND STORES MOVE UPTOWN AND UPSCALE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Calif.)   By LESLIE KAUFMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shopping at secondhand stores, once the passion of an eclectic
few, is becoming a mainstream activity.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to those who have always been willing to hunt for
vintage dresses or the perfect side table at flea markets, more and
more consumers are looking to the resale industry to provide a
cheaper way to purchase everything from computers to designer jeans
to Sub-Zero refrigerators.
</P>
<P>
   Heightening demand is the fact that the industry has worked hard
to transform itself, with many owners adopting sophisticated
marketing techniques, building chain operations and adding
locations in affluent suburbs. Determined to shed their image as
dank backwaters for the down and out, many stores that sell used
goods have installed better lights, dressing rooms and even coffee
bars.
</P>
<P>
   Internet auction sites like eBay have also given new exposure
and high-technology chic to the age-old practice.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, sales at pawnshops, antique houses and secondhand
stores have been growing nearly twice as fast as regular retail. In
1997, the last year for which the Census Bureau kept comprehensive
numbers, Americans spent some $12 billion on merchandise purchased
at these secondhand stores, a jump of 50 percent from 1992. Census
estimates, which will not be confirmed until 2002, suggest that in
1999 the industry grew another 23 percent to $17 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That is spectacular growth by any measure, but all the more
surprising because it comes at a time when consumers can afford to
buy new. Pawnbroking, for example, has traditionally flourished in
hard times. Yet pawnbrokers' revenues in the last five years have
jumped roughly 15 percent to about $700 million in 1999, according
to Brian Smith, a member of the board of directors of the National
Pawnbrokers Association. The business has managed to thrive in part
by remaking itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have moved from inner cities out into the suburbs, so we
are not in bad areas where middle-income people are afraid of
going,'' he said. ``Eight years ago that was just not the case.''
</P>
<P>
   While sales of secondhand goods amount to only a little more
than 2 percent of all dollars spent on general apparel, merchandise
and furnishings in this country last year, the growing demand for
used goods still represents a sea change in the way Americans
perceive cast-offs. ``The used product business has really evolved
to a mainline retail business,'' said Ted Manly, president and
chief operating officer of Grow Biz International Inc., which runs
several chains of used goods stores.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, traditional retailers have trained
consumers to be price sensitive for a variety of goods. Discounters
like Target and Kmart have grown at the expense of department
stores, luring upper- and middle-income customers with low prices
on Martha Stewart pool furniture or embroidered tops.
</P>
<P>
   As buying cheap has become synonymous with smart shopping,
almost-new merchandise has also gained new cachet. ``Just over the
past five years, the increase in the acceptability of buying used
has been amazing,'' said Christa Weil, author of ``Secondhand
Chic'' (Pocket Books, 1999). ``I used to slink around doing it, and
now friends brag about buying secondhand.''
</P>
<P>
   She points to her best friend, who after years of mocking her
for shopping secondhand, actually bought her wedding dress from a
thrift shop specializing in vintage gowns.
</P>
<P>
   And while discount stores are still known for the frequently
second-rate durability of their goods, secondhand stores have built
a reputation as places with high-quality merchandise for low
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like nice things; I'm not a blue-light special person,''
said Pat Bolar, a housewife who shops for secondhand designer wear
at One More Time, a used clothing store in an upscale neighborhood
in Columbus, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the boom economy has supplied secondhand stores
with enormous amounts of quality merchandise. As Americans grow
wealthier, they are more likely to replace barely used sofa sets or
cull from their closets the Gucci pants worn once to a wedding last
year. High-quality tennis rackets bought with the best intentions
find their way to the used-product stores as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people get tired of things very quickly and it is
wonderful,'' said Jane Strauch, owner of Patrick's Consignment
Store in Pacific Grove, Calif. In January, for example, a local
resident consigned a stand-alone cherry wood jewelry chest that
still had the protective plastic from the factory on it.
</P>
<P>
   Some areas of this market are being fueled by the rapid
obsolescence of high-technology gear. The resale personal computer
business barely existed a decade ago. Now industry insiders
estimate it exceeds $5 billion a year as businesses, in particular,
struggle to keep up with the new gadgets and the increases in
computing power unveiled each year.
</P>
<P>
   To afford their power needs, consumers and businesses are mixing
and matching their computer hardware. ``We sell to a very broad
base of customers,'' said Taylor Branch, president of the 210-store
used-computer chain Computer Renaissance, which had $150 million in
sales last year. ``Because our stores offer both new and used
systems, we often build a nice, new customized system for mom and
dad and then the kids will get refurbished machines, because they
are the last people the parents want playing on the new system,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The used music business is also exploding. ``Vinyls would wear
out, but the compact disc won't wear out absent physical abuse,''
said Jerry Grizzle, chairman and chief executive of CD Warehouse, a
360-store chain that sells used discs. ``The technology gave
validity to the used-music market.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the biggest change in the secondhand business has
been the revamping of the stores themselves. In recent years,
businesses ranging from tiny thrift stores to giant nonprofit
charities to pawn shops have upgraded store design, layout and
organization of goods. Goodwill Industries International, for
example, has added coffee bars to a half-dozen stores and has begun
putting couches in its used-book areas so customers can loll about.
</P>
<P>
   ``The retail market is much more competitive, so we have to do
everything we can to attract and retain customers,'' said Christine
Bragale, the charity's spokeswoman, exhibiting the kind of
consumer-first attitude that would make a Barnes &AMP; Noble manager
envious.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Goodwill is hardly alone in sprucing up. Throughout the
nonprofit world, secondhand stores are sweeping away dust bunnies
and adding overhead lighting. And, if anything, the changes have
been more drastic in the for-profit sector.
</P>
<P>
   Grow Biz International is just the largest of several
corporations that have tried to systematize the resale business by
bringing to it the levels of customer service and inventory display
shoppers are accustomed to at chains like The Gap or Limited.
Although most of Grow Biz's stores are independent franchises, they
follow standard policies on returns and guarantees of service.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, resale businesses have been hard to organize on a
national level because individual stores buy their own inventory
piecemeal from local sellers who bring in their castoffs. While
that remains the case, advances in data organizing software are
making it easier. CD Warehouse has a system that tracks customer
purchases at each of its stores, ranks what recordings are popular
with customers and assigns prices to them accordingly. That means
individual clerks do not have to guess what they might be worth.
</P>
<P>
   Secondhand goods have also flourished in the new retail medium
of the Internet. The explosion of used-goods auctions taking place
at popular online sites from eBay to Yahoo to Amazon.com have made
purchasing used memorabilia the cutting edge of chic, something
that owners of secondhand-goods stores think only rebounds to their
own good.
</P>
<P>
   ``EBay and everything on the Internet has helped our industry,''
said Alexandra Carroll, the departing president of the National
Association of Resale and Thrift shops. ``It keeps us on the mind
of our customers. The Internet has been a boon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
