u a BC-STATE-BUDGETS-SURPLUS     04-09 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATE-BUDGETS-SURPLUS-1040(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A RESURGENT MICHIGAN LEADS NEWLY FLUSH STATES 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANSING, Mich. _ Lawmakers here and in many other states, now in
the throes of writing their budgets for the 2001 fiscal year, are
witnessing the biggest of six consecutive years of rising revenues,
which have inspired inventive new ways to spend money and wave upon
wave of tax reductions.
</P>
<P>
   States are collecting revenues from the taxes on surging
industries, fully employed work forces, stock-market gains and _
this year, for the first time _ from a two-decade-long, $246
billion windfall from the settlement of their suit against the
tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The states are overflowing with money and spending a lot of
money,'' said Stephen Moore, an economist at the conservative Cato
Institute in Washington. ``You are starting to see _ among
Republican governors, by the way _ budget increases of 6, 7, 8
percent a year. States are continuing to cut taxes, too. But the
money is coming in so fast they haven't kept pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary S. Olson, director of Michigan's nonpartisan Senate Fiscal
Agency, which tracks the state's finances, said: ``This is sort of
an ideal situation. Michigan had never been able to reduce taxes
and raise spending at the same time. I've worked in the Legislature
since 1978, and clearly these are the best times I've ever seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the peculiarities of their taxation systems or their
economies, a few states like Wyoming, Iowa, Kansas, Tennessee and
New Hampshire are not reaping much of this harvest. But most are.
New York, California, Texas, Maryland, Minnesota, Indiana,
Washington, Pennsylvania and Michigan have been amassing annual
surpluses exceeding $1 billion, typically representing hundreds of
idle tax dollars collected from each of their citizens.
</P>
<P>
   The surpluses have spurred new spending plans and an array of
tax reductions. In Maine, Gov. Angus King, an independent, would
give a laptop computer to every seventh-grader. Gov. Parris
Glendening of Maryland, a Democrat, would buy textbooks for
students in the state's 500 private schools. In the fall, Gov. Tom
Ridge of Pennsylvania, a Republican, will send the state's 3.3
million homeowners a tax-rebate check of $100.
</P>
<P>
   Some states are cutting sales taxes on food and clothes, and
property taxes on automobiles. Gov. Jesse Ventura of Minnesota, an
independent, has handed taxpayers $1.3 billion in sales-tax
rebates. In January, Gov. Bob Taft of Ohio, a Republican, put into
effect tax breaks for adoptions and college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Gov. George Pataki's priority is lopping $1.25
billion from the state's debt, saving taxpayers the cost of
carrying it, but incurring the wrath of Democratic legislators and
many Republicans who want more tax cuts and spending.
</P>
<P>
   In his new budget, Gov. John Engler of Michigan is dipping into
the state's tobacco-settlement money for $83 million to give $2,500
college scholarships to students who pass a state achievement test.
</P>
<P>
   He proposes awarding $1,000 bonuses to the staff of
high-performing schools, from principals to janitors. He is
creating a virtual high school for students to take advanced
courses through the Internet that are unavailable in rural areas.
And he plans to give all 80,000 public school teachers laptop
computers.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are beginning to call their surpluses ``structural,''
prosperity's antithesis to the structural deficits of much of the
1900s. By law, states, unlike the federal government, must erase
one year's deficit the next year with spending cuts or tax
increases. The serial surpluses of the 1990s and 2000 let them
build reserves to tide them over in a moderate recession without
their having to touch programs and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But in choosing where to dispense prosperity's bounty,
Democratic leaders in the states, most of which have Republican
governors, say the big beneficiaries are businesses and the rich.
``There is a percentage of our citizenry,'' said state Sen. Alma
Wheeler, D-Ann Arbor, ``that is not having its boat floated by this
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Hubert Price, D-Pontiac, calculates that a family of
three with Michigan's median income of $40,000 will save $1.20 a
week from a recent cut in the income-tax rate to 4.2 percent from
4.4 percent. ``I haven't had any constituents walk up to me in the
grocery store and say `Thank you,''' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   And public policy analysts say the prudence that states showed
in the mid-1990s in setting aside rainy-day funds to weather
recessions has begun to wane. ``Until now, it's been a series of
happy surprises,'' said Iris Lav, an economist and expert on state
finance at the Center for Budget and Policy Priorities in
Washington, ``Every year, revenues come in higher than forecast.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said three or four years of lowered tax rates and rising
spending were consuming a larger part of the rising revenues,
reducing the surpluses and resources set aside for recessions. The
National Conference of State Legislatures in Denver reports that
reserves have dropped to $30 billion this year from $37.5 billion
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the tax cuts, especially the rebates, are one-time
events, said Mandy Rafool, a senior policy analyst at the
conference. ``They're trying to give the money back but play it
safe,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And to avoid the one-year jolt of sharp tax-rate reductions,
many legislatures favor small, phased reductions like Michigan's
23-year elimination of a tax on business. In that way, she said,
they avoid the political repercussions of raising taxes to cope
with recessions.
</P>
<P>
   No state has gained more from prosperity and surpluses than
Michigan, where the cities of Flint, Pontiac, Benton Harbor and
Detroit formed the downtrodden core of a region that economists
called the rust belt. For decades Michigan and West Virginia shared
the nation's highest unemployment rates, often exceeding 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In February, however, Michigan's unemployment rate was a mere
2.7 percent, one of the nation's lowest, the state's lowest in at
least 30 years, and well below the national rate of 4.1 percent.
Automobile workers are working overtime and earning an average of
$60,000 a year. On top of that, they are collecting $8,000 and
$10,000 annual bonuses _ all taxable income that feeds the surplus.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Such unanticipated tides of revenue are pouring into the state
treasury at a rate of $2 million more a day than the governor's
economists predicted just a year ago, and hundreds of thousands of
dollars a day above their predictions as recently as January, when
Engler submitted his budget.
</P>
<P>
   The governor was first elected 10 years ago as a tight-fisted,
tax-cutting crime-fighter, and has cracked down on parole and young
offenders. Crime is down, as it is in the rest of the country, but
prison terms have stretched, and the prison population has doubled
during his tenure, to 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of next year, Engler and the Republican-controlled
Legislature will have added 10,200 prison beds, with 3,700 opening
this year. Spending for prisons has doubled during his tenure,
reaching $1.5 billion last year, just $100 million less than
spending for Michigan's colleges and universities. This year,
Engler is proposing to raise prison spending by nearly 9 percent,
about the same amount as last year.
</P>
<P>
   He has also chopped hundreds of millions of dollars in state and
federal welfare spending by steering recipients into jobs and
cutting the caseload from 238,000 in 1994 to 74,800 in January _
the lowest in 30 years. Last year for the first time, spending for
day care _ mostly for former welfare recipients who have gone to
work _ exceeded spending for cash assistance programs.
</P>
<P>
   The rising revenues have let Engler make 31 tax cuts since
taking office _ the last five in January _ and accelerate spending
from a 3 percent annual increase to over 4 percent. At that pace,
he has begun letting the rainy-day fund decline from 7 percent of
state revenues to 5 percent, the minimum that economists say a
state needs in a recession.
</P>
<P>
   But 5 percent, representing $1.6 billion, is still well above
the levels of the 1980s, when the fund never exceeded $500 million.
``We could take a two-year hit and still be OK,'' said Robert J.
Kleine, senior economist at Public Sector Consultants in Lansing, a
private, nonpartisan research organization.
</P>
<P>
   Industrially, the state is more diversified, giving lawmakers
confidence that it can ride out recessions better now than in the
past. The old rust-belt industries of automobiles, appliances and
furniture have been driving the boom, but tax cuts may be
reinforcing it.
</P>
<P>
   All together, the governor's office says, the tax cuts have left
taxpayers with $15 billion more to save or to spend to keep the
economy rolling. ``Michigan is a case study that tax cuts work,''
said state Rep. Bill Schuette. ``I think by cutting taxes you're
able to flex your economic muscle.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan's new glut of money has also changed the tenor of
budget debates. To spurn entreaties for aid in the days of tight
budgets, said Mary A. Lannoye, Michigan's budget director, ``You
could say, `There is no money _ just no.''' In this climate, more
money shows up. So, she said, a legislator thinks, ``Here's an
opportunity to get a project I've been looking at for my
community.''
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Harry Gast, a Republican who is chairman of the
Senate Appropriations Committee, said that during the long
recession of the mid-1980s, ``we had to cut the budgets of 19
departments.'' But with year-after-year surpluses, he said, ``we
have programs coming out of the weeds _ groups with something warm
and fuzzy, and some of them have merit.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, as the revenues grow, Engler's adversaries say they have
begun to detect a softer view of the poor. ``I think the governor
is willing, in today's climate, to take itty-bitty steps,'' Price
said.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after taking office, the governor eliminated the state's
general assistance program, casting 83,000 single adults and
childless couples from the welfare rolls.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we haven't had any more of those horrendous program
cuts,'' said Sharon Parks, a director of the Michigan League for
Human Services. And she said that last year the governor approved a
2.5 percent increase in cash assistance for families remaining on
welfare, the first increase in 12 years. Another increase, of 3
percent, will take effect in October.
</P>
<P>
   Engler has also given in to appeals for support of the arts,
with grants to libraries and museums. ``In the early 1990s there
was a significant cutback in arts and cultural spending in the
state,'' said Olson of the Senate Fiscal Agency, which tracks state
finances for the Senate. ``Now we're probably spending more for the
arts and culture than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the face of Michigan's bonanza, smoldering issues remain.
Surging health-care costs are eliminating small businesses' gains
from tax cuts, said the House Democratic leader, Michael Hanley.
More spending for child care, he said, would slow the progression
of young people to crime and prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly,'' said William Sederberg, president of Ferris State
University in Big Rapids, ``it would be better to spend more on
higher education than on incarcerating people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
