u a BC-NY-SPRINGSNOW-NYT &LR;      04-09 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SPRINGSNOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE NORTHEST, APRIL'S FLOWERS HAVE PETALS OF SNOW 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Winter's inevitable last gasp vanquished the glories
of springtime Sunday. In just 18 hours, temperatures plunged 40
degrees, rain turned to whooshing gusts of snow and much of the
Northeast took on the gloomy, slushy mien of January.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was a balmy spring day, with temperatures in the 70s.
But then a vast, lumbering front, formed along a 1,500-mile arc,
swept eastward across the hard greens at Augusta National and the
Catskills and the Adirondacks. As it passed, waves of cold Canadian
air were sucked in from the rear, and in some places temperatures
fell 20 degrees in a matter of 60 minutes. So Sunday morning, as
snow fell at the rate of 2 inches an hour in Albany, N.Y., it was
still in the 60s in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go from spring to winter in a couple of hours,'' said Fred
Gadomski, a Pennsylvania State University meteorologist.
</P>
<P>
   The heaviest accumulations of snow were in central New York
state, with 17 inches recorded in Schoharie County and more than a
foot in Albany. Around the New York City region, snowfalls ranged
from 1 to 3 inches. Temperatures, which were expected to climb to
the mid-50s Monday and Tuesday, brushed but did not break record
lows.
</P>
<P>
   There were scores of traffic accidents, and many flights were
delayed, but the storm did not pose much threat to public safety.
</P>
<P>
   In a telling measure of the storm's limited impact on New York
City, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani kept up his campaign schedule for the
U.S. Senate. Greeting voters in a Manhattan deli with Sen. John
McCain, Giuliani told reporters that hundreds of trucks were
spreading salt and sand on city roads. ``If you see a sanitation
worker out there working,'' he said, ``why don't you say thank
you.''
</P>
<P>
   No storm-related deaths were reported, but there were scattered
power failures, and clearly the rhythms and rites of spring were
rudely interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   Tulips and daffodils tilted sideways under smothering veils of
wet snow. Hardware stores hastily pulled out dusty stocks of rock
salt and snow shovels. Little League games were canceled, only to
be replaced by snow balls being pitched. Sunday golfers moaned and
groaned, and some cross-country skiers poached on their favorite
fairways.
</P>
<P>
   On the boardwalk in Long Beach, N.Y., Ji Min Kim, 31,
contemplated the possibility of surfing in the falling snow. He had
brought along a friend and novice surfer, Chulsoo Yoo, who smiled
agreeably as if surfing in the snow were perfectly normal. ``This
is his third day,'' Kim said.
</P>
<P>
   Snowstorms in April are routinely described as freak storms, and
for good reason. Only seven times in the last 40 years has Central
Park had a measurable snowfall in April. The last year it happened
was 1996. On Sunday, 1.3 inches fell in the park, the most April
snow there since April 6, 1982, when almost 10 inches fell.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's snow shocked people all the more because it was an
uncharacteristic exclamation point on an unusually mild winter. New
York City's average daily temperature in March _ 47.2 degrees _ was
the fifth warmest March on record since 1869. For many people,
thoughts of winter had been packed away weeks ago along with gloves
and hats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to believe the forecast,'' Stanley Schultz,
owner of the Ben Frank Variety Store in Williamsburg, Brooklyn,
said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Joseph Okonski, a 17-year-old from Maspeth, Queens,
peeked out his window and said, ``You've got to be kidding me.''
</P>
<P>
   For some, the transformation was almost dizzying in both its
suddenness and its severity. Many who ventured forth did so with a
look of bewilderment, as if the normal rules of nature had been
rewritten by someone with a warped sense of humor. Even the birds
seemed confused. Hungry robins blindly pecked away at snow-covered
lawns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday my daughter and I were in Sheep's Meadow running
around in the grass with our shoes and socks off,'' said Anne
Ficklen, an editor who lives on the Upper West Side, not far from
Central Park. ``Today we're getting out our snow pants and going
sledding.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Jennifer Pauley was serving double scoops at a Ben
&AMP; Jerry's she manages on Lark Street in Albany. People were lined
up in shorts and T-shirts. But there she was Sunday, gamely
shoveling the sidewalk in front of the store.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Roberts of Brooklyn wore a long, silky summer dress to
the Metropolitan Opera Saturday night. Sunday morning she bundled
up in boots and a heavy parka to walk her German shepherd mix,
Charlotte, who seemed to have the easier time adjusting.
</P>
<P>
   And Gwyn Fletcher, 33, barbecued on Saturday at her parent's
home in Irvington, Westchester County. They cut spring flowers and
pulled out the patio furniture. In other words, she said with a
rueful laugh, it was the perfect time for a snowstorm.
</P>
<P>
   But of course, the big worry was for the flowers _ the pansies
and tulips and magnolias that seemed cruelly out of place in the
snow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost didn't go out, only because I thought it would be so
sad to see all the blossoms die,'' said Kate Combellick, 48, a
Fordham University professor who nevertheless forced herself out
for a jog in Riverside Park in Manhattan. Combellick was
particularly concerned about the magnolias.
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry, gardening experts said.
</P>
<P>
   By itself, the snow will do little long-term damage to plants.
In fact, it can be an excellent form of insulation against cold
weather, they said. Some gardening store managers were only upset
that more snow did not fall to provide better protection against
temperatures that were expected to dip to into the mid-30s
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pansies love the snow,'' said George A. Cluff, owner of Eden
Farms, a gardening store in West Milford, N.J. ``And for tulips,
it's actually better that they have snow going into a cold night.''
</P>
<P>
   For gardening stores, the only disaster was at the cash
register. At Rosedale Nurseries in Hawthorne, Westchester County,
manager Toivo Kivisalu said his business was a fraction of what it
was on Saturday. He even sent many of his workers home early.
</P>
<P>
   But there was one small bit of good news. He sold a bundle of
firewood.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-00 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
