<SLUG> BC-BRAVES0411-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hot Bonilla paces bashing
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The New York Mets wanted to get rid of Bobby Bonilla
so much that they agreed to a $29.8-million settlement to get out
of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' loss is the Braves' gain.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla, rejuvenated at age 37, homered, singled twice and drove
in three runs Sunday as the Braves beat the San Francisco Giants
9-3.
</P>
<P>
   The victory gave Atlanta a 4-2 record for their opening
homestand and sent them off to Chicago in first place in the
National League East.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Rafael Furcal, the youngest player in the majors at 19,
stole home on a double steal and Tom Glavine retired the last 11
batters he faced in a gutsy seven-inning effort. But the story on
Sunday was Bonilla.
</P>
<P>
   With Brian Jordan on the disabled list, Bonilla got his third
start in a row in left field in his biggest game in three years.
</P>
<P>
   His second homer of the season broke a tie at 2 in the fifth
inning. Then he broke the game open with a two-run single in the
sixth. In going 3-for-3, Bonilla raised his average to .429.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having fun again,'' Bonilla said. ``This is a great
opportunity for me and I want to take advantage of it. I know my
role here. I'll do what I can until Brian gets back, then I'll just
help any way I can. I want to win. That's all I care about now.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla, who ballooned to more than 250 pounds last season, will
collect his deferred money from the Mets over 24 years beginning in
2011. Until then, he'd just as soon forget his time in New York.
Injuries limited him to 60 games in 1999, and he hit only .160 in
119 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to call last year,'' said Bonilla, paid the
major-league minium of $200,000 by the Braves. ``I hope my
nightmares aren't that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, out with a strained rib cage, will be eligible to come
off the disabled list on April 19. Until then, Bonilla should see
plenty of time in left field, with Reggie Sanders moving to right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby is swinging the bat as well as I've seen him in three or
four years,'' Glavine said. ``He's been a very good pickup. It's a
big luxury when you can put a player like Brian on the DL and call
on someone like Bobby.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bonilla provided the power, Furcal supplied the speed. In
his third start on the homestand, Furcal went 2-for-4 with a triple
and stole his second and third bases of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That little Pee Wee Herman kid kicked our butt,'' the Giants'
Barry Bonds said of the smallish Furcal.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
