<HEADLINE>
YOU RULE _ AT LEAST WITH THESE BOOKS NEARBY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Book I: ``Baseball America 2000 Almanac'' ($12.95,
416 pages, edited by Paul White)
</P>
<P>
   Book II: ``Baseball Weekly 2000 Almanac'' ($14.95, 444 pages,
edited by Alan Simpson)
</P>
<P>
   Book III: ``2000 Official Rules of Major League Baseball''
(Triumph Books, 201 pages, $8.95)
</P>
<P>
   Why they're essential: As great as the Internet is for instant
reference material, not all of us have Powerbooks with cordless
modems. We need books once in a while. For baseball, these three do
it.
</P>
<P>
   If any two almanacs could look the same but be completely
different, it's these two. Baseball America can't be touched for
its in-depth coverage of the minor leagues, college, high school
and even youth, amateur, foreign and winter leagues. After that,
Baseball Weekly, with help from stepbrother USA Today, goes much
more into detailed graphics and stats on major-league info, past
and present, including listing the final '99 statistics
alphabetically by position a must for fantasy-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, who hasn't been confused by a rule but can't find a
book that explains it, not just to the letter but how the
rulemakers intended for it to be applied? This official MLB
publication clears away the confusion and includes unique
interpretations of particular rules as determined by the Rules
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   For example, did you know that Rule 1.04 on The Playing Field
says that ``it is desirable that the line from home plate through
the pitchers plate to second base shall run East-Northeast.'' Is
that why left-handers are called ``southpaws''? We never were good
with a compass.
</P>
<P>
   It also offers the latest rule revisions to readers who send a
self-addressed, stamped envelope to the publishers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-00 2045EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000409.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1687 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-PERU-ELECTION-510(2TA     04-09 0547
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-ELECTION-510(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN STUNNING REVERSAL, PERU'S PRESIDENT NOW FACES RUN-OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFFORD KRAUSS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru _ In a stunning reversal of political fortunes,
President Alberto K. Fujimori appeared to fall well short of
winning a first-round re-election victory Sunday and ended in a
virtual tie with Alejandro Toledo, a business school professor who
was given no chance of winning as little as five weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   After a campaign riddled by irregularities, Fujimori had been
almost uniformly viewed as a sure winner, as dirty tricks and smear
tactics crippled one opponent after another. But an international
outcry over what appeared to be a systematic attempt to steal the
vote peeled support from the president at an accelerating rate in
the final 10 days of the race, pollsters said.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori, consistently popular, is seeking an unprecedented
third term after a tumultuous decade in which he defeated two
terrorist insurrections and ended years of hyperinflation in this
Andean country.
</P>
<P>
   But Toledo managed to capitalize on the disaffection the
campaign had created, as well as unhappiness over the economy and
the appeal of his own personal story as a one-time shoeshine boy
who rose from poverty in a family of 16 children.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a virtual tie Sunday, with surveys of voters
leaving the polls showing 45.2 percent for Toledo and 43.6 percent
for Fujimori, and the need to hold a run-off by the first week of
June.
</P>
<P>
   That outcome was privately viewed by the Clinton administration
and Organization of American States as the best possible to assure
the political standing and economic stability of a country that has
been a strong American ally in combating insurgencies and drug
trade in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Fears of a fraudulent victory by Fujimori, foreign diplomats
here said, opened the possibility that the Organization of American
States would rule that the election did not meet international
standards and withdraw recognition of the Lima government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite all the irregularities, the people have spoken,''
Toledo, looking relaxed wearing faded jeans and a green work shirt,
said in a formal appearance before reporters. ``We celebrate the
fiesta of democracy.'' But he added that he wanted to wait for
official results to make a detailed statement. Fujimori had no
immediate public comments.
</P>
<P>
   A centrist, Toledo campaigned promising to strengthen the powers
of local government, make the court system independent of
presidential influence and use tax incentives to bolster
agribusiness as a way to boost exports and create jobs.
</P>
<P>
   With his strong Indian facial features, he was able to tap into
the large urban population of mestizos, as people of mixed
Indian-Latino race are known, and offer himself as an example of
what a poor son of a bricklayer and street market fish saleswoman
can do with an education.
</P>
<P>
   Several television networks broadcast the results, as well as
exit polls showing that Fujimori had lost control of Congress.
Fujimori's coalition, Peru 2000, won the largest bloc of
congressional votes, but two-thirds of the seats will be divided
among several opposition groups.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicated that Fujimori was able to cling to his rural
Indian voter base with a campaign that promised to continue tough
policies that would prevent future terrorism and a broadening of
milk and cereal handouts to ease hunger in Andean and jungle
villages. He had also promised to extend lunch programs and
computer classes to schools across the country and build more roads
connecting the provincial hinterlands, while he handed out hundreds
of thousands of land titles to landless peasants.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori sometimes appeared to be a reluctant candidate who was
pushed into the race by eager aides, especially his intelligence
chief Vladimiro Montesinos, concerned about losing their jobs or
future prosecution for corruption. He campaigned in earnest with
only two weeks left before the election, and he frequently appeared
to be going through the motions while on the stump.
</P>
<P>
   In the last days of the campaign, however, Fujimori appeared to
be animated again. He donned Indian costumes and danced on
platforms across the country. The pace of his rallies _ some days
staging well-orchestrated rallies in several desert cities along
the coast and high altitude Andean provincial capitals within hours
_ amazed even his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   He also began airing an effective barrage of television and
radio commercials arguing that now that he had defeated terrorism
and hyperinflation and made peace with neighboring Ecuador, he was
ready to roll up sleeves and attack the problem of unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   But Fujimori was dogged by a scandal amply documented by the
newspaper El Comercio involving campaign workers who forged 1
million signatures to get him on the ballot. The mounting evidence
forced several election officials and congressional candidates
allied with Fujimori to resign, and gave the impression that the
president had lost control over what was once thought to be a
well-oiled political machine.
</P>
<P>
   He was also hurt by steady criticism that he had replaced judges
and manipulated the Congress in order to run for an unprecedented
third five-year term despite a constitutional ban.
</P>
<P>
   In the final days of the campaign, the Organization of American
States observer team released a report expressing concerns that
systematic campaign irregularities had ``impeded the citizenry from
having the confidence that sufficient conditions exist for the
exercise of effective democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, a former World Bank official with a Stanford Ph.D. and a
Belgian-born naturalized American wife, was the surprise of the
election. After running a poor third in the 1995 presidential
election, he was not expected to be a threat this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Toledo surged sharply in the last five weeks of the campaign
after the candidacies of two other candidates were destroyed by a
series of vicious personal attack campaigns appearing in the
leading television networks and tabloid newspapers that were
believed to be directed by Fujimori's intelligence service.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two weeks of the campaign, the smears were directed
at Toledo, but pollsters said they did not seem to have the same
impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``The demolition machine just ran out of steam,'' said Santiago
Pedraglio, a political columnist for the daily Gestion. ``The
element of surprise and credibility were gone.'' Pedraglio
predicted that it would be hard for Fujimori to recover in a second
round because ``he will no longer be viewed as the figure on the
top of Mount Olympus.''
</P>
<P>
   Police vans equipped with water cannons patrolled the streets of
Lima, but there were no reports of serious violence.
</P>
<P>
   But there were reports of electoral computer glitches and at
least sporadic vote fraud from across the country throughout the
day, including instances of convicts voting, ballots filled in
before they were given to voters and people voting with false
documentation presumably to cast their ballots more than once.
</P>
<P>
   Most common were reports of ballots distributed with the name of
Toledo, the leading opposition candidate, cut from voting sheets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is outrageous fraud being committed,'' Toledo declared
on a national radio network when he voted at midday. He said
electoral authorities were confiscating and hiding evidence of
fraudulent ballots after complaints had been filed, adding, ``I
plead that they stop dirtying this process.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Teresa Gonzalez de Fanning School in the lower-middle
class Lima neighborhood of Jesus Maria, dozens of voters
insistently chanted ``fraud, fraud, fraud'' in a spontaneous
demonstration before television cameras while election observers
complained to election officials that Toledo's name had been cut
from the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just too much,'' said Cesar Cary, a 62-year-old
handyman after he voted at the school. ``It's mortifying for the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, observers said, Toledo's support was too great and
the international scrutiny of the vote too daunting for the
government to perpetrate fraud on a scale that would have been
needed for Fujimori to win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-00 2049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000409.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1689 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-SANDERS-PROFILE-ART-N     04-09 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANDERS-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDEPENDENT IS NO LONGER ALONE IN FIGHT OVER DRUG COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Bernard Sanders is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The pharmaceutical industry has a lot of problems
in Washington these days, its prices and profits proving an
irresistible target for politicians with hard-pressed elderly
constituents and an election on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   But there are few more persistent irritants than Rep. Bernard
Sanders, the democratic socialist from Vermont who is one of two
independents in the House. Sanders, a gruff-spoken 58-year-old
native of the Flatbush section of Brooklyn, with a thatch of white
hair and a rumpled '60s-academic style, has twice taken elderly
constituents on well-publicized trips to Canada to buy prescription
drugs, highlighting the lower prices across the border.
</P>
<P>
   He has pushed legislation that he said would allow American
pharmacists and distributors to ``reimport'' prescription drugs
from Canada and Mexico and sell them at lower costs.
</P>
<P>
   When a lobbying alliance backed by the pharmaceutical industry
set up a Web site last month to highlight the problems in the
Canadian health system (www.busfromcanada.org), Sanders quickly
countered with a Web site about the inequities of American drug
pricing and the legislative proposals to deal with them
(bernie.house.gov/bustocanada).
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Thursday night, just after he left the floor
of the House where he had been railing one more time against the
industry, Sanders had the quiet glow of a man who believes that
political lightning is finally striking his cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're dealing here not just with an economic issue or even a
health care issue, you're dealing with a very profound moral
issue,'' he said. ``Time is long overdue for the Congress to stand
up to these people and protect the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackie Cottrell, a spokeswoman for the Pharmaceutical Research
and Manufacturers of America, responded, ``What's moral is to make
sure medicines are available through insurance coverage, but also
to make sure that Congressman Sanders and his allies don't stifle
our ability to invent medicines that help and heal.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders has focused on this issue since the 1980s when he was
the mayor of Burlington, Vt., and created a task force on health
care. Medicare, the health program for the elderly, generally does
not cover outpatient prescription drugs, and a third of its elderly
beneficiaries have no drug coverage at all. ``You can't walk down a
main street in Vermont without someone coming up and saying,
`Bernie, you've got to do something about the high cost of
prescription drugs,''' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These days, of course, nearly every one says they want to do
something to help the elderly with drug costs, but Sanders stands
out. He believes not only in new prescription drug coverage for the
elderly, and not only in finding a way to end what he considers
price discrimination against American consumers, but in a publicly
financed national health insurance program _ a Canadian-style
system, administered by the states _ for everyone.
</P>
<P>
   He does not seem to worry much about the drug industry's
arguments that its prices in the United States are necessary to
cover the cost of research. He said he met with some industry
lobbyists last year and remembers that they were wearing ``fancy
shoes.'' He spoke not with irony but _ to use his word _ with
``contempt.''
</P>
<P>
   In an age of careful centrism, there is an archaic quality to
Sanders' political speech, not to mention a razor's edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what it's like to live in a family without any money,''
he said, ``the economic suffering that is totally unnecessary''
among the uninsured, the working poor and many of the elderly. His
father, who emigrated from Poland at the age of 17, was a paint
salesman. ``He worked very hard. He never made a lot of money,''
Sanders said in a quick staccato, his eyes focused on the floor.
``Lack of money was a constant stress on my parents relationship
and in our household.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders' only sibling, a brother, became a social worker.
Sanders himself, after a year at Brooklyn College, went to the
University of Chicago on a combination of loans, grants and
part-time jobs. He was a lackluster student, he wrote in his
autobiography, but ``learned a lot more from my out-of-class
activities'' in groups like the Congress on Racial Equality and the
Young People's Socialist League.
</P>
<P>
   He moved to Vermont in the late 1960s, working at a mixture of
state government, carpentry and writing jobs, and ultimately ended
up in politics. Initially, he had little success, but he was
elected mayor of Burlington from 1981 to 1989, and in 1990 won
Vermont's only House seat, the first independent elected to
Congress in 40 years. Sanders has four children, and his wife, Jane
O'Meara Sanders, has been a key adviser in his political career.
</P>
<P>
   While he tends to align with the Democrats, he said he never
considered becoming one. Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Both major political parties are heavily influenced by big
money,'' he said. He noted that in nine years in Congress, he has
spent one weekend in Washington. He talked scornfully of the
journalists and the politicians who spend their time talking to one
another, with ``no sense of what's going on in the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders clearly feels he has the drug industry on the defensive.
``What I try to do here is not to be an ideologue, but to talk
issues,'' he said. ``And when you talk issues, people respond
positively.'' Still, he acknowledges, ``I sometimes scratch my head
that somebody like me ever made it to the U.S. Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-00 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
