<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERSHISER TO START DODGERS' HOME OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - Mother Nature and the injury bug did what the Dodgers
couldn't do. Because of the April snowstorm in the Northeast, and
the injury to Kevin Brown, the Dodgers shuffled around their
pitching rotation to create perhaps one of those never-to-forget
moments.
</P>
<P>
   Orel Hershiser, the Dodgers icon who stirred old-time emotion
when he signed with the club last December, will mark his return to
Dodger Stadium by starting the Dodgers' home opener Friday against
the Cincinnati Reds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly deserves that,'' said Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson, who made the announcement with a smile. ``I want to see
it. I just want to see his name up there (on the scoreboard) and
him walk to the mound on opening day at Dodger Stadium. It'll be
special for me and special for him and a lot of fans.''
</P>
<P>
   The naming of Hershiser as the pitcher for the home opener
brought an additional chill to a day filled with shivers. Sunday's
game between the Mets and Dodgers was snowed out. It will be made
up April 24 at Shea Stadium at 7:10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's significant to what he's meant to the organization and
how important he's been to the history of this organization,'' said
first baseman Eric Karros, the Dodger with the most tenure. ``It's
fitting he'll open a (renovated) stadium under new ownership. It
should be a good day.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in spring training the Dodgers talked about setting up
their rotation to allow Hershiser to pitch a nostalgic home opener.
But Hershiser said he balked at the idea because he didn't want the
rotation manipulated on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   But when Brown suffered a broken right pinkie in Saturday's 6-5
10-inning win against the Mets, most likely knocking him out three
to four weeks, the Dodgers had to alter plans. Hershiser was
initially slated to start the inaugural game at Pac Bell Park
against San Francisco on Tuesday, but that's changed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Chan Ho Park will pitch Tuesday, followed by Darren
Dreifort. The Dodgers are yet to announce a starter for Thursday's
series finale, but it's expected to be lefty Jeff Williams.
Hershiser pitches Friday against the Reds, and a starter isn't
named for Saturday, but Eric Gagne is the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sentimentally, Dodger Stadium renovated, year 2000, back as a
Dodger, it will be fun,'' Hershiser said. ``When they approached me
about it (in spring training), I didn't want to do it. With
Brownie, somebody, or everybody, was going to get pushed back. So
why not me?''
</P>
<P>
   However, the circumstances in which Hershiser's been thrust into
the opening-day limelight isn't what the Dodgers need.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and Gagne, who allowed one hit in six innings for
Triple-A Albuquerque on Saturday, are teammates with the Dukes and
are only being called upon because of the injury to Brown and one
to Gregg Olson. The latter two are expected to be placed on the
disabled list before Tuesday's game in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Olson has a strain in his right forearm and Brown broke his
right pinkie. Brown is scheduled to see Dr. Norman Zemel, a hand
specialist, today in Los Angeles. Brown said he wants to continue
to pitch if the injury won't create long-term problems, but the
Dodgers don't want it to come to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about impossible (for Brown to pitch hurt),'' Johnson
said. ``I wouldn't even chance it. But in deference to him, I'm
going to let him see the doctor and then make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of the durable Brown, who's thrown 979 innings the last
four seasons, is a crushing blow to the Dodgers, but players and
coaches are talking otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort and Park are the two who will need to carry most of the
load to keep the Dodgers in contention until Brown returns.
Greatness has been forecast for Park and Dreifort, both in the
early part of developing as starters, but neither has delivered in
the big way expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get production out of everybody, whether Brownie
gets hurt or not,'' Dodgers pitching coach Claude Osteen said.
``Those guys are capable of doing that. It's hard to lose Brownie
because he's such an anchor man, but when they go out to pitch,
there's nobody that can hold their hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always pressure, but it shouldn't cause Chan Ho to
lose focus on what he's trying to do. He has his work cut out with
or without Brown. Same with Dreifort.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
