u i BC-GREECE-ELECTION-NYT &LR;      04-09 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREECE-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCIALIST PRIME MINISTER WINS NARROW RE-ELECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece _ In a harrowingly close vote that showed more
indecision than clear favor, Greek voters on Sunday re-elected the
Socialist prime minister, Costas Simitis, a reserved technocrat who
brought the faltering Greek economy into line with the European
Union.
</P>
<P>
   Simitis' mandate was jolted by Costas Karamanlis, leader of the
New Democracy Party, a fresh, but untested politician who tapped
into voters' thirst for change.
</P>
<P>
   With 90 percent of the vote counted, Simitis' party, the
Panhellenic Socialist Movement, or PASOK, was ahead by less than 1
percentage point, about 30,000 votes.
</P>
<P>
   After a long, emotional roller coaster of a night, a smiling
Simitis, 64, arrived at the central election headquarters at 1:45
a.m. as fireworks in the green-and-white PASOK colors went off in
the sky. He claimed a victory that he described as ``greater than
the numbers.'' He committed himself to work for stability and
greater prosperity for all Greeks and called for an end to
political differences.
</P>
<P>
   The first partial exit polls projected that the conservative New
Democracy Party was ahead by 1 percentage point, which drove
supporters and even some party leaders to predict a premature
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The waves of excitement and crashing disappointment so whipped
up supporters of both candidates in Salonika, where Karamanlis'
district is situated, that the riot police were called in to
separate the two fevered crowds.
</P>
<P>
   The results were clearly not the ringing endorsement Simitis
sought when he called early elections. But the dead heat also
reflected an unprecedented absence of deep ideological differences.
Karamanlis, 43, espoused the same pragmatic path taken by his rival
_ fiscal restraint to meet European prerequisites for inclusion in
the European currency, the Euro, and rapprochement with Greece's
historic enemy, Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   In a concession speech given at 2:30 a.m., Karamanlis referred
to the new leverage his party won in the close race. ``It's obvious
the government cannot proceed without our consent,'' he said. ``Our
battle for a better Greece continues.''
</P>
<P>
   Voting is compulsory in Greece, and turnout among the 9 million
registered voters was close to 75 percent. Under Greece's system,
the party that gets the largest percentage of the vote is assured
of a parliamentary majority.
</P>
<P>
   Voters weighed Simitis' proven, stolid experience against their
yearning for new blood after nearly 20 years of PASOK rule,
interrupted only by a fragile New Democracy government from 1990 to
1993.
</P>
<P>
   Many voters who supported Simitis simultaneously expressed
disenchantment with his party, PASOK, whose longevity in power bred
corruption and inertia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tempted until the last minute to vote for a new face,
but in the end I chose the interests of the country,'' Konduvas
Constantinos, 39, said after voting in an elementary school in
central Athens. ``Greek membership in the Euro is very important,
and when the future is uncertain, it's hard to choose someone who
is also uncertain. I prefer a more experienced leader, even if I am
a bit tired of PASOK.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the Greek economy fell embarrassingly short of
the European Union's minimum standards for membership in the Euro.
Greece has since caught up, and is almost certain to be included in
the Euro next January. But that also proved a liability, since few
voters said they felt Greece's inclusion remained at risk, and many
complained about the punishing effects of the government's fiscal
austerity.
</P>
<P>
   Greek voters, who only recently _ and unevenly _ began feeling
the benefits of economic growth, now at 3.5 percent, had to decide
whether to entrust their fragile stability to a promising, but
inexperienced newcomer.
</P>
<P>
   Karamanlis, a lawyer who got his doctorate degree at the
Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy at Tufts University in
Massachusetts in 1985, ran an energetic, skillful campaign, but he
is chiefly known as the nephew and namesake of Constantine
Karamanlis, the founder of New Democracy and a former president and
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Many Greek voters warmed to his gregarious, exuberant campaign
style, which contrasted with the incumbent's stolid diffidence.
</P>
<P>
   Simitis, an academic who was driven into exile by the military
junta that ruled Greece between 1967 and 1974, was a co-founder of
his party. Since he took office in 1996, he has moved the party
sharply away from its anti-NATO, anti-European, anti-capitalist
roots. Like Tony Blair with his ``new Labor'' in Britain, he
represents a ``new PASOK,'' carefully aimed at the center. That
shift alienated old party loyalists, even as it attracted younger
independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   The vote count was hair-raising, but the nine-week campaign was
bland by Greek standards, which in itself marked a significant
change from the past. ``This is the first time since World War II
that the U.S. was not an issue in the campaign,'' said the American
ambassador, Nicholas Burns. ``Its also the first campaign since
1965 that hasn't been marked by a huge ideological chasm.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, the battle was over social issues. Karamanlis sought to
exploit ordinary people's discontent over unemployment, which is
now at 11 percent, bloated and inefficient social services, and
antiquated state monopolies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
