<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON DOESN'T THINK SHAQ'S INJURY WILL LINGER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT MAGOLOFF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO - Shaquille O'Neal's left ankle has attracted more
attention these last few days than his Madison Avenue smile or
widely publicized struggles at the foul line ever did. After
missing Friday's practice and Saturday's 98-80 loss to San Antonio,
the league's leading scorer and second-leading rebounder sat out
Sunday's light practice as well.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal sprained the ankle during Wednesday's victory over Golden
State and will be re-evaluated before tonight's game against
potential first-round playoff opponent Seattle. The Sonics beat the
Lakers 82-81 at Staples Center on Jan. 17 in the teams' only L.A.
encounter this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what it's like tomorrow,'' said coach Phil Jackson,
who added that it was ``better.'' Jackson also said he did not
expect it to be a lingering problem.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, who did not talk to reporters, received treatment during
the shootaround. Point guard Derek Fisher said O'Neal - the last
player remaining at the training facility - was being administered
hydrotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite there being only five games left in the regular season,
Jackson is not about to get stressed over O'Neal's condition. At
least, not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose if you just had a couple of games left in the
season, that would be enough time,'' Jackson said. ``Two or three
games would probably be the minimum a player would have to play to
get something back again.''
</P>
<P>
   Time is on O'Neal's side. The Lakers have three days off after
tonight's game until they meet Sacramento, another potential
first-round opponent, on Friday at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Big void: The numbers don't lie. Without O'Neal, the Spurs
limited Los Angeles to season lows in points (80) and shooting
percentage (31.6) on Saturday, a day when the Lakers lost for the
first time in 12 games and second time in 32.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant took a career-high 30 shots but made only 12.
Jackson wasn't concerned, however, saying the team's inconsistent
effort was more of a factor in the sluggish offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sideline triangle was once called the triple-post offense
because you can use so many people in the post,'' Jackson said.
``The reality is, we used Michael in the post a zillion times in
Chicago. It's whoever gets to that post first, and the player that
wants to go in there has the free right to go in there. And that's
what happened (with Bryant on Saturday).''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant said he did not put any extra pressure on himself to
produce in O'Neal's absence. He instead pointed out the lackluster
defensive effort and the team's lack of opportunities to practice
an offense sans O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a good film session (Sunday) actually,'' Bryant said.
``We went over the things we need to do. It was good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Downplayed: The Lakers are 2-1 this year against Seattle, which
has won only twice in its last 10 games. Despite the potential
playoff ramifications and the maintenance of the team's confidence
heading into the second season, Jackson downplayed tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may not be ultimately important at all,'' Jackson said.
``Who knows how important it's going to be. The reality is, it's a
game and it's (today) and we want to play and we want to give a
good effort and we want to play better than we did Saturday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
