<DOCNO> NYT20000409.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1702 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-RANGERS-FLYERS-NY     04-09 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-FLYERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS END BITTER SEASON WITH FAMILIAR REFRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With five minutes remaining in the Rangers' season,
the crowd at Madison Square Garden cranked up a new chant:
``Refund! Refund!''
</P>
<P>
   The team's ownership, which spent more than $61 million to miss
the playoffs for the third consecutive season, was probably
thinking the same.
</P>
<P>
   After the Philadelphia Flyers wrapped up the best record in the
Eastern Conference with a 4-1 victory Sunday at the Garden, the
Rangers' 1999-2000 season mercifully ended.
</P>
<P>
   With their third consecutive loss, the Rangers closed out their
third consecutive losing season with an 0-8-1 record. The Rangers
finished 29-41-12-3 over all, their worst record in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   How complete was their collapse? The Rangers were 1-11-2 over
the final 14 games. They lost their final five home games and
finished 15-21-5 at the Garden, the third consecutive season they
have had a losing record at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the end of a nightmare, that's for sure,'' said John
Tortorella, the Rangers' interim coach. ``As far as the
organization is concerned, I guess the best thing to do now is
start looking ahead, because we're rock bottom right now. It can't
get any lower than this.''
</P>
<P>
   The players were scheduled to report to the team's training
facility in Rye, N.Y., Monday afternoon for season-ending
physicals. Each player will report to the Garden offices Tuesday or
Wednesday for individual meetings with the assistant general
manager, Don Maloney, and the Garden president, Dave Checketts.
</P>
<P>
   Then it is up to Checketts to pick a successor to Neil Smith,
the team president and general manager he fired on March 28 along
with Coach John Muckler.
</P>
<P>
   The new general manager's first duty will be to pick a coach.
Then, perhaps, the healing can truly begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is over,'' Tortorella said. ``And now we can start
fresh.''
</P>
<P>
   Only three holdovers remain from the Rangers team that won the
Stanley Cup in 1994: defenseman Brian Leetch, wing Adam Graves and
goaltender Mike Richter. The last three seasons have worn on all
three, and this season hurt the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we had higher expectations,'' Graves said. ``And when
you fall short of your expectations, it's not a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley Cup playoffs begin Wednesday, without the Rangers.
``It's supposed to be the best time of the year,'' said Leetch, who
has been the Rangers' captain the last three seasons. ``It feels
like it can't get any worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Leetch hinted that changes were needed in the dressing room.
``We certainly need a different approach from the way things are
right now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers could use more production from players like Theo
Fleury, a 31-year-old right wing, who finished his worst season in
street clothes because of a sore right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably shouldn't have played the last month,'' said
Fleury, who finished with 15 goals in 80 games, his fewest goals
since he scored 14 in 36 games as a rookie in 1988-89.
</P>
<P>
   Fleury, who signed a three-year, $21 million contract last
summer, repeated his desire to remain a Ranger. He has a no-trade
clause, and said Sunday that he would not waive it.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Fleury has a way to go before he wins his way back into
the good graces of Rangers fans.
</P>
<P>
   That became clear when Fleury was booed during a postgame
fan-appreciation ceremony in which the players took the sweaters
off their backs and handed them to young fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``As players, we have to take responsibility for what happened
this season,'' Fleury said. ``But so many other things happened
here. It obviously could have been better. It should have been
better.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't. Hence the Garden boos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans have actually been pretty good to us, considering the
way this season's gone,'' Leetch said.
</P>
<P>
   The fans saved their best for last, however. As the Rangers were
handing their sweaters to the children, a fan yelled out one last
zinger:
</P>
<P>
   ``Throw it back at them!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
