<HEADLINE>
KENTUCKIAN COULD BE HEADED HOME WITH DERBY FAVORITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ It marvels Jenine Sahadi that she can remember
her first trip to the Kentucky Derby, especially considering her
surroundings that day in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my freshman year at University of Kentucky, and I was
in the infield,'' she said. ``I'll just leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi, 37, is headed back to the Derby, but this trip will be a
lot more tame. In terms of debauchery, Mardi Gras has nothing on
the infield when 50,000 people are packed into it at the Kentucky
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi trains The Deputy, who is going to be one of the
favorites in Kentucky after he won the Santa Anita Derby on
Saturday. With Chris McCarron riding, The Deputy rallied despite a
wide trip and a slow pace to beat previously unbeaten War Chant.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Santa Anita Derby has produced the Kentucky Derby
winner each of the past three years, it has never been the winner
of the Santa Anita Derby. Silver Charm and Real Quiet finished
second at Santa Anita before winning in Kentucky, and Charismatic
was a very unimpressive fourth last year before the trip to
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern might favor the more lightly raced War Chant, whom
jockey Jerry Bailey said was showing his inexperience because he
gawked at The Deputy instead of competing against him in the
stretch. And maybe Captain Steve or Anees shouldn't be thrown out
of consideration because they were trying to close on slow
fractions of 471/5 seconds through the opening half mile.
</P>
<P>
   Surfside set those fractions, but she still ``didn't offer much
resistance'' according to jockey Pat Day when War Chant and The
Deputy made their moves. D. Wayne Lukas trains Surfside and said
she likely will go back in with fillies in the Kentucky Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   Barry Irwin, who put together the ownership syndication that
imported The Deputy from Great Britain for $500,000, thinks he
won't be beaten by any of those horses in the Santa Anita field. He
worries more about Fusaichi Pegasus, who handed The Deputy his only
loss since coming to North America in the San Felipe Stakes on
March 19.
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus has his final Derby prep in the Wood Memorial
Stakes on Saturday in New York. He'll have to beat highly regarded
Gotham Stakes winner Red Bullet, and he'll have to handle his own
notorious nervous disposition once he gets in front of the crowd of
more than 130,000 people at the Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our horse will be bothered by that,'' Irwin
said. ``Unless Red Bullet or some other freaky horse shows up, I
think we're in a great spot.'' \Nsubheds:Lone Star news Bob Baffert
said he might ship Purely Cozzene to Lone Star for the $200,000 USA
Stakes that's part of Lone Star Million Day on May 29.
</P>
<P>
   Purely Cozzene was a front-running winner by 21/2 lengths in the
$75,000 La Puente Stakes at a mile on the Santa Anita turf course
April 2. Baffert trains the colt and said he'll likely run in the
Will Rogers Handicap at Hollywood Park on May 6 before coming to
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Cerin said he's unsure if he'll send Archer City Slew
for the $300,000 Lone Star Derby on April 22. But he confirmed that
he's shipping the Frank Stronach-owned Luftikus, second to General
Challenge in the $500,000 Strub Stakes on Feb. 5, for the $300,000
Texas Mile. The Mile field is likely to include 1999 Met Mile
winner Sir Bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to give \RArcher City Slew\S a little time to
regroup before I decide if I'm going to send him to Lone Star,''
Cerin said after the colt ran seventh in the Turfway Park Spiral
Stakes in his previous start. ``We're obviously off the Derby
trail. So I want to find a race I think he can win.''
</P>
<P>
   David Flores is scheduled to ride Luftikus.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
