<HEADLINE>
ISSUES ASIDE, WARRICK MIGHT BE CATCH OF THE DRAFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHAREAN WILLIAMS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Peter Warrick's past might scare away some
teams. Others might pass on him because of his 40-yard dash time.
</P>
<P>
   But, on film, there is nothing to fear in Warrick but fear
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Warrick caught 132 passes for 2,166 yards and 19 touchdowns the
past two seasons at Florida State. He arguably was the best player
in college football in 1999, and he might be the best player
available in the NFL draft Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But Warrick might not be the first, the second or the third
player selected. Whether it's his shopping scandal, his
unimpressive time in the 40-yard dash or the emergence of Penn
State defenders Courtney Brown and LaVar Arrington, Warrick's stock
has fallen.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're up, people are with you,'' Warrick said. ``But
when you're down, you have a lot of people that go against you. You
can't please everybody. The only person you can try to please is
God. Everything happens for a reason.''
</P>
<P>
   In September, Warrick and a teammate bought $412.38 worth of
clothing for $21.40. Florida State suspended Warrick for two games
after his misdemeanor guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a mistake,'' said Bruce Coslet, whose Cincinnati
Bengals own the fourth choice. ``Ask him if he'd do it again. Well,
how do you learn? You learn from your mistakes. They've got to grow
up. I think he'll be fine. Believe me, I don't think he's any kind
of problem like that.''
</P>
<P>
   There might be more concerns about Warrick's speed. He ran a
4.64 on a gym floor at FSU last month. But Coslet, the only NFL
head coach to attend Warrick's workout at FSU, said Warrick is
capable of a 4.4. In fact, Warrick recently ran a 4.48 for the
Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at that \Rhis 40 time\S, but you keep coming back and
putting on his film and you can't be blinded to the fact that this
is a good football player,'' Philadelphia Eagles coach Andy Reid
said. ``His quickness is second to none at this level or at the
college level.''
</P>
