<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CUBAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBAN A MAVERICK IN THE MAKING AS OWNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ He burst onto the NBA scene in January, a
self-professed geek from the rapidly moving Internet world. He also
had a lot of big _ if not borderline quirky _ ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Cuban, a risk-taker at heart, wanted to solve all of the
Mavericks' problems immediately. He signed the most eccentric
player (Dennis Rodman) maybe ever to play in the NBA in the hopes
of unraveling the mystery of why this franchise has been a playoff
bystander for 10 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But even Rodman turned on the optimistic Cuban, saying: ``I
think that his position and his job is not to sit there and hang on
the players like a coach. That's something like Jerry Jones. That's
kind of dumb.''
</P>
<P>
   At it turns out, Cuban, 41, is no dummy. He made $1.5 billion
last summer selling his Internet company, Broadcast.com, to Yahoo.
Cuban then parlayed that fortune into his lifelong dream _ the
purchase of a professional sports franchise.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 3, Cuban signed a letter of intent to purchase
controlling interest of the Mavericks from Ross Perot Jr. for an
NBA-record $280 million. The final approval of Cuban's bid is
expected tomorrow in New York, where the NBA Board of Governors are
scheduled to meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just excited to get it over with,'' Cuban said. ``It's
been a long time. It seems like forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect any problems. I'm sure if there were any
issues, they'd tell me not to come.''
</P>
<P>
   NBA commissioner David Stern says the 28 owners support Cuban,
that tomorrow's scheduled vote is but a technicality. They are
counting on Cuban's gusto invigorating a dormant franchise in a
league seemingly stagnant since Michael Jordan retired.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban agitated some of the more conservative owners when he
signed Rodman then put him up in his Preston Hollow guest home, and
rented one of his luxury cars to guard Greg Buckner. Many owners
also despise the way Cuban caters to players, while the players
revere Cuban's generosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited he's in the league,'' said Philadelphia 76ers
owner Pat Croce, who became team president in March 1996. ``I love
a guy who's got enthusiasm and excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some of the things in regards to the limos may walk the
fine line of the collective-bargaining agreement law. But he's
learning what that fine line is.''
</P>
<P>
   From limo rides, food in both locker rooms, Super Bowl parties
and a 10-man coaching staff to expensive luggage, towels and
bathrobes, Cuban has spared no expense to provide his players the
best of everything. He has even discussed installing entertainment
centers in each of the Mavericks' lockers in the new arena.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban's ownership style contrasts Perot's. The Mavericks' second
majority owner let coach/general manager Don Nelson run the
basketball portion of the franchise and chief executive
officer/president Terdema Ussery run the business side. Cuban is a
hands-on guy who plans to oversee both the basketball and business
operations of the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's nice now to have a full-time owner who's as
creative as Mark is and has his energy and his passion for the
game, and I think he adds a lot,'' Perot said. ``My ownership style
helped take us through this transition, helped rebuild the team and
put a good foundation underneath the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, Mark's a good owner to take this team into truly the
upper levels of basketball. Mark's going to be a great owner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks never made the playoffs in Perot's tenure, but
Perot succeeded in getting a new arena. The American Airlines
Center is scheduled to open for the 2001-02 season, and Cuban is
determined that it will house a winner.
</P>
<P>
   His passion borders on obsession, and the team's long-suffering
fans appreciate his zest. Cuban has hired a new public-address
announcer, added three assistants to the coaching ranks and hired
former player Derek Harper as a team vice president. Cuban said he
wants to sign an impact free agent this summer, though the team is
already over next season's projected salary cap, and redesign the
team's logo and uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The energy has been fantastic,'' guard Steve Nash said.
``There's been a lot of negative energy surrounding the Mavericks
for quite a while, and for him to come in and alleviate some of
that has been fantastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just given us a shot of energy. ... I think it definitely
hasn't gone unnoticed with the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mavericks were 9-21 before Cuban signed that letter of
intent with Perot. Since, the Mavericks are 24-20 with two
victories over the defending NBA champion San Antonio Spurs, and
are on the verge of finishing with the franchise's best record
since 1989-90. That was also the last time the Mavericks had their
playoff papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a businessman, and he wants to win,'' center Sean Rooks
said. ``At the same token, he's down to Earth, and he gets along
with the guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's only a big upside for Mark and for the Dallas
Mavericks.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern said during All-Star Weekend that he likes what Cuban
offers as an owner. With his background, Cuban will be expected to
help the NBA develop revenue sources online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark's going to be a very good focused and innovative owner,''
said Perot, who will become a minority owner. ``That's why I'm
excited and why I'll continue to be a partner with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The owners are excited to have Mark in. They like his energy,
they like his spirit, and it's good to have owners that are there
full time taking care of these teams. And it's going to be exciting
to watch Mark.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
