<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUGABE-POPULARITY </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUGABE'S POPULARITY WANES AS THE ECONOMY WITHERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIMUKA, Zimbabwe _ At 2:50 p.m., 10 minutes before the rally was
supposed to start, a long flat-bed truck rounded the corner and
raced down the far edge of the soccer field carrying a large mob of
angry men. They were expected.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in 20 years, Zimbabwe is heading into an
election that offers the people a real choice. The stakes are high,
the country is tense, and political violence unfolds almost daily
as if by script. The men in the truck Sunday porters of the ruling
party and President Robert Mugabe. They came with axes, clubs, and
broken bricks to prevent their opponents from meeting.
</P>
<P>
   After a tense standoff, the rally went ahead as planned.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to spread fear so that nobody will vote against
them,'' said Brighton Chingaranda, a member of the Movement for
Democratic Change, a grass-roots opposition group hoping to topple
Mugabe in parliamentary elections next month. ``But the fear has
been completely broken. The people are confident.''
</P>
<P>
   Tapping into deep frustration over economic decay and government
corruption, the Movement has joined trade unionists, human-rights
groups, and ordinary people in a mass call for change. The ruling
class, virtually unchallenged for two decades, is rattled. Mugabe
has resorted to violence, sending veterans of the war for
independence to invade white-owned farms and trucking in toughs to
scare people away from the opposition. More than 800 farms have
been attacked in recent weeks, including several this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis is unprecedented for Zimbabwe. The country faces
crippling shortages of foreign currency. Drivers wait in long lines
for gas and diesel and are often turned away empty. Prices of bread
and cornmeal break meager monthly salaries.
</P>
<P>
   To many Zimbabwe voters, Mugabe seems aloof. While waging a war
in the Democratic Republic of Congo, backing Congolese President
Laurent Kabila at an estimated cost of $3 million a month, he sows
racism and instability to retain his power, his critics contend.
His actions are often considered lawless. Ignoring a high court
ruling, Mugabe has encouraged war veterans to seize and resettle
white-owned farms. As a result, Western governments and lending
institutions last week froze more than $200 million in desperately
needed aid.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Mugabe has used intimidation to keep the public
down, political scientists here said. His military massacred his
ethnic rivals during the mid-1980s. Violence routinely preceded
elections. Critical newspaper reporters and editors have been
detained and beaten.
</P>
<P>
   But the current economic crisis has taken Zimbabweans to a
breaking point, people say, and the fear of challenging Mugabe is
ebbing. What changed?
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone stood up and had the guts to say enough is enough,''
said Burt Pyman, a farm foreman.
</P>
<P>
   That person is Morgan Tsvangirai, a former labor chief and
founding member of the Movement for Democratic Change. Forged by
shop-floor politics and driven by a sense of service, Tsvangirai
comes from a new generation of African leaders who are slowing
replacing their autocratic elders. Understated and determined, he
is nonetheless a reluctant vessel for the people's hopes, accepting
the role he has been given without ever really seeking it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a heavy responsibility,'' he said, ``but sometimes you
get humbled by it. This country has the potential, but it also has
the potential to slide into chaos.''
</P>
<P>
   Tsvangirai is undeterred by Mugabe's threats. He has been
beaten, arrested, and jailed. His house has been attacked. But he
walks around Harare, the capital, unprotected, and jumps in cars
unaccompanied to talk at length with journalists. When he arrives
at rallies, women dance and sing, ``I love Tsvangirai so much I
could strap him on my back,'' as they do their infants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mugabe has moved from hero to villian,'' Tsvangirai said.
``You could not ask for a better opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   Tsvangirai is counting on a generational change to topple
Mugabe. While the president courts the older generation that fought
for liberation, Tsvangirai appeals to a younger audience. And he
vows to make many changes. He'd withdraw from Congo, set up a
commission to arrest and try those in government who are suspected
of having stolen large amounts of public money _ including Mugabe,
he quickly points out _ and impose painful economic measures to
shore up the country's international credit ratings.
</P>
<P>
   On land rights, Zimbabwe's most volatile issue, Tsvangirai said
there is no need to confiscate white-owned farms. Plenty of land
lies fallow, he said. What is needed is a plan for development, he
said, adding that would also scrap the communal land structure,
which has denied peasants the right to own the small plots they
live on.
</P>
<P>
   The critical question is what it will take for Tsvangirai to win
and whether Mugabe would accept defeat. The elections are
parliamentary, and Mugabe still has two years left in his term. But
Tsvangirai believes he can win 65 percent of the seats _ an
ambitious figure, since Mugabe's ruling Zimbabwe African National
Union-Patriotic Front holds 147 of 150 seats now. If Mugabe's foes
control the legislature, Tsvangirai said, Mugabe would be forced to
resign.
</P>
<P>
   Many fear, however, that Mugabe is looking for an excuse to
impose emergency rule, whether by provoking conflict between war
veterans and white farmers or through other political violence.
Would he accept being rejected by the voters? The question does
worry Tsvangirai.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do we encourage Mugabe to have an honorable exit?'' he
said. ``You see, that is the biggest challenge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
