A1714 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKEES-STOTTLEMY     04-09 1141
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-STOTTLEMYRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEL STOTTLEMYRE SAYS HE WILL BEGIN CANCER TREATMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach and a
three-time 20-game winner for the team in the 1960s, revealed
Sunday that he has cancer of the bone marrow, or multiple myeloma.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, 58, will begin chemotherapy treatments this week.
``I feel fine,'' he said. ``Now it's time for me to go in and
tackle this.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre will not be at Yankee Stadium on Tuesday, when the
team plays its home opener against the Texas Rangers, but otherwise
he expects to continue his work. ``My doctors have assured me I'm
going to be able to carry on my normal duties, and I'm going to try
to,'' he said. ``There may be some point later in the season where
I may miss some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Multiple myeloma is a type of cancer formed by malignant plasma
cells. Plasma cells are crucial to the immune system, and when
produced at an abnormal rate, they can cause tumors, particularly
in the bone marrow, and cause anemia, fatigue and increased
susceptibility to infection.
</P>
<P>
   After Stottlemyre completes a four-month series of chemotherapy
_ four days of chemotherapy every four weeks _ he will undergo a
stem cell transplant, in which cells taken from him will be
cleansed and reintroduced into his system. Stottlemyre, who will
receive his treatment at Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in
Manhattan, said he is ``borderline anemic'' but has felt no
fatigue.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Neilson, the coach of hockey's Philadelphia Flyers, also
has multiple myeloma, and he underwent a stem cell transplant last
month, and he left the team to have the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre said: ``They have used the word `cure,' which I'm
very thankful for. The results from this treatment have been pretty
positive. I'm healthy in other standards, so everything is in my
favor.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre said he first learned he might develop the illness
after a blood test taken during a routine physical examination in
spring training of 1999. Yankees Manager Joe Torre underwent
surgery for prostate cancer in March 1999, and afterward
Stottlemyre told Torre of his own ominous test results.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre's blood was tested monthly thereafter. On March 17
this year, he flew to New York for a test while the Yankees were
playing an exhibition game in Orlando, Fla. In the days that
followed, he was told he has the disease. Stottlemyre owns a home
in the Seattle area and in recent days received a second opinion
that supported the initial diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   As Stottlemyre spoke with reporters Sunday, Torre informed the
players in a team meeting, carefully reading from notes. The
players were stunned. He then asked for questions, and they
responded with silence. Stottlemyre went about his work, same as
always, pausing to speak about his prognosis with pitchers Andy
Pettitte and Mike Stanton. David Cone, who flew to New York Sunday
morning to prepare for his start Tuesday, was reached by phone,
with Torre and then Stottlemyre speaking to him in the first
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mel's a real positive man,'' Pettitte said afterward, staring
straight ahead as he dressed. ``He's a tough man.''
</P>
<P>
   Mel Stottlemyre and his wife, Jean, are the parents of three
sons. Jason, the youngest, died of leukemia in 1981. Stottlemyre
and members of his family have done extensive charity work for The
Leukemia and Lymphoma Society. Todd Stottlemyre, the second oldest,
is a pitcher with the Arizona Diamondbacks. After his father
received the diagnosis last month, Todd offered to fly to Florida
to be with him, but Mel encouraged him to remain in Arizona and
prepare for the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, here he had a son go through a similar deal where
leukemia had taken his life, and now to have to battle it in his
adult life,'' Todd Stottlemyre said in a news conference in
Phoenix. ``Yet to do it, as courageous as he is and with the
attitude he is, to me gives him a fighting chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Mel Stottlemyre first pitched for the Yankees in 1964 and
compiled a record of 164-139 during an 11-year career. After
several years out of baseball, Stottlemyre went into coaching,
first as a roving instructor with the Seattle Mariners. He became
the pitching coach of the Mets in 1984, and he worked with Dwight
Gooden, Ron Darling and Cone. The Mets won the World Series in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre joined the Houston Astros for two seasons before
being hired by the Yankees before the 1996 season. The Yankees have
won three championships in the last four seasons, pitching always
the foundation of their success.
</P>
<P>
   Uniformly optimistic and gregarious, Stottlemyre is respected by
the pitchers because he effectively relates to them. Cone said last
year that Stottlemyre anticipates how pitchers prefer to be treated
and coached, during and between games. Stottlemyre said he had
learned a lot from talking with his two oldest sons, both of whom
have played in the majors. ``It's like he never got older,'' Cone
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees players have said, only half-joking, that
Stottlemyre could still pitch in the majors. A sinkerball pitcher
when he played, Stottlemyre throws batting practice and has been
considered by the players as the most difficult coach to hit
against because his pitches sink and dart and move all over the
place. He has always been in excellent condition, not appearing
much different now than in his playing days.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I sit here now, I feel the same as I have for the last five
years,'' Stottlemyre said. ``I've had no hints, no signs of any
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty important for me to continue to work, something
that I enjoy doing, something I enjoy being around, for my state of
mind. It's real important. Obviously, if it comes to a point where
it's going to interfere with my work, my health is first, and if it
creates a problem for my family, it will change. Right now, I do
really feel I need to stay a part of the ball club.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Cloninger, the Yankees' bullpen coach, will serve as the
pitching coach Tuesday, working alongside Torre in the dugout, and
if there are days during the season when Stottlemyre's treatments
cause him to miss work, Cloninger most likely would step in.
</P>
<P>
   Mel and Todd Stottlemyre spoke Sunday morning, before Mel made
his illness public. ``What he said to me this morning was, `Win one
for me tomorrow,''' Todd Stottlemyre said, choking back tears.
``I'd love to get out of here now, but at the same time I know he
wants me to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said: ``When I was diagnosed last year, I had to leave. I
was just scared to death. Mel's a strong guy, and I think I can
understand why he wants to keep working. That's better than sitting
around and thinking about it and worrying about it. There's nothing
more than hurt. It makes the nights very long.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-00 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000409.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1717 &Cx1f; tth-z
r d BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      04-09 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES OF MILITARY CHOW NEVER GROW COLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As you may have heard or read, some of the brightest minds on
Madison Avenue have been recruited to help generate more recruits
for the Army, Navy, Air Force and Marines.
</P>
<P>
   So far their efforts have achieved minimal results. That's
because the government obviously didn't recruit any ``old
soldiers'' to write the advertising copy.
</P>
<P>
   First you have to define the problem. And as any veteran can
attest, the pay is bad, the hours are lousy, the clothes don't fit
and the food is inedible. Oh, yeah, and on occasion complete
strangers shoot at you.
</P>
<P>
   To be successful, a media recruiting campaign must attack these
problems one by one. I'm not sure our generals and admirals are
ready to eliminate bullets and baggy fatigues. But I suspect they
may be nearing a breakthrough on food poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   At the intelligence level, the age-old problem has been
code-named SOS.
</P>
<P>
   That does not stand for, ``save our stomachs,'' but that comes
pretty close. SOS is the chow-line equivalent of ``friendly fire.''
It is poison we inflict upon our own troops, usually at dawn when
defenses are down.
</P>
<P>
   For the uninformed (and ununiformed), SOS stands for Saute on a
Shingle, a staple of service cookery. I will repeat the recipe,
which I first encountered a few decades ago at Fort Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Select three medium-size basic trainees. Remove from their bunks
at 3:30 a.m. and lead them from the barracks to the mess hall, at
the point of an automatic rifle. Assign one to help a cook burn 100
pounds of hamburger, the second to help prepare 30 gallons of
library paste, and the third to char the edges of 1,000 pieces of
bread.
</P>
<P>
   Combine all three ingredients and serve, on cold metal trays, to
500 grumbling, shuffling gourmets who will mutter, in unison,
``Don't tell me they expect us to eat this saute ...'' Or something
like that.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe they don't have to eat it anymore. A recent news
report described experiments now under way to provide quick energy
to troops in emergency situations with a sort of nutritional
Band-Aid affixed to the arm. It supposedly will give the GIs an
energy boost, like they might otherwise get from a candy bar or a
cold beer.
</P>
<P>
   Why haven't the advertising copywriters seized upon this? The
hours will still be lousy, the pants will still be baggy, you'll
never get rich by digging a ditch. But a Band-Aid solution to Saute
on a Shingle could prompt a whole lot of old veterans to re-enlist.
</P>
<P>
   On second thought, naaaaah.
</P>
<P>
   And it's doubtful if they will all adopt the Band-Aid diet in
their civilian lives. Not when there are alternatives like these:
</P>
<P>
   Old Sergeant's Stew
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup canola or olive oil
</P>
<P>
   4 pounds lean beef chunks
</P>
<P>
   One-half cup flour
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds large onions, thickly sliced
</P>
<P>
   6 cloves garlic, put through a press
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons thyme leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 teaspoons salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Lots of freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 and one-half cups beef broth or bouillon
</P>
<P>
   2 12-ounce cans or bottles of beer
</P>
<P>
   4 large carrots, in one-inch chunks
</P>
<P>
   Cut the beef into three-quarter-inch chunks.
</P>
<P>
   OK, heat the oil in a large skillet. Coat the beef with flour,
then brown in small batches. When each batch is done, transfer with
a slotted spoon to an oven casserole.
</P>
<P>
   When all the meat is done, toss the onions into the skillet and
let 'em sizzle for about two minutes. Add the garlic and cook
another minute, then add this mess to the casserole, along with the
sugar, vinegar, thyme, salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the beef broth into the empty skillet. Stir with a wooden
spoon to incorporate any brown bits in the pan, then pour this
sludge into the casserole. Add the beer, and I prefer a dark brew.
</P>
<P>
   Cover the casserole and shove into a 325-degree oven for two
hours. After the first hour, stir in the carrots then return to the
oven.
</P>
<P>
   When done, move the casserole to the burner on your range. Stir
in three tablespoons of Wondra flour that have been mixed with a
third of a cup of water. Keep stirring and when the sauce has
thickened, serve the stew with:
</P>
<P>
   Civilian Cornbread
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half cups flour
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-half cups yellow cornmeal
</P>
<P>
   One-third cup grated Romano cheese
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup chopped green pepper
</P>
<P>
   One-quarter cup sliced green onions
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons melted butter or canola oil
</P>
<P>
   4 teaspoons chili powder
</P>
<P>
   1 and one-third cups milk
</P>
<P>
   2 slightly beaten eggs
</P>
<P>
   Sift together flour, baking powder, salt and sugar. Stir in
cornmeal, cheese, green pepper and onion.
</P>
<P>
   Plunk the butter or oil in small bowl and stir in the chili
powder, milk and eggs. Mix, then plop this mess into the dry
ingredients and stir just until all the flour is moistened.
</P>
<P>
   Pour batter into a greased, 9-inch-square cake pan. Bake in a
400-degree oven for about 35 minutes, or until a toothpick comes
out clean after you poke the bread in the middle. We are assuming
that the toothpick was clean when you stuck it in. Cut in squares
and serve warm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
