u a BC-JONBENET-NEW-THEORY-8     04-09 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JONBENET-NEW-THEORY-825&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONBENET'S MOTHER WAS KILLER, DETECTIVE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A former Boulder police detective who spent almost two years
investigating the murder of JonBenet Ramsey says in a new book that
he and other investigators concluded that the 6-year-old girl was
killed by her mother, Patsy Ramsey.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Thomas, who resigned from the police department in
mid-1998, writes that he concluded that Patsy Ramsey strangled her
daughter in a panic on Christmas night 1996 after accidentally
causing a serious wound to the little girl's head. He also contends
that the girl's father, John Ramsey, after realizing what had
happened, ``chose to protect his wife'' rather than help the
authorities determine what happened.
</P>
<P>
   By outlining his theory in ``JonBenet: Inside the Ramsey Murder
Investigation'' (St. Martin's Press), which is scheduled to be
released to the public on Tuesday, Thomas has become the first
person with direct knowledge of the investigation to publicly
accuse Patsy Ramsey of killing her daughter. He also says he
concluded that John Ramsey played no role in the girl's death.
</P>
<P>
   The accusations against Patsy Ramsey were disputed by her
lawyer, L. Lin Wood, who called them ``fiction and utter
nonsense,'' and other Boulder officials are believed to have views
that differ from Thomas'.
</P>
<P>
   Wood said in an interview that Thomas' theory ``is refuted in
its entirety by medical evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ramseys deny that they were involved in the killing. In
their own book, ``Death of Innocence'' (Thomas Nelson), which was
released last month, they argue that JonBenet was killed by an
intruder, a theory that some detectives favor.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas concedes in his book that one veteran homicide detective
who worked on the case, Lou Smit, believes that the evidence
suggests someone broke into the Ramseys' home in Boulder, Colo.,
strangled JonBenet ``in some sort of autoerotic fantasy'' and hid
her body in the basement where John Ramsey discovered it the next
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Guided by a police axiom that ``murders are usually what they
seem,'' Thomas counters, ``the simplest explanation for ... one of
the most perplexing and notorious murders of the decade is also the
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' book is unlikely to spur any new police action. His
theory of the crime, as well as Smit's, has been vetted by
investigators and Alex Hunter, the Boulder district attorney. The
conflicting views, which mirror conflicting evidence, were largely
the reason that Hunter dismissed a grand jury last October that
heard evidence in the case for 13 months without indicting anyone.
</P>
<P>
   As Thomas admits in his book, Hunter and others did not feel
confident that all the evidence pointed in one direction.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter declined to discuss any specific points raised by Thomas,
but said in an interview, ``It is improper in my judgment for a cop
to be talking about confidential information in an ongoing case.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lack of indictments, the authorities in Boulder said
they were keeping the Ramseys ``under the umbrella of suspicion,''
as Mark Beckner, Boulder police chief, told reporters after the
grand jury was dismissed. But nobody in the case before Thomas had
revealed how detectives believed one scenario might point to Patsy
Ramsey as the killer.
</P>
<P>
   By Thomas' analysis, Patsy Ramsey had grown frazzled by
Christmas night 1996 because of ``an approaching fortieth birthday,
the busy holiday season, an exhausting Christmas Day and an
argument with JonBenet'' over a bed-wetting incident that led to
``some sort of explosive encounter in the child's bathroom,'' which
resulted in a mortal head wound.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas says he concluded that while JonBenet's head was probably
injured by accident, Patsy Ramsey, rather than summon help,
panicked after her daughter fell unconscious. That, he says, led
her to write a note suggesting that JonBenet had been kidnapped,
after which she ``faced the major problem of what to do with the
body.''
</P>
<P>
   It was at that point, Thomas concludes, that the accident turned
to murder. He says that on the way to placing her in a remote room
of the basement, Patsy Ramsey realized JonBenet was still alive.
``Only feet away was her paint tote,'' he writes. ``She grabbed a
paintbrush and broke it to fashion the garrote with some cord. Then
she looped the cord around the girl's neck.''
</P>
<P>
   To make it look like a kidnapping, he says, Patsy Ramsey tied
the girl's wrists and taped her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Smit, a former Colorado Springs detective who worked on hundreds
of homicide cases before joining the Ramsey case at Hunter's
invitation in 1997, has often said that he believes the parents are
innocent. He contends that JonBenet was a victim of a pedophile who
molested her, used a stun gun to disable her and, after JonBenet
began screaming, killed her with a blow to the head, possibly with
a flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   Smit, who resigned from the case after a year, has also said
that medical evidence supports his theory more than Thomas'.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Thomas, certain of his interpretation of the evidence, still
regards Smit as a friend but ultimately dismisses him in the book
``as a major problem'' whose views went a long way toward what the
author feels was deferential treatment of the Ramseys by
prosecutors in the district attorney's office. That stance, more
than anything, Thomas writes, led to his resignation from the
police force.
</P>
<P>
   Wood said that Thomas' accusations could expose him to a
lawsuit, a view echoed by Hal Haddon, a lawyer who represents John
Ramsey. Wood also said it was inconceivable that either of the
Ramseys could have killed their daughter, or that if one had, the
other could cover it up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
