<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: `THE ONLY POOR SHOT I HIT ALL WEEKEND' 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ For decades, the storyline at the Masters always
was that the golf tournament didn't really start until the back
nine on Sunday, but Augusta National's back nine seems to have lost
its sense of theater, especially on the 13th and 15th holes where
eagles used to fly.
</P>
<P>
   As Vijay Singh won Sunday, there was only one eagle 3 at the
485-yard 13th hole, by Colin Montgomerie, and none on the 500-yard
15th hole.
</P>
<P>
   The only theater occurred when David Duval, only one stroke
behind Singh at the time, splashed a 5-iron from 196 yards into the
narrow grassy creek in front of the 13th green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to hit it in the same area that Vijay hit it,
kind of up the left center of the green,'' Duval would explain
later. ``I got over the ball, the wind picked up, then it would
die, and the same thing would keep happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just decided on the right line and the right club and hit a
poor golf shot. It was the wrong time to do that and I feel like
that was probably the only poor shot I hit this weekend. I really
don't know what else to say about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of possibly putting for an eagle, Duval wound up with a
bogie 6 as Singh birdied _ a sudden two-shot swing that created a
three-shot lead. Duval, with a 70, tied for third with Loren
Roberts, four shots back.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the bogie at the 13th, in other years Duval would have
had more of a chance to eagle the 15th, but before last year's
Masters, the green jackets planted a few pine trees to the right of
the fairway there to dissuade the golfers from just blasting away
on their tee shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's virtually impossible to get much closer on your second
shot than Vijay did,'' Duval said, referring to Singh's two-putt
birdie there. ``So that means you're going to have to hole out for
an eagle.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els, the South African who finished second, three shots
back, had never played really well at the Masters before. His best
finish had been a tie for eighth in his first appearance, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew from watching this tournament through the years that
everything happens on the back nine, and I had my chances,'' said
Els, whose 68 was the best score in the final round. ``I had an
eagle putt on 13 and I made birdie putts on 11 and 15.''
</P>
<P>
   But not much happened on the back nine Sunday and Els' three
birdies weren't nearly enough as Singh closed with a solid
three-under-par 69 after 72-67-70.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Vijay a very long time,'' Els said. ``He's been my
practice-round partner for quite a few years. He showed his mettle
Sunday. He's done it before, winning the PGA, and now he's done it
again. This golf course is suited to his game. He's never really
putted here, but he really did the job today.''
</P>
<P>
   After Tiger Woods' 12-stroke victory that was a record 18 under
par in 1997, the Masters green jackets apparently did not want
Woods or anybody else tearing up their pea patch like that again.
</P>
<P>
   ``No doubt about it, this course is more difficult to play now
that it was in 1997,'' Woods said after a 69 that left him in fifth
place, six shots back. ``They've lengthened No. 2 about 40 or 50
yards. They've changed some of the greens. We had a new pin on No.
10 today. Traditionally, it was back left. Now it's front right.
Anything short is going down to the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough test now. I'm not saying it wasn't tough back
then, but it's tougher now because obviously you've got to drive
the ball better and you've still got to be good with the irons, but
now you've got to play out of the rough and you catch fliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They kept the scores down, that's for sure,'' Woods continued.
``But the harder they make it for everybody, the better it plays
into the longer hitters. Look at the leaderboard. Vijay, Duval,
Els, myself, Davis Love, Lehman, Mickelson, all of us are long-ball
hitters. It makes it easier for us to play and more challenging for
people who can't hit the ball as far.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods thought that three missed putts prevented him from
exerting any pressure on the leaders on the back nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those putts go in at 10 and 11,'' he said with a shrug. ``I
hit beautiful putts there that just grazed the edge, then I misread
the putt on 13. If I make birdies there, I'd have been right in the
ball game.''
</P>
<P>
   But those putts didn't go in and Singh won in a Masters that was
more methodical than melodramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago Duval thought he might win or at least be in a
sudden-death playoff until Mark O'Meara birdied three of the last
four holes. And yesterday he thought he might win until that 5-iron
splashed into the grassy creek in front of the 13th green. In his
disappointment, he was asked what he'll take away from what
happened?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'll try again next year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's when the world's No. 2 ranked golfer was reminded that he
would take away about $266,800 in prize money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great,'' he said, sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   David Duval already has $266,800, but he doesn't have a green
jacket. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
