<SLUG> BC-CONGO-CEASEFIRE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOES IN CONGO APPEAL FOR U.N. PEACEKEEPERS
</HEADLINE>
  By DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KAMPALA, Uganda _ All sides in the slow-burning war in Congo
appealed Sunday for the United Nations to deploy peacekeepers
swiftly in the vast Central African country after another
cease-fire in the 18-month-old conflict was signed in the Ugandan
capital over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting Sunday with President Laurent Kabila in Kinshasa,
Congo's capital, his allies in the war _ the presidents of Angola,
Namibia and Zimbabwe _ urged the deployment of a planned 5,500
peacekeepers ``as rapidly as possible,'' state radio in Congo
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Congolese rebels backed by Rwanda and Uganda, all of whom have
been fighting Kabila, also said they supported swift deployment.
</P>
<P>
   The elements of the arrangement signed on Saturday in Kampala
were that all combatants would stop fighting by Friday, then hold
their positions for three months while the U.N. peacekeepers were
deployed in a buffer zone between the warring parties.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, the warring countries can begin to withdraw
after three months.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press, reporting from Kigali, the Rwandan
capital, quoted a spokesman for the Congolese rebels, Kin-Kiey
Mulumba, as saying that his forces would respect the latest
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``By April 14, I think we'll do everything possible to be ready
to pull back,'' Mulumba was quoted as saying. ``But we don't know
what Kabila will do. So we would like to have the United Nations
deploy as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Moise Nyarugabo, a leader of the Rally for Congolese Democracy,
one of the rebel factions opposing Kabila, said no fighting was
taking place in sectors his men controlled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never opposed a cease-fire,'' he said in a radio
interview from Goma in eastern Congo. ``But when you're attacked,
you have to defend yourselves.'' The first cease-fire was signed
last summer in Lusaka. None of the provisions of that cease-fire
was met in full: The fighting did not really end, nor were
independent militias disarmed.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the latest arrangements have argued that the number
of U.N. peacekeepers envisioned is much too small. Congo, the
former Zaire, has 400 times the land mass of Kosovo, with worse
roads and thick forests, and Kosovo has proved a big task for
nearly 40,000 NATO troops, who are generally better trained and
equipped than U.N. peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   However, both pro- and anti-Kabila factions in Congo now appear
militarily weary and financially pressed.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the drama took place during the opening weeks in fall
1998, when the rebels, backed by Ugandan and Rwandan regulars,
managed a startling airborne assault on Kinshasa. They hijacked
planes and used them to ferry troops across the country from the
east to the mouth of the Congo River. But their advance was
repulsed in the capital's suburbs, largely by Zimbabwean troops.
</P>
<P>
   After that defeat, the rebels spread out from the east,
gradually capturing about one-third of the country. But no major
battles have been reported, and the rebels have failed so far in
one important objective: taking the diamond-mining areas around the
southern city of Mbuji-Mayi.
</P>
<P>
   Profits from those mines are allegedly being used to pay the
Zimbabwean government to keep fighting, despite widespread anger in
Zimbabwe over the war's human and economic toll.
</P>
<P>
   Uganda and Rwanda had a falling out last August near the central
city of Kisangani, and their troops fought for two days, leaving
200 dead.
</P>
<P>
   The Ugandan newspaper the Sunday Monitor published an account
Sunday based on interviews with senior Rwandan army officers who
described the August clash as a misunderstanding between friends
that turned violent, not a premeditated attack.
</P>
<P>
   One officer was quoted as saying that some officers from both
armies were playing cards together when the fighting broke out,
that the Rwandans had no doctor with them and would never have
attacked without medical support and that the wounded were all
treated together. ``How could that have happened if we were
enemies?'' Col. James Kadareepe was quoted as asking.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda supported Kabila in his own revolt against Congo's
longtime dictator Mobutu Sese Seko, but turned against him once he
was in power because he sought alliances with Hutu militias that
Rwanda's Tutsi-led government held responsible for 1994 mass
killings in Rwanda. Uganda, too, backed Kabila against Mobutu but
has since turned against him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-00 2126EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000409.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1729 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT &LR;      04-09 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENEWED CONFIDENCE DRIVES SINGH TO FIRST MASTERS TITLE
</HEADLINE>
  By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Vijay Singh used to arrive at the Masters with
trepidation, but he found a way to become its champion.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing fazed Singh on his determined march toward his first
green jacket. He played with precision through howling winds
Saturday. He putted with confidence for four days on greens that
used to confound him. Sunday, he was pursued by some of the best
names in golf _ Ernie Els, David Duval and Tiger Woods. But Singh
never flinched, and never relinquished the lead.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Singh came to Augusta National Golf Club not just to
make the cut, or to contend. Singh came to win. And his confidence,
coupled with his formidable game, carried him to his second major
championship.
</P>
<P>
   Never relinquishing the final-round lead, and calmly navigating
his way through one of golf's most pressure-packed back nines,
Singh won the Masters by three strokes over Els, by four strokes
over Duval and Loren Roberts, and by six strokes over Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a final-round three-under-par 69, Singh finished at 10
under par for the tournament at 278) to beat Els, who shot a
final-round 68. Roberts shot 69 Sunday but fell short in his bid to
win his first major, as did Duval, who shot 70 and made a costly
bogey at No. 13 after his second shot tumbled into Rae's Creek.
Woods, the world's No. 1 player, shot a final-round 69, and he
never seriously threatened Singh on the back nine.
</P>
<P>
   When Singh won the PGA Championship in 1998, he was overjoyed to
win his first major, proving to himself and to others that he had
the talent to win one of golf's most coveted prizes. But Sunday's
victory will elevate Singh's status even higher, because his best
finish at the Masters in sixth previous tries was a tie for 17th
place in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Never known for his putting prowess, Singh admitted in past
years that he was frustrated by Augusta's speedy and undulating
greens, a fact that made many believe that he would never win the
Masters. But this week, Singh was rock-solid with his putting
stroke, and with his powerful tee-to green game, he charged to the
top of the leaderboard after three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   Once there, Singh played too well for anyone to overtake him. He
had won the Masters. And the feeling was hard to describe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walking up that 18th hole, knowing that a two-putt was going
to win the golf tournament was probably one of the greatest
feelings I've had for a long, long time,'' said Singh, a
38-year-old native of Fiji, who lives in Ponte Vedra Beach, Fla.
``Two years ago, I'd have said I can't win this because of the way
I was putting. Augusta's greens are so severe, if you're not a good
putter, you're not going to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm a better putter than I was, and this week was
exceptional, because I drove the ball so well. I was really
confident that with a three-shot lead, as long as I played solid,
they'd have to come up and catch me.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody did catch Singh, who started the final round with a
three-stroke lead, after completing the final four holes of the
third round in the morning, making a key 15-foot putt at No. 17 in
the morning to save par and maintain his three-stroke lead.
</P>
<P>
   But there were several key moments on the back nine that turned
the day in Singh's favor. Paired with Duval in the final group,
Singh reached the par 4 No. 11, the start of the famous three-hole
stretch known as Amen Corner, with a two-stroke lead over Duval.
But Singh made one of his few errors at No. 11, when his pulled his
second shot into the water. But Singh got a break, when his ball
entered the pond from left side, allowing him to drop his ball by
the left side on his next shot, instead of in the penalty drop
area, which was farther away from the pin.
</P>
<P>
   After a penalty stroke, Singh hit a beautiful chip shot that
landed about 3 feet from the pin, then he made the putt to turn
what could have been a double-bogey into just a bogey. That allowed
Singh to keep a one-stroke lead over Duval, who made par at No. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Then at the par 3, No. 12, Singh got another break. His tee shot
sailed over the green into the bushes, but then the ball bounced
out off a slope and back toward the hole, landing in the back
bunker. The bunker shot was far easier than a shot from the bushes
would have been.
</P>
<P>
   Singh got up and down from the bunker for par, and he still led
by one stroke heading to No. 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the kinds of things you need to happen to win,''
said Duval. ``You need those breaks. I didn't get any of those, I
don't feel, at least not big ones like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Duval could only blame himself for his mistake at the par 5,
No. 13, when he hit his second shot, a 5-iron from 196 yards, into
Rae's Creek. Seconds after the ball left his club, Duval dejectedly
lowered his head, knowing the ball would end up wet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a poor golf shot,'' Duval said. ``It was the wrong time
to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   After his penalty stroke, Duval chipped onto the green 15 feet
from the hole, but then he missed the putt and made bogey on a hole
that he felt he should have birdied. Meanwhile, Singh did birdie
No. 15, reaching the green in two shots, then two-putting. That
moved Singh to nine under par, while Duval dropped to six. Now
Singh had a three-stroke cushion with five holes to play.
Meanwhile, Els was making a charge in the next-to-last group, with
birdies at No. 13 and No. 15 to reach seven under par, two strokes
off the lead. But Els missed three birdie attempts on the final
three holes _ from 9 feet on No, 16, 15 feet on No. 17, and 12 feet
on No. 18. On the final putt at No. 18, Els was forced to back away
just before he was about to putt, when a photographer's shutter
clicked and broke Els' concentration.
</P>
<P>
   Els went through his pre-shot routine again, but he was visibly
upset, and his anger increased after he missed the putt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if I had made the putt I might have still lost, but I
would have at least given Vijay a chance to think about,'' said
Singh. ``That guy should never take a golf picture again in his
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I misread a putt on No. 16, and on No. 18, I hit it too
hard through the break. It wasn't meant to be for me this week.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was meant to be for Singh. Though he three-putted No. 16
for bogey, he still led Duval by two strokes with two holes to
play. Then Singh hit a great approach shot on No. 17 to secure his
par, then after Duval could only make par on No. 17, Singh came to
No. 18 with a two-stroke lead. Then when his approach shot at No.
18 landed on the green, Singh strolled up the final fairway and
soaked in the applause, knowing he would join an exclusive club.
</P>
<P>
   What did Singh think when he looked down at his new jacket,
which is traditionally awarded to the Masters champion? ``I just
love the color green,'' said Singh. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
