<SLUG> BC-CYBER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE TRENDSPOTTING ON THE WEB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The San Francisco Giants' home opener at their new
launching pad (against the Dodgers) on Tuesday has been sold out
for months, and it's no wonder why. It's the
instant-millionaire-rich Silicon Valley showing us the way.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal reported last week that nearly halfof
all the San Francisco Giants' single-game tickets were told over
the Internet on their Web site (www.sfgiants.com). In addition, 15
percent of the 30,000 season seats were Web-generated.
</P>
<P>
   That is what helped the team sell out 73 of 81 home dates.
</P>
<P>
   -New England Patriots quarterback Drew Bledsoe has become the
first major pro athlete to start his own Internet service provider
- Bledsoenet.com - which he told the Boston Globe was started so
that parents of young kids can have a certain level of comfort
knowing that access to sites to pornography and hate crime, for
example, will be filtered out.
</P>
<P>
   -Santa Monica-based Broadband Sports, which includes
AthletesDirect.com among its properties, announced that it reached
a deal with Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones to be the new
designer, producer and manager of the team's official site
(www.dallascowboys.com).
</P>
<P>
   Jones, famous for his anti-establishment business dealings, was
one of two who recently voted against the NFL's decision to combine
all Internet revenue under one umbrella company and split profits
evenly among the teams. Broadband says the agreement is structured
to comply with the principles of the NFL's Internet guidelines and
does not violate any recently passed provisions regarding the
operation of team sites.
</P>
<P>
   -If the 9-to-5 workweek has lost its luster, shop over at
JobsInSports.com. There's a database that, for $29.95 a month, will
list hundreds of sports jobs and internships, updated each week.
Positions in marketing, administration and sales are the norm but
are quickly being supplanted with Web site and other multimedia
careers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
