<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-FATHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULES FOR NEWS HOUNDS ON HEELS OF ELIAN'S FATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Md.)  (Eds.: With CUBAN-BOY) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHESDA, Md. _ Please don't pick the cherry blossoms. Turn off
those portable generators after 9 p.m.; the children need to sleep.
But do buy their lemonade and ices; business at the stands is
usually slow. Come in for coffee but don't throw the cups on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   These are rules for the news-media pack chasing Juan Miguel
Gonzalez, who has stayed here at the suburban home of Cuba's chief
diplomat since arriving on Thursday from Cuba to reclaim his son,
Elian Gonzalez, and end an international custody fight.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps only a suburb of Washington stocked with diplomats,
politicos and journalists would be so good-natured about a news
media invasion.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 television satellite trucks line the streets of the
Kenwood Park neighborhood here. An equal number of cameras are
trained on a certain beige brick split-level on Millwood Road, and
a few dozen journalists camp round-the-clock (in case Gonzalez
defects at 3 a.m.).
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors have witnessed vigils and demonstrations _ journalists
outnumbered protesters at the most recent. Cameras and microphones
record everyone who enters or leaves the house and stampede after
anyone who might make news.
</P>
<P>
   It is, of course, a two-way street. One resident put a soda
machine on his driveway. Another serves coffee and doughnuts from
her kitchen table and offers tidbits on the diplomats who give the
neighborhood an international flare.
</P>
<P>
   There have been complaints about barricades, noise and crushed
spring grass. But people generally have been accommodating, said
Lt. William O'Toole, a spokesman for the Montgomery County Police
Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the media does not really bother me,'' said Kitty Strauss,
who lives around the corner from the house and took on the moniker
``the bathroom lady'' for obvious reasons. ``It could last a month,
six months, a year, but my life is eventually going back to normal.
I don't think Elian's is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-00 2148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000409.0178 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1745 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-NY     04-09 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS HAS POOR OUTING AFTER HEARING ABOUT MENTOR'S ILLNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ They have been through this so many times before, the
terrible news delivered in a team meeting, the Yankees emerging
somberly. Darryl Strawberry was diagnosed with cancer, and then
Manager Joe Torre, and now the pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre. You
push ahead because that's what you must do, Torre said Sunday,
after Stottlemyre revealed he has a form of blood cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees played Sunday and played badly, losing to the
Seattle Mariners, 9-3, Roger Clemens surrendering seven runs, one
earned, in six innings. After winning the first two games to open
the season, the Yankees lost three of the last four games of the
six-game trip and return to play the first game in Yankee Stadium
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers and their pitching coaches sometimes communicate like
spouses, Andy Pettitte said Sunday. Clemens formed a bond with
Stottlemyre in the 13 months since Toronto traded him to the
Yankees, a friendship formed in the many hours of tinkering in the
bullpen, discussing scouting reports, arm slots, fastball grips and
pitching mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   When Clemens learned in March that he was going to pitch the
first game in Houston's new ballpark, Enron Field, part of his
delight stemmed from the fact that Stottlemyre had pitched the
first game in Houston's Astrodome in 1965. Clemens wanted to
acquire a game program from that day 35 years ago, for Stottlemyre
to autograph; then Clemens intended to get a Enron Field program,
with Clemens' signature, and mount both programs, side-by-side.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens learned of Stottlemyre's illness as most of his
teammates did, in a meeting conducted by Torre, who offered a brief
synopsis before encouraging the players to take questions to
Stottlemyre. Clemens did so, speaking with Stottlemyre about a half
hour before he was scheduled to warm up, and as always, Stottlemyre
was standing next to Clemens as he threw in the bullpen, coach and
player. They walked in from the bullpen together, Stottlemyre
veering off to toss the warmup ball to a young boy wearing a
Yankees uniform in the second row of the stands in left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's somebody that you care about, and you know he cares about
you as a person,'' Clemens said. ``I consider him a mentor,
watching over what I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens had great stuff, as he did in his first start last week,
his fastball thumping into the mitt of the catcher Jorge Posada,
and Jamie Moyer, the Seattle starter, was just as good in his own
way, confusing the Yankees' hitters with his changeup. There were
no hits in the first two and a half innings.
</P>
<P>
   An error by Derek Jeter led to the Mariners' first run, Mike
Cameron scoring Carlos Guillen on an infield single, but Jeter and
Chuck Knoblauch hit back-to-back doubles in the fourth and the
Yankees moved ahead, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   But an error on a disputed call created a trouble for the
Yankees in the fifth, and Clemens was unable to avoid damage. Torre
said afterward that Clemens sometimes tries too hard to be perfect,
rather than concede a little. After Dan Wilson led off with a
single, Guillen bunted the ball in front of the plate and Posada
rushed out, picked up the ball and underhanded a throw to first,
where the second baseman Chuck Knoblauch was covering.
</P>
<P>
   Posada's throw was offline and Knoblauch stretched to make the
catch. Posada turned around and headed back toward his position,
satisfied the play was made _ until the roaring of the crowd spun
him around. Ted Barrett, the first base umpire, ruled that Guillen
was safe, saying that Knoblauch's foot had come off the bag. Torre
and others argued, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt in my mind he was out,'' Posada said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Knoblauch: ``I didn't see a replay, but I don't need to see
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark McLemore, the next hitter, then attempted to bunt, but
Clemens walked him, loading the bases _ an example of how Clemens
might have been better off just conceding the bunt and getting the
out, as Torre said. ``With the successes he's had,'' said Torre,
``he still thinks he's capable of superhuman things.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens broke the bat of the next hitter, Mike Cameron, but the
Seattle center fielder lifted a looper that barely nicked off the
glove of a leaping Knoblauch, a run-scoring single. Single runs
scored on outs by Alex Rodriguez and John Olerud, but Edgar
Martinez prolonged the inning with a run-scoring single and Jay
Buhner blasted a two-run homer to right. Six runs in the inning, in
all, and the game was effectively over.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a pretty good job of attacking him,'' Stottlemyre
said. ``The bunt play was a big play, as they always are in a close
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte had gotten a sense Stottlemyre was ailing over the last
year, after Stottlemyre vaguely mentioned doctors' appointments. He
and Stottlemyre often fished together when the Yankees came here,
but that was impossible last year, he said, because Stottlemyre
needed to undergo tests.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte said he would have had a difficult time pitching Sunday
after learning the exact nature of Stottlemyre's illness, but
Clemens rejected the suggestion that he was distracted. That's not
what Stottlemyre wants, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Clemens spoke of Stottlemyre, his response was
steeled. It seemed hard for him to share his feelings. He thought
of Stottlemyre throwing batting practice to the pitchers in spring
training, sweating but happy in his work, coping all the while with
the knowledge that he might have cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's kept it to himself and not allowed it to interfere with
what we do on a daily basis,'' Clemens said. ``That just shows the
strength that he has. We're just going to have to watch how this
evolves over the next couple of months. What we're hoping and
praying for is the best to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-00 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
