<HEADLINE>
BLAKE GETS BACK TO PLAYING HIS PART
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM - Kings captain Rob Blake could have sat out the
regular-season finale. His left knee is that bad.
</P>
<P>
   But he played, and it involved more than just playing the cross-
town Ducks on Sunday or the chance to get in some real ice time
before the first round of the playoffs begins Thursday in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a team standpoint, he wanted to be a part of the group,''
coach Andy Murray said after the Kings won 4-3 in overtime. ``There
are a few days before the playoffs begin, but there are still a lot
of positive things to do before then.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake gave the Kings a 3-2 lead at the 3:56 mark of the third
period. The Ducks tied the game five minutes later on Teemu
Selanne's second goal of the game. Blake's goal was important. It
was his 18th of the year, but he hadn't scored since March 13 and
had just one goal in his last 18 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think getting that goal puts him right back in the middle of
everything,'' defense mate Mattias Norstrom said. ``It was probably
more important to get back in the flow of things after missing a
week. But the goal sure was nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Blake was injured during the second period of last Saturday's
2-1 playoff clincher at Staples Center. He tried to take out Ted
Donato coming across the middle; the two clipped knees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really was a dumb play on my part,'' Blake said. ``I had a
chance to give it some rest, but it definitely was time to get
back.''
</P>
<P>
   Power play: The Kings finished the season 5 for 11 on the power
play in the last three games. In March the team was 5 for 59 and
during one stretch did not score in 36 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Blake's goal came with the Ducks' Stu Grimson off for
interference. He turned around at the right faceoff circle and let
go a shot that sailed through the legs of Ducks goaltender Guy
Hebert.
</P>
<P>
   In overtime, Glen Murray also beat Hebert through the legs after
defenseman Oleg Tverdovsky was whistled for high-sticking Ian
Laperriere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The power play is so important during the playoffs,'' Blake
said. ``Fewer penalties are called and you have to take advantage
of the opportunities. We had some trouble recently, but now things
seem to be falling into place. Couldn't happen at a better time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
