<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1757 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT &LR;      04-09 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVIS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI AND SAMPRAS FINALLY BRING ENERGY TO U.S. TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ They had seen this act before, here at the
Great Western Forum. Two very different stars, as players and
people, orchestrating Showtime, lighting up the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Agassi was Magic. Pete Sampras was Kareem. Agassi revved
up the crowd with his energy and wizardry. Sampras punctuated the
day with his special brand of hooks and slams. The United States
dream team of Davis Cup singles was finally together, in concert,
and so up to the task that John McEnroe could have left the court
and gone to sit with one of the attending celebrities, Captain
Kirk.
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe's second tie at the helm of the United States team was,
in the end, a replication of the first, except it was Sampras in
for Chris Woodruff, finally finishing off a feisty little country
that did not know its place. After Agassi cracked the Jiri Novak
code, winning by 6-3, 6-3, 6-1, Sampras turned lights out on the
Czech Republic, with a 6-4, 6-4, 7-6 (2) drubbing of Slava Dosedel
that was no more compelling than a bedtime kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it looked like, however long it took, McEnroe's team
was on to the semifinals, in Spain July 21 to 23 with a 3-2 victory
over the Czech Republic. What we originally expected here was what
we got. After annoying McEnroe with a lack of fire in his
straight-sets loss to Novak last Friday, Sampras did what he does
best. Shoulders stooped, wiping beads of sweat from his brow, he
policed the hard court with Wimbledon law, with his Grade A
unreturnable serve.
</P>
<P>
   He served as high as 129 miles per hour, and his second serve
was typically faster than Dosedel's first. Sampras faced
triple-break point in the fourth game of the first set, already up
a break on Dosedel. In rapid succession, he lined up a service
winner, a second-service ace, another service winner, a service
winner down the T, and a second-service winner. End of game. End of
Dosedel's chance to establish himself as a threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never played the fifth match in Davis Cup,'' Sampras
said. ``It was time to remember who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   He injured his quad muscle in the first game, had it treated
twice during changeovers during the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suck it up,'' McEnroe told him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `I'm going to do what I can,''' Sampras said,
adding, ``I could see it in his eye that he didn't want any part of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughed, in the context of McEnroe's criticism of him the
previous day. McEnroe wondered where the energy was, why he didn't
throw his body onto the hard court. McEnroe, Sampras understood,
was just being McEnroe, fueling a potentially flammable situation,
unable to stop himself.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras said it wasn't as if didn't try against Novak. It was a
bad day at the office, the home office, in the city he is from.
</P>
<P>
   His friends were at the Forum this weekend, as was his family,
including his father, Sam, which is about as rare as a
straight-sets Sampras defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was down in the dumps on Friday night,'' he said. ``It was
more than a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, who hugged him afterward, came into the interview room
and, along with the losing American doubles team, defended his
career-long rival and character opposite. ``You know, all we can do
is our best out there and Jiri played the match of his life against
Pete,'' Agassi said. ``Pete's accomplishments speak for themselves,
so at the risk of sounding like I'm criticizing John, I have no
idea what he could possibly mean.''
</P>
<P>
   McEnroe insisted he didn't mean anything personal by it. He was
just being captain, just coaching. like another high profile mentor
who once prowled the same Forum sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   That was before Pat Riley became so infatuated by success that
he became The Windbag Within, making every post-analysis a lecture
on work ethic. In effect, both Agassi and Sampras agreed with the
Czech captain, Jan Kukal, who predicted prosperity for Captain
McEnroe, with a more experience and the understanding that he's not
playing and it's a players' game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of, unfortunately, not being able to make more of
a difference than giving us a platform to do well by preparation,''
Agassi said.
</P>
<P>
   There was nothing, meanwhile, that Kukal could have done for
Novak against Agassi. Against any other player, perhaps even
Sampras again, the stubborn Novak would have not gone in straight
sets. But Agassi was entirely another proposition, all wound up
with the crowd charged up.
</P>
<P>
   Kukal had warned, ``Be careful of Jiri - iron is his best
friend,'' meaning the weight room. Agassi, more the outdoorsman
when he runs up what he calls Magic Mountain in Las Vegas, gave the
Czech a lesson in staying power, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   He hit Novak with too much aggression and not enough of a
target. Novak pushed Agassi hard in the first set, trading breaks
and making him save two break points to cement a set-deciding
second. But Agassi always had an answer, a winner off the ground, a
slick drop shot. And in what was the most depressing development
for Novak, Agassi also had a brilliant day serving, 72 percent of
his first balls in, 12 for aces.
</P>
<P>
   For the one hour and 36 minutes that the match lasted, it was
too much for Novak to stand in and trade with this buzz saw dressed
in all black. ``I was getting tired and tired,'' he said, calling
Agassi a ``special player.''
</P>
<P>
   Last to argue with this point would be McEnroe, for whom Agassi
has won all four Cup matches without dropping a set or breaking a
sweat.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have to realize that this is the type of situation that
brings out the best in Andre,'' McEnroe said, reiterating the
obvious. ``The hell with those other tournaments. He's saving
himself for me and Davis Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not playing for John,'' Agassi said. ``I'm playing for my
country.''
</P>
<P>
   With McEnroe around as the human sound bite, it is sometimes
easy to forget that this not about the captain as much as it about
the competitors and their countries. But when it was over, when the
celebration commenced and the American flags came out, all seemed
forgiven and forgotten. McEnroe said he'd try to be more of a Zen
Master, like Phil Jackson, who sat serenely in the crowd. Sampras,
for his part, passed the glory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all the coaching,'' Sampras said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah,'' McEnroe said.
</P>
</TEXT>
