<HEADLINE>
WORLD'S TOP GOLFERS FALL SHORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Tiger Woods bemoaned a trio of missed putts.
David Duval hung his head in disbelief after blocking a 5-iron
approach into the water at the 13th hole. Ernie Els gnashed his
teeth over an ill-timed camera click.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Vijay Singh slipped into a green jacket.
</P>
<P>
   On the way to becoming the first player from Fiji to win a
Masters championship, Singh brushed aside a pair of final-round
charges from the top two players in the world golf rankings
yesterday at Augusta National Golf Club. For good measure, Singh
also slammed the door on Els, who posted the lowest closing score
among the front-runners (68) and said he ``felt like I'd win from
the minute I stepped on the first tee'' yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the round, Singh had changed Els' tune. Playing
with Duval in the final group, Singh bagged five birdies during a
round of 69, including a 20-footer at No. 18, to win by three
strokes.
</P>
<P>
   But Singh also showed signs of vulnerability. He three-putted
two greens, dumped an approach shot into the water at No. 11 and
airmailed the 12th green before saving par. Those bobbles opened
opportunities for Woods, Duval and Els. Each fell off the pace in a
different manner.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, the world's top-ranked golfer, collected three birdies on
the front nine but lipped out putts for birdie at No. 10 (20 feet)
and No. 11 (15 feet) before misreading an 8-footer at No. 13 and
sliding it right of the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I make those three, I'm right in the ballgame,'' said
Woods, who finished at 4-under after posting the best weekend
scores (68-69) at Augusta. ``The first two, it was hard to believe
they didn't go in. They just grazed the edge. I guess the golfing
gods just didn't look down on me in a good way this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who played the final 36 holes with Singh, saw his title
hopes disappear when he drowned a 5-iron approach from 196 yards at
No. 13. Duval was a stroke behind Singh at the time. The errant
shot resulted in a two-stroke swing at the par-5 hole. Duval never
recovered, finishing at 6-under after a closing bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got over the ball, the wind picked up, then it would die,''
said Duval, the No. 2 player in the world rankings. ``The same
thing kept happening. Then, I decided on the right line and hit a
poor golf shot. That was probably the only poor shot I hit all
weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Els, the No. 12 player in the world rankings, moved crisply up
the leader board with a back-nine 33. He left himself with putts
for birdie inside 15 feet on each of the final three holes. He
failed to make any of them. Els was most disappointed in a missed
12-footer at No. 18, which left him at 7-under with Singh watching
from the fairway while sitting on a 9-under total.
</P>
<P>
   Before rolling the putt, Els backed off at address after hearing
the click a photographer's camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guy got way ahead. I wasn't even taking the putter back
and he was off,'' Els said. ``If I made the putt, I might still
have lost. But I would at least have given Vijay a chance to think
about it. That \Rphotographer\S should never take a golf picture in
his life again.''
</P>
<P>
   After Els missed, Singh, the No. 8 player in the world rankings,
wrapped up the event with a closing birdie to reach 10 under.
Although distracted by the photographer at No. 18, Els said: ``I
had my chances. ... It wasn't meant to be for me. I'll try again
next year.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
