<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-GOSSETT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOW AMATEUR TIE NICKLAUS WITH 78
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ David Gossett, the reigning U.S. Amateur champ
from the University of Texas, accepted his silver medal yesterday
for being the low amateur at the Masters Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the most vivid memory Gossett, a sophomore, will
take back to Austin. Gossett played the final round paired with
Jack Nicklaus, the six-time Masters champ, and matched scores with
the Golden Bear. Both players shot 78 to finish at 15 over for the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing with Jack Nicklaus on Sunday at the Masters, it
doesn't get any better than this,'' said Gossett, 20. ``I just wish
it wasn't such an early tee time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gossett, the only amateur to survive the 36-hole cut, completed
his final round before the leaders teed off. He finished in a tie
for 54th place but said it was ``an honor'' to finish as the low
amateur in his Masters debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll take a lot of positives out of this week,'' Gossett
said. ``I'm not pleased with the way I played on the weekend
(79-78), but it's an honor to be the low amateur. I'm very proud of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he referred to his final-round playing partner,
Gossett said: ``I called him `Mr. Nicklaus.' He never told me to
call him, `Jack.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Although he has two years of eligibility remaining, Gossett said
he is leaning toward turning professional after playing as an
amateur in the British Open (July 20-23).
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't hurt my decision any,'' Gossett said of his
Masters finish. ``I'll take a good hard look at things after the
British Open. But I know I can play out here. I don't feel I'm very
far from being competitive.''  &QL; 
Nicklaus' last stand?
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus said yesterday it is ``possible'' he has taken his
final competitive walk up the 18th fairway at Augusta National Golf
Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying it was. I'm not saying it wasn't,'' said
Nicklaus, 60. ``I have no idea. I know I can play here. But it's
possible that was my last walk at No. 18.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus has uttered similar sentiments after past Masters
disappointments. But if this was the end, Nicklaus would bow out on
a down note. He shot a 78 in yesterday's final round. He completed
his final 32 holes of the tournament without posting a birdie. His
81 during the third round marked the highest score of Nicklaus' 156
career rounds at Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have much enthusiasm, I'm afraid. I couldn't grind or
make anything happen,'' said Nicklaus, who talked boldly of
challenging for the title after posting an even-par total through
36 holes. Nicklaus finished at 15 over and tied for 54th, his worst
Masters finish since missing the cut in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 38 years when Nicklaus has completed four rounds at
Augusta, the 54th-place effort marks his worst finish on the leader
board.  &QL; 
Putting problems
</P>
<P>
   Tarrant County residents Mark Brooks and Brandt Jobe backtracked
during the final round of the Masters because of balky putters.
Both players shot closing rounds of 74. Both players posted their
highest putt totals of tournament week: 31 for Brooks, a Fort Worth
resident, and 33 for Jobe, a Southlake resident.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks finished at 7 over and tied for 40th. Jobe, who placed
14th at the 1999 Masters, faded to 48th with a 9-over total.  &QL; 
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus said he is unsure of his upcoming schedule, but he
might compete in the Houston Open (April 27-30) and the Compaq
Classic of New Orleans (May 4-7) with his son Gary. During the week
of the Houston event, Nicklaus is scheduled to accept the Dave Marr
Award, a lifetime achievement award presented by the Houston Golf
Association, as well as open a new course in The Woodlands.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy Aaron, 63, on becoming the oldest Masters cut survivor:
``I may not make another cut, so I'll probably look back on this
with pretty nice terms despite what happened on the weekend.''
Aaron shot 86-81 during the weekend rounds, the high scores of the
cut survivors.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
