<HEADLINE>
CLARK GETTING SKIPPED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL AND MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Left-hander Kenny Rogers will start Thursday
against the Yankees in New York in a move designed to ``give us the
best chance overall to win the most ballgames,'' manager Johnny
Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Mark Clark, the Rangers' fifth starter, is not
scheduled to pitch until Saturday against the Indians in Cleveland.
Clark (1-0, 5.06 earned-run average) is 0-3 with a 9.28 ERA through
five career appearances spanning 211/3 innings against the Yankees
and won his only start against the Indians in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Oates' decision to start Rogers (1-1, 2.40) on his regular day
to pitch also means the Rangers will start two left-handers during
their three-game series against New York. Oates plans to start
left-hander Darren Oliver (0-0, 7.71) in tomorrow's opener. Yankee
Stadium favors left-handed pitchers with its spacious power alley
in left-center field. \Nsubheds:Delgado slowing down \Nagatea:This
weekend represented progress for the Rangers in their struggle
against Blue Jays first baseman Carlos Delgado.
</P>
<P>
   The left-handed power hitter wore the Rangers out last season by
hitting .447 (17-for-38) with seven home runs and 15 runs batted in
over 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado did not hit a home run during the three-game series, but
he went 3-for-11 with three doubles and drove in four runs.  &QL; 
Chilly reception
</P>
<P>
   Snow forced the postponement of yesterday's game between the
Dodgers and Mets at New York's Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   What can the Rangers look forward to this week at Yankee
Stadium?
</P>
<P>
   The forecast calls for rain tomorrow and Thursday and highs
ranging from 51-53 degrees and lows ranging from 39-46 degrees.  &QL; 
Rounding third
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning with Frank Catalanotto at first base, Luis
Alicea hit a double to right field, easily scoring Ruben Mateo. But
it wasn't deep enough to send Catalanotto home, so third base coach
Jerry Narron threw up the stop sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I assumed I was going to score easily,'' Catalanotto said.
</P>
<P>
   Catalanotto ran through the sign, and, with the aide of the
relay throw that sailed up the third base line, Catalanotto did
score easily, giving the Rangers a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it \Rthe sign\S late, and it was too late,'' Catalanotto
said. ``I didn't keep my eye on it, and I have to keep my head up.
It's something I have to make sure I do, and it won't happen
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's a Detroit thing.
</P>
<P>
   On Opening Day against Chicago, Catalanotto's former Tigers
teammate, Gabe Kapler, avoided a stop sign and scored when he
bowled over White Sox's catcher Mark Johnson, dislodging the ball
to score the run.  &QL; 
Looking blue
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's game had a distinct blue look to it.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Rangers and Blue Jays wore blue uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my fault we wore blue \RSaturday\S night,'' said
Rangers starting pitcher Rick Helling, who selected the team colors
yesterday. ``Kenny \RRogers\S made that call. I thought we were
supposed to wear blue at all day games, and \Ryesterday was\S a day
game.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a superstitious thing. He wore white in his first
start of the season, Tuesday against the White Sox.
Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates gave catcher Ivan Rodriguez the afternoon off after
Saturday's night game. The move actually provides Rodriguez with
two days off with the Rangers not scheduled to play tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Ruben Mateo extended his hitting streak to
career-best six games with a 2-for-4 performance.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Gabe Kapler is 1-for-14 in his past four games.
nn
</P>
