<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE OF ROBERT FLEMING BY CHASE IS SEEN THIS WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Robert Fleming Holdings, one of Britain's last independent
banks, is expected to announce this week that it will be acquired
by Chase Manhattan for close to 5 billion pounds, or nearly $8
billion, executives close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   That price is higher than most analysts expected when reports of
the negotiations emerged last month.
</P>
<P>
   A PRIVATE SOLUTION FOR MICROSOFT?
</P>
<P>
   With a federal judge ruling last week that Microsoft repeatedly
violated the law, the government has the easy part of the antitrust
case behind it. The real policy challenge comes now: What are the
right remedies? One respected economist suggests that the
government could just walk away and leave remedies to private
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   TURNED ON TO THE NEW ECONOMY
</P>
<P>
   Despite their obvious differences, the Internet era and the
radical 1960s are linked in the psyches of many. For one thing, the
Internet is a radically youth-centric culture, convinced that dewy
college graduates can better see the future than those already
tainted by their role in the old economy. There is also an aura of
vitality and era-defining importance around the activities of those
who are plugged into the new economy.
</P>
<P>
   MALLS LOOK TO COMPETE ONLINE, TOO
</P>
<P>
   Web merchants have had a lot of fun at the expense of shopping
malls, contending that mall shopping was a waste of time and money.
Now, with investors fleeing Web merchants en masse, malls are
poised for a counteroffensive. They are vying to fill the gaps left
by traditional and online retailers in areas like ordering and
customer service. Efforts include Internet connections inside malls
for merchants and hand-held scanners that allow shoppers to select
items, either to put on a wish list or to buy.
</P>
<P>
   A TEST CASE FOR PRESS FREEDOM
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, advocates for freedom of the press hope that a case
involving the author of a best-selling crime book will set a
precedent for the kind of reporters' shield legislation that spread
in the United States in the 1970s. Stephen Williams' book,
``Invisible Darkness,'' contains precise details of a gory
sex-murder scene. Williams has been charged with two counts of
disobeying a judge's order to disclose the source of the details.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL WEB SITES PLANNED
</P>
<P>
   British Airways and the online business-travel service
GetThere.com plan to announce Monday that they will create
customized Web sites to provide corporate travel services for small
and midsize businesses in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   AD CAMPAIGN FOR INDUSTRY STANDARD
</P>
<P>
   At a time when swings in technology stocks are feeding a debate
about the Internet economy, The Industry Standard, a magazine
devoted to e-commerce, is starting a $10 million campaign to
attract a broader range of readers.
</P>
<P>
   `SOPRANOS' CONSOLIDATES ITS POWER
</P>
<P>
   The mob-family hit ``The Sopranos,'' burdened this season with
expectations heavier than cement shoes, finished its second burst
of 13 episodes Sunday night, having added to the biggest
programming phenomenon in HBO history. Ratings soared for ``The
Sopranos'' in its second season, climbing more than 60 percent.
Though the ratings are important, there is something broader at
stake. HBO does not measure the success of its series in direct
income. Because HBO is a subscription channel dependent on monthly
fees, the prime consideration is selling people on the channel in
an increasingly crowded marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   CHILDREN'S ALL-COTTON SUPERHERO
</P>
<P>
   The tales of the children's book character Captain Underpants
are stealthily gaining popularity against the more mainstream Harry
Potter books. The two characters share the same children's
publisher, Scholastic, which has now issued more than 6 million
copies of books featuring Captain Underpants.
</P>
</TEXT>
