u i BC-CHINA-TENSIONS-NYT &LR;      04-09 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TENSIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMBASSADOR REJECTS PROTRAYING CHINA AS ENEMY 
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI _ As China repeated threats against Taiwan, the
American ambassador to Beijing made remarks over the weekend that
encouraged prudence, saying that viewing China as an enemy could
become a self-fulfilling prophecy.
</P>
<P>
   The ambassador, Joseph Prueher, said in an interview here that
the United States had ``both the strength and the time'' to work
with China and to try to ensure that its government and economy
develop in ways that fit American interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important, not to get a mind-set that sees China
as an enemy,'' he said during a visit to Shanghai. ``We need to
hope and work for the best, while remaining prepared for the
worst.''
</P>
<P>
   The tensions over Taiwan have complicated Clinton administration
efforts to rally support for a bill before Congress that would
grant China permanent normal trade relations. China has demanded
that status as a condition for wide-ranging trade concessions it
has promised if it is allowed to join the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing's threats of war against Taiwan, if ever carried out,
would probably draw the United States into direct conflict with
China. Under the Taiwan Relations Act, the United States promises
to help ensure the security of the island, which has operated as an
independent state since the Nationalist army fled there after
losing the civil war on the mainland in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Tensions across the Taiwan Strait have risen since the election
last month of Chen Shui-bian as Taiwan's new president. His
Democratic Progressive Party advocates declaring independence from
Beijing, which China warns would mean war. Chen has softened his
stance on the issue but has refused to accept Beijing's ``one China
policy'' that would subjugate Taiwan to Beijing's sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   The bill on American trade relations with China, which will be
voted on next month, would remove an annual congressional review of
China's trade status that has been in place since the 1989 killings
of pro-democracy demonstrators in Beijing. Many people in
Washington regard China as an emerging adversary that should be
dealt with harshly.
</P>
<P>
   But Prueher echoed Clinton's view that the United States could
help effect positive change in China by engaging the country.
Granting it permanent normal trade relations is part of that
process, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Prueher is a retired admiral and was Pacific Fleet commander in
1996 when the United States sent two carrier groups to the seas
around Taiwan as a warning after China fired missiles into the
waters off the island. China had been trying to intimidate
Taiwanese voters during the country's first presidential elections
and was infuriated by the action.
</P>
<P>
   Prueher said that despite Beijing's threats he believed the
mainland would maintain its wait-and-see attitude. ``All sides
agree that we need to be very cautious, prudent and creative here
in the post-election period,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said there had been no indication that Beijing had made any
military moves to back up its threats. And while he said China's
leadership had made it clear that the Taiwan issue transcends trade
organization membership or other issues, it was ``not a military
problem'' and it did not ``yield to a military solution.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Taiwan security _ for Taiwan not to get kicked around _ comes
from U.S. backing, not from any particular weapon system,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan has asked the United States to sell it more advanced
arms.
</P>
<P>
   Prueher said that with economic modernization a priority the
Chinese generals with whom he spoke remained frustrated by the slow
modernization of China's armed forces. But its accelerating
procurement of arms from Russia ``is not a troubling issue because
of degrees of scale, but it's a trend we'll have to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Russia and China have improved in recent
years, particularly since NATO's intervention in Kosovo, which both
countries opposed. And Russia has recently supplied China with
advanced weapons systems, including Sovremenny guided missile
destroyers designed to challenge American aircraft carrier groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
