<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ STOPS ANGELS 5-2
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Angels manager Mike Scioscia said his club shouldn't
be intimidated by Red Sox pitcher Pedro Martinez. Angels starting
pitcher Kent Bottenfield said it didn't matter whom he was facing.
</P>
<P>
   Then they played the game.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez again showed he has no equal in the game today, taking
a shutout into the eighth inning before giving up a run in the Red
Sox's 5-2 victory Sunday afternoon before 35,847 at Edison Field.
Martinez's 12 strikeouts marked the 10th consecutive start he has
struck out at least 10, including both starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   He struck out every hitter in the Angels lineup at least once
except Adam Kennedy and Benji Gil, who had two hits. Troy Glaus
struck out all three times he faced Martinez, who walked only one.
</P>
<P>
   It was after the walk to Darin Erstad with one out in the eighth
that spelled the end for Martinez (2-0) after 112 pitches. Kennedy
singled home a run later in the inning off Derek Lowe, but the run
was charged to Martinez, ending his consecutive scoreless-innings
streak of 32 1/3 innings (including last postseason). It was the
first earned run allowed by Martinez in 35 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you keep it close against him, you have a shot,'' said
Angels first baseman Mo Vaughn, who grounded out twice and struck
out against Martinez. ``But if you give him a big lead, you can
cancel Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield (0-1) did keep it close early, even though he said
he had trouble locating his fastball. The game was scoreless in the
fourth inning when with two out, Bottenfield gave up back-to-back
homers on consecutive pitches to Troy O'Leary and Carl Everett. The
pitch to O'Leary came on a 0-2 count.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a matter of good hitters taking advantage of my
mistakes,'' Bottenfield (6 innings, 3 runs, 5 hits) said. ``I had a
situation where I could have gotten out of it, but I didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez didn't make such mistakes, and he threw all three of
his pitches -- fastball, curveball, changeup -- exactly where he
wanted to. The velocity on his fastball wasn't as great as it
normally is -- he topped out at 96-mph, but was in the low 90's
most of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a normal outing,'' said Martinez, who has allowed one
run in his two starts (14 1/3 innings). ``My changeup is better and
my curveball is better. Everything seems to be coming along fine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was there (Boston) he didn't use the breaking pitch
like now,'' Vaughn said. ``He used it to set guys up. Now he uses
it to get guys out. It's hard to say he's gotten better, but he's
gotten better. It's scary.''
</P>
<P>
   The last time the Angels faced Martinez last season, they were
shut out the following day by the Indians. Angels manager Mike
Scioscia was asked if there was anything he could do to keep his
hitters from suffering from another ``Martinez hangover.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just make sure he's on the plane back to Boston or wherever
they're going,'' he said, ``and we'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had opportunities early against Martinez, putting a
runner in scoring position in three of the first four innings. But
Martinez got outs when he needed them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did he dominate us? No, we had opportunities,'' Scioscia said.
``It's not like we didn't have chances to score off him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels added a run in the ninth inning against Lowe on Scott
Spiezio's team-leading second homer of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels can at least take solace in knowing they won't have
to face Martinez again until August, the next time they play the
Red Sox, and that Martinez is lined up in the rotation to face
their division foes Oakland and Texas later this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now he's the best pitcher in baseball,'' Vaughn said.
``He can tell you what's coming and you're not going to hit it. It
doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there is any way to prepare for facing Martinez, Vaughn
said: ``You don't. Go out and have a drink.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
