<HEADLINE>
RENO SEES QUICK RESOLUTION TO DISPUTE OVER ELIAN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The international showdown over the fate of
6-year-old Elian Gonzalez could be headed to a climax this week,
with Attorney General Janet Reno saying Sunday that she is ``very
firm'' about resolving the matter in a few days. The Miami
relatives caring for the boy said through their lawyer that they
would ``stand back'' if US officials sought to transfer Elian to
his father.
</P>
<P>
   But with negotiations being conducted both in private and on the
Sunday television talk shows, questions remained about when and
where the transfer would occur, whether it would it would be
peaceful, and whether a court appeal by the relatives might slow
down or stop the process. It also remained possible that Elian
might be transferred to his father within days, but that the pair
would not return to Cuba for weeks while court appeals are
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   One of the relatives caring for Elian, Marisleysis Gonzalez,
reportedly was hospitalized Saturday with stomach and
stress-related complaints. It was unclear where she was staying and
whether the illness was serious enough to stall the transfer. At
the request of Reno, the Miami relatives are slated to meet Monday
with psychologists and psychiatrists who are helping to prepare for
Elian's transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder, while expecting a peaceful
transfer for Elian, said that the US government would ``do what is
necessary to reunite father and son.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno, appearing on ABC's ``This Week'' Sunday, expressed her
admiration for Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who told her
last week that he has no interest in defecting to the United
States. Reno said Gonzalez is willing to stay in the United States
for as long as it takes to resolve the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who is staying at the Maryland home of Cuban
diplomatic official Fernando Remirez, will stay here as long as
necessary ``if he could have the child turned over in a careful,
thoughtful way,'' Reno said. ``If you talked to his father, you
would feel like you were talking to Elian Gonzalez about 30 years
later. He cares so much'' for Elian, Reno added.
</P>
<P>
   Spencer Eig, a lawyer for the Miami relatives, said Sunday that
the family would allow immigration officials to take the boy, but
did not want to help facilitate the transfer. That left open the
question of whether the relatives would agree to go to a location
outside of Miami to transfer Elian to his father. US officials want
the transfer to occur outside Miami to avoid confronting the crowd
of protesters gathered outside the relatives' house.
</P>
<P>
   If US officials come to the house, Eig said, the relatives will
not resist the transfer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll unlock the door and stand back,'' Eig said. ``They'll
stand back, they'll cry, and their hearts will break.''
</P>
<P>
   Eig and another attorney for the relatives, Linda Osberg-Braun,
suggested that Juan Gonzalez was acting under duress from the Cuban
government.
</P>
<P>
   But Holder, the deputy attorney general, said on NBC's ``Meet
the Press'' that he saw no evidence of that when he met with
Gonzalez on Friday for an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not with any Cuban official, he was alone with his wife
and 6-month-old boy,'' Holder said. Holder said that he came
prepared to offer asylum to Gonzalez, but that the Cuban began the
meeting by saying he wanted to return to his homeland with Elian.
</P>
<P>
   Ricardo Alarcon, president of the Cuban National Assembly, said
on several of Sunday's talk shows that Gonzalez was under no
pressure from the Cuban government. Alarcon said that if Gonzalez
wanted to defect, he could have done so at the Justice Department
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had wanted to remain in the US, ask for asylum or
whatever, he was in the right place, completely alone without any
Cuban official accompanying him,'' Alarcon said via satellite from
Cuba. ``Alone with his family and the authorities that are
entitled, according to US law, to grant him an asylum.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Miami relatives may have no choice other than to hand
over Elian to his father, they would at least like to prevent Elian
from being taken to Cuba. A federal court is slated to decide that
aspect of the case in May. In addition, the relatives are still
seeking custody of Elian in a Florida state family court.
</P>
<P>
   The boy came to the United States last Thanksgiving Day, when he
was found off the Florida coast by two fishermen. Gonzalez's mother
and nine others perished during the sea voyage on an aluminum
motorboat from Cuba; he managed to survive by clinging to an inner
tube.
</P>
<P>
   One of the fishermen, Donato Dalrymple, came to Washington
Sunday and met with Juan Miguel Gonzalez in an effort to persuade
him to remain in the United States with Elian. Dalrymple said after
the meeting that Gonzalez embraced him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was eternally grateful to me. He embraced me. And you could
tell it was not fabricated,'' Dalrymple said.
</P>
<P>
   While efforts to get Gonzalez to defect to the United States
apparently have failed, Elian's US relatives still hoped to
persuade Gonzalez to meet with them. But Gonzalez's attorney,
Gregory Craig, said that he had ruled out the possibility of a
Miami meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Information from wire services was used in this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
