<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI POINTS KNICKS INTO A DIFFERENT DIRECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It was not a trump of the stardusted shot the Knicks'
Allan Houston made here last May to eliminate the Heat in the first
round, but Tim Hardaway came up with a little magic in his
fingertips Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   With 4.7 seconds left in overtime, and the Heat down by 2
points, Hardaway drove hard to his left with Chris Childs riding
his hip the whole way. Hardaway stopped behind the 3-point arc and
then flung up a one-handed hook over the leaping Childs. With the
ball in midair, the crowd rose. It was good as it plunged down the
throat of the net at the buzzer to give the Heat a critical 95-94
victory at American Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The loss for the Knicks was devastating to their plans of
stealing the No. 2 seeding in the Eastern Conference from the Heat.
Instead of cutting the Heat's lead in the East to one game, the
Knicks fell three games behind them with six games left in the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Alonzo Mourning led the Heat with 33 points and took care of
Patrick Ewing (13 points, 14 rebounds). The Knicks were led by
Houston's 23 points and Latrell Sprewell's 19.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the Knicks had their spirits sapped by the Heat. So
often, it has been the other way around for the Heat, which has had
its psyche tramped by Knick miracles. For a while it looked like
another disappointment for Miami.
</P>
<P>
   When the Knicks looked doomed, they responded to force the
overtime. With 1 minute 11 seconds left in regulation, Dan Majerle
was left open by Houston for a 3-pointer to give the Heat a 88-85
lead. Things looked bleak for the Knicks. Ewing missed a jumper,
but then the Knicks' defense shut down the Heat and forced a
24-second violation.
</P>
<P>
   Then in a whirlwind of tipped balls and misses, somehow the
Knicks tied the score. On the desperate possession, Houston missed
a 3-pointer, then Sprewell missed one, too. All the while, Ewing
kept each miss alive with tips. One ricochet went to Houston, who
zinged a pass to Childs, who put down a 3-pointer to tie the score
with 11.9 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks had a chance to put the game away earlier. But
Mourning scored 6 points during a 13-5 run that enabled the Heat to
take the lead, 85-83, with 1:44 left in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   For three games, the combination of Sprewell and Houston had
been fizzling quietly in the background of Ewing's domination. They
had been unable to combine for more than 20 points as a result of
their inability to adjust to the pressure and their opponents'
double teams and traps.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been struggling offensively,'' Coach Jeff Van Gundy
said before Sunday night's game. ``We've won the last two. But I
don't think you can do that consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, both players were more assertive. They had to be.
Ewing exited the game with 7:22 left in the first quarter after his
second foul. Before he sat down, he baited the fans by flapping his
arm.
</P>
<P>
   Houston and Sprewell responded to Ewing's absence. Although the
aggressive Majerle and the long-armed Bruce Bowen played him
physically, Houston had an edge about him as he drove, stopped and
pulled up for fadeaway jumpers. Although Sprewell was playing
against the bulk of Jamal Mashburn and Clarence Weatherspoon, he
used his quickness to get around them and also beat both down the
court in transition.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Ewing returned, the Knicks kept pushing the ball. At
times, they ignored Ewing's pleas for the ball in the paint. By the
end of the first half, Sprewell and Houston had combined for 21
points and had the Knicks ahead, 49-46. Playing just 14 minutes
because of foul trouble, Ewing shot just four times and had 4
points. His counterpart, Mourning, was doing the heavy lifting for
the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   Wheeling inside of Ewing, as well as fading away for jumpers,
Mourning scored 15 points, while Hardaway added 9 points. They kept
the Heat in the game despite a poor performance by Mashburn, who
was 0 for 8 around the aggressive defense of Sprewell in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell continued to make an impact in the third quarter.
Making life miserable for Mashburn, he drove by him for a dunk and
then faded back for a jumper to give the Knicks a 58-53 lead with
7:13 left. Coach Pat Riley had seen enough. He took out a
frustrated Mashburn and put in Bowen.
</P>
<P>
   That made all the difference. In the span of three minutes,
Bowen stayed glued to Sprewell and then bolted free of him for a
3-pointer. Bowen also found Mourning on a bullet pass that led to a
dunk. With Bowen in the game, the Heat went on a 9-4 run to tie the
score with 3:14 remaining in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks did not shake at all. Instead, they took off on a
10-0 run. Taking advantage of some loose defense by the Heat,
Houston popped a 3-pointer and then hit a free throw when Hardaway
was hit with a technical foul. After getting tied up with Ewing,
Hardaway yelled at the official Dan Crawford and paid for it. With
1:06 left in the third quarter, the Knicks led 72-62, and held onto
a 72-64 lead as they entered the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   It was clear that the Knicks did not let their two days of
sunshine distract them from their purpose early in the game. They
came out focused and sharp, shooting a mind-boggling 70 percent in
the first quarter. The Knicks led by as many as 11 points before
the Heat regrouped, buckled down on defense and worked the ball
inside to Mourning to cut the Knicks' first-quarter lead to 28-21.
</P>
<P>
   Then a few defensive lapses cost the Knicks. During a 10-4 run
by the Heat, Houston, whose defense doesn't always coincide with
his hot offense, lost Bowen for a 3-pointer and a driving layup.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, who missed six of their first seven shots in the
second quarter, found themselves behind, 33-32, with 8:30 left in
the half. But Sprewell and Houston found their groove again and led
the Knicks on a 15-5 run to take back control of the game before
the half. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
