<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LeBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOXIE KEPT HELLING DOWNSTAIRS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON _ In baseball parlance, Rangers pitcher Rick Helling
likes to work upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, unfortunately, happens to be in the same neighborhood
as downtown. And downtown, 68 times over the past two seasons, has
been the final destination of some of Helling's proudest fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's road map to impending trouble, therefore, was plain
to see _ namely, fly-ball pitcher plus weeklong gusty winds equals
lots of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   But there was Helling yesterday, still battling the Toronto Blue
Jays in the sixth inning, shuffling pitches, writhing to find the
strike zone and, in the end, leaving the Rangers in position to
grab a 7-5 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``After three innings and 75 pitches, it didn't look like he
would go far,'' manager Johnny Oates correctly observed. ``But that
just shows you what a competitor he is. He just kept battling and
battling and gave us a chance to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates' math was correct. Helling threw 29 pitches in the first
inning yesterday, when the Jays' Carlos Delgado laced a two-run
double, and by the end of the third inning Helling's pitch count
had bulged to 75.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd fidgeted. The manager, surprisingly, didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, it has been a three-year soap opera, this unspoken
scrimmage between Helling's pride and Oates' patience. You've
watched it unfold _ Oates walking to the mound, quick hook in hand,
while visible steam seems to spew from Helling's ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day I'm happy when he comes to the mound to take me out is
the day I'll quit,'' Helling assured yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Six of the first 13 Blue Jays that Helling faced yesterday
reached base. Through the first four innings, Helling had recorded
only one ground-ball out.
</P>
<P>
   ``His command wasn't there,'' Toronto manager Jim Fregosi said.
``We swung at a lot of bad balls. We had a ton of opportunities,
but we just didn't get it done. He was effectively wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever he walked, he should have walked more.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. But Luis Alicea's two-run double had staked the Rangers a
3-2 advantage, and Helling, like a dog with a yard bone, had
refused to give it up.
</P>
<P>
   And Oates, for his part, could see that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You buy rope,'' Oates explained. ``But I didn't just give him
the rope. My feeling is that he's earned that rope.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the past two seasons, Helling started 68 times for the
Rangers. Yes, he has been taken downtown an equal number of times.
But he has also won 33 of his 51 decisions over those two seasons.
And with runners in scoring position, Helling allowed opponents to
bat only .224, the sixth-lowest average allowed in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see Rick as being able to throw a lot of pitches,'' Oates
said, ``and being able to work himself into trouble but out of
trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly. Helling faced seven Toronto hitters yesterday when
runners were in scoring position; the Blue Jays were 0-for-7.
</P>
<P>
   He did it this time while toying with something new, a sinker
pitch. In the past, Helling mostly has been a fastball-curveball
pitcher, with something of a changeup mixed in. This season he is
trying to add the sinker and a slider.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw everything today,'' Helling said. ``I even threw some
first-pitch sliders to right-handed batters that were taken for
strikes, and they kind of looked back, as if to say, `What was
that?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Old bulldogs, even 29-year-old ones, are not supposed to be able
to learn new tricks. But if Helling, the quintessential fly-ball
pitcher, can effectively add a pitch that allows him to work the
lower extremities of the strike zone, he would be nasty.
</P>
<P>
   Oates and the Rangers dearly needed him yesterday, after a week
when the Ballpark winds mostly howled and 22 home runs escaped the
premises.
</P>
<P>
   But as the manager said, Helling earned the slack. The four hits
that he allowed were the fewest by Helling since June. By battling
through six innings, Helling also allowed Oates the luxury of not
having to go to the bullpen one inning too soon.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers head for their first road trip of the season still a
mystery. It was a week of both encouraging news and erratic news,
of winds and losses.
</P>
<P>
   It ended yesterday with the Blue Jays never quite making it
``downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Helling has no problems with the change in neighborhood.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
