<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
 
GOOD NEWS FOR DiSARCINA 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Shortstop Gary DiSarcina hasn't had much luck with
his thumbs during his major league career, but Sunday he got a
break when he learned he had no break.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina bruised his left thumb when trying to field a smash
hit by the Red Sox's Nomar Garciaparra in the second inning on
Saturday night. DiSarcina dived to his left to try to field the
one-hopper, but it deflected off the thumb on his glove hand and
into center field. DiSarcina stayed in the game until being
replaced by Benji Gil to start the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina had X-rays taken Sunday morning, which were negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to rush it,'' said DiSarcina, who is day-to-day.
``As soon as I can get my hand in my glove, we'll take it from
there. I woke up (Sunday) and expected the worst. I couldn't move
it. When the X-rays showed nothing, it was a sigh of relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he played six more innings after sustaining the
injury, DiSarcina said: ``Because I'm stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina's bad luck with his thumbs goes back to 1993 when he
broke the knuckle of his right thumb when hit by a pitch. Then in
1995, DiSarcina tore a ligament in his left thumb sliding into
second trying to break up a double play. He missed six weeks with
each injury.
</P>
<P>
   After starting four of the first five games at DH, Scott Spiezio
got his first start in the field Sunday at first base, moving Mo
Vaughn to DH. Signed as a free agent from the A's, Spiezio was
competing for the starting spot at second base and was the
frontrunner until the Angels acquired Adam Kennedy in a trade with
the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   That left Spiezio without a position, but he has become the
primary DH. It's a new role for him, but he says he's adjusting
well.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great thing about this park is you've got the (batting)
cage right there next to the dugout if you want to hit,'' he said.
``And there's an (exercise) bike to keep loose, or you can look at
video. You couldn't do that in Oakland, you'd have to run upstairs.
Now everything's right by the dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   He's only 27, so he doesn't see himself as a DH. But Spiezio
said he can be happy there for now.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as I'm hitting, I don't care,'' he said. ``You could
put me behind the plate if you wanted to. The reason I came here
was for the at-bats.''
</P>
<P>
   Spiezio homered both Saturday and Sunday and leads the team with
two.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starters Jason Dickson, Ken Hill and Kent Bottenfield
have combined to throw three consecutive quality starts (at least 6
innings, 3 earned runs or less). ... Winning two of the three games
against the Red Sox, the Angels surpassed last season's win total
-- one -- vs. Boston. ... Catchers Bengie Molina and Matt Walbeck
have combined to throw out 67 percent (4 of 6) of would-be
basestealers.
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS VS. TORONTO
</P>
<P>
   Time: 7:05 at Edison Field
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: No TV; KMPC-1540, XPRS-1090
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: Scott Schoeneweis (1-0, 7.50 ERA) will make his second
start of the season for Anaheim against Toronto's Chris Carpenter
(0-1, 4.05). Schoeneweis beat the Yankees in his first start,
thanks to the offense's 12-run outburst. Left fielder Darin Erstad
has hit safely in all six games, and is hitting .556 (15 for 27)
with a team-leading seven RBI. The Angels lost nine of 12 games
against Toronto last season.
</P>
<P>
   -- Joe Haakenson
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
