<DOCNO> NYT20000409.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1774 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-WEBS&AMP;MAGS-AZR &LR;      04-09 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBS&AMP;MAGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEBS&AMP;MAGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (EDITORS: Story moving in the  &UR; ``E'' and  &UR; ``L'' categories) Here
are Bill Muller's reviews of a Website and current magazines: &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEBSITE: www.dailynewspix.com
</P>
<P>
   The photo archive of the New York Daily News includes several
free features, including a gallery that showcases famous photos
taken over the years, many wit strong historical significance.
</P>
<P>
   From the main site, click on Photo Gallery, and you'll reach a
screen with `Greatest Hits'' and `New York Noir.'' The Greatest
Hits section includes a number of notable Daily News photos,
including the well-known Charles Hoff picture of the Hindenburg
zeppelin ablaze after exploding at Lakehurst, N.J., i 1937, plus
the obligatory duck-and-cover photo from a 1960s atomic bomb drill
and a portrait of John Lennon and Yoko Ono. There is also a Rosie
the Riveter photo from the World War II era, during which women
entered factories to replace men who were fighting overseas; a
photo of David Berkowitz, the Son of Sam killer, being led into
police headquarters; and poet Allen Ginsberg reading his work in
Washington Square Park.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Noir section is devoted to crime photos, including
the picture of Ruth Snyder being executed in the electric chair at
Sing Sing prison, the aftermath of the assassination of mobster
Albert Anastasia and several other graphic street crime photos.
</P>
<P>
   The site also features a portfolio work from Evy Mages, a Daily
News photographer who was named the New York Press Photographers
Association Photographer of the Year. There are several other
features, including a search engine for guests and members and a
link to the Daily News Web site (www.nydailynews.com). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MAGAZINES &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``ARCHAEOLOGY'S DIG'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trying to drag your kids away from those dreaded Pok mon cards?
Want to trick them into learning something? Then Dig, a bi-monthly
published by the Archaeological Institute of America, is for you.
It's archaeology for kids, chock full of interesting articles,
games, puzzles and cartoons, all based on ancient cultures and
discovery. Written in a straightforward, accessible style, the
magazine actually tries to make learning fun. Don't let the board
of education hear about this. Lead story, about the great pyramids
of Egypt, does a fine job explaining why the pyramids are such an
amazing feat of engineering (no slide rules, pocket protectors or
the Internet back in those days). Of course, it goes a little over
the top in quoting Napoleon, in the original French, remarking on
the pyramids. There is another good piece on how archaeologists
date artifacts, explaining how different items are found on
different levels of a dig, and how carbon-14 dating is used.
Another interesting piece trie s to determine whether Hercules
really lived, or is just a creation of Greek mythology and Michael
Eisner. Can you dig it?  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``BIOGRAPHY'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This week's cover story profiles Paul Newman, salad dressing
entrepreneur and part-time actor. Naturally, the story is a fawning
piece of fluff, but the pictures are cool, stretching from Newman's
high school yearbook photo to studio shots of him in Cool Hand
Luke, The Sting, Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid and The Color
of Money, for which he won an Oscar. The story starts out talking
about how amusing Newman is, but none of the jokes he tells are
very funny. But he does, the author slyly notes, still have those
same blue eyes. Let's hope so. In the way of actual history, there
is a decent piece on John D. Rockefeller, founder of Standard Oil,
the mammoth monopoly that was broken up by a trust-busting Teddy
Roosevelt and turned into most of the gas stations you see on
corners today. The story also notes that Rockefeller turned
philanthropist in his later years, giving millions to education,
health care, churches and orphanages. Bully. In the Masters of the
Stunningly Obvious section, there's a story noting that movie star
Cameron Diaz is quite fetching. Bully, bully. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``DISCOVER'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lead story examines the hullabaloo around the Microwave
Anisotropy Probe (MAP for short), a NASA project that will catalog
microwave photons to answer the largest questions of the universe:
how old it is, how it will end, whether space is really infinite
and where exactly did I leave my car keys? The mission is a
follow-up to the Cosmic Background Explorer (COBE) that found the
faint afterglow of the Big Bang. If it survives its testing, and
launch, MAP will use its sophisticated equipment to recreate ``the
universe's baby picture.'' Another article notes that chimpanzees
speak in dialects, invent odd grooming styles and drum better than
most kids in marching bands, meaning they are closer to humans than
previously thought. And their TV shows are better than prime time,
too. In the category of Tediously Pointless Pursuits, a group of
climbers clambered up Mount Everest to stick a global positioning
device on top, to finally, once and for all, get its exact
elevation. And they got it. Plus or minus 7 feet. Doh!  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; ``ROLLING STONE'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cover story checks in on the Red Hot Chili Peppers, noting that
Flea and the boys are back on their game with the release of
``Californication,'' which the mag calls ``their finest sustained
work ever.'' Piece holds that the Chili Peppers have evolved from
half-naked out-of-control young turks to half-naked elder
statesmen, after 17 years and seven albums. Article's funniest line
points out that the Chili Peppers ``have had so many guitarists _
seven _ they could hold a reunion barbecue for them every summer.''
There is also a well-written piece on Levon Helm, drummer for The
Band (``The Night They Drove Old Dixie Down,'' ``Up On Cripple
Creek''), who is recovering from throat cancer and revisiting the
Delta blues and daughter Amy. In a Q&AMP;A, Latino heartthrob Marc
Anthony admits that he used to get sick to his stomach at the idea
of performing. Now he's engaged to a former Miss Universe. Go
figure. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-00 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
