<HEADLINE>
DERIDING RIVAL'S CRITICISM, GIULIANI CAMPAIGNS WITH MCCAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC LIPTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, joined Sunday for the second
time in a week by Sen. John McCain, ridiculed a suggestion by the
Clinton campaign that he and the senator are linked to the
Republican Party's far right wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to show everybody that I want to associate with the
senator,'' Giuliani said during a brief appearance at a midtown
Manhattan delicatessen with McCain, the former presidential
candidate from Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's comments were a reaction to a remark about McCain
made last week by Ellis Verdi, media consultant to Hillary Rodham
Clinton's Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am surprised that Mayor Giuliani would associate himself
with someone who is that far to the right,'' Verdi was quoted in
The New York Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who made a campaign swing with the mayor through Long
Island on Tuesday, made repeated references to the remark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed that, since my last visit here, I am now part of the
`vast right-wing conspiracy,''' he said, referring to a term once
used by Clinton to describe certain critics of her and President
Clinton. ``I am very proud to be part of that organization.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, McCain joked, while he and the mayor sat down for a cup
of coffee at Ben's Kosher Deli on West 38th Street, ``we seized
this opportunity to hatch several plots.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said Verdi's comment inspired him to spend more time
with the senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read that I wasn't supposed to associate with John
McCain,'' Giuliani said, ``I wanted to show that I was not going to
be deterred by comments from the other side.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain holds more conservative views than the mayor on a number
of issues, such as abortion rights. But during his recent
unsuccessful bid for president, he was popular with moderate
Republicans in part because of his criticism of the role leaders of
conservative religious groups play in the party.
</P>
<P>
   It is those same moderate voters that Giuliani, who polls
suggest has slipped behind Clinton in the Senate race, wants to
attract. And McCain tried Sunday to help that effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason why I am so committed to getting Rudy Giuliani in
the United States Senate is he will be a voice of independence,''
McCain said. ``He will be a voice that speaks for those who many
times in the halls of the United States Senate are not spoken
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Dunn, a spokeswoman for the Clinton campaign, said
Giuliani should spend more time talking about issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``John McCain is not running for the Senate; Rudy Giuliani is,''
Dunn said. ``And at some point, the mayor is going to have to tell
the people of New York where he stands on the issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
