<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGH HOLDS OFF ALL CHALLENGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ If it's something colorful you want, Fiji is
pleased to offer the kaleidoscopic kula bird. Another one of the
South Pacific archipelago's treasures, Vijay Singh, is a decidedly
different bird.
</P>
<P>
   He's as monochromatic as men come.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, at dusk on Sunday Singh stood behind the 18th green at
Augusta National Golf Club, looking a lot like the green-winged
parrot that's indigenous to his native land. His limbs were covered
by the green wool fabric of his 46L Masters jacket, Singh's prize
for finishing atop a leaderboard so illustrious it could have been
lifted straight from the world golf rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Singh fired a 3-under-par 69 from the hardest possible spot -
the top of the leaderboard - to hold off his good friend, Ernie
Els, who closed with a 68. David Duval, who started the day three
shots behind Singh, carded a 70 to finish in a tie for third with
Loren Roberts (69).
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods made another of his patented charges but fell a few
putts short, chasing his third-round 68 with a 69 to wind up fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wearing this green jacket tops it all,'' Singh said. ``I can't
describe the feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Stranded on the course Saturday when darkness descended, the
one-time teaching pro came out Sunday morning and parred his last
four holes to carry a three-stroke lead into the final round.
</P>
<P>
   Many golfers before him have found the final-round lead an
onerous burden but the world-weary 37-year-old never seemed to
sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Singh remained composed even when one of his golf balls splashed
down in the pond to the left of the 11th green and another ball
flirted with an azalea bush protecting a green-side bunker on the
12th green, while all the while Duval was breathing down his back.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of a felicitous drop at 11, Singh scrambled to
save par. On the next hole he got another lucky break when the
azalea bush spit his ball out in the bunker and he was able to get
up and down from there to maintain his one-stroke cushion over
Duval.
</P>
<P>
   To that point the final pairing of Singh and Duval was unfolding
like a match-play final. Duval, bidding for his first victory in a
major, drew to within two shots of Singh with a birdie on the par-5
second hole, gained another stroke on his playing partner when
Singh bogeyed the par-4 third, and then matched him birdie for
birdie on the sixth, eighth and ninth holes.
</P>
<P>
   On the 13th hole, an ill wind rose to greet Duval as he stood on
the fairway preparing to hit his second shot to the par-5 green.
Duval stepped away when he felt the gust, re-considered his club
choice, waited for the wind to die down and then, using a 5-iron,
hit the ball into Rae's Creek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hit a bad golf shot. It was the only poor shot I hit
(in the final two rounds),'' said Duval, who bogeyed the hole while
Singh was blithely birdieing it. With the two-shot swing, it proved
to be the swing hole of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Els, playing in the group ahead of Singh and Duval, shaved three
strokes off par on his back nine to keep some heat on Singh, his
regular practice-round partner.
</P>
<P>
   He found himself within two strokes of the lead after Singh
three-putted for a bogey on the par-3 16th. But Els couldn't
convert 12-foot birdie putts on each of the final two holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't meant to be for me this year,'' said Els, who echoed
a common refrain in the clubhouse when he said he was glad Singh's
time had finally arrived.
</P>
<P>
   The Fijian works harder on his game than most any golfer on the
Tour, which endears him to his fellow pros who appreciate success
well-earned. Singh's skills go less appreciated outside the closed
ranks of the golfing community, as he's too busy working on his
game to promote himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's absolutely no doubt in my mind Vijay's one of the top
five players in the world right now,'' said Nick Price, who tied
for 11th. ``He has been for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   If the public was largely unaware of it until Sunday, that's
because ``Vijay's a very quiet, introverted man,'' Price said. ``If
anything, he shies away from the limelight.''
</P>
<P>
   For Singh, shirking attention just got a whole lot harder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
