<P>
   (NYT5) SAN FRANCISCO -- April 9, 2000 -- NEWS-DELIVERY-MEDIA --
From America Online and Microsoft to Reuters and The Associated
Press to The New York Times, news and information organizations are
bringing their wares to the diminutive screens of portable
electronic devices. Felix Lin founded AvantGo when the Palm Pilot
was introduced, aiming to offer information for users of the
devices. By developing alliances with media companies, stock
tracking services like Stock Smart, and other sources of
information, AvantGo has developed an inventory of hundreds of
``channels'' that mobile device owners can receive. (Thor Swift/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- April 9, 2000 -- SANDERS-PROFILE -- Bernard
Sanders, the democratic socialist from Vermont who is one of two
independents in the House, says ``pharmaceutical companies are on
the defensive.'' Sanders, 58, has pushed legislation that he says
would allow American pharmacists and distributors to ``reimport''
FDA-approved prescription drugs from Canada and Mexico and sell
them at lower costs. ``I know what it's like to live in a family
without any money,'' he says, trying to explain his anger at the
extremes of a boom economy, ``the economic suffering that is
totally unnecessary'' among the uninsured, the working poor and
many of the elderly. (Susana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- April 9, 2000 -- MORGAN-THEATER-REVIEW --
Frances Conroy, left, Patrick Stewart and Shannon Burkett in ``The
Ride Down Mount Morgan,'' Arthur Miller's seriously discomforting
comedy at the Ambassador Theater on Broadway. As the latest entry
in the astonishing resurrection of Miller's work on Broadway, and
elsewhere, over the last two years, ``The Ride Down Mount Morgan''
bears comparison to his other recently revived plays, not least
because it revisits, in a comic vein unusual for this most sober
playwright, many of their concerns. (Sara Krulwich/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) OXFORD, England -- April 9, 2000 -- OED-ONLINE-2 -- A lot
has happened to society and the context for language since 1879,
when professor James Murray took control of an awesomely ambitious,
and awesomely unrealized, at that point, project to create an
all-inclusive historical tour of the English language. In its
familiar version, the Oxford English Dictionary stretches over 20
volumes, weighs 138 pounds and so thoroughly plumbs the history of
640,000 words and phrases that there would seem to be nothing left
to plumb. Murray, far right, circa 1900, the first editor of the
Oxford English Dictionary, during the compilation of the first
edition of the dictionary. (Jonathan Player/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) OXFORD, England -- April 9, 2000 -- OED-ONLINE-1 --
Thomas Murray, age 6, a descendant of James Murray, the first
editor of the Oxford English Dictionary, online at the University
of London. Earlier last month, the mild-mannered dictionary ducked
into a phone booth, put on some high-tech tights and a cape, and
emerged as the Superman of reference works. Its new electronic
version does not fit on any shelf, but it is the first phase of a
$55 million, 10-year online overhaul that will add more than
600,000 new words, and revise the 19th-century entries for many old
ones. (Jonathan Player/The New York Times)
</P>
