<HEADLINE>
HAND-HELD SYSTEMS TEMPT NEWS-HUNGRY CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NEWS-DELIVERY-MEDIA) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ This is a city ravenous for news and mobile
communications, with more than a half-dozen national newspapers and
nearly half the population owning cellular phones. So the prospect
of devices that can deliver news to the palm of one's hand is
making the English downright giddy.
</P>
<P>
   Already there is so much pent-up demand for the new generation
of cellular phones offering Internet access based on the Wireless
Access Protocol, or WAP, that Vodafone AirTouch PLC, the world's
largest mobile-phone operator, has a waiting list for the phones
that may take months to fulfill.
</P>
<P>
   Europe has long been the leader of the cellular-telephone
revolution. In some countries, over 60 percent of the population
have wireless phones, compared with only about 25 percent in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when it comes to Internet access at home, Europe has been
the laggard. And while hand-held devices like the Palm Pilot have
taken off in the United States, Europeans have been slower to adopt
them.
</P>
<P>
   But mobile Internet access is a completely new game on both
sides of the Atlantic. U.S. cellular operators are offering an
array of mobile Internet options, though the offerings are based on
a hodgepodge of technologies. But in Europe, where all mobile
phones are based on a continent-wide standard called GSM, mobile
Internet access is limited so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of services have rolled out really quickly in the
U.S.,'' said Noah Yasskin, an analyst for the research firm of
Jupiter Communications in London. ``In Europe, everyone's waiting
for the phones and the standards. When it does roll out, it will be
really big because of the unified standards and the number of
people who use mobile phones.''
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers and other information providers are rushing to format
their content for mobile phones and to negotiate deals for
placement on the phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in a lot of negotiations for WAP content,'' said Mike
Caldwell, a spokesman for Vodafone, who himself owns a WAP-enabled
mobile phone with links to the BBC and The Independent newspaper.
``We believe WAP is going to be big by next Christmas.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested a technical transition was responsible for the slow
rollout of interactive services on mobile telephones. Caldwell
compared the situation to Europe's changeover from analog cellular
service to the digital GSM format in December 1991. ``You couldn't
get a phone until a year later,'' he said. ``People said GSM stood
for God Send Mobiles.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the current delays can be traced to a bug in some of the
early Nokia WAP phones that Vodafone ordered. ``There was a glitch
in the first batch,'' he said. ``So we returned them.''
</P>
<P>
   Wireless Access Protocol will give users access to Internet
sites specially formatted for the small screens of mobile phones.
Headlines, sports scores and listings are being developed for the
phones.
</P>
<P>
   Yasskin, the Jupiter analyst, predicted that WAP phones would
supplement, rather than replace, other types of Internet access.
``The mobile screen is so small that you are not talking about a
rich media experience,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An information delivery system that has already caught on in
Europe and is expected to grow is SMS, a text-based messaging
service. The service was initially developed so telephone users
could send each other quick text messages like those on pagers.
Recently, though, companies have begun developing commercial
applications for the service, like sending users news headlines and
movie listings.
</P>
<P>
   Since the SMS messaging capacity is already built into phones
that use the GSM standard, it is likely to remain a popular
function even after the introduction of WAP, Yasskin predicted.
</P>
<P>
   With so much information to deliver and so little screen space
to deliver it to, it is unclear whether advertising banners like
those on the Web will support the new hand-held ventures. So who is
going to pay for it all?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the big question,'' Yasskin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
