<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1787 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-UKULELE-FAME-ART-NYT &LR;      04-09 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UKULELE-FAME-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UKULELE MAKE AN ENCORE WITH PLUNKERS SEEKING SERENITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: See also UKELELE-BACKGROUND) 
(ART ADV: Photo of ukulele players at Ukulele Expo 2000 is being
sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time
rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST ORANGE, N.J. _ Robert Wheeler was explaining the two-word
slogan stitched across the back of his black satin baseball jacket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ukulele Consciousness,'' he said carefully, ``is an awareness
of ukuleles and their history and their place in society. And it's
a way to gain serenity.''
</P>
<P>
   Wheeler, 65, has 169 ukuleles back home in Littleton, Mass., and
he had just bought two more, but he does not like to be called a
collector.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people hear `collector,''' he said, ``they want to talk
about monetary value. But money just distracts from the true value
of ukuleles.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what?
</P>
<P>
   ``Spiritual,'' he said, unblinking.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the 140 brave souls who packed the Councilwoman Toby
Katz Civic Center here for Ukulele Expo 2000 came to shop. Some
came to learn new chord fingerings at the workshops, or gawk at the
antique ukes, or hear a few songs from old-timers or modern
Hawaiian virtuosos.
</P>
<P>
   Others came to see the inductions into the Ukulele Hall of Fame
of a master instrument-maker, Sam Kamaka of Hawaii; Cliff Edwards,
a performer better known as Ukulele Ike, and May Singhi Breen, New
York City's Ukulele Lady of the 20s and 30s.
</P>
<P>
   But in truth, all came to spend a weekend in the arms of a
supportive community, where they could indulge their passion for
the most maligned instrument this side of the kazoo without
embarrassment or apology, in a place where every plink was a
droplet in a swelling ocean of ukulele consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing to see all these people here,'' said Peter
Stuart, an Upper West Side computer programmer who plays in a ``hot
vaudeville'' group called Ewa's Hawaiians.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is,'' said Ewa Noskowicz, 34, sitting beside him.
``It seems like the ukulele has been kind of a joke instrument and
no one wants to admit to playing it.''
</P>
<P>
   The ukulele (pronounced oo-koo-LAY-lay in its native Hawaii) is
enjoying one of its periodic surges in popularity, said Nuni Walsh,
a director of the Ukulele Hall of Fame Museum (a largely virtual
institution, consisting of a group of devotees in several states
and their ukes). As a resident of West Orange, Walsh was also a
de-facto hostess of the event.
</P>
<P>
   Ukulele makers are springing into business all over the country,
and the venerable C.F. Martin &AMP; Co., the country's biggest maker of
acoustic guitars, has just started mass-producing ukuleles again
after a 20-year hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   Japan and the West Coast are the centers of the new cult of the
ukulele. But the expo, held in the New York area for the first time
after three previous ones in Rhode Island and Massachusetts, sold
out well in advance, and many would-be attendees were turned away
at the door.
</P>
<P>
   Experts cited several possible reasons for the revival.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Beloff, a former associate publisher of Billboard who quit
his job in 1998 to make a slope-sided, flat-bottomed uke called the
Fluke and has sold 2,300 of them in nine months, said many mature
folkies, whom he called ``lapsed guitarists,'' were out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who, due to the demands of family life or a
career, have fallen away from the guitar,'' he said. For them, he
said, the uke makes perfect sense.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how their numbers grow, ukulele players get no
respect. Tiny Tim is a sore point.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did some damage,'' said Walsh, who prefers more traditional
jazz-influenced Hawaiian players like Eddie Kamae and Israel
Kamakawiwo'ole. ``He's very cute and we like him, but in terms of
people's image of a ukulele player, it's not the image we want to
come into people's minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Others defended Tiny Tim. Wheeler credited him with keeping the
ukulele alive during the post-Arthur-Godfrey era of public disdain.
Beloff praised his encyclopedic knowledge of Tin Pan Alley
classics.
</P>
<P>
   And many attendees, Walsh conceded, have only themselves to
blame for the ukulele's reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the people are real kooky,'' she said. ``I love them
all, but as you can imagine, someone who's really into the ukulele
can be kind of kooky.''
</P>
<P>
   The high point Sunday was a medley that started with Fred
Fallin, a retired schoolteacher in a sailor hat, and Bill Watson,
an old vaudevillean from Richmond, Va., and spread like wildfire.
</P>
<P>
   When the chorus of ``Nagasaki'' (``Back in Nagasaki where the
men all chew tobacky and the women wicky-wacky-woo'') rolled
around, a couple more pickers had joined in, and as Fallin, sweat
running down his face, finished off ``Do the Raccoon'' and got into
``Collegiate,'' a big hit for Fred Waring and His Pennsylvanians in
the 20s, the ensemble included five more sets of fingers, including
a mandolin player.
</P>
<P>
   Many said the ukulele had turned their lives around. Wheeler
found the instrument after his third marriage collapsed. Denny
Moynahan, an actor from Hollywood who performed in a grass skirt as
King Kukulele, got a uke after breaking up with a girlfriend, and
perfected his act on a yearlong trip around the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
