<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS GET GOOD PLAYOFF TUNE-UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Playing the Mighty Ducks on Sunday was the perfect
way to end the Kings' regular season. Despite their record, the
Ducks look an awful lot like the Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   Even though they now have missed the postseason four years in a
row, the Ducks have the speed, quick-strike offense and aggressive
defense to give the Kings a glimpse of their first-round playoff
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it isn't expected to be as easy as the Kings' 4-3
overtime victory that was played in front of 17,174 at the Pond.
But even though the Kings will enter Thursday's opener in Detroit
as overwhelming underdogs, they probably learned a little about
Steve Yzerman and Sergei Fedorov by watching Paul Kariya and Teemu
Selanne.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very good team we played today and I'm not sure why
they aren't in the playoffs,'' defenseman Mattias Norstrom said.
``They are very fast, much like Detroit. The Red Wings probably
have more weapons but if you can defense the Ducks, it's good for
your confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   That was boosted by losing just once in their final 10 games.
When they qualified for the playoffs two years ago, the Kings
limped to the finish line and were swept by the St. Louis in the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't hurt that the Kings finish the season two games
over .500 (18-16-7) on the road. However long the playoffs last,
most of it will be spent away from home.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is something we've been working on since training camp,''
said captain Rob Blake, who returned to the lineup after missing
three games with a bruised left knee. ``If you keep your composure
on the road, positive things can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Kings also took advantage of a vulnerable goaltender
in Guy Hebert, who looked shaky on the Kings' final two goals. If
Detroit has a weakness it's goaltender Chris Osgood, who has come
under fire from coach Scotty Bowman for inconsistency.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert, playing in his 400th game with the Ducks, had dominated
the Kings the past two seasons, going 7-0-2 before losing last
Saturday in their playoff clincher at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   But Blake gave the Kings a 3-2 lead with a long goal that sailed
through Hebert's legs. Selanne tied it five minutes later with his
second goal of the game and 33rd of the season. But Glen Murray
provided the game winner 1:05 into overtime when he also beat
Hebert between the pads.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you keep getting shots on net, you never know,'' said
Murray, who finished with 29 goals. ``We just stayed aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were fully aware that the Ducks might come in deflated
after getting eliminated Friday night. They beat the Predators 5-1
in Nashville. But just hours later Edmonton came back from a 3-1
third-period deficit to beat Vancouver in overtime and claim the
final playoff spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings also were playing without Ziggy Palffy, who has missed
the past month nursing a sprained right shoulder. The Kings medical
staff decided Saturday to keep Palffy out of action until the
playoff opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``With practice, he can get a good one-hour non-stop workout
every day,'' coach Andy Murray said. ``In a game, he isn't going to
play more than 20-22 minutes. There is a certain rhythm you lose
not playing in a game, but the time off will help him more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings will not skate today, but will meet with the coaches
and plot strategy for Detroit. As for the Ducks, who finish the
season (34-36-12), they are he heading home for the fourth
consecutive year. Selanne looks at the Kings a and isn't sure why.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had good success against them,'' he said. ``It's not
like they're getting in because they beat us. We played well in our
division, but there were games in the East where we did not come up
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the Kings are heading East, hoping they learned a few
things from the Ducks in order to survive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the past few weeks we have played well and I think that is
something that will carry over to the playoffs,'' Norstrom said.
``This is no longer a six-month season it is a two-week season. We
just have to continue to play well for the next two weeks and see
where it takes us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
