<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARTUP-SPAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING NEW COMPANY WITH SOME ACCIDENTAL `SPAM' 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIM RACE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The old joke about publicity goes: Print whatever you want; just
spell the name right. So for the record, the company's name is
spelled E-V-E-R-Y-P-A-T-H.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the story may or may not serve the publicity
purposes of Everypath, a Silicon Valley start-up that converts Web
information to a form that can be sent to hand-held devices over
wireless networks.
</P>
<P>
   Because the company had been keeping a low profile, it is likely
that few journalists had even heard of Everypath before a week ago
Saturday. But as hundreds of business reporters and editors checked
their e-mail that day, they found a message sent the night before
from someone with an address at everypath.com.
</P>
<P>
   The subject line read ``Partner Launch Status,'' and an attached
document contained a status report _ evidently for some sort of
event to introduce a new business in which the partners would
include Intel, Hewlett-Packard and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   But within two hours, another e-mail message had arrived from
everypath.com, this time with the subject line ``We apologize for
the accidental spam ....''
</P>
<P>
   In the second message, Everypath's communications director,
Giselle Bisson, explained that an employee ``working long hours on
our launch'' had meant to send the first message only to the
executive staff _ but accidentally copied it to the entire
invitation list for the company's coming-out party. Bisson's note
added, ``Please do not reply to that message or you will get
hundreds of out-of-office replies and junk e-mails.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, asking hundreds of reporters and editors to not reply
to even an accidental public relations ``spamming'' is like posting
a ``No food fights'' sign in a junior-high cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   All across America, sticky mouse fingers began stabbing at the
reply or reply-to-all button. Soon, e-mail boxes were overflowing
with messages labeled ``Re: Partner Launch Status'' and ``Re: We
apologize for the accidental spam ....'' Hundreds of messages.
</P>
<P>
   Some were hostile, like: ``I hate PR people. They waste the one
precious thing in this work: TIME!'' from
editor(at)siliconalleyreporter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Some were forgiving, like: ``I've known Giselle B. for many
years, and she is a consummate professional, who I am sure was not
directly responsible for this fiasco,'' from
rsantalesa(at)smartedge.com.
</P>
<P>
   Then others became even more hostile, as in the big red letters:
``STOP YOU MORONS. EACH TIME YOU HIT REPLY YOU SEND TO THE SEVERAL
THOUSAND PEOPLE ON THIS IDIOTIC MAILING LIST,'' from
CEO(at)e-shortcut.com.
</P>
<P>
   The spamming angered some executives involved in the plans,
Bisson said. But the party did proceed _ a 1920s-theme event last
Wednesday night in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Those in attendance included Helen Spade, the Everypath
executive whose wayward e-mail had set off the spam fight. Spade
said people at the company had tried to make her feel better after
her mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past few days I feel like Monica Lewinsky,'' Spade
wrote in reply to an e-mail query, ``but I didn't have nearly as
much fun as her, and didn't even get a cigar out of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
