<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DAVISCUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS CAPS U.S. COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD - Throughout this week's Davis Cup quarterfinal, from
the early-week practices to the matches, people have called Pete
Sampras a champion. Not just because he has won a record-tying 12
Grand Slams, but because he finds a way to win.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, perhaps the greatest of hometown players, proved
everyone correct in Sunday's decisive match and brought some needed
redemption for himself and U.S. tennis.
</P>
<P>
   In front of numerous friends and family among the 12,002 fans,
and after being outplayed on Friday, Sampras fought off an
inconsistent backhand and a quadriceps injury to beat the Czech
Republic's Slava Dosedel 6-4 , 6-4, 7-6 (7-2) Sunday at the Great
Western Forum, giving the United States its second consecutive
come-from-behind 3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. rallied to beat Zimbabwe in February's first round,
causing plenty of hugging and flag waving among the team and its
followers. Since that match was in Africa, it felt better Sunday
for Sampras, Andre Agassi and John McEnroe to take victory laps
around the court, holding the flag behind them, for they are in the
semifinals against Spain July 21-23.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras was the hero, but his herculean efforts wouldn't have
happened had Agassis not won earlier. Agassi cooled the hot Jiri
Novak 6-3, 6-3 , 6-1, tiring the Czech with trips across the
baseline and mixing in 12 aces.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's shocker, Sampras was visibly despondent, looking
stunned as he told of being outplayed by someone ``in the zone.''
Not mentioned was his disappointment that his parents, who haven't
seen him play too much in his career, witnessed his worst Davis Cup
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   How sweet is must have felt when Sampras hugged his father, Sam,
after winning Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   When Sampras was in his early 20s, he said he was so focused on
tennis that family came second. He even moved to Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he's 28 and moved back here last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The older you get, you appreciate your parents,'' Sampras
said. ``Having them here today was a great moment for my parents.
... My dad doesn't see me play a lot. He's never been to Wimbledon,
which is so much a part of my career. I want them to be a part of
my tennis life. Plus, the Forum's close to their home, so they had
to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras' parents, like everyone else, saw him dominate Dosedel
with his serve, which more than made up for his backhand
deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   Hurting his quadriceps in the first set affected his backhand,
but Sampras still can serve, rocketing most of his 18 aces past
Dosedel at more than 120 mph. It didn't matter he was on his first
or second serve, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got one of the best serves in the world, and I figure I
should use it,'' Sampras said. ``I got into a great rhythm. My arm
felt loose and strong. Even if I got a couple of doubles (faults),
I was confident. ''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best serve in the history of tennis,'' U.S. captain
McEnroe said. ``I've never seen anybody who's had a better one.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras broke Dosedel in the first set to go ahead 3-1. In the
second set, after breaking Dosedel to go up 5-4, Sampras leaped and
did a Tiger Woods kind of fist pump.
</P>
<P>
   In the third-set tiebreak, Sampras went up 6-2 after breaking
his string while returning Dosedel's serve, then placing a
backhander down the line. He skipped to the bench to get a new
racket then held serve, finishing the match with a service winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slava was playing his best tennis, but it wasn't enough for
`Pistol Pete,' '' Czech captain Jan Kukal said. ``His serve was too
unreturnable for anybody today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
