<HEADLINE>
A DIFFERENT DERBY TRIP FOR SAHADI
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ The first time Jenine Sahadi attended a
Kentucky Derby, she was a homesick University of Kentucky freshman
scandalized by the sight of the Woodstock-style crowd in the
Churchill Downs infield.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember SWAT teams and naked people up the flagpole,''
Sahadi, trainer of Santa Anita Derby winner The Deputy, said of
that day in 1981, the year Pleasant Colony won the Kentucky Derby.
``I never saw a horse all day. It was a wild, wild scene. I was
right out of the Santa Catalina School for Girls. You can use your
imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   She got closer to the on-the-track action in 1983, when she
cheered from the box seats as her family's Desert Wine ran second
to Sunny's Halo.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a fun day,'' said Sahadi, who had transferred to USC
by then.
</P>
<P>
   It might turn out that neither experience was as intense as her
third Kentucky Derby trip will be. Sahadi will fly to Louisville
Thursday, a day after The Deputy's scheduled flight east, to get
the colt ready for the May 6 race.
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy, ridden by Chris McCarron when he won Saturday's
Santa Anita Derby by one length over War Chant, with Captain Steve
third and Anees fourth, is a small but well-conformed Irish-bred
whose consistent sharp efforts and even temper will entice Kentucky
Derby bettors.
</P>
<P>
   As for Sahadi, 37, the first woman to train a Santa Anita Derby
winner she'd also be the first to train a Kentucky Derby winner
said she'll be happy to talk to reporters about the vital role of
women in male-dominated thoroughbred racing.
</P>
<P>
   What she said she won't entertain are questions about her Santa
Anita Derby-week feud with Bob Baffert, trainer of Captain Steve
and two of the past three Kentucky Derby winners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks I'm joking,'' Sahadi said. ``I will not talk
about it anymore. It's ancient history.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, angry about newspaper criticism, said he didn't know
he'd touch a nerve when he asked McCarron at Thursday's
post-position draw ceremony, ``Who's training The Deputy, you or
Jenine?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a male chauvinist pig,'' Baffert said.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared Sunday morning that the top four Santa Anita Derby
finishers will go on to Kentucky. Neil Drysdale, trainer of War
Chant, hopes the colt, previously unbeaten in three starts, will
get better with experience. Baffert acknowledged Captain Steve must
improve on his recent races. Richard Mulhall, racing manager for
The Thoroughbred Corp, which owns Anees, looks for a faster pace to
set up the colt's late charge.
</P>
<P>
   D. Wayne Lukas said he'll defer to owner William T. Young on
whether fifth-place finisher Surfside goes to the Derby or returns
to the fillies division for the May 5 Kentucky Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Anita Derby, run in 1:49.08 for 1 miles on a dull
track, earned a Beyer speed figure of 109, the highest for a major
3-year-olds race in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Deputy was described by his trainer as healthy and ``proud
of himself'' Sunday morning. He could be the Derby favorite if
Fusaichi Pegasus, the only horse to beat him in the United States,
is unimpressive in next Saturday's Wood Memorial at Aqueduct in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Sahadi placed a box of sugar doughnuts on her barn desk to
welcome a stream of well-wishers and members of The Deputy's
dozen-member ownership syndicate. A congratulatory bouquet of
flowers and balloons lay on a sofa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to (the next four weeks). I'm looking
forward to being with the horse,'' Sahadi said. ``I'm thinking of
it as a once-in-a-lifetime shot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
