<SLUG> BC-WILL-WAR-DEBT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT BACKS 1927 BEQUEST ON WAR DEBT 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ World War I ended in 1918. A resident of
the Westchester County town of New Rochelle named James Bertram
died in 1934. But it took until last week for a court to approve
Bertram's request that part of his estate, which has grown to about
$4.3 million, go to the U.S. government to help repay Britain's
debts from that war.
</P>
<P>
   It has taken so long, in fact, that Britain long ago stopped
trying to pay those debts, and the United States apparently stopped
caring.
</P>
<P>
   Bertram cared deeply. In his will, written in 1927, Bertram, a
native of Scotland, left his money in a trust fund to his wife and
daughter with the provision that after they died, if there were no
other children or grandchildren, whatever was left should go to
repay some of the $4.2 billion Britain had borrowed from the United
States to finance its war effort before the Americans formally
entered the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``James, an astute businessman working for the Carnegie
Institute, was allegedly motivated by patriotic spirit when he
devised this gift to the UK,'' Judge Albert J. Emanuelli of
Westchester Surrogate's Court said in a decision last Wednesday.
``He simultaneously wished to help his adopted home, the USA.''
</P>
<P>
   Bertram's only child, Jean Ewing Bertram Underhill, died in
1996. She had no children.
</P>
<P>
   Over the objections of Underhill's estate, Emanuelli ruled that
since there were no other direct descendants, the will must be
enforced. A lawyer for Jean Underhill's estate had argued that the
money should go to a foundation she had set up to benefit animals
and finance scholarships for veterinary students.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, the judge said that Britain stopped paying its
World War I debt to the United States in 1934 and in 1947 stopped
carrying it on its official records as a debt, but that this did
not give him the legal authority to ignore Bertram's wishes. He
said it was irrelevant that the United States had made no effort to
collect from Britain, as there was no evidence that the United
States had waived its right to be repaid. He also noted that
Washington still listed the debt in a Treasury Department
publication, and that as of 1994, with the addition of interest, it
was put at more than $14 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Once the government got wind of the dispute over Bertram's will,
it joined in supporting the Bank of New York, the trustee to the
estate, which argued in court that Bertram's wishes be followed.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for Underhill's estate, Robert L. Ecker, said he did
not know whether he would appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-09-00 2331EDT &QL; 
