<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1936 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PORN-STAR-TRADING-NYT     04-09 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORN-STAR-TRADING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET'S RACY INSIDER-TRADING TRIAL, AND A MISSING WITNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When federal prosecutors in Manhattan charged a Wall
Street chief executive last December with leaking confidential
stock information to an X-rated film star, it promised to be one of
the most salacious cases of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The star, Kathryn B. Gannon, was described by prosecutors as an
exotic dancer and actress who used the stage name Marylin Star. The
prosecutors charged that James J. McDermott Jr., the former chief
executive of the investment bank Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods, illegally
gave Gannon inside information on potential bank deals that enabled
her to make $88,000 in illegal profits on stock trades. She is also
accused of passing some of the information on to another investor.
</P>
<P>
   But it is unlikely that the jurors in the trial, which is to
begin Monday, will see any of the seamier side of the case. Gannon
has not appeared in Federal District Court in Manhattan to face the
charges against her, and is believed to be in Canada. And the judge
has told prosecutors that they cannot mention Gannon's career in
pornography.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she will be referred to as an actress and a dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Barring an unexpected development, such as an appearance by
Gannon or a change in the judge's ruling, it is likely that the
trial will proceed as a straightforward insider-trading case,
typical fare for a courthouse just a short walk from the financial
district.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors will try to prove that McDermott gave Gannon, with
whom they say he was having an affair, confidential information
about a series of bank takeovers. They say Gannon used the
information for stock trades and passed it on to a New Jersey
businessman, Anthony Pomponio, who has also been charged with
insider trading and with lying to the Securities and Exchange
Commission during the agency's investigation of the trades.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials have said McDermott is the first Wall Street
chief executive to be charged with insider trading.
</P>
<P>
   Both McDermott and Pomponio have pleaded not guilty in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's ruling on Gannon's work reflects one of the many
battles quietly fought as the case moved to trial. Prosecutors and
defense lawyers have jousted over several aspects of the case,
often over single words in a transcript, and references to Gannon's
work have been the subject of contention.
</P>
<P>
   In one letter to the trial judge, Kimba M. Wood, prosecutors
argued that it was important to mention pornography to establish
the relationship between the defendants and contended that
information about Gannon's occupation ``is highly relevant _
indeed, crucial _ to the government's case.''
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that references to X-rated films could be
distracting and inflammatory, the prosecutors said they had come up
with a compromise that would ``maintain the dignity of the
proceedings.'' The prosecutors offered to restrain from listing the
titles of Gannon's films, the content of her Web site, or from
offering ``photos depicting Gannon in a sexual context.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers objected to any mention of Gannon's occupation,
arguing that it had nothing to do with charges of insider trading.
For the most part, Wood agreed. ``My view on this issue remains the
same as at our last hearing, that is, that it is unduly prejudicial
and distracting for the jury to learn that Gannon was a porn
star,'' Wood said during a March hearing.
</P>
<P>
   When prosecutors asked to call Gannon an exotic dancer, Wood
deleted ``exotic.'' The prosecutors asked for adult-movie actress,
but the judge cut the ``adult.'' She did allow prosecutors to refer
to Gannon as a model and to her stage name.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Gannon will appear to answer the insider-trading charges
against her has been the subject of other hearings. Gannon, who is
a Canadian citizen, returned to Canada before she was charged,
although prosecutors have said she did so after receiving a
subpoena from the Securities and Exchange Commission. Prosecutors
have asked for delays to pursue extradition procedures, but the
defense has objected, arguing that it would violate the other
defendants' right to a speedy trial.
</P>
<P>
   Under the extradition treaty between the United States and
Canada, it is up to the Canadian Justice Department to detain
Gannon if officials believe there is sufficient evidence. A
spokesman for the department declined to comment on the case other
than to say Gannon has not been detained.
</P>
<P>
   Wood has made it clear that she was not willing to wait
indefinitely for Gannon to be brought to the United States. In a
hearing in February, defense lawyers said extradition could take
more than two years. Prosecutors said a more likely estimate was
more than a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
