<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Monday, April 10, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call Dominick Calicchio at 415-777-6206
or the business desk at 415-536-5172. For business stories running
in main news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOYSRUS:  &LR; Toysrus.com is determined to have a merrier Christmas
this year. After suffering meltdowns in delivery and site access
during the 1999 holiday season, the toy e-tailer is moving
aggressively to beef up its infrastructure. On Monday the company
will announce that it is setting up huge fulfillment centers in
Ontario, Calif., and Chambersburg, Pa., and is refitting its
existing Memphis, Tenn., warehouse. The snake arrived shortly
before midnight.  &UR; BY CAROLYN SAID &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELLME: &LR;  Some of the key people who brought the world the
Internet browser are now heading a company that has little to do
with the Internet. Backed by former Netscape Communications and
Microsoft executives, TellMe Networks, a Palo Alto, Calif.,
company, instead plans to offer information about everything from
the weather to stock quotes and a list of local restaurants via a
toll-free telephone number. TellMe plans to announce Monday that it
is launching a trial of the service and will make it available more
widely in June. &UR; BY TODD WALLACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EFAX:  &LR; It isn't easy being free. Just ask eFax. The Menlo Park,
Calif., firm runs one of the world's best-known free online fax
services, with more than 2 million users, and has ambitious plans
to make money by selling ads and signing up users for paid versions
of its service. But some Wall Street investors appear to be losing
faith in that vision.  &UR; BY TODD WALLACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIOSCOPE (COLUMN): &LR;  Opponents of genetically modified foods got
great media last year over the monarch butterfly, that charismatic
creature that seemed to choke on the pollen drift of so-called
``killer corn.'' But now one detects a not-so-subtle change in the
winds of publicity, which increasingly depict bioengineered plants
as the best hope of feeding the Third World. In contrast to last
year's script, which cast Monsanto as corporate demon, the poster
child of the remake is the well-fed environmental elitist.  &UR; COLUMN
BY TOM ABATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; B2B: &LR;  Mike Brossier was drowning in excess olive oil. Critelli
Olive Oil, where he is director of food service, had listened to
suggestions from its chef customers and crafted an oil similar to
that sold in Mediterranean countries: raw, unfiltered, strongly
flavored. The result was a deep green, cloudy olive oil that was a
little too daring for the U.S. market.  &UR; BY CAROLYN SAID &LR;
</P>
