<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYSRUS-WEBSALES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TOYSRUS.COM BUFFS UP FOR CHRISTMAS RUSH  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Toysrus.com is determined to have a merrier
Christmas this year.
</P>
<P>
   After suffering meltdowns in delivery and site access during the
1999 holiday season, the toy e-tailer is moving aggressively to
beef up its infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday the company will announce that it is setting up huge
fulfillment centers in Ontario, Calif., and Chambersburg, Pa., and
is refitting its existing Memphis, Tenn., warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the three facilities will have just short of 2 million
square feet of space. Each warehouse will be highly automated and
employ about 300 full-time workers, ramping up to 800 each over the
holidays.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, we will have excess capacity. No one is going to
question our willingness to step up to the plate this year,'' said
chief executive John Barbour, who joined the firm in September 1999
_ too late to affect major changes before the crucial fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The company, a subsidiary of giant bricks-and-mortar chain Toys
R Us, has a fresh infusion of $57 million from Internet giant
Softbank Corp. A Toysrus.com spokesperson said the two new
facilities would cost about $26 million to $30 million each; a
figure for retrofitting the Memphis warehouse was not available.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a way of telling the world that Toysrus.com is going
to grow,'' said Sheldon Grodsky, an analyst with Grodsky Associates
in South Orange, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Barbour said Toysrus.com is also improving its Web site's
interface, which he admitted ``was a little bit clumsy'' and
increasing the amount of traffic it can handle to up to 60,000
simultaneous visitors.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of November, the online store got so
overloaded that only 58 percent of people attempting to visit it
could get through.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in December, the company faced an unpleasant realization:
It couldn't guarantee delivery of some customers' orders in time to
for the holidays. Toysrus contacted affected customers and gave
them $100 vouchers so they could complete their shopping at any
Toys R Us store.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of TOY10 (43922 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Barbour said only about one day's worth of sales were affected,
but the company got hammered in the media. One customer filed a
class action suit over late deliveries and the Federal Trade
Commission began an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   For the five-week period ended December 26, Toysrus.com drew
more than 1.49 million shoppers, versus 1.66 million at rival
eToys, according to research firm Media Metrix.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News reported that the Internet subsidiary had $50.9
million in 1999 sales _ a drop in the bucket compared to the parent
chain's $11 billion. Bloomberg said Toysrus.com's first-quarter
2000 sales were $10.6 million. Barbour declined to cite specific
numbers, but said first-quarter sales were 30 times greater than in
the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few months, Toysrus.com will add new channels for
BabiesRUs, the parent company's infant-care business, and Rzone,
its computer and electronics division.
</P>
<P>
   While not discounting a future spin-off to capitalize on
Internet stock valuations, Barbour said he values the online firm's
clicks-and-bricks synergies with the retail chain. When Internet
collectors snapped up Harley-Davidson Barbie, the site was able to
turn to its physical counterpart for more inventory. And when
stores sold out of Sega Dreamcasts ``virtually instantaneously''
after its September launch, Toysrus.com lent the real-world stores
a week's worth of its supply of the video game consoles.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
