<SLUG> BC-TELLME-PHONE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELLME TO OFFER INFORMATION VIA TELEPHONE 
</HEADLINE>
   By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Some of the key people who brought the world the
Internet browser are now heading a company that has little to do
with the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Backed by former Netscape Communications and Microsoft
executives, TellMe Networks, a Palo Alto, Calif., company, instead
plans to offer information about everything from the weather to
stock quotes and a list of local restaurants via a toll-free
telephone number.
</P>
<P>
   TellMe plans to announce Monday that it is launching a trial of
the service and will make it available more widely in June.
</P>
<P>
   The service will mimic information services already offered
nationwide by newspapers and telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   The two main differences between TellMe's service and existing
services is the company's extensive breath of topics, and the fact
that users won't have to rely on pressing keys on their touch tone
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, TellMe uses computerized speech technology to accept
spoken commands like ``weather'' or ``stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   The company has raised a total of $53 million from high-profile
investors, including the Barksdale Group, the venture capital firm
run by former Netscape Communications Corp. chief Jim Barksdale.
</P>
<P>
   The firm has been shrouded in secrecy for some time, but details
have been starting to dribble out since late last year.
</P>
<P>
   Heading up TellMe are chief executive Mike McCue and co-founder
Angus Davis, both from Netscape. Board member and vice president
Hadi Partovi &UR;  &LR; came from Microsoft, where he helped managed the
software company's Internet Explorer browser.
</P>
<P>
   TellMe executives are quick to point out that much of the
software used to power the information service relies on Internet
technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technically, we consider ourselves an Internet company,'' said
spokeswoman Marci Gottleib. But the user just needs a telephone.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
