<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EFAX-FREEWEB-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 FREE WEB SERVICES ARE STRUGGLING  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It isn't easy being free. Just ask eFax.
</P>
<P>
   The Menlo Park, Calif., firm runs one of the world's best-known
free online fax services, with more than 2 million users, and has
ambitious plans to make money by selling ads and signing up users
for paid versions of its service.
</P>
<P>
   But some Wall Street investors appear to be losing faith in that
vision.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock was off 83 percent as of Friday. And last
week, eFax sold itself to Jfax for roughly $74 million in stock
(excluding debt), a pittance by Internet standards. The company was
running so low on cash that Jfax had to lend eFax $5 million to
help keep it afloat until the deal can be completed in July.
</P>
<P>
   Jfax, with 800,000 users and a market value of $144 million, is
doing only slightly better. Its stock is off 62 percent since it
first sold shares to the public last July. Though the company
offers free faxes, it also offers voice mail and e-mail and plans
to change its name to ``something without the word fax.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just free fax services that are losing favor on
Wall Street. Stock in NetZero, a Southern California company that
offers free Internet service to 2 million users, has sagged more
than 50 percent this year. It, too, is showing no signs of breaking
into the black.
</P>
<P>
   EFax chief executive Ronald Brown said Wall Street is no longer
willing to award giant valuations to companies just because they
have millions of users.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last summer, everyone was talking about (attracting) eyeballs
and building an installed base of users,'' Brown said. ``Now the
market is very much looking for tangible evidence of developing
revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, there's no lack of interest from new players trying
to launch services and raise money. At least three companies this
year have unveiled plans to start offering free high-speed Internet
service over phone lines.
</P>
<P>
   And Freei Networks, a more traditional free Internet service
provider, announced plans last week to raise $172 million by
selling stock to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the stock slump, NetZero is still valued at $1.4
billion despite just $12 million in sales and a $25 million loss
during the last three months of last year.
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street wasn't as kind to eFax.
</P>
<P>
   The company lost $10 million for the last three months of 1999,
including a $2 million charge related to its old business of making
computer cards for printing and faxing. Though growing, its eFax
business generated only $725,000 in revenue, not enough to impress
some investors. (Before the sale, the company planned to raise more
money from private investors to keep the business afloat, in
addition to the $60 million investors have already pumped into the
firm.)
</P>
<P>
   EFax executives said they were mystified when Phone.com in
Redwood City, Calif., bought Onebox.com, another unified messaging
service, for $787 million in February _ 10 times the value eFax
fetched. But Onebox.com, which claims more than 1 million active
users, said it had started to focus on a different market: selling
messaging services to wireless telecommunications companies that
could in turn peddle them to users. EFax has been marketing itself
directly to users, mainly professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Jfax, meanwhile, lost $4.4 million on $2.6 million in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jfax and eFax have potential to turn many of their 2.8
million users into paying customers and generate a profit, said
Mark Levitt, an analyst with International Data Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Both offer free phone numbers to users, and automatically route
faxes to users' e-mail. But they offer additional services, such as
letting users send faxes, for a fee. Already, Jfax has 60,000
paying subscribers and eFax has about 65,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they get users, they will get revenue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Levitt said investors have started to look harder at the
immediate potential for profits and revenues during the past six
months to a year. ``This is a fairly new phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   Fellow IDC analyst Steve Harris added:
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street is finally waking up to the fact that not all
these companies are going to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris said NetZero is likely to survive, but many smaller free
ISPs could be squeezed as traditional companies such as banks offer
free Internet service as part of a package of services. ``It
doesn't bode well.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; . &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
