<HEADER>
A1944 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MERCE-DANCE-REVIEW-NY     04-09 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERCE-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MULTIHUED CREATURES AFOOT WITH JOHN CAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Any new dance piece by Merce Cunningham is worthy
of special attention; ``Interscape (2000),'' which was commissioned
by the John F. Kennedy Center for the Performing Arts here, sounds
good on paper and looks even better onstage.
</P>
<P>
   The ingredients are right, making for a visually striking
exercise in perception that recalls the Merce Cunningham Dance
Company's early creative collaborations.
</P>
<P>
   The music is a John Cage solo for cello, played by Loren Kiyoshi
Dempster. But Cage-fashion, the score offers choices and can also
be performed with an orchestra. On the eye-filling side, Robert
Rauschenberg, the troupe's resident designer from 1954 to 1964, has
come up with tricky, witty and stunning decor.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the same images are seen in double. The front
curtain suggests a montage of smudged black-and-white photographs.
The backdrop has the same images in color, with a crayonish tint.
The objects depicted are from Rauschenberg's grab-bag vision of
life, civilization's artifacts.
</P>
<P>
   Among these are a large carousel horse, a wooden figurehead, a
frame house that suggests an old hotel and a terraced castle. The
pictures fly through space on a flat surface, disconcerting in
their overlapping assemblages and yet soothingly reminiscent of a
Victorian postcard. At the premiere of ``Interscape (2000)'' on
Thursday night at the Kennedy Center's Eisenhower Theater, the
dancers appeared to have postmarks imprinted on the multihued
leotards that Rauschenberg designed.
</P>
<P>
   That these wonderful creatures in shades of blue, green, pink
and orange were going somewhere was obvious in Cunningham's
choreography, which had leitmotifs that underwent sudden changes.
As a title, ``Interscape (2000)'' suggests connections between
sites.
</P>
<P>
   The dancers initially appear like ghostly blurs, barely visible
as the smudgy frontcloth turns transparent under Aaron Copp's
gorgeous lighting. As this curtain rises, Jeannie Steele and Derry
Swan are onstage in straight-legged positions, joined later by
three women. The choreography is full of details like arched backs
and small steps in place. Duets (especially by Holley Farmer and
Daniel Squire) initiate motifs that will recur: a head thrown back,
arms linked, back-to-back dancing and shifts of weight, sometimes
in the pelvis alone.
</P>
<P>
   The men have a habit of leaping in, adding a web of musculature
and volume to the women's lighter jumps. Non sequiturs abound. A
female septet, for example, suddenly rotates shoulders, with one
shoulder moved forward just before a soloist, Banu Ogan, with red
paint on her costume, is enclosed by a group.
</P>
<P>
   The central duet goes to Cedric Andrieux and to Lisa Boudreau,
whose blond curls make her look like a movie ingenue, especially
when she smiles at her partner after he has placed his hand in the
small of her back. There was a time when modern dance involved no
partnering. Cunningham is not one to live by other people's
conventions. The surprise of the duet is in its varied lifts. At
the end, the man is in profile and the woman, astride his shoulder,
faces the audience: a sharp image.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interscape (2000)'' is not one of Cunningham's overt
crowd-pleasers. It is a bit long, but its richness is in the
detail. Just as Rauschenberg's two curtains are the same with a
difference, so the choreography requires keen looking: its tone is
generally the same throughout, but there are unexpected moments. In
one, Ogan starts out with one leg behind the other, twists and
winds up in a plie, feet apart.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to say that such technical points are for
specialists, but Cunningham knows how to theatricalize movement on
a formal level. The cast, superb and articulate, included Ashley
Chen, Maydelle Fason, David Kulick, Koji Minato, Robert Swinston
and Cheryl Therrien.
</P>
<P>
   A major contribution came from Dempster, the cellist in the pit
playing Cage's music. Cage died in 1992 and this score has not been
recorded. But according to Cage's instructions, the music for the
soloist, ``One8 ,'' may also be performed with an orchestral piece
for 108 musicians, titled ``108.'' Cunningham has left open that
possibility, or a program note suggests that the dancing could be
accompanied by orchestra only. On this occasion Dempster did a
capital job with a clear, rich sound that respected the built-in
silences and the range of the score, including its occasional
warblings and ululations.
</P>
<P>
   The program was completed by ``Summerspace'' and ``Pond Way,''
two Cunningham pieces of great beauty seen last summer at Lincoln
Center Festival '99. Unfortunately the company is not scheduled to
perform in New York until next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
