<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BIOSCOPE: GENETICALLY ENGINEERED FOOD TOUTED AS HUNGER RELIEF  &HT;     By TOM ABATE 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Opponents of genetically modified foods got
great media last year over the monarch butterfly, that charismatic
creature that seemed to choke on the pollen drift of so-called
``killer corn.''
</P>
<P>
   But now one detects a not-so-subtle change in the winds of
publicity, which increasingly depict bioengineered plants as the
best hope of feeding the Third World. In contrast to last year's
script, which cast Monsanto as corporate demon, the poster child of
the remake is the well-fed environmental elitist.
</P>
<P>
   A perfect example of this new genre is the favorable portrayal
of Monsanto chief executive Robert B. Shapiro in the April 10
edition of New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro is revealed to us as ``a thin almost painfully
contemplative Jew from the Upper West Side of Manhattan'' (a
factoid of ethnographic significance to New Yorkers, perhaps).
</P>
<P>
   This sensitive mensch, who still believes firmly that genetic
engineering can create disease-resistant crops to feed a hungry
world, must ``fight back tears'' as he mulls the vilification
leveled at him and the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel hurt, and we feel angry,'' he says. Not to mention
misunderstood, implies the New Yorker. Remember those Terminator
seeds, the ones engineered to die on the vine? Suicide seeds, we're
told, had ``the potential to address a worrisome environmental
issue'' making sure ``unwanted traits do not cross-pollinate and
spread to other species.''
</P>
<P>
   The foil to Shapiro's unappreciated corporate citizenship is
Lord Peter Melchett, organic farmer, Greenpeace activist and former
Labor Party minister.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Melchett, as he is referred to in the article _ an
honorific that conjures the despised powdered wigs of Rumpole of
the Bailey _ states that his opposition to genetically engineered
foods need not be based on scientific objections.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do things for all sorts of reasons that are rational,
but they are not scientific or technical,'' Melchett says. ``Why
does somebody buy a Rolls-Royce or a Mercedes? It's a box with four
wheels. But nobody says you are completely irrational to buy an
expensive car. If it's acceptable to choose your car based on
emotion and not science, why should it be wrong to choose your food
that way?''
</P>
<P>
   Marie Antoinette could not have said it better. M'lord
Greenpeace, it seems, cannot put himself in the shoes of the
starving masses who, after all, go around barefoot.
</P>
<P>
   Now I do believe much of the criticism of genetically engineered
foods has been ill-founded and occasionally Luddite, and that a
better treatment of biotechnology advocates, a better understanding
of gene-splicing techniques and a willingness to consider the
benefits of genetically engineered crops is in order.
</P>
<P>
   But I've also heard some very reasoned concerns raised by
ecologists like University of California at Berkeley professors
Miguel Altieri and Ignacio Chapela, as well as Marc Lappe, director
of the Center for Ethics and Toxics, located in Mendocino, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   I would summarize their arguments this way.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture is becoming increasingly industrialized, dominated
by heavy machinery and requiring large amounts of chemical
fertilizers, pesticides and herbicides, which are designed to mesh
with hybrid seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Gene-splicing techniques are only the latest, most far-reaching
example of this approach. Ecologists worry that this
agro-industrial gestalt threatens the web of microorganisms,
natural nutrients and topsoil on which all civilization depends.
</P>
<P>
   This growth zone has been 4 billion years in the making.
Perhaps, they say, we should consider the ecological effects of our
relatively recent practice of mixing tons of chemical agents into
the soil and devoting millions of acres to industrial growing
techniques that may produce quick yield improvements, but
eventually burn out the soil.
</P>
<P>
   I understand how that argument may have fallen out of the New
Yorker. They gave the piece only 12 pages, not room enough, it
seems, to explain the shades of gray.
</P>
<P>
   SHAMELESS PLUG: The Commonwealth Club of California will hold a
debate on ``The risks and benefits of genetically modified foods''
at 4:45 p.m. PDT Tuesday at 595 Market St. in San Francisco.
Presenting the pro side will be Dr. Martina McGloughlin, director
of the University of California at Davis biotechnology program. Dr.
Peter Rosset, executive director of Food First in Oakland, will
present the opposing view. I will moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Call (415) 597-6700 for information.
</P>
<P>
   WILD &AMP; WOOLY: Biotech stocks have taken investors for a
roller-coaster ride in recent weeks. Expect the wild gyrations to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   After a stunning climb that began in January, sparked by
optimism about new gene discoveries, the sector plunged in March,
thanks in part to confusion about whether President Clinton and
British Prime Minister Tony Blair were opposed to gene patents.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech stock indexes lost more than a third of their value in
March and, despite a brief uptick or two, seemed to be trending
slowly downward.
</P>
<P>
   Then last Wednesday, Clinton tried to repair the damage by
personally emphasizing that he had no objection to private gene
patents. The next day, Celera Genomics, one of the leaders in the
private gene discovery effort, announced another milestone in the
race to read the entire human genome.
</P>
<P>
   Biotech stocks started to bounce back faster than you could say
fuhgedaboutit. The Nasdaq biotech stock index, which tracks 200
firms, gained 8 percent last week. Even after a brutal March, the
index is ahead 27 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Strong stock gains and front page news often attracts novice
investors, like the person who asked me for the ticker symbol for
Celera. It's CRA, short, I should have mentioned, for Caution, Risk
Ahead.
</P>
<P>
   This is a fickle sector, driven up and down by news over which
the average investor has no control or even a clue. My colleague,
financial columnist Arthur Louis, helped me understand the
mathematics of biotech volatility.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poors index has a price-earnings ratio of 32. The
Nasdaq, heavily weighted with technology firms, has a PE of 211,
high but still positive. And it is notably more volatile than the
S&AMP;P.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq biotech stock index, by comparison, has a negative
PE. That's because most of the 200 firms in the index will lose
money, until and unless they get some drug through the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   So the conventional investment measures can't be applied to a
biotech portfolio. There are sound companies in the sector, but if
you throw money at biotech momentum players before you've done
enough homework to separate the wheat from the chaff, you'd better
expect to get blown about a bit.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Tom Abate at abate(AT)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
