<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1947 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-B2B-BROKERS-SFCHRON &LR;      04-09 1763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-B2B-BROKERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ONLINE BROKERS ATTEMPT PERFECT BUSINESS-TO-BUSINESS MATCHES  &HT;     By CAROLYN SAID 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mike Brossier was drowning in excess olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Critelli Olive Oil, where he is director of food service, had
listened to suggestions from its chef customers and crafted an oil
similar to that sold in Mediterranean countries: raw, unfiltered,
strongly flavored.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a deep green, cloudy olive oil that was a little
too daring for the U.S. market.
</P>
<P>
   That left the Richmond, Calif., plant sitting on 12,000 liters
of the oil. Plus 4,800 liters of another style that hadn't sold and
2,616 bottles of flavored oil from a canceled order. And the clock
was ticking on the shelf life.
</P>
<P>
   So last week, Brossier turned to the Internet and a
business-to-business exchange.
</P>
<P>
   He listed the oil on Rebound, an exchange for excess inventory
of finished consumer products.
</P>
<P>
   After five days, Critelli had inquiries from a retailer in South
Korea and a wholesaler in China, both countries where robust olive
oil is more accepted. No deal is set, but Brossier anticipates
getting offers soon; Rebound will get about a 6 percent commission.
</P>
<P>
   Brossier's story illustrates why B2B exchanges are this year's
Wall Street darlings, even though many could be next year's
has-beens. These online middlemen essentially overhaul supply
chains, trimming costs and time, and open up larger markets for
goods. Each exchange is a like an eBay devoted to a specific
market: car parts or factory equipment or plastics.
</P>
<P>
   Rebound has targeted a niche market _ excess inventory of
consumer goods _ and is leveraging contacts and knowledge gained
from its founders' brick-and-mortar experiences in that field. Like
many exchanges, the company said it strives to maintain the human
dimension; each customer works with an account manager, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   But the company also exemplifies the potential pitfalls for
exchanges. There's nothing to stop Brossier, or any other customer,
from taking his business across the virtual street to a rival. And
Rebound's foray into cyberspace is so new _ its official site
launch was just a month ago, although a beta version had been up
for over a year _ that it's too soon to gauge the profit potential.
</P>
<P>
   For all B2B exchanges, the potential market size is staggering.
A forthcoming report from research firm Keenan Vision of San
Francisco predicts that the dollar volume of B2B exchange
transactions will vault from $33.9 billion this year to $1.3
trillion in 2004. That's almost 12 percent of the U.S. GDP gross
domestic product, which the White House projects will be $10.9
trillion in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, those huge numbers reflect the entire pie of deals;
the exchanges only get a slice as a commission, plus bonuses if
they arrange ancillary services such as shipping and financing.
</P>
<P>
   And some huge corporations want to keep those slices for
themselves, instead of sharing with independent companies that set
up an exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The much-ballyhooed February deal among General Motors, Ford and
DaimlerChrysler to form an online marketplace for car parts means
they'll be their own middlemen. Retail giants Sears, Roebuck and
France's Carrefour &LR;   &LR; are starting an exchange for purchasing from
more than 50,000 suppliers. Chevron and Wal-Mart's McClane division
are teaming up to create an exchange for convenience stores. (All
those companies are partnering with technology firms such as Oracle
and CommerceOne, which will share in the riches.)
</P>
<P>
   Whether suppliers will be enthusiastic about exchanges run by
their customers remains to be seen. ``These e-marketplaces have to
learn the role of neutrality,'' said Bruce Temkin, research
director at Forrester Research. ``They have to figure out how to
make it work for not just them, but for their suppliers as well.
Otherwise, it will be just a bunch of big guys bullying up on their
supply chain.''
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, B2B exchanges replace informal _ and chaotic _
systems that rely heavily on buyers faxing orders, sellers calling
potential buyers, or salesmen hitting the road. ``We're not selling
anything new, just something more efficient,'' said Marybeth Dee,
president and co-founder of Rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Headquartered in both San Francisco and Hong Kong, Rebound helps
connect Asian and North American markets, particularly factories in
Asia seeking ways to sell overruns and discontinued goods.
</P>
<P>
   It deals with home and lifestyle products (for example, a
Chinese factory owner who was shutting down shop and desperately
needed to unload 42,000 10-piece knife sets of a brand very
familiar to infomercial fans), food (700,000 packages of frozen
teriyaki chicken wings), clothing and accessories (7,000
Teletubbies vinyl knapsacks), consumer electronics (100,000 laser
pointers) and computers (14 IBM ThinkPads, $1,102 each).
</P>
<P>
   B2B exchanges cut business costs in two ways. By creating a
broader, more open market, they can result in better prices for
products. And, more importantly to many firms, they can
dramatically slash procurement costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We focus on taking cost out of the channel,'' said Bob Flury,
executive vice president of Santa Clara, Calif.'s Neoforma, an
exchange for medical supplies ranging from bandages to radiology
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Flury quotes an industry study that hospitals, doctors and
nursing homes spend up to $15 billion annually in excess cost on
order entry, processing and logistics. Each individual order costs
$8 to $10 if made via fax, $5 to $6 via phone, $2 to $3 via
Electronic Data Interchange (a proprietary technology format used
by about one-fifth of the health care industry), and 50 cents or
less when made via the Internet, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If businesses save big bucks on supplies, what will it mean to
the average person?
</P>
<P>
   When a manufacturer pays less for steel for a Chicago skyscraper
or chemicals for lab tests, it's not going to affect Joe Consumer.
Even with goods further down the consumer chain _ produce, for
example, or the finished goods sold on Rebound _ you can't map a
direct impact at the checkout.
</P>
<P>
   But B2B proponents say consumers still win under the
trickle-down theory. ``When the supply chains get cheaper and
computer automation makes things more efficient, it enables
companies to maintain price stability,'' said Vernon Keenan,
president of Keenan Vision. ``It could introduce further restraint
on inflation in our economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of firms call themselves B2B exchanges, although many
aren't yet open for business. About two dozen B2B firms plan to go
public this year, and plenty more are in the pipeline. ``We get
five to 10 business plans for B2B exchanges on a daily basis,''
said Mark Hilderbrand, a partner at Onset Ventures, a Menlo Park
venture capital firm.
</P>
<P>
   So many exchanges means it's inevitable there will be a big
shakedown, soon.
</P>
<P>
   Neoforma, for example, competes against at least half a dozen
medical-supply exchanges. And Wall Street already seems soured on
the company's prospects. It went public at $13 in January, and
after soaring to $73.53 in February, plunged back to earth. It
closed at $14.13, down 38 cents, on Friday. Analysts said the stock
has been hammered by concerns over Neoforma's acquisitions and last
month's announcement that five of the biggest medical supply
companies, including Johnson &AMP; Johnson and GE Medical Systems, will
form their own online marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say ancillary services like financing, transportation
and insurance will be key to determining which B2B exchanges
survive.
</P>
<P>
   Most exchanges partner with outside vendors for these
value-added services.
</P>
<P>
   For example, IronPlanet, a Palo Alto, Calif., exchange in the
$28 billion market for used heavy construction equipment says it
has contracted with huge government contractor Dyncorp for
impartial inspectors who will personally examine each backhoe or
tractor at the seller's site, analyze oil samples from the engine
and transmission, and write a detailed report with pictures of each
moving part.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers who want to kick the tires themselves before laying out
more than $100,000 for a 4-year-old Caterpillar excavator can still
do so _ but those who don't can save on their airfare and time.
</P>
<P>
   IronPlanet also offers assistance with insurance,
transportation, financing, and parts and service.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Rebound has partnered with logistics, financial
services and quality assurance firms, and hopes to soon ink a deal
with freight forwarders.
</P>
<P>
   Keenan sees exchanges going to a model where they generate most
of their revenue from value-added services and cut out transaction
fees altogether.
</P>
<P>
   A Livermore, Calif., exchange for produce called
TradingProduce.com is already ahead of this wave. Last month, it
eliminated its transaction fee. Buyers and sellers pay a flat, $99
monthly fee to use the service, but its primary revenues come from
helping with logistics, financing and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Gib Papazian, president of Lucky Strike Farms, a South San
Francisco, Calif., distributor, shipper and broker of vegetables
and melons, uses TradingProduce for about a tenth of his company's
annual $50 million in sales. He said the financing services were
particularly attractive. ``The accounting practices of large
customers have become aggressive and slow,'' he said.
TradingProduce is backed by giant agricultural bank Rabobank,
which, for a fee, will pay growers and brokers within 40 hours and
collect from the slow-paying stores or brokers who bought the
produce.
</P>
<P>
   Early mornings at a produce dealer's office are a blizzard of
faxes and phone calls, setting up deals to get hundreds of cases of
lettuce and artichokes from Salinas fields to the local Safeway,
for example.
</P>
<P>
   Papazian said TradingProduce gives him a streamlined, paperless
way to handle information bottlenecks. ``I can go ahead and flip on
the Internet and see what product is available,'' he said.
``Instead of dialing each individual grower and saying `Here's how
much of this or that I need packed up,' I just fill out an order on
the Internet and zip it over to them, and they zip the pickup
number back to me in 15 seconds, instead of five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are afraid it's going to replace human contact,''
he said. ``I look at it as the opposite; it's going to enhance
contact. You're spending less time doing rote, mechanical monkey
work and more time discussing how to improve things and tend to the
affairs of the firm.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  E-mail Carolyn Said at  &LR; csaid &LR; (AT) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
