   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   STATE-BUDGETS-SURPLUS (Lansing, Mich.) _ Lawmakers here and in
many other states, now writing their budgets for the 2001 fiscal
year, are witnessing the biggest of six consecutive years of rising
revenues, inspiring inventive new ways to spend money and wave upon
wave of tax reductions. ``The states are overflowing with money and
spending a lot of money,'' said Stephen Moore, an economist at the
conservative Cato Institute. ``You are starting to see _ among
Republican governors, by the way _ budget increases of 6, 7, 8
percent a year.'' By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   SILICON-GEEKS (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ Palo Alto, arguably the
center of the Silicon Valley universe, has a whopping 36 percent
more men than women. And since this is also the land of the best
educated, highest paid workers in the world, single women in search
of smart, successful men should be having a ball. But the valley is
a weird world, unto itself. By Evelyn Nieves.
</P>
