<HEADLINE>
ROUTINE MASTERY: SINGH ANSWERS EACH CHALLENGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Four days at Augusta National brought more
unfounded threats than lawyers in a divorce proceeding. Tiger,
Nicklaus, Duval, lightning, it all went out with the green trash
bags.
</P>
<P>
   What we were left with was the Unemotional Open.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks and weeks of Tiger Woods instigating gallery riots
and turning CBS into the Golf Channel II, we saw the Big Fiji beat
the Big Easy, the Incredible Shrinking Man and either Oral or Julia
Roberts in a pillow fight.
</P>
<P>
   Golf fans begged for another excitement fix. Vijay Singh Sunday
gave them routine and mundane instead, claiming the Masters with a
three-stroke victory.
</P>
<P>
   This might play at Sahalee, where Singh packed off the PGA
Championship trophy in similar fashion two years ago. Half of
Microsoft was there to cheer him on. But people here expect a
little swagger with their green jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Masters winners usually break down and cry. They single out
Augusta National as the ultimate golfing experience.
</P>
<P>
   The soft-spoken Singh said thank you. That's it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try not to think differently of (any) of the majors,'' he
said diplomatically. ``They're all really big tournaments and mean
the same to me. The Masters, PGA, British Open and U.S. Open,
they're all right there. I just hope one day I can finish the next
two.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh had people in their cars by the 13th hole, heading up the
interstate. His closest pursuer at the time, David Duval, put one
in the water at the back door of Amen Corner and it was over.
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old Fiji native shot 3-under-par 69 in the final
round, actually 3-under 85 over 22 holes Sunday, forced to finish
Saturday's weather-interrupted effort early in the morning. He
never trailed during any of it, though the lead shrank to one at
times.
</P>
<P>
   Singh finished with a 10-under 278 total, good for his ninth PGA
Tour victory and a paycheck worth $828,000 _ $228,000 more than he
wheelbarrowed out of Sahalee.
</P>
<P>
   With a couple of late birdies, South African Ernie ``Big Easy''
Els was runner-up, shooting 68 and 281. Duval and laid-back Loren
Roberts were tied for third, both at 282. Not exactly the makings
for a frat house party.
</P>
<P>
   Woods was fifth, at 284, unable to coax enough magic out of his
clubs after an opening-day 75.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still had a chance,'' the ever-confident Woods said. ``I'm
proud of that, the fact I got back in this tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people pined for Duval, the tour's fitness freak, to win.
He was one of them, a former Georgia Tech player, another man with
a slow, Southern drawl and true appreciation for these parts.
</P>
<P>
   He also came up with a fade instead of a draw on the 13th hole.
Splash. Trailing by a stroke, Duval's 5-iron shot from 196 yards
caught the creek that guards the right side of the 485-yard par 5.
Duval bogeyed and Singh birdied, and the split was three.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than commend Singh's good fortune, the gallery turned
eerily silent, tepidly applauding the man in front.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do we do now?'' one woman asked her husband, who pointed
to the parking lot. They were not alone in the exodus.
</P>
<P>
   So precise and error-free for much of the day, Duval had no
details to provide on what went wrong on the unlucky 13th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hit a poor golf shot and it was the wrong time to do
it,'' he said. ``It was the only one I had all weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh stayed close throughout the proceedings, trailing Dennis
Paulson by one shot after the first round, Duval by one after two
rounds and then easing himself in front during blustery conditions
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Singh let his putting lead him to a green jacket. His first
three-putt of the tournament came on his 57th hole. He had just two
at Augusta.
</P>
<P>
   ``He putted wonderful,'' Duval said. ``He putted more wonderful
than he played.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh goes by feel. He has 1,000 putters at home, and one is
never around long.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not an understatement,'' he said, referring to the
stockpile and exchange rate. ``I have a lot of putters. If it's not
working, you get something that will.''
</P>
<P>
   As a teen in Fiji, Singh used to catch the Masters on TV, on
tape delay. That's kind of what happened Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was evident and much of the excitement was gone, but
he hung in there just the same.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Dan Raley can be reached at 206-448-8008
</P>
<P>
   or danraley &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
