<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-09 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1951 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      04-09 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S SMACK YANKEES TO CAP 4-2 HOMESTAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After spending the better part of a week kicking sand
in the bullies' faces, the Mariners don't exactly own the beach.
</P>
<P>
   They do, however, own a sense that the bullies will give them a
wide berth after Seattle's completion of a 4-2 homestand against
Boston and New York. Sunday's 9-3 win over the Yankees gives the
Mariners as many wins against the Beasts of the East as they had in
all of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope everybody in the clubhouse realizes what we've done
here this week,'' right fielder Jay Buhner said. ``We went against
two of the best teams in baseball, and they threw their big boys at
us. We played well enough we could have won all six games, and we
did win four.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stunk against East Coast teams last year. But this is a
totally different team. We've got the pitching to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   One week into the season, Seattle has the best team earned-run
average in baseball at 2.83. That's a little like saying
Switzerland has the world's best Navy. It doesn't compute.
</P>
<P>
   But, said starting pitcher Jamie Moyer after his eight-inning,
three-run start chipped the Yankee bats into so much sawdust, maybe
it should compute.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a team full of people who can pitch,'' Moyer said.
``I believe we've got really good arms here. On top of that, we've
played good defense. Everything we've done this first homestand has
been very, very positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game was huge for the Mariners. A 3-3 homestand would
have been acceptable, given the M's 4-16 stroll over hot coals
against the Red Sox and Yankees a year ago. But a loss would have
meant back-to-back setbacks after Saturday's 3-2 heartbreaker.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees threw former Cy Young Award winner Roger Clemens at
Seattle Sunday. Clemens owns as many career wins against Seattle
(20) as any pitcher ever _ Dave Stewart also stung the Mariners 20
times.
</P>
<P>
   And whittling away at Clemens was as difficult as advertised.
The first four innings saw just one unearned Seattle run _ Mike
Cameron's infield single brought home the game's first run in the
third. But that was gone moments later when doubles by Chuck
Knoblauch and Derek Jeter led to two fourth-inning Yankee runs.
</P>
<P>
   But a throwing error by catcher Jorge Posada in the bottom of
the fifth helped Seattle to load the bases with no one out against
Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron's infield single off the glove of the leaping Knoblauch
brought the tying run home. Alex Rodriguez gave the M's the lead
with a grounder to second base. John Olerud added a sacrifice fly.
Edgar Martinez slipped a single between third and short for another
run.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, the Mariners kept taking pitches, fouling off
pitches and making Clemens work. Perhaps the best example of that
was Buhner, who worked and worked Clemens until he got a 3-2 pitch
he could juice. The ball, which came on Clemens' 32nd pitch of the
inning, landed five rows deep in the right-field bleachers for a
two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, the upstart was in command, and the beach bully
was sullenly trying to find a way to get all that sand out of his
Speedos.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens is still a terrific pitcher, but he's 37 and, just
maybe, becoming vulnerable. He started 29 times last year, and the
Yankees only went 16-13 in those games.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner, for one, can see a chance for hitters to maybe get a
little revenge for all those nuclear third strikes Clemens used to
throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I shouldn't say this, but I think Roger's only got so
many fastballs and split-fingers left in him,'' Buhner said. ``We
kept working him hard, and I saw him going more to sliders and BP
(batting practice) fastballs, you know, 88 mph.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens needn't feel picked upon by the hurry-up-and-wait
Mariners. The Mariners have made a habit of getting deeper into the
game with virtually every pitcher they've faced this year. Seattle
hitters have one of the worst batting averages (.230) in the
league, but they've walked 31 times, tied for the best total in the
AL. Even the club's AL-worst 49 strikeouts have served a purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there's ever such a thing as a good
strikeout,'' Rodriguez said. ``But we've gotten a lot of the
pitchers we've faced into high pitch counts. Even when we've struck
out, it's usually been on a 3-2 pitch, not just 1-2-3.''
</P>
<P>
   That's always been the Yankee way, but the Bronx bummers didn't
have a chance to try that with Moyer. The lefty didn't walk a
batter and was seldom behind in the count. As a consequence, the
Yankees only saw 93 of his pitches in eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was his stuff,'' Knoblauch said with a tip of his cap to
Moyer. ``He changes speeds, throws strikes. It just goes to show
you it doesn't matter how hard you throw _ you can be successful if
you change speeds and keep guys off the bases.''
</P>
<P>
   Moyer allowed just three base-runners. He retired 18 of the
final 19 batters he faced, and reliever Jose Paniagua set New York
down in order in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get the kind of pitching we're getting, it takes
pressure off the offense,'' Rodriguez said. ``When you go out there
feeling you have to score 10 or 12 runs to win, there's a tendency
to press. We scored nine today, but we know we don't have to score
nine every day to be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
