</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVAMPED BULLPEN GIVES MARINERS WHOLE NEW LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Start spreading the news.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have delivered on a promise: They can pitch.
</P>
<P>
   After a 24-year legacy of abusing the truth, not to mention the
strike zone, the local baseball club has started a season as it
said it would: A lot less Paul Bunyan-style hacking, and a lot more
Sheriff Andy Taylor-style whittling.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the New York Yankees, if you can find them in the pile of
wood chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is they can bring guys out of the bullpen,''
said Yankees manager Joe Torre, whose defending champs last year
beat the Mariners nine of 10 times, but lost two of three over the
weekend here. ``Their staff is stronger. Now a one- or two-run lead
is enough for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday the Mariners made it even easier, hanging a fifth-inning
six-spot on Roger Clemens to rout the Yanks 9-3. Only a single
inning from the bullpen was required, because starter Jamie Moyer
delivered an April gem of eight innings and 93 pitches, only three
of them returned as hits.
</P>
<P>
   That completed a 4-2 opening home-stand whose virtues can best
be understood by comparing it to the first six games of 1999 in the
Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners started out 3-3 against Chicago and Oakland but
gave up a spirit-crushing 42 runs. Remember Eric Weaver, Mac Suzuki
and Brett Hinchliffe?
</P>
<P>
   This season's opponent total: 18 runs, to the Yankees and Red
Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Only once in the first six games a year ago did the Mariners
give up fewer than three runs. In the first six games of 2000, they
gave up more than three runs only once. Mariners fans risk the
threat of injury from two-season whiplash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does wonders for your confidence, being in every game,''
said Jay Buhner, who put up a double and homer Sunday to lead the
Mariners with a .389 average. ``We could easily have been 6-0.
There's a lot of new guys here, guys who don't know what went on
here the last three or four years ... it's in the back of your
mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The nightmare scratching at the underside of Buhner's shaven
skull has to do with going into the seventh inning with six runs
and knowing it wouldn't be enough.
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen has blown so many eighth and ninth innings for so
many seasons that there was some off-season rules-committee
discussion of renaming a bases-loaded walk ``the Mariner,'' because
the label was so concise and universally understood.
</P>
<P>
   The cure isn't complete _ witness Jose Mesa surrendering the
game-winning run in the ninth Saturday for New York's only series
win _ but with just five earned runs given up in 18{ innings by the
'pen, neither is reliable relief a mirage. As for the new relief
ace, Kazu Sasaki, only the dim outlines are visible of his imminent
largeness.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're serious, they have a pact going,'' Buhner said. ``You
can see they're going off on each other, picking each other up.''
</P>
<P>
   The history of repeated failures not only was hard on the
pitching staff, it wore acutely on the offense. Already prone to
overswinging, the lineup largely convinced itself that a five-run
homer was the only way out of most messes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a lot out of the offense knowing that you have to
keep tacking on runs,'' manager Lou Piniella said. ``Now, we can do
the little things, like bunt or hit and run. We don't need the big
inning. But we got one anyway, just doing the little things.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the decisive fifth, when a little Yankee screw-up on
the littlest play, a sacrifice bunt, led to much baseball bleeding.
Here's how the first four runs were produced: Soft single to
center, sac bunt and throwing error by catcher Jorge Posada, walk,
infield single for one run, run-scoring ground-out for a second
run, sacrifice fly for a third run, ground single to left for a
fourth run.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens, who was seeking his 21st career win over the Mariners _
most by any opponent in club history _ instead was dripping from
multiple paper cuts. Buhner's subsequent reversion to the ancient
Mariners style, a two-run homer to close the scoring, was
superfluous.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner, the surprising early season offense leader while waiting
for others to defrost _ Edgar Martinez and Dan Wilson had their
first hits of the season Sunday, and John Olerud is batting .167 _
is getting a chuckle out of the transformation in ways more than
winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun to watch Lou,'' he said. ``He's really doing some
great things managing. We're running, using the hit-and-run, the
other day he was talking about a squeeze play.''
</P>
<P>
   While a successful opening week will be followed by inevitable
seasonal stumbles, the Mariners established that they did what they
set out to do _ transform a failing team to a new park and to
proven ways of winning.
</P>
<P>
   And thanks to the Seattle chill, the Mariners are hardened off
for nine days in the frostbelt of Detroit, Toronto and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   There must be some excuses somewhere. But at this early moment,
one must go to Cincinnati for them.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
